<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STAY ALIVE WITH WIN OVER PIRATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scoreboard that looms in right field at Shea
Stadium was a garish monolith that blinked in yellow lights the
scores from the Houston and Cincinnati games Friday night, the
scores that would go a long way toward determining whether the
postgame New York Mets clubhouse would be about bitter reflection
or sustained tension.
</P>
<P>
   The board had already shown bad news for the fans: the Mets had
surrendered a two-run lead to the Pittsburgh Pirates in the eighth
inning and were in extra innings for the second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Mets batted in the 11th, it also showed that the
Astros had lost to the Los Angeles Dodgers in Houston and the
Brewers were on their way to defeating the Cincinnati Reds in
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   So there was good reason to roar when Shawon Dunston hit a
leadoff single and the Mets loaded the bases with two out for Robin
Ventura, who had hit a home run earlier. On a one-ball count,
Ventura singled to right field to score Dunston for a 3-2 victory
that kept the Mets' gasping season breathing for another day.
</P>
<P>
   With two games left in the regular season, the Mets are a game
behind in the National League wild-card race. A victory over
Pittsburgh Saturday night and another Sunday still won't guarantee
a postseason shot if the Reds or Astros fail to lose this weekend.
But Friday night's victory and losses by the Astros and the Reds at
least gave the Mets a better chance to perhaps force a one-game
playoff on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the struggling I've had, it's nice to contribute and do
something to help win the game,'' said Ventura, who made the
game-ending out in Thursday's 11-inning loss to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard served as much as a target as it did a warning
sign Friday night. But after Ventura and Mike Piazza had hit home
runs to give the Mets a 2-0 lead, the scoreboard reflecting the
Mets' doings brought nothing but smiles to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Mets gave up the lead in the top of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers had pitched spectacularly until then, but he tired
and walked the leadoff pinch hitter, John Wehner. After striking
out Al Martin on a curveball _ Rogers' 10th strikeout _ he yielded
an infield hit to Pat Meares that rolled so slowly toward Rey
Ordonez at shortstop that he could not make a play.
</P>
<P>
   A single by Aramis Ramirez cut the Mets lead to 2-1 and brought
right-handed Turk Wendell in from the bullpen. He struck out Kevin
Young on fastballs, but then he walked Chad Hermansen on four
pitches to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wallace, the Mets' pitching coach, headed to the mound with
the crowd howling. They knew what was coming. Dennis Cook was
unavailable because he was serving a suspension for bumping an
umpire in Tuesday's game. So it would be John Franco, who has been
mostly ineffective since returning from the disabled list, to face
the left-handed Warren Morris, a .292 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch, Morris rapped the ball back to the mound,
and it caromed off Franco's leg slowly toward Edgardo Alfonzo at
second. Alfonzo's throw to first was too late, and Meares scored
the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets loaded the bases in the bottom of the inning off two
Pirates relievers. But Marc Wilkins got Melvin Mora to hit into a
force play at second to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, manager Bobby Valentine used
closer Armando Benitez in a nonsave situation. Benitez pitched two
splendid innings on Thursday, and this time he struck out the side
in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort failed to inspire his teammates, who did not
score in the bottom of the ninth, forcing extra innings for the
second straight night.
</P>
<P>
   The sparse crowd of 29,528 _ did they misunderstand and think
the Mets were already out of it? _ provided a midseason,
laissez-faire mood. In the clubhouse before the game, there was
something closer to resignation. General manager Steve Phillips
sounded as if he were already talking about the team's postseason
hopes in the past tense when he essentially said that if it did not
make the playoffs, it would have underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our minimum goal was to get to the playoffs,'' he said.
``Therefore, we will not have reached our minimum goal. We assumed
competitiveness and that we'd have an exciting team. With that
being the basis, it won't feel like a success. This season has been
filled with small successes but that's not what we're in it to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets continued to grasp for larger success by matching the
control pitcher Rogers against the Pirates' hard-throwing Jason
Schmidt. The Mets had a few scoring opportunities in the first two
innings, but Schmidt got out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, though, Ventura came to the plate. He had been in
a 2-for-13 funk on the homestand before this game. Worse, his left
knee had to be drained before Wednesday's game to relieve swelling
from a soreness he first felt in Houston more than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   But on a 3-1 count, Ventura pivoted on the left foot and slugged
one of those 92 mph fastballs over the right-field wall, to the
right of the scoreboard. It was his 32nd home run and it gave the
Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, that was all Rogers needed. The former Yankees
left-hander is still battling the label that he is incapable of
success in New York. But in this game he used his curveball
extensively, and was as dominant in the early innings as he has
been since joining the Mets two months ago. And he benefited from
the Pirates' own inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   They had won four of their last five games, but they were 13 for
78 (.167) with runners in scoring position over the previous nine
games. The biggest early threat from Pittsburgh came in the fifth
inning, when the Pirates had runners on first and third with two
out and Martin at the plate. On a 1-2 count, Rogers threw Martin a
curveball that dropped sharply. But Martin swung and missed, and
the inning was over.
</P>
</TEXT>
