<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE SHAKY BUT YANKS CLOSE IN ON HOME FIELD   ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ David Cone was shaken out of sleep this
morning by a pounding on the door of his hotel room, and there were
shouts and screams, voices he recognized. Some of his teammates had
just arrived from Baltimore, where the Yankees had clinched the
American League East hours before.
</P>
<P>
   They yelled for Cone to open the door, but the pitcher declined.
Cone had flown to Florida a day ahead of the others to ensure a
full night's sleep in preparation for his start against the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees may have clinched the division, but they will remain
on full alert until they exhaust their possibilities for home-field
advantage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of a short and lousy outing from Andy Pettitte, the
Yankees pummeled the Devil Rays, 11-7, and with two games to play,
they matched Cleveland's 97-63 record; the Indians lost to Toronto
Friday night, 8-6. If the Yankees finish with a better record than
the Indians, or in a tie, they will possess home field advantage
throughout the AL playoffs because they took 7 of 10 games from
Cleveland during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte surrendered six runs on six hits and six walks in
four-plus innings, hardly a confidence boost for the left-hander in
his last start before the playoffs. But the Yankees overcame his
poor performance. Tino Martinez, who seems to have finally regained
his stroke at the best possible time, banged a three-run homer,
just before Darryl Strawberry unloaded what he thought was his
longest home run ever.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's drive caromed off a pole that hangs from the
ceiling over right field, the point of contact some 120 feet above
ground. The estimated distance of Strawberry's shot was 425 feet,
to where it traveled before ricocheting onto the field. If the ball
hadn't hit the pole, it would've gone much further. ``That thing
was longer than Reggie Jackson's home run in the '71 All-Star Game
in Detroit,'' said manager Joe Torre, who played in that game
against Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone chuckled about the 425-foot estimate. ``Off by about
100 feet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably once in a lifetime I can hit a ball like that,'' said
Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, the Yankees will open the best-of-5
division series on Tuesday at Yankee Stadium against the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is fluid, and without knowing for certain who
the Yankees will play Tuesday, or where they will play, Torre will
wait at least one more day before naming the starting pitcher for
his team's first playoff game. Either Roger Clemens or Orlando
Hernandez will pitch Game 1, but Torre said Friday that he
continues to weigh his choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to know what all the aspects of the decisions
are,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had the most victories for the Yankees this season
with a 17-9 record, and his ratio of quality starts _ which is
perhaps the best measure of consistency _ is among the best in the
league at .697. Torre knows from last year's postseason that
Hernandez is unfazed by pressure, and if the division series is
forced to a deciding fifth game, it would be pitched by the Game 1
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is more durable within each game than perhaps any
pitcher in baseball. Opponents have batted .232 against him in his
first 75 pitches of games this season, according to STATS Inc., but
incredibly, they have hit .202 after his 75th pitch.
</P>
<P>
   There are arguments to start Clemens in the first game, too. His
earned run average is about 2 1-2 runs lower when he has pitched at
Yankee Stadium this year, as compared with when he pitches on the
road. Game 1 and Game 5 would be in Yankee Stadium, if the Yankees
have home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has not pitched well when he gets more than his usual
four days of rest, and if he does not pitch Game 1, he may have to
wait more than week for his next start.
</P>
<P>
   If Clemens does not start Game 1, Torre said ``he's just going
to have to simulate'' game action until he makes his next outing,
in Game 3 or Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, acknowledged that
if Clemens is not the Game 1 starter, he might pitch some on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There are other choices to be made. Torre, who will meet with
the team's principal owner, George Steinbrenner, for lunch
Saturday, will pick between Clay Bellinger and Shane Spencer for
the 25th spot on the roster. Bellinger appears to have an edge. He
must also pick a 10th pitcher to round out his postseason staff,
and that will probably be Hideki Irabu or Jason Grimsley.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, too, must decide who will catch. Jorge Posada always
works with Hernandez, Joe Girardi with Pettitte, a left-hander. In
late August, when Clemens was in a deep pitching funk, Torre
switched Girardi _ who usually caught for Cone _ to Clemens, and
Posada to Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has generally pitched better since then, while Cone has
not done so well. It has been apparent, in several games, that Cone
is not as comfortable with Posada as he is with Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still things we are evaluating,'' Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
