<HEADLINE>
BIBLE WEEK SUIT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By EDYTHE JENSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bible Week'' once again has a prayer in Gilbert, thanks to a
court ruling in a lawsuit against the town and Mayor Cynthia
Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Roslyn Silver of U.S. District Court said in the ruling,
released Friday, that Gilbert residents and Holocaust survivors
Ellis and Ellen Sklar did not have standing to sue. Nor could they
prove they were injured by Dunham's vow to designate Nov. 22-29,
1998, as Bible Week, the judge ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling did not address the proclamation's constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Civil Liberties Union filed the suit in November on
the Sklars' behalf after Dunham said she would set aside a week to
honor the Bible, as she did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull and mayors of other Phoenix area cities abandoned
plans to proclaim such a week after the ACLU launched its legal
challenge in Gilbert. Dunham halted plans for the 1998 proclamation
after Silver issued a restraining order. Dunham was in Utah on
Friday and couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Vice Mayor Maggie Cathey said she will encourage Dunham to
sign a 1999 Bible Week proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU Executive Director Eleanor Eisenberg said her organization
may appeal Silver's ruling or file other challenges if Dunham tries
to proclaim Bible Week again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling came as a surprise because we believe the Sklars
were injured,'' Eisenberg said. ``A violation of a fundamental
constitutional right is in and of itself an injury. One of those
constitutional rights is freedom from government intrusion in our
religious lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said the fact that Silver did not rule on the
constitutionality of Bible Week leaves the door open for future
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Sklar said the ruling was ``a shame, a terrible shame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Dunham is a despot,'' she said Friday after learning of
the dismissal. ``She believes all people should abide by her
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure she's feeling proud of herself and her right-wing
attorneys right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Evangelist Pat Robertson's American Center for Law and Justice
represented the mayor at no cost to the town.
</P>
<P>
   Town spokesman David Cannella said Dunham was told of the
dismissal and issued a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' the mayor's statement read. ``I felt all along
that the proclamation did not violate the separation of church and
state, and am happy and grateful that the court reaffirmed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannella said Dunham has received hundreds of messages and
letters about Bible Week, and ``better than 90 percent (were) in
support of the mayor's position.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Larry Morrison, who supported Dunham's proposed 1998
Bible Week proclamation, said Friday that he will neither encourage
nor discourage her from issuing it this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad at this point it seems to be over,'' Morrison said,
``And I hope we can go on with more important issues of the town,
like what are we going to do about taxes and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathey believes Silver's ruling vindicates the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we've listened to the ACLU, and we want to
recognize all groups,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Evans' vocal opposition to Bible Week created a
rift between him and Dunham, his political running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because something isn't illegal doesn't mean that it's
right,'' Evans said Friday. ``Bible Week is an activity in which
the town shouldn't be taking part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sklars said Friday that they are bracing for hate mail and
anti-Semitic telephone calls like those they received after they
sued last year.
</P>
<P>
   They're also leaving Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a big error in judgment moving here,'' Ellis Sklar
said. ``Our friends in Philadelphia warned us that Arizona was one
of the most anti-Semitic states in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we won this lawsuit,'' his wife added, ``we would have
lost, because either way, the phone calls will start.'' &QL; 
Edythe Jensen can be reached at (602) 444-7939 or at
edythe.jensen(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
