<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BAVASI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' BAVASI STEPS ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Citing irreconcilable differences in their approaches
to make the Angels a winner, team president Tony Tavares and
general manager Bill Bavasi decided a change needed to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, who has served as the club's GM since 1994, has resigned
and was re-assigned as a special assistant to Tavares.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was reached Thursday when the two had lunch.
Tavares had planned to meet with Bavasi after the season, but
Bavasi felt it was something that couldn't wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is not a happy day,'' Tavares said during a
news conference. ``Any time we get involved in change, there is
consternation caused and unpleasantness in it. But in this case
it's minor because Bill and I like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference stems from Bavasi's unwillingness to make drastic
changes to a team that he had a huge role in developing. Many of
the club's ``core'' group of players ascended through the minor
league system when Bavasi was the minor league director.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bavasi said: ``There will not be a
housecleaning approach. We have to get better at certain spots. You
can't clean house. Cleaning house is a knee-jerk reaction, and it's
a wrong one. I heard the same things in '96, but I'll say the same
thing I said then: We'll be real aggressive to change things in the
clubhouse, but there will not be a housecleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, however, is no longer in a position to decide who stays
and who goes. And Tavares made it clear that no one is untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is, this seems to be a team that for whatever
reason always gets this close and falls off,'' Tavares said. ``What
we'll try to do is analyze this and determine what causes this.
Anyone out there can say we need a second baseman, a catcher, more
pitching, but that's easy to recognize. It's deeper than that. We
decided to call timeout and take a hard look at where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi was asked if he was too attached to his players to be an
effective general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, maybe...'' he said. ``I never had a problem trading
guys, not emotionally. Did I over-evaluate a player or two?
Possibly, but I still don't think so. I think there are players who
haven't reached their potential yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tavares admits he has no business evaluating baseball talent.
But he believes the club's problems have nothing to do with talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What troubled me is when we got everybody back (from
injuries), why didn't we jell, why didn't we come together?'' he
said. ``We have to take a hard look at how we develop players. Not
fundamentals, but do we instill the proper values? What's missing
is the concept of `team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tavares pointed to the finger-pointing during the club's
collapse, calling what came out of the clubhouse on nearly a daily
basis ``revolting.'' But he said the club wouldn't make personnel
decisions without thoroughly thinking them through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get to the point where we make irrational or
emotional judgments on people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi's role as a special assistant to Tavares has not been
defined. Tavares said that he ``still respects'' Bavasi and will
seek his advice, though Bavasi said he didn't anticipate having
much input on deciding who will be the next GM. Once the club hires
a GM, his first order of business will be to hire a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seek out a new GM as soon as possible,'' Tavares said.
``But we haven't even put a list together. We haven't talked to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, normally unemotional and stoic, had to pause to collect
his emotions once during the news conference and spent a lot of
time thanking many in the organization and former members of the
organization he's worked with.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, 41, also said he is ``very happy right now'' with his
situation, although there is disappointment in the team's
performance this season. He began his career with the organization
as a minor league administrator in 1980, was appointed director of
minor league operations in 1984, became assistant GM in 1993 and
took over as GM in January 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
