<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAVASI JOINS SELECT GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (set ital) Today's defrocked Halo edition of The Sporting Muse:
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bavasi may not have succeeded in getting the Angels to a
World Series, but he joins a rather privilaged group by resigning.
</P>
<P>
   It includes his father Buzzie, who was G.M. for seven years
(1988-94), and Bill never let anyone the stature of Nolan Ryan get
away, although we'll always wonder how things might have changed if
the Angels had traded for Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes trader Harry Dalton (1972-77), who lived up to
his name but never had a winning season. It also includes Fred
Haney, the team's first G.M., and Mike Port, who, like Bavasi and
Buzzie, had three winning seasons during their stay.
</P>
<P>
   This stat is more indicative of the Angels than any of Bavasi's
wins and losses. Success eludes the Angels, flirting with the team
just long enough to make the pain feel worse.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi's efforts were sincere, and they were a lot more
heartening to fans than the rent-a-free agent philosophy elsewhere
in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi and Bob Fontaine scouted, signed and nurtured the nucleus
of the current Angels. If the Angels hadn't fallen to earth so hard
in the last month of 1995, and had made the postseason, Bavasi
likely would have been mentioned in the same breath as Atlanta's
John Schuerholz and Cleveland's John Hart as smart and savvy
baseball architects.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of those players and the effort they gave, Bavasi
hasn't a single regret. ``The players are special. It isn't a crime
if someone underachieves for a season, or if a guy gets hurt.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Considering all of the turmoil in 1999, which saw many of
Bavasi's favorites berating each other and Bavasi himself having to
admonish their actions, it might have been difficult for the same
cast to move forward. Terry Collins realized the situation was out
of his control, and Bavasi's policy took too much friendly fire.
</P>
<P>
   But as easy as it is to say Bavasi and Collins failed, it's a
major challenge this days to find the right people to make a bad
situation better. One only has to look at the struggles of Kevin
Malone and Davey Johnson, men respected in the field, to see how
difficult starting over can be. ...
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of up the road, Disney could do worse than consider
hiring Fred Claire and Bill Russell as their G.M. and manager. The
old Dodgers image is very sympatico with Disney's. In light of the
way Fox has bollixed the Dodgers, it wouldn't necessarily cast a
Dodger shadow over the franchise. ...
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the Dodgers' Raul Mondesi: The best time to apologize to
fans for your conduct is not (set ital) after (end) the final home
game of the season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line on Homermania, the sequel: I'm glad both Sammy Sosa
and Mark McGwire hit 60 again to show it was no fluke. I'm even
more pleased than no one else shot up to 60. And I'm ecstatic that
70 didn't fall, because it would have cheapened last year's
celebration. ...
</P>
<P>
   I know UCLA once played stout defense, because the Bruins
produced nine All-Americans on that side of the ball between 1987
and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But they've had only one since (Shaun Williams in 1997), and the
points allowed under Bob Toledo now exceeds the gross national
product of Guam. Headed into today's game at Arizona State, Bruin
opponents have scored 30 points or more in 16 of Toledo's 39 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was vogue to blame '98 defensive coordinator Nick Alioti for
the troubles last season, but the problem dates back to the weird
attack defense installed by his predecessor, Rocky Long. The '97
team thrived and survived on turnovers, which always has more to do
with mistakes by opponents than planning by a defense. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's strange to see the way certain patterns emerge over time.
USC, once revered for its running game, has had difficulty
recruiting blue chip backs and offensive linemen the last decade,
and UCLA hasn't produced a first-team all-conference defensive
lineman since current assistant Terry Tumey in 1987. ...
</P>
<P>
   If Paul Hackett is such an offensive specialist, why doesn't he
use the whole field?
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's Trojans definitely pass more than previous teams, but
most of those passes are on the perimeter. The middle of the field
gets ignored, which seems like a waste of perfectly good space R.
Jay Soward and Kareem Kelly could be using.
</P>
<P>
   Isolating fast receivers on the edges obviously has merit, as
does spreading a defense from sideline to sideline. But the lack of
variety in the attack seems limiting. ...
</P>
<P>
   I could definitely get behind a Stanford-Purdue Rose Bowl, and I
could care less whether they play for the national title or free
car rentals at National.
</P>
<P>
   The final score of the game would be 69-66 in double overtime.
There would be 1,800 yards of total offense and the game would last
five hours, long enough for Keith Jackson to retire and then
unretire. ...
</P>
<P>
   I could not, however, support a Raiders-Rams Super Bowl. And the
way the 1999 season is going, it's not an entirely dismissable
notion.
</P>
<P>
   The topsy-tursy season has put life into several division races
that seemed pre-ordained during the preseason. Thanks to the sudden
mortality of the Broncos and Jets, every AFC team outside Ohio
seemingly has a shot. And while the NFC Central is a monster, with
Green Bay, Minnesota and Tampa Bay solid, Detroit surprising and
the Bears improved, they could easily knock each other silly before
the playoffs. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles have a very good chance of becoming the
first team to go winless since the 1976 Tampa Bay Buccaneers went
0-14. The 1982 Baltimore Colts were also winless, but with an
asterisk: They went 0-8-1 during the strike-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a pair of games against the struggling New York
Giants, the pivotal game on the Eagle schedule is an October date
at Chicago. Cleveland is in the hunt for anti-perfection, too, but
two games against Cincinnati could spoil things. ...
</P>
<P>
   This week's official ranking of soon-to-be fired NFL coaches: 1,
Bruce Coslet, Cincinnati (unanimous); 2, Jim Fassel, N.Y. Giants;
3, Andy Reid, Philadelphia. Honorable mention: Dennis Green,
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   This week's official one-man Heisman poll: 1, Stanford wide
receiver Troy Walters. 2, Florida State wide receiver Peter
Warrick. 3, Purdue quarterback Drew Brees. 4, Georgia Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton. Great prices can be found on Great (Ron)
Dayne t-shirts at the Wisconsin campus bookstore. ...
</P>
<P>
   Gazillionaire Marvin Davis wanted to buy an NFL expansion in Los
Angeles for his two sons. Now he'll just have to buy them Nintendo
like everyone else. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
