<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BAGGARLY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSECLEANING HAS JUST BEGUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Remember that enchanted broom in ``Fantasia?'' The one
that danced magically across the castle floor?
</P>
<P>
   Disney had better get it out of storage. The Angels'
housecleaning will need all the help it can get.
</P>
<P>
   It officially began Friday, when vice president and general
manager Bill Bavasi announced his resignation in a tearless and
emotionally stunted news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The level-headed Bavasi did not break down during the 30-minute
session in the press dining room. But his departure signals that
almost everything else colored periwinkle will this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi was the final shield, the final protector for a season
gone horribly awry and a sniping, back-biting clubhouse that only
further corroded it.
</P>
<P>
   With Bavasi gone, this team stands to be ripped apart _ if you
can call this season's collection of players a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing missing on this amalgamation of players,'' club
president Tony Tavares said, ``is what it means to play as a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tavares said it became clear during a lunch meeting Thursday
that he and Bavasi were in conflict as to the team's future
approach. Tavares described it as being ``on different planes.''
Bavasi said it was ``something between Tony and I.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither would specify on the nature of that insurmountable
fracture. But it was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Tavares wants to take the wrecking ball and start over. Bavasi
wants to keep the team's core together.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi worked five years to sign those players, and nine more
before that as farm director developing them.
</P>
<P>
   Gary DiSarcina, Garret Anderson, Jim Edmonds, Tim Salmon, Troy
Percival, Chuck Finley _ they were more than Bavasi's home-grown
signings. They were members of his extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi remained committed to his core to the end. The same
caustic, bickering bunch that has caused this once-blooming season
to become a foul cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players ... are special to me,'' Bavasi said, stopping for
the only time to compose himself and clenching his jaw to hold back
tears.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the 1995 team, whose September collapse made the '69
Cubs look like a slip on a banana peel. He defended the current
bunch of malcontents, citing injuries as their downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of faith in the players we have here,'' Bavasi
said. ``This year, a few guys underperformed. Having a bad season
is not a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Given another chance, Bavasi said he felt this year's team could
contend next season.
</P>
<P>
   Add a starting pitcher or two and Bavasi might be right. But
that postulation clearly will not be tested. Key personnel will be
gone, swept out the door like so much rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Tavares hasn't made the personal investment in the current core
that Bavasi has. And after seeing the way the team responded to an
adversity-filled season, Tavares is fuming.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fired public shots at each other to the point where
then-manager Terry Collins couldn't walk through the clubhouse,
fearing he would be caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   When Collins resigned 28 days ago, Tavares made no effort to
hide his outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Angels' 16-10 record since Collins' departure _ their
first winning September since 1991 _ hasn't cooled Tavares' anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is shocking what went on here,'' Tavares said Friday. ``I
am disgusted. Revolted.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Tavares would go down to the clubhouse and discuss
Friday's move with players, he responded: ``What useful purpose
would that serve?''
</P>
<P>
   So Tavares will have his way. The edifice will be razed. The
demotion of the team's architect is a clear enough signal.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels aren't two days away from the offseason. They're two
days away from Hurricane Tony. And even the longest-tenured players
are at high risk of being uprooted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
