<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WISHING AND HOPING FOR METS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robin Ventura slammed a game-winning hit in the 11th
inning Friday night and Mets fans went wild. But all you needed to
see to understand the intensity of the Mets' madcap chase for a
playoff berth was the scene inside the Mets' clubhouse 15 minutes
after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   While the stars of the Mets' victory answered questions before
circles of cameras and microphones, pens and pads _ John Olerud
over here, Ventura at a stall over there, Mike Piazza across the
room _ a cluster of other players were riveted to television sets.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Mets had learned that Los Angeles had beaten
Houston, and now the Milwaukee Brewers were tracking down the
Cincinnati Reds, moving into the bottom of the ninth inning tied at
3-3. When a Milwaukee batter reached base, the players cheered;
when the Brewers put men on first and third, the Mets roared; they
groaned when the inning ended still tied.
</P>
<P>
   When the Brewers won an inning later, the clubhouse exploded. In
72 hours the Mets had seen their hopes dashed to pieces by Atlanta,
then picked up and at least partly reassembled by Los Angeles and
Milwaukee. Kenny Rogers, who pitched 7 1-3 innings Friday night,
said it was comforting to know that Houston and Cincinnati were
feeling the heat the Mets have felt for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are tough games _ every pitch, every strike, is
important,'' Rogers said. ``There really is no margin of error.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Rogers and outfielder Darryl Hamilton made
the drive from Manhattan to Shea Stadium. Since coming to the Mets
in trades _ Hamilton from Colorado, Rogers from Oakland _ the two
new Mets settled in the same Manhattan apartment building and have
ridden to the ballpark together. At first the conversations were
light and general _ Rogers talked about hitters, Hamilton about
pitchers. When the Mets began gaining ground on Atlanta in what
seems like ages ago, they talked division. The last few days the
conversations have been mutual therapy sessions on handling the
immense pressure of a postseason berth nearly gained and then
nearly lost, and now one that hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every day we're talking about must-win games,''
Rogers said. ``This was a big win. Now tomorrow is a must win.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets' season boils down to wishing and hoping; it comes
down to a bushel of ``what ifs'' and one of the most awful laments
of human existence: woulda, coulda, shoulda. The Mets have to play
the hoping and wishing game. Hoping that Los Angeles and Milwaukee
will go as hard at Cincinnati and Houston as Philadelphia came at
the Mets last week and Pittsburgh came at them Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're facing the same obstacles that we faced last week,''
Hamilton said. ``They're looking at it like: `It's right there for
us, all we got to do is go out and win.' That sounds so simple, but
really, it's not. I don't expect Milwaukee, and I really don't
expect the Dodgers to sit there and look at the celebration. You
hate being in a position like that, but that's the position we're
in.''
</P>
<P>
   So many of the Mets' problems during their recent slump revolved
around the fact that the Mets went from executing the plays to
hoping that someone would execute. Even as recently as Thursday,
when the Mets tied the game at 2-2, and then at 3-3, Hamilton felt
the Mets relied on faith and miracles, not consistent execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been our problem,'' Hamilton said. ``We've been
hoping for that big break, waiting for that big break to happen,
and it hasn't happened. When you wish for breaks, basically you're
hoping that the other team screws up. When you play good teams like
the Braves, it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, you go to the Mets' clubhouse not really
knowing what to expect, especially now that the team's fortunes
hang by such a slender thread _ pitch to pitch, inning to inning.
What will it be this weekend? Jubilation? Exhilaration? Depression?
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at the beginning of the Mets' final series of the
season, everything seemed normal. This team, with its back against
the wall, appeared loose as it prepared for yet another crucial
series, this time with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he thought that in the last two weeks there was a
collision of wills on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who were here last year were hoping it wasn't going
to happen again,'' Hamilton said. ``The guys brought in for this
year were saying it's not going to happen again. All of a sudden
it's happening and we're wondering, `What are we going to do
now?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy. Hope. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
