<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a !dlim!     10-02 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 !dlim! 
!jump1! MODESTI !jump2!!dlim!!jfrom1! MODESTI !jfrom2!!dlim!!pcred! 
Don Ryan/Associated Press !off! 
!capt! Casey Martin needed to take on the PGA in court last May in
order to play golf, and he has been nothing but a professional
since. !dtpost!!dlim!!head!Golf's 
grand 
illusion!dlim!!shead!Quietly, Martin 
has made his point!dlim!!head!Martin just another golfer!dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; MORENO VALLEY _ On the driving range at Moreno Valley
Ranch Golf Club Friday morning, Casey Martin was chatting with a
fellow Nike Tour pro about playing with pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wear contact lenses?'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' said the blond young man at the next tee.
</P>
<P>
   They were talking about how sunny and windy it's been the past
two days in the dusty hills of Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' Martin said. ``By the end of the day, you want to rip
your eyes out.''
</P>
<P>
   See, he's not much different from everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half after Martin, 27, became a legal !ital!cause
celebre!off!, the strange thing about watching the man with the
painfully withered right leg pursue a PGA career in a golf cart is
how normal it all seems.
</P>
<P>
   The cart he drives in the Nike Tour's Inland Empire Open this
week does not come equipped with a hammock and wet bar. It carries
a plastic water bottle, a scorecard and a stumpy little pencil.
There's a crumpled napkin in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The cart does not allow him to speed ahead of his pedestrian
partners and take extra minutes pondering his next stroke. Nor does
it lag behind and hold everybody up. Martin chugs along at a
walking pace.
</P>
<P>
   The cart is not used as an easy chair between shots. Martin
stands and banters with rivals about the slow players in front of
them or the foibles of pro-am partners. He helps to look for an
opponent's lost ball.
</P>
<P>
   Martin hasn't caused golf's Triple-A tour to be overrun with
adoring throngs or crowds of protesters. His group's gallery Friday
never grew larger than 20.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, despite some people's fears in February 1998 when
the former Stanford teammate of Tiger Woods won a court ruling over
the PGA Tour, granting him clearance to ride in tournaments, none
of his fellow pros has concocted a congenital condition in a bid
for the advantage the cart supposedly gives Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Martin is neither tearing it up nor embarrassing
himself on the Nike Tour. He hasn't won a tournament in 1999, but
he's 14th on the money list with $101,527.
</P>
<P>
   This is the guy who was going to turn golf upside down?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like that big a deal,'' Martin said with a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Which has been his point all along.
</P>
<P>
   I got my first in-person glimpse of Martin in action as he shot
a 68 in the second round here to move to 7-under par, tied for 12th
and six strokes off Patrick Lee's lead. Watching him changed my
perception of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Burke, a PGA and Nike tour veteran from Coto de Caza,
played with Martin for the first time Friday. The experience
changed Burke's perception too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit different playing with Casey,'' Burke said,
and then he smiled. ``Because he's nice. Do I envy him sometimes on
a (hot) day like this? Yeah. Does it get in the way? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first, hair-trigger reaction (to the controversy) was, `You
joined the tour, you follow the rules.' (Now he thinks) as a human
being, `Should guys who have injuries, or life issues like Casey
has, not be allowed to play?' ``We need more great stories (in
golf).''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a congenital problem with circulation in the lower
leg; it might eventually require amputation. Other players have bad
knees or temporary injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Burke would have the PGA Tour take up cart requests by players
like them on a case-by-case basis, though he fears that would
result in different rules for different people, depending on their
value to the tour marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA Tour apparently isn't interested in such a
common-sense approach to the issues raised when Martin won the
famous court victory in his native Oregon under the federal
Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour is appealing the ruling. A decision by the Court of
Appeals for the Ninth Circuit is due in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   That could hit Martin with a cruel blow, barring him from PGA
Tour competition even if he qualifies by remaining in the top 15 in
Nike Tour earnings after the Oct. 21-24 season finale in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if he's just one of the guys. His crowds, though
small by Tiger standards, are bigger than anybody else's on this
Tin Cup circuit where gallery ropes are necessary only at the tees
and greens. His sponsor is a major insurance company, something few
at this level can claim.
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't beg autographs from Mike Grob and Ashley Chinner.
They do pester Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tuesday press conferences are no longer needed. And last
year's public frenzy, Martin said, sitting in the cart at the end
of a relatively pain-free day on the course, ``has died down.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin is doing this the right way. He passes up the
sponsor-granted berths in PGA Tour events that his unique fame
could bring. If he makes the big tour, he'll do it by earning his
way, by finishing the Nike season strong.
</P>
<P>
   Golf for Casey Martin these days is a test of heart and mind,
not much different from everyone else. &QL; 
!hair! &QL; 
!ital!Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a
week. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &UR; !dlim! &LR; NIKE TOUR EVENT
