<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FOOD-GIVEAWAY-LADN     10-02 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GIVEAWAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD GIVEAWAY BY GRAMMY-WINNING GOSPEL SINGERS IS LABOR OF LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Food for body and soul was on the menu at the
fourth annual Help Heal our Streets block party.
</P>
<P>
   Help Heal Our Streets, a community outreach arm of the New
Christ Memorial Church in Pacoima, is distributing 40 tons of food
to needy in the Pacoima area of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley.
But, as they do every year, organizers are making sure the giveaway
is only a portion of a larger event _ a two-day block party
designed to entertain, inspire and unite an entire community. On
Friday, organizers estimate that 2,000 to 3,000 people came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful. A lot of churches don't participate in
the community, but this one does,'' said Karen Thomas, who came to
the event for her mother, Pacoima resident Pearline Thomas.
Pearline Thomas went last year but is sick in the hospital this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have fallen on hard times one way or another,'' said
Thomas, visiting from Washington, D.C., and getting her sacks
loaded with Hi-C juice, Campbell's soup, onions, and dry beans and
rice doled from 100-pound sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in this society who care about others,'' said
Sandra Crouch, co-pastor with her brother, Andrae, of the New
Christ Memorial Church. Both are San Fernando Valley natives and
Grammy Award-winning gospel singers.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch said the volunteers at her church feel it's important to
go outside its four walls to help those in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want you to know somebody loves you, and that somebody is
God,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch said an essential part of the gathering is the sense of
togetherness it tries to foster in the ethnically diverse area _ a
message Jennifer Corley, 24, said was one of several things that
attracted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music, to hear the Gospel Word and all the free food, and
to see the community come together, all races,'' Corley said.
``Help Heal Our Streets _ I think that's really neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday and again today, the block party will feature carnival
rides, face-painting for children, magic shows, fire eaters,
professional wrestling matches and craft booths. In addition,
dancers will perform in Indian, African and hip-hop styles, while
musicians ranging from country and western to mariachi and jazz
will play. The Crouches themselves will perform at 9 p.m. tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really good for the community. And it will really
help me personally,'' said Nancy Misfeldt, 43, the single mother of
three teen-agers, waiting in the food distribution line.
</P>
<P>
   The block party has its origins in the aftermath of the
Northridge Earthquake. Crouch said church members saw people in
long lines at social services offices and handed out tuna and
peanut butter sandwiches to them. They also distributed water to
apartment buildings that had none.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with pallets full of nonperishable food donated by the
international relief agencies Feed the Children of Oklahoma City
and the Children's Hunger Fund of Los Angeles, the church hopes to
help about 10,000 people, Crouch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody looks at anybody like, Who are you? We don't say, let
me see your ID,'' she said. ``I imagine that if people stand in a
line three blocks long, they need the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Chatman Edwards, spokeswoman for Help Heal Our Streets,
added that people don't often speak up even if they're going
without.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because someone looks like they're working, they look
like they're OK _ they may have nothing at home in the
refrigerator,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said she found herself in that situation 20 years ago
when she was a single parent struggling to raise her 7-year-old son
and her salary as a bank employee was barely enough to cover
necessities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to bed not eating sometimes, so my son could
have something to eat,'' she said. ``I wish there had been
something like this then.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
