<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4360 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     10-02 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RALLY TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Their leaders have fallen, and now all that's left
for the 1999 Angels is to play their final series against the team
that is sitting atop the A.L. West, a place the Angels had hoped
and expected to be.
</P>
<P>
   In what the schedule-makers foresaw as a season-ending division
showdown between the Texas Rangers and Angels has instead turned
into a sidelight thanks to general manager Bill Bavasi's
resignation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with Terry Collins' resignation as manager Sept. 3,
Bavasi's resignation and re-assignment in the front office
essentially has left the Angels players alone in their sea of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Angels rallied from a five-run deficit to
beat the Rangers, 7-6, on rookie Jeff DaVanon's ninth-inning home
run Friday night before 25,515 at Edison Field. Never mind that
they are in the midst of their first winning September since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened on the field the past four weeks has little
meaning compared to the transformation the club is undergoing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Rangers have something to play for -- the American
League's best record. With the Indians losing Friday, the Rangers
had a chance to cut the Indians' lead to one game. And they got off
to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez, one of the leading candidates to win the A.L.
MVP, singled in the first inning, stole second (No. 25) and scored
on a single by Rafael Palmeiro. Rodriguez was at it again in the
third inning, hitting a solo homer (No. 35) to give the Rangers a
2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With 35 homers, Rodriguez set an American League record for home
runs in a season by a catcher, breaking Terry Steinbach's mark of
34 set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers used the longball again in the fourth inning,
getting a three-run homer by one of their most unlikely sources.
Tom Goodwin hit his third homer of the season with Lee Stevens and
Royce Clayton on base to put Texas in front, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began their rally in the bottom of the fourth,
getting an RBI single from Mo Vaughn and a two-run homer from Troy
Glaus (No. 29). Vaughn now has 107 RBIs, tying him for sixth best
on the Angels' single-season all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers knocked Angels starter Ramon Ortiz out of the game
in the seventh after Ortiz walked Goodwin and gave up a single to
Scarborough Green. Green scored later in the inning on a wild pitch
by reliever Mike Holtz, the Rangers going up, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, in his final start of the season, went six-plus inning
and allowed six runs and eight hits.
</P>
<P>
   Down three going into the eighth, the Angels benefitted from an
error by third baseman Todd Zeile. After a walk to Vaughn, Tim
Salmon double home one run and Glaus singled home two more to tie
the game at 6.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan entered the game in the ninth and DaVanon, who got
his first major league hit earlier in the game (single), homered
over the center-field fence to win it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
