<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran, Iran) _ Iran's supreme religious leader
moves decisively to head off a fresh confrontation with the
country's reformist president, instructing hardline Muslim clerics
and their loyalists in the country's police not to ``take matters
into their own hands'' in a new and potentially explosive dispute
involving Tehran university students. By John F. Burns. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHIS (Rampur, India) _ The political and personal soap
opera of Sonia Gandhi and Maneka Gandhi: Sonia is the aloof woman
who now wants to run the country. Maneka is the ``other
daughter-in-law,'' and oh, how the irony grates on her. She has
been in politics for 20 years, Sonia for two. She is the widow of
Sanjay, who was his mother's right-hand man. Sonia's husband was
Rajiv, an airline pilot disinclined to governance. Sonia is the
leader of the venerable Congress Party; Maneka, the cabinet
minister for welfare. From 1974 to 1982, the two daughters-in-law
lived under the same roof. ``They hated each other's guts from the
word go,'' said the writer Khushwant Singh. By Barry Bearak. 1,900
words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE (Seoul) _ Interviews with relatives of victims of
the reported massacre of Korean civilians by U.S. troops in the
Korean War. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUN-COMPANIES (Undated) _ Leading gun manufacturers react to the
growing pressure from lawsuits by cities across the nation. At
issue is gun safety and reducing the flow of guns to criminals. By
Fox Butterfield. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEWYEAR-VACANCIES (New York) _ Despite everything you may
have heard about millennium madness, out-of-towners have not booked
every overpriced hotel room in the city for New Year's Eve. They
have not snapped up every $3,000 seat in the Rainbow Room,
purchased every $1,000 ticket to every ``gala'' event, hired every
limousine _ or even every baby sitter. By Leslie Eaton. 1,700
words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-EDUC-ASSESS (Undated) _ The last time American governors
met to discuss what to do about education in America, they didn't
want to talk about what to do about students who aren't doing well.
Now the governors realize that just imposing standards is not
enough. A news analysis by Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-VOICES (Washington) _ Following the Census report on
income and poverty, we talk to people who might feel left behind as
a million others rise above the poverty level. And even for the
latter group, are things any better? By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOYS-R-US (Undated) _ Last fall, shoppers at Toys ``R'' Us,
armed with holiday wish lists, often left the chain's cavernous
stores frustrated and empty-handed, and the company felt the pain
acutely in its bottom line. This year, as the company heads into
the crucial Christmas season, it is trying mightily to do things
differently. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphics
clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No staff-written editorial columns for Saturday's New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS-BIOGRAPHY (Undated) _ In ``Dutch,'' a biography of Ronald
Reagan, Edmund Morris has produced a book that is anything but
scholarly or substantial. He has produced a bizarre, irresponsible
and monstrously self-absorbed book _ a Ragtime-esque ``memoir''
featuring a self-annotating narrator out of a Philip Roth novel and
childlike hero out of ``Being There.'' A Critic's Notebook by
Michiko Kakutani. 2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADVISORY: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ANATOMY-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ New theories of how
architecture mimics human anatomy. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-WORK (Undated) _ A feature on ``The Oxford Book of
Work.'' By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MARRIAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``A Rather English
Marriage.'' Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
