<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-HMOS-DOWN-LADN     10-02 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-DOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO STOCKS HURT BY LAWSUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of area health maintenance organizations
closed lower Friday, as some of the country's most prominent
lawyers confirmed they are preparing class-action lawsuits against
the nation's largest HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Following nearly double-digit percentage losses Thursday, shares
of WellPoint Health Networks fell 37.5 cents to close at $56.625
while shares of Foundation Health Systems lost 6.25 cents to close
at $9.375.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sellers, an attorney with Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP;
Toll in Washington, said he was ``in the process of developing a
class-action lawsuit against one of the nation's largest HMOs
alleging fraud.'' He said he expects the lawsuit to be filed next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers wouldn't name the company, but said the lawsuit would
allege the HMO ``is willfully misrepresenting the benefits it
provides patients in an effort to maximize profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the attorneys participating in drafting the various
lawsuits is Richard Scruggs of Pascagoula, Miss., who helped
produce tobacco settlements nationwide that totaled $246 billion;
and Sellers' co-counsel David Boies, who recently concluded the
U.S. Department of Justice's antitrust lawsuit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   David Olson, senior vice president of investor relations with
Foundation Health Systems Inc., described the lawsuits as
``absurd,'' saying, ``Any action is truly and completely without
merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our role is to be certain that patients get all the health
care they need. That is our duty to them,'' said Olson.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint Health Networks spokesman Larry Bryant said the
company had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suits are grossly inappropriate,'' added Walter Zelman,
president of the California Association of HMOs Inc. in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers said the suits won't seek to dismantle managed care.
``We want people in HMOs to get the information they need,'' he
said, to get proper care.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Chockley, president of the Washington-based National
Institute for Health Care Management, said that if a lawsuit
forcing more health care were successful, the lawsuits could be
very harmful to the managed care industry nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to drive up health care costs, which will lead to
more people losing their insurance,'' said Chockley. In California,
an estimated 7 million people are without health care, which
continues to grow by approximately 50,000 people each month, said
Zelman.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of WellPoint and FHS dropped sharply Thursday on the
first report of the lawsuits. WellPoint fell $6.1875 to $57; FHS
dropped $1.0625 to $9.4375.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint shares fell 8.9 percent at their low Friday, before
rallying. FHS shares were down 9.9 percent at their low point.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
