<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      10-02 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FACES TESTS OF AUTHORITY ON TOBACCO, PRIVACY ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 3) 
(Eds.: Also see: Scotus-docket) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton hopes the Supreme Court this term
will grant him the authority to regulate tobacco and to prevent
states from selling personal information gleaned from driver's
license applications.
</P>
<P>
   But the odds are against Clinton as the high court, under Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist, has reined in federal power in recent
years. The conservative court, in a series of 5-4 decisions, has
interpreted narrowly the authority the Constitution gives the
president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a major test of the president's authority, one that pits
Clinton against Big Tobacco, the justices will consider whether the
federal government can regulate cigarettes as a drug.
</P>
<P>
   Washington business attorney Roy Englert Jr., in explaining what
is at stake for Clinton and the tobacco industry, called the
Supreme Court case ``a battle royale pitched at the high levels.''
A presidential victory would create a ``dramatic vista of powers''
for the federal government in its effort to deter cigarette
smoking, particularly by teen-agers, Englert said.
</P>
<P>
   States have taken the lead in regulating cigarette sales to
minors, but Clinton has made tobacco control a major agenda item of
the last two years of his presidency, angering the industry.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case, FDA vs. Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
is the validity of strict regulations Clinton's Food and Drug
Administration has imposed on the sale of cigarettes and smokeless
tobacco to children.
</P>
<P>
   The well-heeled tobacco companies and their retailers have
successfully argued so far that FDA lacks the statutory authority
to regulate their products.
</P>
<P>
   In support of Clinton, Texas has joined 38 other states in
urging the justices to rule in favor of FDA's regulatory authority.
The states argue that carcinogenic tobacco products have imposed
enormous health costs on the nation and should be subject to
federal as well as state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, a staunch opponent of the tobacco industry, settled a
lawsuit with cigarette companies in January 1998 for $17.6 billion
to recover its Medicaid costs for treating victims of
smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   FDA's controversial regulations prohibit the sale of cigarettes
and smokeless tobacco to anyone under age 18, require retailers to
check the identification of would-be tobacco buyers under age 27
and restrict vending-machine sales of cigarettes and smokeless
tobacco to adult-only locations.
</P>
<P>
   In another case addressing federal authority, Reno vs. Condon,
the justices will decide whether states must comply with a U.S. law
barring them from selling to companies and individuals the personal
information gleaned from driver's license applications.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the controversial law, the 1994 Driver's Privacy
Protection Act, after it was revealed that Rebecca Schaeffer's
killer, Robert John Bardo, was able in 1989 to track down the
California home address of the television actress through state
motor-vehicle records.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, in an argument that appears to
contradict recent Supreme Court precedent, says Congress'
constitutional authority to regulate interstate commerce allows the
federal government to bar states from selling information in their
possession. The administration also argues that the federal
restriction on the sale of information is necessary to protect
citizens' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, in its apparently contrary 5-4 ruling, said in
1997 that the U.S. government's ability to compel state officials
to act is limited. In that case, Printz vs. United States, the
court said Congress could not order state police to conduct federal
criminal background checks on people seeking to buy firearms.
</P>
<P>
   In the South Carolina case now before the justices, the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals cited the Printz decision in ruling the
federal restriction on the sale of driver's license information is
inconsistent ``with the system of dual sovereignty established by
the Constitution'' between the federal and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   Urging the justices to strike down the law, South Carolina says
the law unconstitutionally permits the federal government to
trample on the states' sovereign right to handle driver's license
information as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of driver's license records can be quite lucrative for
states, as New York in one recent year earned $17 million from
individuals and businesses who sought access to the information,
the federal government reported.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative majority that formed the Printz decision still
dominates the high court and asserted its control most recently on
June 23, the final day of last term.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of three decisions, the conservatives, led by
Rehnquist, struck down federal laws that sought to give individuals
and businesses the right to sue states for money damages. The
court, in its 5-4 rulings, held that the Constitution's 11th
Amendment generally grants states ``sovereign immunity'' from being
sued in federal and state courts.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases restricting federal authority over states,
Rehnquist was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M.
Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. Composing the minority
then, as they continue to do in cases of federal authority, were
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 0940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-DOCKET-HNS &LR;      10-02 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DOCKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE WORK, POLITICS, PORN AMONG ISSUES ON HIGH COURT DOCKET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 3) 
(Eds.: Also see: Scotus-Clinton) 
(Optional trim included) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court officially returns to work
Monday, prepared to consider cases that could change the methods
police use in high-crime neighborhoods, affect how people finance
candidates and college campus groups and limit the way officials
can regulate pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The court also will consider a case that could alter
governmental treatment of parochial-school students. The justices
are expected to render their decisions by July.
</P>
<P>
   But the nine-member court might have to start its 1999-2000 term
with only eight justices on the bench. Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg,
appointed by President Clinton in 1993, is recovering from
colon-cancer surgery and might miss the first two weeks of oral
arguments, which begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg could still participate in the court's decisions, many
of which might have broad significance for police, politicians,
pupils and pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in an Illinois case being closely watched by police
and civil rights groups, the high court will consider whether the
Constitution allows police in crime-ridden areas to stop and frisk
people solely because they run upon seeing officers.
</P>
<P>
   The case pits the interest of law enforcement against the Fourth
Amendment right of people to be free from unreasonable searches.
The Illinois Supreme Court, in a ruling against the police, said
Sam Wardlow's decision to run from Chicago officers did not give
them sufficient reason to suspect him of having committed a crime
or frisk him.
</P>
<P>
   The search uncovered a firearm and led to Wardlow's conviction
for unlawful gun possession and two-year prison sentence, which the
Illinois high court overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois' appeal to the Supreme Court, the state argues that
police in dangerous neighborhoods nationwide would be hamstrung in
their ability to fight crime if they were prohibited from chasing
people who bolt at the sight of officers. The Clinton
administration and the National Association of Police Organizations
have submitted briefs to the justices supporting Illinois'
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unprovoked flight from identifiable police officers is
ordinarily a sufficiently valid indicator of illicit conduct to
justify a brief investigatory stop,'' the administration wrote.
``Although such flight may be undertaken for innocent reasons, it
is not behavior in which innocent persons commonly engage _ and it
is far more likely to signal a consciousness of wrongdoing and a
fear of apprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wardlow counters that the constitutional rights of innocent
people would be jeopardized if police were allowed to search them
simply because they run. The NAACP Legal Defense &AMP; Educational Fund
agreed in a brief to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why an inner-city resident flees at the sight of a police
officer is at best ambiguous, and cannot by itself provide
sufficient indicia that the citizen is about to commit a crime,''
the group wrote. ``Many residents in such communities, and
particularly minority members, have in the past been harassed by
some law enforcement officers and continue to suffer from such
abuse. They possess a legitimate and reasonable fear of such
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Also before the high court is the issue of campaign finance,
which has dogged Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a Republican
presidential candidate. The justices will consider in a Missouri
case, Nixon vs. Shrink Missouri Government Political Action
Committee, whether a state law limiting campaign contributions for
state elections violates the First Amendment free-speech right of
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised more than $50 million, angering party and
Democratic opponents who say he is bought and paid for by special
interests. Supporters of limits on campaign donations say the
controversial restrictions are needed to prevent the appearance, if
not the reality, of political corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In the case before the court, Missouri is urging the justices to
overturn an 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling that struck
down the state's contribution limits as a violation of political
donors' right to free speech. Under the Missouri statute,
individuals may contribute at most $1,075 to candidates for
statewide office, $525 to candidates for state senate and $250 to
state representative candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which is urging the justices to
uphold the law, praised the campaign limits as a narrow,
constitutional way for states to ensure that elections are not
tainted by the corruption that can be associated with large
donations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Missouri political action committee, joined by longtime
foes the National Rifle Association and the American Civil
Liberties Union, is pressing the justices to rule the state's
restrictions unconstitutional. The committee says political
contributors ``speak'' through their financial support for
candidates and that laws that limit their contributions infringe on
their First Amendment right.
</P>
<P>
   In considering the case, the high court will revisit its
landmark 1976 decision in Buckley vs. Valeo in which the justices
upheld the constitutionality of a $1,000 limit for personal
contributions in federal campaigns. But the high court in recent
years has displayed unease with its 23-year-old ruling, increasing
speculation that the justices might scale back that decision and
permit greater, if not unlimited, campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In another First Amendment case, which could affect political
advocacy on college campuses, the justices will decide whether a
state university can require students to make financial
contributions toward groups with whom they disagree.
</P>
<P>
   In University of Wisconsin vs. Southworth, conservative law
students are challenging the school's mandatory $331.50 activity
fee, which helps support the gamut of campus organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with the
conservative students, saying the mandatory charge violates their
First Amendment right to refrain from financing groups that espouse
views they find repugnant, such as abortion- and gay-rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Wisconsin, in its appeal to the justices, argues that a
school should be a forum for diverse views and, to ensure
diversity, it must assess fees on students. Wisconsin adds that the
fee revenue is distributed to all campus groups, without regard to
the viewpoints they espouse.
</P>
<P>
   The law students, however, counter that if the justices
eventually rule for the school, ``a state university could force
Jewish students to fund a Christian evangelical newspaper (and)
force African-American students to fund neo-Nazi or Ku Klux Klan
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
All Texas state universities have mandatory student activity fees,
similar to Wisconsin's, that go toward funding campus organizations
without regard to the opinions they espouse. University of Houston
law Professor Michael A. Olivas said many campus voices would be
silenced if students were free to select the groups to which their
money goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (would) ruin student affairs as we know it,'' said Olivas,
an expert in higher-education law. ``Only those programs that have
a small band of zealots to organize funding will be able to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a free-speech case involving Playboy's television channel,
the justices will consider the constitutionality of a federal law
that requires cable operators either to block sexually explicit
channels from reaching nonsubscribers' homes or air its shows
between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m., when children likely would not be
watching.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, which lost in the U.S. District Court in
Delaware, argues that its controversial demand on cable companies
is necessary to prevent curious, impressionable children from
glimpsing lewd televised images even when the images are scrambled
for nonsubscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society has an interest independent of the choices made by
parents in seeing to it that children are not exposed to sexually
explicit materials,'' the Clinton administration wrote in its brief
to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   But Playboy Entertainment Group Inc., a media conglomerate that
provides sexually charged programming, counters that the broadcast
restriction violates the company's right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In a Louisiana case involving religious rights, the Supreme
Court will consider the constitutionality of a federal program that
helps states provide computer equipment to parochial as well as
public and private nonsectarian schools. The 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, which governs Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi, said
the program violates the First Amendment's prohibition on
governmental establishment of religion.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and parochial-school parents in
Jefferson Parish, La., are urging the high court in Mitchell vs.
Helms to rule the program constitutional, arguing that providing
computers to sectarian as well as secular schools does not favor
religion. The program simply ensures that no child is denied access
to computers at school, no matter where he or she attends classes,
the administration argues.
</P>
<P>
   But parish taxpayers challenging the program contend that the
federal government is violating the constitutional separation of
church and state by assisting religious institutions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
