<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Oct. 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-RECKONING (Santiago, Chile) _ The arrest of Gen. Augusto
Pinochet in London a year ago has opened a quiet and long-postponed
reckoning in Chile over its years of dictatorship that is finally
bringing former military officers to task for the deaths or
disappearances of thousands of political opponents. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-DOME (Greenwich, England) _ When the first stanchions
went up in 1997 for the mammoth cupola being erected here to mark
the millennium, the image that rose in the mind's eye of many
Britons had the pale coloration and oversized contours of a white
elephant. ``The millennium fiasco,'' The Evening Standard called
it. Now, though, the $1.2 billion Millennium Dome has developed a
more alluring fragrance, and become a beast that Britons seem eager
to climb aboard for their ride into the new century. By Warren
Hoge. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POOR (Jagdispur, India) _ When Laloo Yadav, the son of an
illiterate cowherd first came to power in the northern state of
Bihar in March 1990, he symbolized the rise of India's peasant
castes to the political heights _ and the hope that this new
generation of leaders would improve the lives of people long
dominated by the ruling upper castes. For various reasons, these
hopes have been dashed. By Celia A. Dugger. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian troops continued to move into
Chechnya on Saturday, spurring speculation that the Kremlin may be
planning a land offensive against the breakaway republic. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE-ASSESS (Tokyo) _ A string of embarrassingly
unanswered questions stretched long in the wake of Japan's worst
nuclear accident, one day after the crisis was officially declared
over. An analysis. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, East Timor) _ All across Dili _ and now in an
increasing number of towns around East Timor _ patrols like this
are constantly on the move as they attempt to intimidate and flush
out the irregular militias that have wreaked havoc here. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-JOSPIN (Paris) _ A political cartoon here last week
showed France's Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, getting
ready to meet a roomful of reporters. Behind a closed door, Jospin
_ sweating with effort _ was repeating to himself: ``I am from the
Left. I am from the Left. I am from the Left.'' Since he declared
two weeks ago that the Government ``could not be expected to
control the economy,'' Jospin has been under heavy pressure to take
back his words. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-RUSSIA-HOTLINE (Moscow) _ The United States and Russia,
updating the ``hot line'' concept between leaders of the world's
most heavily armed nuclear powers, opened a new state-of-the-art
video-conferencing center Saturday that will enable Russian and
American nuclear officials to see, as well as talk directly to each
other during a nuclear emergency. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-VOTE (Vienna, Austria) _ Can a politician so tanned that
he's known as the Hero of the Solarium, so narcissistic that he's
posed in everything from lederhosen to silver togas to near nudity,
and so controversial that his opponents openly call him a
crypto-Nazi actually beat this conservative country's red-and-black
coalition government until it's black-and-blue? That question will
be answered Sunday, when Austria's voters go to the polls. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PEACEKEEPING (United Nations) _ The U.N. strategy for
dealing with regional conflicts has undergone a significant shift,
as shown by its new involvement in Kosovo and East Timor, and a
third mission under consideration in Sierra Leone, U.N. officials
and other diplomats say. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-UNREST (Najaf, Iraq) _ This year tensions are again running
high in southern Iraq, whose overwhelmingly Shiite population has
long harbored deep resentment against a central government
dominated by minority Sunni Muslims. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLINICAL-TESTS (Undated) _ For years, Dr. Larry Norton tried
to conduct a medical study to determine, once and for all, whether
bone marrow transplants could really save the lives of women
desperately ill with breast cancer. His efforts _ and those of
dozens of other doctors _ were largely futile. Year after year, few
women were willing to participate in the clinical tests, which, to
be scientifically valid, required patients to be randomly assigned
to either the experimental treatment or standard chemotherapy. By
Gina Kolata and Kurt Eichenwald. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PEDIATRICS _ If there is a model for an effective way to
handle experimental procedures, it is the world of pediatric
cancer. In that arena, most doctors refuse to offer such treatments
outside clinical trials, insurance companies usually pick up the
tab and experimental procedures are tested quickly, before they
reach the marketplace. The result is that the procedures that work
are adopted widely; those that do not are quickly abandoned. By
Gina Kolata and Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MUSEUM-OPENING (New York) _ The Brooklyn Museum opens its
controversial show at 5 p.m. Saturday. Protests are slated for 11
a.m. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-ASTRODOME (Houston) _ Once promoted as the Eighth Wonder
of the World, the Astrodome is now a relic, as outdated as a
polyester leisure suit. On Sunday, the Astros will play their last
regular season game at the Astrodome before moving next season to a
new, state-of-the-art downtown ball park. Mammoth enough to contain
an 18-story building, the Dome was a monument to the Texan appetite
for big things and an emblem of a colorful era when men like the
stadium's eccentric creator, Judge Roy Hofheinz, reshaped Houston
and Texas through will and money. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   HEMP-BIRDSEED-FIGHT _ What do 40,000 pounds of birdseed have in
common with America's war on drugs? Nothing, says Jean Laprise, an
Ontario farmer who shipped the birdseed _ sterilized seeds
processed from industrial hemp _ to his American customers only to
have it seized when it crossed the United States-Canadian border.
Everything, say the U.S. government and its critics, but for
altogether different reasons. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-BATTLE-OF-SEXES (Bremerton, Wash.) _ Both fighters are
brashly predicting a knockout, which is nothing new in boxing. But
some of the other prebout banter is certainly unusual. After the
state of Washington declared that its gender-equity laws give it no
authority and indeed no reason to prevent the match, what is billed
by its promoters as the nation's first officially sanctioned bout
between a man and a woman was scheduled for Oct. 9 at Seattle's
Mercer Arena. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FRAUD (Washington) _ A look at fraud in federal programs
that are meant to feed poor children in day care homes. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Opening its new term on Monday, the
Supreme Court returns from a three-month recess to a docket that
places the Justices squarely in the midst of some of the country's
most passionate debates, from health care to campaign finance to
government aid to religious schools. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MILK-FEUD (Washington) _ For most families, the outcome
of a battle in Congress over milk prices will mean just a few cents
a week at the supermarket counter. But the livelihoods of tens of
thousands of dairy farmers are at stake, and the issue has provoked
a civil war between lawmakers from the East and those from the
Midwest. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-EXPO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ A report soon to be issued by
State Department investigators is critical of management and
spending at the 1998 World Exposition in Lisbon, Portugal, an event
whose American participation was overseen by Tony Coelho, now Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign chairman. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-SPORTS-POLITICS (Washington) _ For most of his nearly 40
years in the limelight, Bill Bradley, the former senator and
basketball star, regarded celebrity _ his own, in particular _ with
a gimlet eye. Once asked if too much fame inevitably ruined the
famous, he replied, ``Absolutely.'' But in his tightening race for
the Democratic presidential nomination, Bradley, 56, has decided to
exploit his Hall of Fame career to the hilt, recruiting a host of
basketball greats to help him raise money, grab attention and
remind a younger generation that this balding, slightly potbellied
candidate once had a velvety jump shot of his own. By James Dao and
Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-UNION-ENDORSE (Washington) _ In the first good news for his
campaign in some time, Vice President Al Gore received the support
of the second-largest local health-care workers union in the
country on Saturday. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-SPENDING (Washington) _ If the phenomenal pace of
political fund-raising continues, candidates for federal office
will spend about $3 billion in the 2000 campaigns, an increase of
about $800 million from four years earlier, according to
projections based on Federal Election Commission data. By Don Van
Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (New York) _ Even as she has quickened the pace of
her visits to the state, Hillary Rodham Clinton has yet to take the
lead in trying to frame the discussion of a Giuliani-Clinton race
for Senate. Her public remarks, while increasingly substantive,
have struck many New York Democratic strategists as cautious and
lawyerly. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   HATCH-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ In the last quarter-century, only
one senator, Bob Dole in 1996, has won his party's nomination for
president. But this has not been for lack of trying. This year, the
prominent senator running seemingly quixotically for president is
Orrin Hatch of Utah, a 65-year-old Republican, the chairman of the
Judiciary Committee. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIOGRAPHIES (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
never been a particularly fervent reader of books. But he is about
to become a favorite subject of them. Publishers are rushing out a
string of competing biographies of Bush, most of which are due in
stores even before the first Republican caucus or primary in late
January. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move by 11:30 a.m.
</P>
