<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-VISITATION-RIGHTS-REV     10-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISITATION-RIGHTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST VISITING: DEFINING WHO CAN SEE THE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea that grandparents have a right to see their
grandchildren, even after their son has died or divorced the
child's mother, has a lot of sentimental appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But legally, the question of which third parties should have
visitation rights, even against a parent's will, is not so simple.
</P>
<P>
   Should a man who helped raise his lover's son for all the years
he lived with her have the right to keep seeing the boy even after
the mother's new husband adopts him?
</P>
<P>
   Do a man's parents and siblings have the right to maintain a
relationship with his child, born by artificial insemination, after
the man and his mother-in-law shoot each other in a gunfight?
</P>
<P>
   These are among the real Washington state cases in which
visitation rights were awarded and appealed under a law adopted in
1972 opening such privileges not just to grandparents, but also to
unspecified third parties. Last week, in a case that is being
closely watched by family-law experts, the U.S. Supreme Court
agreed to consider the constitutionality of the Washington law.
</P>
<P>
   As society's sense of what makes a family has shifted, and the
possibilities of child-bearing and child-rearing become more fluid,
courts across the nation are being asked to balance parents' rights
to autonomy against the claims of others seeking an ongoing
connection with their children.
</P>
<P>
   The laws have expanded dramatically since the 1970s, when the
issue was framed around a Norman Rockwell-ish view of grandparents'
rights: Almost every state responded to grandparents' advocates
lobbying for laws that would protect their ability to visit their
grandchildren after their children's marriage ended through death
or divorce _ and, in some states, even when the married children
just wanted to keep the grandparents and grandchildren apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``While conservatives generally support parents' rights, this is
one area where they favored grandparents over parents, because of
lot of this came in the context of grandparents who thought their
hippie children were behaving badly and raising their children in a
disorderly way,'' said Carol Sanger, a family law professor at
Columbia University's law school.
</P>
<P>
   The movement to give third parties visitation rights was also
fed by a growing acceptance of the idea of the ``psychological
parent'' _ the adult, not necessarily a biological parent, to whom
the child is most securely attached.
</P>
<P>
   These days, there are all kinds of people clinging to
relationships with children they have loved and cared for, without
any biological tie: widowed stepparents who spent years raising a
spouse's child, gay parents who have split up with their former
partners, and former live-in lovers. There are also a handful of
cases brought by would-be adoptive parents who were forced to give
up babies they were raising when a biological parent reclaimed
them.
</P>
<P>
   The case the high court will hear grew out of the claims of Gary
and Jennifer Troxel, who won the right to spend one weekend each
month with their two young granddaughters after their son, Brad,
committed suicide in 1993. The girls' mother, Tommie Wynn, now
married to a man who has adopted the girls, did let the Troxels see
their grandchildren from time to time, but opposed court-ordered
visitation as a violation of her authority over the girls' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Her appeal was joined in the state Supreme Court with the two
other cases cited above.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with those cases, the state supreme court declared
the law unconstitutional, ruling that it violated parents' rights
to privacy and liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks they're acting in the best interests of the
child, but it really should be the parent who decides what's best
for the child, except where the court sees some harm to the child
if the contact is stopped with a strong psychological parent,''
said Catherine Wright Smith, the lawyer for two of the three
mothers who appealed the visitation orders to the Washington state
Supreme Court. ``But that's rare, and in the more common cases, I
don't think grandparents' desire for contact is a good enough legal
reason for the government to interfere with a parent's
child-rearing.''
</P>
<P>
   While most legal experts were shocked that the Supreme Court has
ventured into such a messy area of law and family life, many are
hoping that the case will set forth useful guidelines for how this
kind of dispute should be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that whatever the rule is, it ought to apply to
all families, that we shouldn't give the married, two-parent family
living with their children any protection from state intervention
that we wouldn't give to a single mother who is divorced, widowed,
or never married,'' said Nancy Polikoff, a family law professor at
American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional realities of third-party rights are complicated.
Many family law experts say the law should reflect, and respect,
the variety of nontraditional families that now raise many
children. But, they caution, there should also be some way to make
sure that children will not be dragged into unnecessary litigation,
torn between two sets of people they love.
</P>
<P>
   The politics are complicated, too. In California, when
gay-rights advocates sought legislation that would let gay and
lesbian parents win visitation of children they had helped raise,
by opening visitation rights to anyone who had lived with a child
for a significant time period, the effort was blocked by advocates
for battered women, who argued that such a law would force many
mothers who had fled abusive boyfriends to share their children
with those batterers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington law, giving any third party the right to seek
visitation, is too broad, and really does intrude on parents'
rights to raise their children as they want to,'' said Ms.
Polikoff. ``But I also think there has to be some way to recognize
the rights of people who function as parents, but who don't have
the legal status of parents. These are hard questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
