them.
</P>
<P>
   The case the high court will hear grew out of the claims of Gary
and Jennifer Troxel, who won the right to spend one weekend each
month with their two young granddaughters after their son, Brad,
committed suicide in 1993. The girls' mother, Tommie Wynn, now
married to a man who has adopted the girls, did let the Troxels see
their grandchildren from time to time, but opposed court-ordered
visitation as a violation of her authority over the girls' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Her appeal was joined in the state Supreme Court with the two
other cases cited above.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with those cases, the state supreme court declared
the law unconstitutional, ruling that it violated parents' rights
to privacy and liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks they're acting in the best interests of the
child, but it really should be the parent who decides what's best
for the child, except where the court sees some harm to the child
if the contact is stopped with a strong psychological parent,''
said Catherine Wright Smith, the lawyer for two of the three
mothers who appealed the visitation orders to the Washington state
Supreme Court. ``But that's rare, and in the more common cases, I
don't think grandparents' desire for contact is a good enough legal
reason for the government to interfere with a parent's
child-rearing.''
</P>
<P>
   While most legal experts were shocked that the Supreme Court has
ventured into such a messy area of law and family life, many are
hoping that the case will set forth useful guidelines for how this
kind of dispute should be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that whatever the rule is, it ought to apply to
all families, that we shouldn't give the married, two-parent family
living with their children any protection from state intervention
that we wouldn't give to a single mother who is divorced, widowed,
or never married,'' said Nancy Polikoff, a family law professor at
American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional realities of third-party rights are complicated.
Many family law experts say the law should reflect, and respect,
the variety of nontraditional families that now raise many
children. But, they caution, there should also be some way to make
sure that children will not be dragged into unnecessary litigation,
torn between two sets of people they love.
</P>
<P>
   The politics are complicated, too. In California, when
gay-rights advocates sought legislation that would let gay and
lesbian parents win visitation of children they had helped raise,
by opening visitation rights to anyone who had lived with a child
for a significant time period, the effort was blocked by advocates
for battered women, who argued that such a law would force many
mothers who had fled abusive boyfriends to share their children
with those batterers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington law, giving any third party the right to seek
visitation, is too broad, and really does intrude on parents'
rights to raise their children as they want to,'' said Ms.
Polikoff. ``But I also think there has to be some way to recognize
the rights of people who function as parents, but who don't have
the legal status of parents. These are hard questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
