<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-SPORTS-POLITI     10-02 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-SPORTS-POLITICS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE BRADLEY REACHES INTO HIS BASKETBALL PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES DAO and DON VAN NATTA Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most of his nearly 40 years in the limelight,
Bill Bradley, the former New Jersey senator and basketball star,
regarded celebrity _ his own, in particular _ with a gimlet eye.
Once asked if too much fame inevitably ruined the famous, he
replied, ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his tightening race for the Democratic presidential
nomination, Bradley, 56, has decided to exploit his Hall of Fame
career to the hilt, recruiting a host of basketball greats to help
him raise money and remind a younger generation that this balding,
slightly potbellied candidate once had a velvety jump shot of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill was not blessed as a player with phenomenal physical
skills,'' said Bill Walton, the former Portland Trailblazer who
recently introduced Bradley at a breakfast in La Jolla, Calif.,
that raised $150,000. ``He was a guy who could always outthink the
opposition. And that's why he will win.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 14, Bradley's campaign is planning to hold a huge
afternoon fund-raiser at Madison Square Garden, where Bradley
played for 10 years as a New York Knick, that will feature a raft
of basketball legends, including Jerry West, John Havlicek, Willis
Reed, Julius Erving, Bill Russell and Isiah Thomas. The event,
where the most generous contributors will most likely be invited to
shoot against the stars, could raise $1 million, Bradley's aides
say.
</P>
<P>
   The following month, the campaign is planning a similar
fund-raiser in Los Angeles, where it is counting on another cast of
Hall of Fame players to help garner a similar amount.
</P>
<P>
   Raising money is just part of the Bradley campaign's efforts to
use sports and sports stars to burnish his image, particularly
among voters who do not follow politics closely. And the
culminating event of that strategy may be recruiting the assistance
of Michael Jordan, who has quietly pledged to support Bradley,
possibly through appearances, fund raising or a commercial. Jordan
and his wife, Juanita, have each contributed $1,000 to Bradley's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is willing to help Bill,'' said Phil Jackson, a close
friend of Bradley's who coached Jordan to six world championships
with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to quantify how much professional athletes have
helped raise for Bradley, and much of his money comes from people
outside sports.
</P>
<P>
   But one Chicago event alone, called Hoopla, where contributors
were allowed to shoot against former All Stars, raised $350,000 in
July. Several former players and coaches, including Jackson, Billy
Cunningham of the Philadelphia 76ers, Calvin Hill of the Dallas
Cowboys, Dean Smith of the University of North Carolina and Dave
DeBusschere, a former Knicks teammate of Bradley's, have also been
featured speakers at events that raised several million dollars.
And many other athletes have contributed money or called friends
and business acquaintances on behalf of the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking to people on my own, unbeknownst to the
campaign,'' said Oscar Robertson, whom Bradley once called ``the
perfect player.'' Asked why he supported Bradley, Robertson said,
``He's an honorable person who handles himself well under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley fund-raising network now extends well beyond his
former basketball colleagues. Abe Pollin, owner of the Washington
Wizards basketball team, is one of his fund-raisers. So is John
Moores, chairman of the San Diego Padres baseball team. Moores is
part of a group that has raised more than $500,000 for Bradley in
the San Diego area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sports is all we were about, it wouldn't bring people
out,'' said Moores, who met Bradley through another Padres
executive, Larry Lucchino, who played basketball with Bradley at
Princeton. ``But it helps the story. It's another difficult area at
which he excelled.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the fund-raising race, Bradley has pulled slightly ahead of
his Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore, having raised $6.7
million in the last quarter to Gore's $6.5 million. Bradley, who
was called Dollar Bill by his Knicks teammates because of his
reputation for frugality, also has slightly more in the bank than
Gore because his campaign has spent less.
</P>
<P>
   But fund raising is just part of a broader effort by Bradley,
who played for the Knicks from 1968 through 1977, to weave
basketball into the daily fabric of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At rallies, his aides distribute autographed basketballs.
Bradley also recently published a book, ``Values of the Game,''
describing lessons that he learned playing basketball, like
courage, leadership and teamwork, which just happen to be central
themes of his campaign. And his stump speeches are peppered with
anecdotes, jokes and morality tales from his hardwood days.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To a group of union workers in Oakland, Calif., he recounted
serving as the Knicks representative to the players union and
negotiating to get longer beds for his tall teammates. At an event
in Harlem, he could point to a former Knick teammate, Dean
Meminger, in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   And to voters everywhere, he pokes fun at politicians' vanity by
describing how, after he helped the United States win an Olympic
gold medal in 1964, President Lyndon B. Johnson refused to be
photographed with him because Bradley, at 6-foot-5, was 2 inches
taller.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As with all politicians, Bradley uses such stories to help him
connect with audiences. But basketball serves a deeper purpose as
well. By talking about the game, Bradley, who represented New
Jersey for 18 years in the Senate, is also telling voters that he
had a career before politics and is not a Washington insider, as he
describes Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Often it works. ``I like Bradley,'' said Len Larson, 53, a
building contractor in Manchester, N.H. ``Maybe it's because he's a
basketball player. Or maybe it's because he's not hooked up with
the Clinton administration.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By telling stories about the stars he once played with and
against, Bradley is also able to remind people that he was a very
good player _ an All-American, Olympian and two-time NBA champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports plays a special role in our society,'' said Bob Teeter,
a Republican pollster. ``There are probably more people, if you
asked them, who would say they would rather be sports stars than
actors or other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls in New Hampshire and New York, which show Bradley
neck-and-neck with Gore, or even slightly ahead, also indicate that
Bradley is doing well among men, which pollsters and political
strategists say may be largely a reflection of their fond memories
of his talent and intense work ethic as a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides say that his stardom is not enough to get people
to give him their votes or their money. But they acknowledge that
it does help draw people to his rallies who might not normally be
interested in politics. So does having former NBA stars speak at
his fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know who all these old stars are,'' said Rick
Wright, Bradley's financial chairman. ``The legends really appeal
to all age groups.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of Bradley's using his sports connections as a
campaign weapon is that he has long been ambivalent about his
celebrity. Lionized as the nation's greatest collegiate player
while at Princeton and celebrated in an article in The New Yorker,
John McPhee's ``A Sense of Where You Are,'' when he was 21, Bradley
considered quitting basketball after college because he felt fans'
expectations had become hopelessly high.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two years at Oxford on a Rhodes Scholarship, he
signed a four-year contract with the Knicks worth $500,000, making
him the league's highest paid player. But he refused endorsements,
saying they demeaned and commercialized the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, he struggled at first, and felt the wrath of angry
fans, whose catcalls deeply hurt him. Years later, after getting
elected to the Senate in 1978, he again fretted that once-adoring
fans would expect his speeches to dazzle just because his jump shot
once did. ``When those magic moments don't materialize, they feel
double let down,'' Bradley wrote in his 1996 memoir, ``Time
Present, Time Past.''
</P>
<P>
   In his early years in the Senate, Bradley avoided playing in
congressional pickup games. But he understood the political value
of basketball and started playing with House members when he was
lobbying for his tax reform bill of 1986.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that he and others friends had to coax Bradley into
using basketball on this campaign. ``We kind of encouraged him that
it was a relating point to reach back to his past history,''
Jackson said. ``It is a way to relate to a generation that did not
see him play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who played with Bradley on the Knicks, is the new coach
of the Los Angeles Lakers, the Knicks' archrivals of the 1970s.
(One of Jackson's top players, Shaquille O'Neal, recently endorsed
Gore.)
</P>
<P>
   But before accepting the Los Angeles coaching job in June,
Jackson was asked by Bradley to manage his campaign in Iowa.
Jackson said he spent a few days in Des Moines on a road trip from
Chicago to California. ``I wanted to see what it would be like,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he found that it felt as if he were running for office
himself, a role he was not quite comfortable with. So he took the
Lakers job instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of regret it,'' Jackson now says. ``There won't be
another campaign like this, and there might be another similar
basketball opportunity along the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
