<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BUSH-FATHER&AMP;SON-REVIE     10-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FATHER&AMP;SON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FINDS HIS FUTURE INTERSECTING WITH HIS FATHER'S PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a recent banquet here of some formality, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, a man seldom inclined to sartorial musings,
recalled a conversation with his wife, Laura, about what he planned
to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush informed the hundreds of men and women he was addressing
that Mrs. Bush had begged him not to dust off a ratty outfit that
was crying out for replacement. But he had stood firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read my lips,'' he said he told her. ``No new tuxes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific line, but a curious one. On the one hand, it
took his father's infamously scuttled promise of ``no new taxes''
and turned it into a weightless joke. On the other, it brought to
mind the worst miscalculation of President George Bush's years in
office.
</P>
<P>
   As the younger Bush stakes his own claim to the White House,
both son and father still seem to be resolving _ or, just as often,
failing to resolve _ how to play this whole filial-parental thing.
And they continue to discover that the older Bush's history and the
younger Bush's destiny intersect in odd and unexpected ways.
</P>
<P>
   Last week provided several examples. On Tuesday, former
President Bush was on the ``Today'' show, and what he ended up
doing there was damage control over the assertions, in a new
biography of President Ronald Reagan, that Reagan and Bush, his
vice president, were not on the friendliest, most respectful terms.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer etiquette would call on Bush to quibble with this. But his
son's political ambitions absolutely demand a denial. In Republican
circles these days, Reaganism is a holy creed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, past and present collided again. Gov. Bush, in
Bakersfield, Calif., questioned whether ``personal vendettas''
might be at play in an apparent alliance between the conservative
commentator Pat Buchanan, who may seek the presidential nomination
of the Reform Party, and Ross Perot, that party's benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was alluding to the fact that in 1992, when his father lost
the White House, President Bush's efforts were hampered by both
Buchanan and Perot. Buchanan, who ran for the Republican
nomination, attacked President Bush viciously in the primaries, and
Perot, the Reform Party candidate, siphoned many votes away from
President Bush in the general election, which Bill Clinton won.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's pronouncement in Bakersfield reflected his
inconsistency and indecision about how and when to invoke Dad.
Previously, advisers had said that Gov. Bush was avoiding any
confrontation with Buchanan in part because he did not want to
sanction certain kinds of speculation about the motives behind his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he reacts too aggressively,'' said one adviser, before
Bakersfield, ``you're getting into that whole situation of: Are you
trying to right the wrongs done to your father?''
</P>
<P>
   What Bush often seems to be doing is burnishing his father's
legacy and recasting his father's record in terms that are always
flattering but occasionally disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Bush made his first major policy speech on the
military in September, he mentioned his own familiarity with the
sacrifices and heroism of the men who fought World War II. He was
alluding to his father's decorated stint as a fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Bush's memories were selective. As he criticized the
Clinton administration for spending too little on national defense,
he never acknowledged that President Bush had begun winnowing that
budget before Clinton arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gov. Bush had forgotten, or had not been duly reminded;
after all, the elder Bush has said he is not providing counsel to
his son's campaign, that the younger Bush is entirely his own man.
And yet, even though the central figures in Gov. Bush's campaign
are Texans with no connection to the elder Bush's presidency,
several of President Bush's former advisers have indeed risen anew
with the son.
</P>
<P>
   There may not be any new tuxes this time around. But there are a
few old suits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0798 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BUSH-FATHER&AMP;SON-REVIE     10-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FATHER&AMP;SON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FINDS HIS FUTURE INTERSECTING WITH HIS FATHER'S PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
