<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GOP-BUDGET-REVIEW-NYT     10-02 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUDGET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND OLD SPENDING PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In life's rich pageant, few spectacles are as
dizzying as watching Congress spend the public's treasure. The sums
are huge, the oratory windy, the techniques tricky as three-card
monte.
</P>
<P>
   As the old fiscal year ended and the new one began Friday,
Congress was playing a giant shell game, saying one thing, doing
another, and all the while juggling more than half a trillion
dollars, leaving a huge stack of spending bills undone and the
government running on three weeks of legislative life support.
</P>
<P>
   What is going on here is no carnival. There is a crossroads
coming between the old ways of Congress and a new way, a trail
still unblazed.
</P>
<P>
   Just as this dimming decade, the post-Cold War era, is defined
by what it is not, the Republicans running Congress keep defining
themselves by their opposites. Democrats tax and spend, they say;
we cut taxes and spending. But they cannot this year; the green
eyeshade of accountability doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have promised _ publicly, daily, fervently _ not
to finance the operations of the government by spending money out
of the Social Security trust fund. No Congress has done this since
1967.
</P>
<P>
   To try to keep this pledge, they have used every accounting
device in the book, and some previously unrecorded.
</P>
<P>
   More than $20 billion dollars, nearly twice the previous record,
is being drawn down from the ledger for fiscal 2001. A nearly equal
amount is simply being erased from the books by a device known as
``directed scorekeeping,'' which one respected federal budget
analyst, Stan Collender of the Fleishman-Hillard public relations
firm, defines as ``lying about the numbers.'' Venerable projects
like the decennial census ($4.5 billion), a home-heating assistance
program ($1.1 billion), agricultural aid ($8.7 billion at last
count), along with still-uncounted billions for defense, have been
deemed unforeseeable ``emergency spending'' _ meaning Congress can
pretend they do not really count against the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is subterfuge,'' said Rep. John Spratt of South Carolina,
ranking Democrat on the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more, much more, as the millennial fiscal year
2000 began. On the floor of the House, members of Congress almost
unanimously passed a nonbinding resolution _ a promise made with
fingers crossed _ pledging never again to spend a dime of the
Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, at that minute, their number-crunchers at the
Congressional Budget Office were calculating that they were in fact
spending $18 billion of the surplus, a number growing with every
closed-door conference.
</P>
<P>
   And at the very moment President Clinton was signing into law a
pay increase for members of Congress averaging $4,600 a year,
Republican strategists were figuring that the only way to avoid
spending the surplus was to delay a tax break for 20 million
Americans on the lower rungs of the economic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   None other than Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican standard-bearer, denounced the idea, saying, ``I don't
think they should balance their budget on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders figured that by delaying that tax
break, they could say with a straight face that they would be $400
million shy of dipping into the Social Security coffers. At the
same time, behind closed doors, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
was convincing them to add $500 million for an aircraft carrier to
be built at his home state's shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   Most ennobling of all was the speechifying in the well of the
House as Rep. Wally Herger, R-Calif., led the charge for the vote
resolving not to spend the Social Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is break the addiction that we have
had,'' he said, and sat back as Democrats ridiculed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gentleman from California ought to get the equivalent of
the Congressional Medal of Honor for being picked to drag this
mother out here,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash. Rep. Lloyd
Doggett, D-Texas, said the resolution ``gives hypocrisy a bad
name.'' Democratic Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said it was like
``saying we're going to quit drinking while we pour out a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed, 417-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was barely two years ago that Congress overwhelmingly passed
the Balanced Budget Act, which the president called a monument and
Lott hailed as ``the beginning of a new era of freedom.'' The act
helped balance the budget, all right, although the tax revenues
generated by a roaring economy were the key. They created what
would have been the first real surplus in general government funds
in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   For each of those 30 years that the government ran in the red,
Congress has used the money from Social Security revenues to make
up the difference. But now the spending limits, or caps, imposed by
the Balanced Budget Act have cut spending on domestic programs,
excluding the military, to their lowest level, expressed as a
percentage of the overall economy, since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   This relative penury in boom times proved intolerable for many
Republicans. They have drained the once-in-a-generation general
government surplus and are about to draw down the Social Security
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Democrats express shock and dismay at the
Republicans' spending practices, things were arguably worse in many
of the 40 years from 1955 through 1994, when Democrats controlled
congressional spending panels and became skilled at extracting
federal dollars for their own districts.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures on the Republican leaders to spend more money than
they have on hand continue. The Pentagon consumes half the money
they will spend this year, and what's left is not enough to divide
between members clamoring for money to distribute to constituents,
and popular programs like education, health care and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The path from the past that no one has charted is how to spend
money wisely in a coming era of surpluses, linking public policy to
public funds, instead of the present gathering at the federal
trough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
