<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0804 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-REAGAN-BIO-REVIEW-NYT     10-02 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-BIO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE CHARACTERS IN SEARCH OF A MEMOIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the Rev. Mason Weems wrote a book about a
president who chopped down his father's favorite young English
cherry tree: ``The sweet face of youth brightened with the
inexpressible charm of all-conquering truth, he bravely cried out,
`I can't tell a lie, Pa; you know I can't tell a lie. I did cut it
with my hatchet.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Run to my arms, you dearest boy,' cried his father in
transports. `Glad am I, George, that you killed my tree. Such an
act of heroism in my son is more worth than a thousand trees.'''
</P>
<P>
   So much for ``all-conquering truth.'' Parson Weems made up the
cherry tree story, and lots of others about Washington now found in
paintings, on postage stamps and in the popular imagination. But a
legend was born.
</P>
<P>
   Today, mythologizing is more difficult, as shown by last week's
publication of ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' (Random House).
Edmund Morris knew he would be laughed out of town if he tried to
spin tales of cherry trees, so he makes a more post-modern attempt
at spinning. He turns himself into a fictional character who runs
into Reagan over the years, throwing in other imaginary characters,
plus scenes in screenplay format.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said he invented a new kind of biography inspired by his
subject. He didn't meet Reagan in 1926, but can imagine doing so. A
lot of people who haven't read the book but can imagine reading it
have complained that too much of it is imagined. I myself can
imagine how it all came about.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)(Fade in: The oval office. A president, an
in-house historian, an old friend. Two notebooks. A jar of jelly
beans.)(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   RON: Let me tell you about the time I played football in 1924
... or was I in a movie?
</P>
<P>
   ED: Mr. President, no one could ever understand what it's like
to try to write about you. Maybe if I made up some characters _ one
who hates your guts, one who follows you around. You're like the
sum of people's projections. You don't exist without an audience.
</P>
<P>
   RON: You're kind of a character yourself, Ed. Have a jelly bean.
</P>
<P>
   JENNY LYN (to Ed): Maybe you're spending too much time with him.
</P>
<P>
   ED: What are you doing here?
</P>
<P>
   JENNY LYN: I put myself in. It's a new journalism technique,
inspired by you.
</P>
<P>
   RON: Jenny Lyn, would you like a jelly bean?
</P>
<P>
   JENNY LYN: Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   RON: Ed?
</P>
<P>
   ED: Mr. President, I don't want a jelly bean! I want a narrative
that coheres!
</P>
<P>
   JENNY LYN: Shh. Ed, you seem upset.
</P>
<P>
   ED: I think I'm going to have to invent a new genre to convey
what he's like. It's going to combine elements of academic writing,
personal memoir and B-movies. And it'll switch smoothly but
suddenly, without warning, just like he does.
</P>
<P>
   JENNY LYN: Don't worry, you'll do it. It'll be wild. I've seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   ED: How is that possible?
</P>
<P>
   RON: Anything is possible. You're the first presidential
in-house historian. Make it up.
</P>
<P>
   And so he did, even bursting into stretches of first-person
italics when necessary. Between the debunking of myths and the
magic of digital enhancement, it's almost impossible to idealize
legendary figures these days, but it's quite possible to hang out
with them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) When I used to encounter Ed, on the tarmac
boarding Air Force One, or on the White House porch, he had the air
of a man with a serious mission. Our friends would worry that he
was just writing another historical-gimmick thing like ``Forrest
Gump,'' or ``Zelig,'' or ``Dick,'' taking huge historic license,
trying to pass off fiction as nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   I lived across the street from Ed in Washington, and at that
time everyone I knew in D.C. was doing it.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what was odd about his little project. When he
told me the title I nearly fell over. He was mixing biography and
autobiography! A ``memoir''? I guess a memoir is nonfiction without
the responsibility. But isn't a memoir supposed to be stuff you
remember? How can a memoir just be conjured up?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I think Ed was up to something else. He was just
trying to make myths the only way they can be made in our ironic
times: by pretending another guy is narrating.
</P>
<P>
   And if an invented character remembers memories for you, is that
character accountable? It reminded me a little of something Ron
once said: ``Mistakes were made.''
</P>
<P>
   This was more like a mystical happening: ``Books were written.''
</P>
<P>
   Myths were made. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
