<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-VOTE-2TAKES(T     10-02 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-VOTE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA VOTE MAY PUT FAR-RIGHT PARTY IN THICK OF THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Can a politician so tanned that he's known as
the Hero of the Solarium, so narcissistic that he's posed in
everything from lederhosen to silver togas to near nudity, and so
controversial that his opponents openly call him a crypto-Nazi
actually beat this conservative country's red-and-black coalition
government until it's black-and-blue?
</P>
<P>
   That question will be answered Sunday, when Austria's voters
choose between the Social Democrats (the reds), the conservative
business-and-church-oriented People's Party (black), and the newly
powerful right-wing Freedom Party (color code: blue) led by Joerg
Haider. (The Green Party and the ``yellow'' Liberal Forum are not
expected to do well enough to tempt pundits with a ``traffic-light
government.'')
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters predict that the reds will hang on to their No. 1 spot
with about 35 percent of the vote, but that Haider's blues are
expected for the first time to outstrip the black column, 27
percent to 25 percent. If the People's Party slips to third place
for the first time since 1945, its leader says he will drop out of
the longstanding red-black coalition to rebuild his demoralized
forces. Color schemes aside, that leaves Haider _ whose party had a
mere 5 percent when he took it over in 1986 _ as a potential
kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The idea horrifies the Austrian political establishment. After
all, the reds and blacks only got together in their highly unusual
left-right coalition in 1986 in order to keep Haider from power.
And their partnership has lasted mostly on the shared perception
that it was necessary to keep things that way. Vienna's liberals,
who are prominent in the press and academia, also shudder at the
prospect of Haider gaining even more influence in Austrian
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The vision reverberates, too, beyond Austria's borders: Guenter
Grass, Germany's new Nobel laureate for literature, celebrated the
honor on Friday morning by giving the early morning weather
forecast on German state television. He predicted sunshine in the
south Sunday, and then directly urged Austrians _ many of whom
watch German television _ to vote against Haider, widely
characterized as the head of Europe's largest far-right party.
</P>
<P>
   The terms used to describe Haider would barely be utterable in
Germany: his parents' time in the Hitler Youth is repeatedly
brought up; his takeover of the Freedom Party and ousting of its
liberal wing is called a putsch, the corps of handsome young men
around him is likened to a Praetorian Guard or 1930s street thugs.
Dozens of protesters at a Haider rally Friday night chanted
``Nazis, out!''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Haider has not helped. In 1991, he snapped at a Socialist rival
in his home province of Carinthia: ``They had a sound employment
policy in the Third Reich, which is more than your government in
Vienna has managed,'' and was immediately accused of endorsing
slave labor and forced to resign as the province's governor, an
office he regained after a comeback in provincial elections last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Haider spoke to a reunion that included former Waffen
SS men, calling them ``decent people with character who stuck to
their belief through the strongest headwinds.'' The Museum of
Tolerance at the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles displays
Haider's picture in its Contemporary Demagogues section, alongside
the former Ugandan dictator Idi Amin, Louisiana's David Duke and
the French rightist Jean-Marie Le Pen.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But a Haider party leader, Peter Sichrovsky, who is Jewish,
bristles at Nazi cracks. ``It's a stupid comparison, and I don't
accept it,'' he said. ``I will accept any criticism of our
immigration policy, but I refuse dialogue with anyone comparing us
to mass murderers. The Green Party in Rome has an anti-Gypsy policy
and no one compares them to Mussolini.'' Haider, he said, has
visited Israel and took his daughters through Washington's
Holocaust Museum shortly after it opened.
</P>
<P>
   The party does want all immigration halted, but insists that
jobs, not skin color, is the issue. ``Our strongest supporter is
the Turkish guy who's been here 10 years cleaning floors and is
scared a guy from the ex-Yugoslavia will take his job for half the
money,'' Sichrovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The party also has ideas for which Americans know the roots: it
wants a 23 percent flat tax and calls its platform Contract With
Austria. But other platform planks are, in American terms, classic
tax-and-spend liberalism: Haider promises $400 a month to every
Austrian mother so she can stay home with her children. Workers
like him because he defends costly cradle-to-grave benefits against
cuts made by the current government in order to qualify for
Europe's single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's opponents say his books do not balance _ tax receipts
would sink to $30 billion from $40 billion while expenses soared, a
Social Democrat spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What is baffling is why a far-right party is having such success
now.
</P>
<P>
   Austria is not remotely in crisis; economically, it approaches
paradise. It has only 8 million people _ about as many as desperate
Zimbabwe _ but they produce enough to have a higher standard of
living than the Germans. Unemployment is 4.3 percent; inflation is
negligible. No one ever strikes. The spotless streets of Vienna and
Salzburg brim with culture, and women walk them safely at night.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, 10 percent of the population consists of
immigrants. Without them, the economy would fibrillate: Polish
carpenters build housing, Filipino nurses staff hospitals,
Hungarian nannies tend babies.
</P>
<P>
   So why do a quarter of all Austrians believe Haider's assertions
that the country is going to the dogs?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly in a nation that has Sigmund Freud, a native
son, on its equivalent of the $5 bill, there is no shortage of
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fatigue _ Austrians are complainers,'' said Hans Raucher,
a political columnist for the newspaper Der Standard. After 13
years of the same government, and almost 30 years under Socialist
chancellors, ``People are really fed up with the same faces in
power.''
</P>
<P>
   The reds have dominated Parliament for three decades, and Haider
plays on old resentment over the careful red/black control of daily
life. For decades, anyone seeking a civil service job, even as a
teacher, bank teller, postman, railway porter or street sweeper
usually had to first join one of the two governing parties.
</P>
<P>
   Austrians are also apprehensive. During the Cold War, this was a
neutral island in the Alps. Now, hard by the crisis in the
countries that were part of the larger Yugoslavia, it is debating
joining NATO and would be the doorsill for eastern European
countries if the European Union's door opens to them.
</P>
<P>
   Haider takes these jitters and weaves an earthquake, saying
child molesters are buying their way out of jail and foreigners
have turned the country into ``a center for international crime _
drug dealers, car thieves, pimps and bandits.'' His crime slogan:
``No mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperbole, even inflated to absurdity, does not backfire on him
as Hitlerism does. Opposing the entry into the European Union four
years ago, he said Austrians would be forced to pump their bracing
water to Spain and import lice-infested yogurt. The yogurt is still
good; and he still draws crowds. His railing against immigration
actually changed policy. The government slowed it to a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as he fans xenophobia, the ruling parties bicker and
run dull ads.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first black campaign blitz was a folk song book. ``This is
not still the country of the von Trapp singers,'' sneered a red
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Viktor Klima of the reds has said he will ``never,
never'' form a coalition with Haider, so his party is hoping the
black leader, Wolfgang Schuessel, will either change his mind or
even be ousted by someone less willing to give up ruling for
soul-searching. But Haider is still the one who makes every other
politician angry or nervous.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The only guy who speaks out, who wants to change anything, is
Haider,'' said Georg Hoffman-Ostenhof, a columnist for the Profil
weekly. ``And since he's so eclectic and voters are generally not
rational, they find him attractive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-KOREA-ATROCITIES-REVI     10-02 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ATROCITIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCIVIL WARS: NO PLACE FOR CIVILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ War, wrote Gen. Omar Bradley in his memoir, ``A
Soldier's Story,'' was ``a wretched debasement of all the thin
pretensions of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the thinnest pretensions is that civilians should be
spared the worst of war's horrors. In fact, modern war is too often
all about civilians, making it devilishly complicated to figure out
how to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Associated Press disclosed new evidence of the
deliberate killing of hundreds of Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers
and warplanes near the village of No Gun Ri at the start of the
Korean War in 1950. The report raised the uncomfortable question of
whether U.S. soldiers committed an atrocity against the very
civilians they had been sent to protect, just as they have been
shown to have done at My Lai in Vietnam in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a larger question too: At the end of the century of
total war, can the protection of civilians ever be more than a thin
pretension, even when protecting civilians is the declared war aim?
</P>
<P>
   Recent experience in the Balkans is not encouraging. When NATO
forces, led by the United States, intervened in Kosovo last spring,
it was with the declared intention of protecting ethnic Albanians
threatened with massacre by Serbs. But the allies did not go in on
the ground and stop killings and wanton destruction there; instead,
intent on keeping their own casualties down, they waged an air war
that continued for 78 days before the Serb forces pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   Bombing from 15,000 feet so that they would not be shot down,
allied pilots on April 14 killed Albanian refugees fleeing in a
convoy mixed in with Serbian armored vehicles. Consequently, to
avoid further risk of civilian casualties, pilots were ordered not
to target such vehicles when they were mixed up with civilian
traffic. And one result was that Serbian forces could continue
laying waste to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The hard fact, as Kosovo illustrated, is that however much the
saving of civilians may be an ultimate aim of a war, commanders are
loath to place higher value on protecting specific civilians than
on protecting their own soldiers or mission.
</P>
<P>
   In Bradley's war, World War II, little heed was paid to the
notion that civilians and combatants were distinct at all. The
Nazis and the Japanese set the pattern for this, but by the end of
the war the Allies sometimes followed suit. Concentration camps on
one side, and the bombings of Hiroshima, Hamburg and Dresden by the
other side, bear witness.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the discovery of the enormity of the Holocaust, the
victorious powers tried in the Nuremberg trials to make war more
humane, by banning the most unthinkable actions as crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the countries that wrote the verdicts at Nuremberg
still sometimes fall into the abyss, as was made clear in 1968 with
the massacre at My Lai of up to 500 Vietnamese civilians by U.S.
GIs. And even then, the commanders were reluctant to admit fault.
Lt. William Calley's superiors let him take the blame, and then he
served only a fraction of the life sentence he received for his
conviction of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In the Korean War, military historians have long known of
reports of atrocities committed against civilians by both sides,
and have known that the North Korean communists often used
civilians as cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a common experience to see a herd of refugees shuffle
toward an American position, then sweep aside at the last moment to
reveal the North Korean infantrymen sheltering among them,'' wrote
British journalist Max Hastings in a 1987 book, ``The Korean War.''
But Hastings also quoted witnesses who said U.S. F-86 fighters
sometimes deliberately strafed columns of civilians on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Did U.S. commanders give soldiers free rein to shoot civilians
indiscriminately? New evidence that they did was what prompted
Defense Secretary William Cohen last week to order a new year-long
review of the historical evidence of a massacre; for several years,
U.S. officials had said they had no such evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No refugees to cross the front line. Fire everyone trying to
cross lines,'' ordered the 1st Cavalry Division, whose units were
dug in near No Gun Ri at the end of July 1950, when ill-prepared
U.S. troops were reeling in retreat from the Communist onslaught
that had begun a month earlier. ``Use discretion in case of women
and children,'' read the order, one of several recovered by The AP
from military archives.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with that last order is that in the heat of battle,
``discretion'' can be the first civilized pretension shed by
panic-stricken troops. ``The sense of facing a merciless Asian
enemy caused many Americans to extend their fears and suspicions to
the entire people of Korea,'' Hastings wrote. ```The gooks' meant
not merely the communists, but all Koreans. Communist atrocities
provoked callousness in many Americans, fighting a desperate
struggle for survival, toward the Asians around them, creatures
from another planet whose language they could not understand, whose
customs bewildered them, whose country seemed most vividly
represented by the universal stench of human excrement manuring the
fields.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the same factors would combine to bring U.S. soldiers
to shoot old Vietnamese men and peasant women and children in the
ditches of My Lai.
</P>
<P>
   It was My Lai _ indeed, the whole Vietnam War _ that led
Americans to question the premise that had seemed unassailable
during World War II, that lifting the restraints on military force
can be justified if the ultimate end is to achieve good.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the war in the Persian Gulf in 1991 did the United
States and some of its allies again mobilize on a grand scale to
chase an aggressor, Saddam Hussein, out of an occupied country,
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   When they did, it was with a new, and not entirely clear, set of
attitudes toward warfare and the risks that an aggressive military
strategy poses for civilians. And here the paradox behind those new
values first became clear. When U.S. guided bombs killed scores of
civilians who had taken refuge in a command bunker in Baghdad, the
Americans began to lose their nerve. That was one factor when
President George Bush halted the war without sending allied troops
all the way in to remove Saddam; one result is that Americans are
still waging an air war of pinpricks against him.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kosovo war, Col. Edward Boyle, one of the air war
planners, summed up the choices left to the planners this way: ``It
was not a perfect world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But, then, war never is. Times change, but war is still hell, as
somebody else put it differently more than a century ago _ William
Tecumseh Sherman, who did not spare civilians on his march to the
sea. And they were his fellow Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-KOREA-ATROCITIES-REVI     10-02 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ATROCITIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCIVIL WARS: NO PLACE FOR CIVILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
