can be justified if the ultimate end is to achieve good.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the war in the Persian Gulf in 1991 did the United
States and some of its allies again mobilize on a grand scale to
chase an aggressor, Saddam Hussein, out of an occupied country,
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   When they did, it was with a new, and not entirely clear, set of
attitudes toward warfare and the risks that an aggressive military
strategy poses for civilians. And here the paradox behind those new
values first became clear. When U.S. guided bombs killed scores of
civilians who had taken refuge in a command bunker in Baghdad, the
Americans began to lose their nerve. That was one factor when
President George Bush halted the war without sending allied troops
all the way in to remove Saddam; one result is that Americans are
still waging an air war of pinpricks against him.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kosovo war, Col. Edward Boyle, one of the air war
planners, summed up the choices left to the planners this way: ``It
was not a perfect world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But, then, war never is. Times change, but war is still hell, as
somebody else put it differently more than a century ago _ William
Tecumseh Sherman, who did not spare civilians on his march to the
sea. And they were his fellow Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
