<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-RIGHTS-REVIEW     10-02 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RIGHTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN QUIETLY SAYS IT'S TIME TO ADOPT A BILL OF RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ They set out to challenge the law. But when four
Britons dismissed from the British military because they are gay
accused the government of violating their basic human right to
privacy, they couldn't find a remedy in a domestic court. They had
to take their case to the European Court of Human Rights in
Strasbourg, France.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in October 2000, however, people like Duncan
Lustig-Prean, Graeme Grady, Jeanette Smith and John Beckett _ who
won a landmark decision last week when the European court ruled in
their favor _ will no longer have to make that long trip to France.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, doggedly, somewhat nervously, Britain is preparing
itself for a constitutional revolution that will profoundly alter
its citizens' relationship to the state and to the rule of law. A
year from now, when Britain incorporates the European Convention on
Human Rights into domestic law, ordinary Britons will for the first
time have a set of fundamental human rights that can be enforced in
British courts, similar to those guaranteed by the Bill of Rights
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very exciting, and will make a significant change in the
landscape of the types of cases that can be brought in this
country,'' said Di Luping, a legal officer at Liberty, a human
rights group, which represented several of the complainants in the
military case.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's decision to enshrine personal rights in its own legal
system has been a long time in coming. In 1951, Britain ratified
the human-rights convention, which guarantees its citizens a set of
basic human rights including the right to privacy, the right to
freedom of expression and the right not to be tortured.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas behind the convention arose in the aftermath of World
War II, with much of the Western world united in horror at the
excesses that totalitarian regimes could visit upon their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Britain agreed to let its citizens seek redress in
Strasbourg. That was revolutionary in itself _ Britons never before
had specifically delineated rights, only implied ones arising from
common law _ but for various reasons, both political and
philosophical, successive governments shied away from making the
convention part of domestic law. This meant the European Court was
the only option for Britons with specific rights-based complaints,
and it is only open to people who could afford to pay: Legal aid is
not available for such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, aggrieved Britons have trekked to Strasbourg,
bringing cases about a host of issues, from the treatment of
suspected criminals to corporal punishment in schools and the
censorship of material offensive to religious groups. And time and
again, the British government has lost _ on more than 50 occasions,
giving it one of the poorest records among European nations _ and
has had to re-write various laws, however grudgingly, to take into
account the rights guaranteed by the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the days of a European court regularly forcing changes in
British law are nearly over. With the formal incorporation of the
human-rights convention in domestic law, a move that Tony Blair's
Labor government made part of its agenda, Britons will be able to
take complaints to British courts.
</P>
<P>
   Even Britons who feel that the modern culture of entitlement has
gone too far are pleased that, finally, in the words of Sir Ivan
Lawrence, a former Conservative member of Parliament, citizens will
be able to ``wash our dirty linen here, rather than in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Practically, the coming change means that new laws are already
being written with human rights in mind. Judges are undergoing
training to cope with the new system and will have increased power,
not to strike down laws, but to determine whether they adhere to
the rights guaranteed by the convention. And ordinary citizens will
for the first time be able to think of the law as granting them
positive rights, instead of just telling them what they can't do.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the notion that people have rights exists in British
law. But rights are generally couched in the negative, as in, for
instance, laws making it illegal for people to discriminate on the
basis of gender or race. ``Never before has there been enshrined in
any piece of legislation a set of positive rights,'' Ms. Luping
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Britain ever had a written constitution. Its laws are
based purely on precedent, said Francesca Klug, a senior research
fellow at the Human Rights Incorporation Project at King's College
London. It is a system in which old laws remain in effect only
until they are overtaken by new laws, and there is no underlying
written set of principles against which they are measured.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself makes the incorporation of the convention
thrilling to human-rights lawyers and many judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unique in our constitutional history,'' Ms. Klug said.
``We've never had a higher law which applies to everything _ to all
other laws _ before. In a more general sense, it's the first time
in the United Kingdom that we'll have had a set of values in which
we can say that this is what we stand for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
