``You can't buy that kind of publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com Opens Its Doors
</P>
<P>
   Looking for more cash, Amazon.com opened its popular Web site to
any interested merchant. Like most Internet retailers, Amazon loses
lots of money. But by selling access to its 12 million customers,
the retailer gains a new revenue stream without the costs
associated with a warehouse of products. Merchants will pay $9.95 a
month to be listed on the site. If they choose to have Amazon
process credit card purchases, they will pay 4.75 percent of the
total sale.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LESLIE KAUFMAN
</P>
<P>
   California Aims at HMOs
</P>
<P>
   For years, consumer groups have complained that health
maintenance organizations deny coverage of treatments unfairly. The
state of California is offering a prescription: lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis signed legislation that will give consumers the
right to sue their health insurers to seek independent review of
decisions to deny coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which could influence managed health care
coverage across the country, also guarantees coverage of
contraceptives and expands coverage for severe mental illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
<P>
   Court Gets Sex Crimes Case
</P>
<P>
   A law that permits victims of rape and other sex crimes to sue
their attackers for damages in federal court may seem an unlikely
battleground in the federalism wars. But that is what the Violence
Against Women Act became earlier this year when a federal appeals
court declared it unconstitutional as beyond the ``limited
authority'' of the federal government to enter a traditional
province of state law. Now the Supreme Court has announced it will
take up the case.
</P>
<P>
   One issue is whether Congress may, in enforcing the equal
protection guarantee of the 14th amendment, enact a law permitting
one private person to sue another.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said no, casting a shadow over other civil
rights laws and raising the stakes in this case.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia Submits a Bill
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia gave its own estimate of the damage wreaked by NATO's
bombing campaign last spring. Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zividan
Jovanovic told reporters that the bombing caused $100 billion worth
of damage, and demanded that NATO pay the bill. Some European
officials have estimated that it could cost $30 billion to $50
billion to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later for a tally of the repairs needed, the Yugoslav
Mission at the United Nations conceded it didn't have any.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN
</P>
<P>
   A Nobel for Guenter Grass
</P>
<P>
   Forty years after the publication of his masterpiece, ``The Tin
Drum,'' a book that vividly confronted the ghosts that post-war
Germany seemed inclined to forget, Guenter Grass was awarded the
Nobel Prize for literature. A man of passionate political
engagement, a persistent critic of what he has often portrayed as
the smug complacency of German society, Grass was praised by the
Swedish Academy for his portrayal of the ``forgotten face of
history.'' That face has come alive with an often Rabelaisian gusto
in the writings of the 71-year-old Grass.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Man Dies in Gene Therapy
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year old patient died four days after receiving a gene
therapy treatment at the University of Pennsylvania. If the therapy
proves to be the cause, it will be apparently the first
treatment-related death in a gene therapy trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Gelsinger was among 18 patients being treated for a rare
metabolic disease caused by a genetic inability to process ammonia.
A high dose of adenovirus carrying a corrective gene was injected
into his liver.
</P>
<P>
   Although the virus is usually harmless, Gelsinger seems to have
reacted badly to it. Some 50 other gene therapy trials are now in
progress with adenovirus.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   The Perils of Babyhood
</P>
<P>
   The government insisted the advisory was purely a matter of
safety. One outraged child-rearing expert called it
``self-righteous baloney.'' And many parents did not know what to
think when the federal Consumer Product Safety Commission warned
that sleeping with infants and toddlers can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1997, the agency found, 121 children under 2
were smothered by a parent or other adult sleeping in the same bed;
394 others died after becoming trapped in the bed structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not sleep with your baby or put the baby down to sleep in
an adult bed,'' said Ann Brown, the commission's chairman. Critics
charged that the study's methods were flawed. Practiced
responsibly, they argued, bed sharing is good for babies.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERICA GOODE
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian Gets Huge Gift
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the Smithsonian Institution has received huge
gifts from two refugees who were driven from the same homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is from Steven Udvar-Hazy, whose family fled Hungary &QL; 
when the Soviet Union crushed the 1956 uprising. Udvar-Hazy, who
became a billionaire in the aircraft leasing business, is giving
$60 million toward a new aviation museum.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier gift was from the late Dr. Paul Singer, who left the
museum his collection of ancient Chinese artifacts, valued at $50
million to $60 million. Singer, a psychiatrist, was born in an
Austro-Hungarian town that is now in Hungary, and he fled Austria
in 1938 when the Nazis marched in.
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRVIN MOLOTSKY &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
