<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIOGRAPHIES-825&AMP;     10-02 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIOGRAPHIES-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL BIOGRAPHIES OF BUSH ARE RUSHING TO PRINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has never been a
particularly fervent reader of books. But he is about to become a
favorite subject of them.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most telling measures yet of the aura of
inevitability surrounding his presidential candidacy, publishers
are rushing out a string of competing biographies of Bush, most of
which are due in stores even before the first Republican caucus or
primary in late January.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Times Books, a division of Random House, will
publish ``First Son: George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty.''
That is not to be confused with ``Fortunate Son: The Rise of George
W. Bush and the Next Generation of American Politics,'' which
Thomas Dunne Books, an imprint of St. Martin's, will release around
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion expects to join the scrum in January with ``W: the
Rise, Fall and Rise of the Bush Dynasty.'' And soon after that,
Random House weighs in again with ``Shrub: The Short but Happy
Political Life of George W. Bush,'' co-written by Molly Ivins, the
acerbic Texas journalist, and Lou Dubose, editor of the Texas
Observer, a liberal biweekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The publishers and writers of these books say that even if
Bush's campaign falters in the months ahead, his ancestry and
stewardship of the nation's second most populous state make his
story a compelling one.
</P>
<P>
   But they also concede that there is an element of soothsaying
behind this literary gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely got the nomination,'' said Martha Levin,
publisher of Hyperion, referring to Bush's sizable lead over other
Republicans who want to represent the party in the general
election, which is still more than a year away.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin added that if Bush then fails to win the presidency
itself, ``There's no question in my mind that he'll be president at
a later date _ he's not going away.''
</P>
<P>
   These books _ all set in motion before Bush announced his
candidacy in June _ underscore the extraordinary extent of the
early, widespread, perhaps self-fulfilling assumption that Bush is
the presidential candidate to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But they also point out a potential downside of running so far
ahead of the pack: a level of scrutiny that has writers tripping
over one another to find new nuggets of information and fresh
strands of thought about Bush that could turn out to be
unflattering.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Bush and his aides have hastened to finish his
own book, which has had a turbulent production. A Texas journalist
originally paired with Bush to do the writing was replaced by Karen
P. Hughes, the director of communications for Bush's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers deemed it important that he answer the other
versions of his story with his own. So Ms. Hughes spent about four
weeks in August and September holed up in her Austin, Texas, home,
ensuring that the book, ``A Charge to Keep,'' published by William
Morrow and Co., will be in stores by November.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hughes, one of Bush's most trusted advisers, did not leave
her writing and return to the campaign trail even when Bush
encountered several tense days of repeated questions about whether
he had used illegal drugs in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush said that Ms. Hughes stepped in after the book's
initial author, Mickey Herskowitz, a sports columnist for the
Houston Chronicle who has known Bush for decades, missed his first
deadline in July.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said that the few chapters that Herskowitz, who has
written autobiographies with Mickey Mantle, Dan Rather and Gene
Tierney, turned in had been disappointing, lacking the kind of
insight into Bush's political decision-making that they wanted the
book to have.
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz said that he had missed his first deadline by only a
few days. And he said he had trouble completing his work, because
Bush's advisers had expected him to write the majority of the book,
which was to be about Bush's political philosophy, by simply
reading transcripts of his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz said that when he asked Bush's staff for more
detailed policy information, he was told that it was still evolving
and that they did not want the book to pin Bush down or provide
fodder for later criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between your everyday book project and a
book that's attached to a political campaign,'' Herskowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidential candidates are also producing their own
books, in an increasingly standard rite of political passage that
blurs any line between literary and elective aspirations. ``Faith
of My Fathers,'' an autobiography of Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
one of Bush's rivals for the Republican nomination, is a current
best seller.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan's recent historical book, ``A Republic, Not an
Empire,'' drew furious criticism for his isolationist views on
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is the only Republican in a crowded field of
presidential contenders who is inspiring so many unauthorized
biographies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bill Minutaglio, the author of ``First Son,'' said that one
reason was the fleetness of Bush's political ascent, which has
created a gap between people's awareness of him and their actual
familiarity with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real thirst for some knowledge,'' said Minutaglio, a
reporter for the Dallas Morning News who is based in Austin, the
state capital. ``People want to know: Why all the fuss?''
</P>
<P>
   Minutaglio's book _ the only one so far for which an advance
copy was available _ is written in a fairly detached tone and
strives to be an objective, comprehensive portrait of Bush's
ancestry, life and times.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ivins said that the book she and Dubose are writing, which
focuses on Bush's political record, reaches the pointed conclusion
that Bush ``is a gifted politician neither interested in, nor
gifted at, governance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sex, no drugs, no Sigmund Freud,'' Ms. Ivins added.
``Why would anyone read this book? Because it's funny _ it's about
Texas. We couldn't help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicity materials for ``Fortunate Son,'' by J.H. Hatfield,
make it sound a bit racier than its competitors and promise juicy
tidbits about the way Bush ``avoided the draft at the height of
Vietnam'' and the reason ``Bush's parents pressured him to break
off his engagement to his first fiancee.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's previous book was a similarly unauthorized biography
of Patrick Stewart, the bald-headed star of the television series
``Star Trek: The Next Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin said that ``W,'' by Elizabeth Mitchell, a former
contributor to George magazine, will focus on the dynamics within
the Bush family and the extent to which Bush's presidential bid is
an attempt to avenge the 1992 defeat of his father, President
George Bush, by Bill Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
