<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4446 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-SPENDING-2TA     10-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-SPENDING-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CAMPAIGN CASH POURS IN, SPENDING RECORDS SHATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the phenomenal pace of political fund-raising
continues, candidates for federal office will spend about $3
billion in the 2000 campaigns, an increase of about $800 million
from four years earlier, according to projections based on Federal
Election Commission data.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has raised an unprecedented
$56 million in just seven months, is hardly alone in reaping the
benefits of this cash-flush political season. This year's
fund-raising totals for House and Senate incumbents and the
national political parties have shattered all records, easily
exceeding the most optimistic projections of chief fund-raisers and
political operatives.
</P>
<P>
   By November 2000, the congressional races alone could cost $1
billion, experts estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Fund raising for the congressional elections is being bolstered
by the intense fight for control of the House of Representatives,
where Republicans hold a six-seat majority. In the first six months
of 1999, House incumbents raised $77.9 million, which is 47 percent
more than they raised in the first half of 1997 and 88 percent more
than they raised in the first half of 1995, according to Federal
Election Commission statistics.
</P>
<P>
   And soft money donations, the unlimited contributions to the
parties for party-building activities, have increased 55 percent in
the first half of 1999 over the same period in 1997. Soft money
contributions are 75 percent higher this year than they were in the
first half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Experts project that there is likely to be at least $525 million
in soft money contributed to the six major national political party
committees by November 2000. That would be more than double the
$262 million in soft money that was contributed to the parties in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate prepares to debate later this month the merits of
a sweeping campaign finance bill that would ban soft money, several
campaign finance experts helped The New York Times project the
total amount of money that would be raised by candidates and the
national parties for the 2000 federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, the president of Democracy 21, a public policy
organization here, assisted the Times by studying the pace of fund
raising in the first six months of 1999 and comparing it with the
same periods in the past three election cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer estimated that the 2000 elections would cost nearly
$3 billion, which he called ``a conservative estimate.'' But he and
others said that the figure very likely could exceed $3 billion,
especially if campaign fund raising continued at its current torrid
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extraordinary numbers,'' said Wertheimer, who is an
outspoken advocate of overhauling campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ending this century with oceans of political influence
money flooding our democracy and drowning out the voices of average
citizens,'' said Wertheimer, who has accurately projected costs of
campaigns for 20 years. ``The historic idea we have contributed to
the world, democratic self-government, is at risk here in our own
country because of the corrupt campaign finance practices that
pervade Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer said that fund raising was up 95 percent in the
House, but he estimated that the increase would be only 35 percent
by November 2000. ``Fund raising in the first six months this year
has been extremely intensive,'' Wertheimer said. ``But that doesn't
mean this pace will sustain itself for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Steurer, an aide to Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who is
the Senate's most ardent opponent of limits on campaign
contributions, did not dispute the $3 billion estimate, but he
added that the costs of campaigns had increased markedly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some campaign finance experts say it is very difficult to
estimate at this stage how much money will be raised by the end of
the election cycle in November 2000. There are too many variables,
they say, and they cautioned that the projections could be gross
overestimates or underestimates of the actual figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's throwing darts,'' said Kent Cooper, a former senior staff
member at the Federal Election Commission who is the co-founder of
a Washington research firm, Public Disclosure Inc., that operates a
comprehensive research Web site (www.tray.com).
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raisers and campaign finance experts offer several
explanations for the windfall this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raisers attribute much of their success to the booming
economy, saying that the nation's prosperity makes it easier for
more people to write checks of $1,000, the maximum an individual
can give to one candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel flush,'' said Herbert E. Alexander, a professor
emeritus of political science at the University of Southern
California who has written extensively on campaign finance trends.
``People have enormous paper profits from the stock market boom,
and the technology people are suddenly millionaires and
billionaires. I just think there is a lot of money around, and
people want to use it to influence the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible explanation for the early fund-raising pace is
the early presidential primary schedule, in which most of the major
primaries will be over by late March. The earlier schedule has
added to the perception among fund-raisers that they have less time
to raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, the executive director of the Center for
Responsive Politics, said he agreed with the estimate that $3
billion would be spent on the 2000 elections. ``A 50 percent
increase from 1996 sounds right to me,'' he said. He also agreed
with the projection that at least $1 billion would be raised and
spent on the congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition breeds the appetite for money,'' Makinson said.
``It's impossible to imagine higher stakes. You have the real
tangible potential for the Republicans to control all three
branches of government _ the presidency, the Congress and let us
not forget the Supreme Court. A lot of donors are licking their
chops at the prospect of a Republican-dominated government, and
they will give big money to try to attain it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Makinson also said that he thought there would be ``an
explosion'' in independent expenditures on such things as issue
advocacy advertisements. In 1996, the Annenberg Public Policy
Center estimated that $45 million to $60 million was spent on issue
advocacy advertisements. In February, John J. Sweeney, the
president of the AFL-CIO, declared that the labor federation would
spend as much as $46 million in 1999 and 2000 on grass-roots
lobbying and campaigning. Sweeney emphasized that the money would
be used for political literature, phone banks to get out the vote,
issue advertisements and voter registration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the unions spent $35 million on such activities,
although the Republican leaders dispute that figure. Republicans
estimated that organized labor spent as much as $500 million on the
1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican congressional leadership, meanwhile, is also
helping to raise millions of dollars for issue advertising to
counter the union effort.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer said that he estimated that at least $200 million
would be spent this year and next year on such issue
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, fund-raisers said that they were astonished by
the rate of contributions pouring in for House and Senate
incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 73 Senate candidates have raised $50 million in the
first six months of 1999, according to election commission figures.
</P>
<P>
   That amount is more than seven times the $7 million that 50
candidates raised through the first half of 1993, the last election
cycle for the current group of 33 Senate seats that are now up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Makinson predicted that the presidential race might very well be
``locked up'' by October 2000, but that the fight for control of
the House would produce enormous last-minute contributions. ``Let's
not forget the impact of the wide-open race for control of the
House of Representatives,'' he said. ``When we're a month out, the
House race will be the most important race to be decided, and it
will attract a lot of last-minute money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than $60 million of soft money was raised in the first half
of this year, a 75 percent increase over the first half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance experts predicted that the parties would raise
at least $500 million in soft money by November 2000. But they
cautioned that the figure could be significantly higher, especially
after more contributions solicited by Bush's ``Pioneers''
fund-raising club of 150 people are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Republican fund-raising officials have already said that the
Pioneers network is a ready-made soft money club. By June 1999, the
Pioneers had contributed $3 million of soft money, but campaign
finance experts predict that they will raise huge sums of money for
the Republican Party later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be going gangbusters for the unlimited soft money
contributions,'' Makinson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
