<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      10-02 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO RULE ON NATION'S MOST ARDENT DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opening its new term on Monday, the Supreme Court
returns from a three-month recess to a docket that places the
justices squarely in the midst of some of the United States' most
passionate debates, from health care to campaign finance to
government aid to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the court will continue its re-examination of the
boundary between federal authority and state sovereignty, taking up
new cases that move the federalism battleground into the arena of
civil rights legislation, where the stakes are higher than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The justices accepted 15 new cases in the last three weeks,
bringing the total to 44 and filling their argument calendar
through January. Cases to be heard in the late winter and spring,
perhaps several dozen more, will be added over the next few months
to complete the 1999-2000 term.
</P>
<P>
   Important cases scheduled for the term's opening days suggest
the range of what awaits the justices. On Monday, they will hear
arguments on whether a 1996 law, the Anti-Terrorism and Effective
Death Penalty Act, left any meaningful role for the federal courts
in reviewing state prisoners' convictions and sentences.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the court will hear Missouri's defense of its $1,075
contribution limit for statewide political campaigns, in a case
with clear implications for the similar limits under federal
election law.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the court will take up a constitutional challenge
to a provision of Hawaii law that limits to descendants of the
native Hawaiians the right to vote in certain elections.
Transcending its exotic locale, this dispute could be a vehicle for
a broader ruling about using race as a basis for government
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how early in the term Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg will be able to return to work, after her surgery for
colon cancer on Sept. 17. After her doctors found no sign that a
small tumor had spread, she was discharged from a hospital here
last week with an excellent prognosis. If Ginsburg cannot
participate in the early arguments, she has the option of listening
to the tapes and voting in the cases.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the opening day, the court will also announce the
disposition of more than 1,700 appeals that have accumulated during
the recess, nearly all of which the justices will turn down without
further review.
</P>
<P>
   These are the highlights of the new term so far:
</P>
<P>
   Federalism
</P>
<P>
   In a series of decisions over the last four years, the court has
invoked a variety of constitutional doctrines to curb the authority
of Congress to impose requirements on state governments or to make
the states answerable for their behavior as defendants in private
lawsuits in either federal or state court. Most of these cases were
decided by 5-4 majorities, and federalism remains the current
court's most contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   The four federalism cases on the docket for the new term may
well fan the flames even higher, because these cases have broad
implications for the ability of Congress to enact civil rights
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The question in United States vs. Morrison, No. 99-5, is whether
Congress had the authority to pass the Violence Against Women Act,
a 1994 law that permitted victims of rape and other crimes
``motivated by gender'' to sue their attackers in federal court. A
federal appeals court ruled that the law was not a valid exercise
of the power of Congress either to regulate interstate commerce or
to enforce the equal-protection guarantee of the 14th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In Kimel vs. Florida Board of Regents, No. 98-791, the court
will decide whether employees of state agencies can sue states for
age discrimination under a federal law, the Age Discrimination in
Employment Act. The justices' answer may determine whether other
anti-discrimination laws, including such measures as the Americans
With Disabilities Act, can be applied to the states.
</P>
<P>
   The court will decide in Reno vs. Condon, No. 98-1464, whether
state motor vehicle agencies can be bound by a federal law that
prohibits the commercial sale of drivers' personal information,
which many states have found to be a profitable commodity. And in
Vermont Agency of Natural Resources vs. United States, No. 98-1828,
the question is whether states are constitutionally immune from
suit by private whistle-blowers under the federal False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   Free Speech
</P>
<P>
   The court has six First Amendment cases on the docket, an
unusually high number that may reflect the unsettled nature of many
free-speech questions. For example, the lower federal courts appear
to be uncertain about the continuing validity of aspects of the
Supreme Court's 1976 ruling in Buckley vs. Valeo, which established
the current constitutional framework for campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals court in St. Louis struck down Missouri's
$1,075 limit on contributions, close to the $1,000 limit the court
upheld in the Buckley case, on the ground that inflation since 1976
has whittled the value of $1,000 to under $400. That amount is too
restrictive of the right of a citizen to ``speak'' by means of
political contributions, the appeals court said in Nixon vs. Shrink
Missouri Government PAC, No. 98-963.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Supreme Court does not appear to have much appetite
for reopening the campaign-finance issue itself, even a narrowly
based upholding of the Missouri decision could have that effect by
presumptively invalidating the federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   In a case involving the privacy of government records, the court
will decide the constitutionality of a California law that makes
arrest records available for journalistic and some other purposes,
but not for commercial use, such as for sale to lawyers and
insurance companies. In Los Angeles Police Department vs. United
Reporting Publishing Corp., No. 98-678, the department is appealing
a federal appeals court's ruling that the restriction on commercial
access violates the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Another First Amendment dispute involves student activity fees
at public universities. The federal appeals court in Chicago,
viewing the fee at the University of Wisconsin as equivalent to
compelled speech, ruled that students who objected to particular
student organizations that received a share of the money had a
constitutional right not to contribute. In Board of Regents vs.
Southworth, No. 98-1189, the university is arguing that the fee
simply establishes a public forum in which all viewpoints are
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Two cases concern sexually explicit speech or expression. In one
_ Erie, Pa. vs. Pap's A.M., No. 98-1161, the court will revisit,
for the first time in eight years, the government's ability to
regulate nude dancing. The question in United States vs. Playboy
Entertainment Group, No. 98-1682, is the validity of a federal law
requiring providers of sexually explicit cable television
programming to scramble the signal or limit the hours so that
nonsubscribing homes cannot receive the programming inadvertently
when children are watching.
</P>
<P>
   In Hill vs. Colorado, No. 98-1856, the court will consider, for
the third time in recent years, the validity of restrictions on
protests outside abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Religion
</P>
<P>
   A program under which local school districts use federal money
to provide computers and other equipment to private schools,
including religious schools, within their boundaries was declared
unconstitutional by a federal appeals court. The Clinton
administration is supporting the appeal in Mitchell vs. Helms, No.
98-1648, a case that may indicate how receptive the justices will
be in cases not yet before the court to arguments for publicly
financed vouchers for parochial school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Equal Protection
</P>
<P>
   Under the Hawaii Constitution, the Office of Hawaiian Affairs
decides how millions of dollars are to be spent on behalf of the
state's native Hawaiian people, and only people of Hawaiian
ancestry may vote for its trustees. The lower federal courts have
rejected a Hawaii-born white man's challenge to this restriction as
an illegitimate racial qualification on voting. Defending its
system in Rice vs. Cayetano, No. 98-818, Hawaii is arguing that the
restriction is based on Hawaii's special history and not on race as
such.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Law
</P>
<P>
   Several cases have important implications for federal regulatory
programs and policies. In Food and Drug Administration vs. Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco, No. 98-1152, the court will decide whether the
government has authority under current law to regulate tobacco as a
drug, a proposition that was rejected by a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   In Pegram vs. Herdrich, No. 98-1152, the justices will decide
whether people who receive medical care as a benefit of employment
can sue health maintenance organizations for putting
cost-containment goals above their duty to act in the best interest
of individual patients.
</P>
<P>
   The question in Friends of the Earth vs. Laidlaw Environmental
Services, No. 98-822, is whether a defendant in a suit brought by
private citizens under the Clean Water Act can escape liability for
civil penalties if it stops polluting while the lawsuit is in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal Law
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois vs. Wardlow, No. 98-1036, the court will decide
whether someone's unprovoked flight at the sight of a police
officer is such inherently suspicious behavior as to justify the
officer in pursuing and stopping the person and conducting a
pat-down search.
</P>
<P>
   The question in Williams vs. Taylor, No. 98-8384, is what degree
of deference the federal courts owe to state-court determinations
in reviewing a state prisoner's constitutional challenge to a
conviction or sentence. The court will be interpreting the central
portions of the 1996 law by which Congress sharply restricted the
jurisdiction of federal judges to issue writs of habeas corpus; the
question is, how sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents' Rights
</P>
<P>
   In a case from the state of Washington, the court will rule on
the constitutionality of state laws that give grandparents, and
other relatives and ``third parties,'' the right to seek
court-ordered visitation over the objection of children's parents.
The Washington Supreme Court struck down the law as violating the
fundamental right of parents to decide how to raise their children.
</P>
<P>
   While this case, Troxel vs. Granville, No. 99-138, will give
high visibility to the question of grandparents' rights, it also
raises the deeper question, under the 14th Amendment's guarantee of
due process, of how courts should identify and analyze fundamental
rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
