<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-MILK-FEUD-AR     10-02 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MILK-FEUD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE IN CONGRESS OVER MILK PRICES PITS EAST AGAINST MIDWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Vt., N.Y., Texas, N.H.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most families, the outcome of a battle in
Congress over milk prices will mean just a few cents a week at the
supermarket counter. But the livelihoods of tens of thousands of
dairy farmers are at stake, and the issue has provoked a civil war
between lawmakers from the East and those from the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Normal allies like the liberal Democratic Sens. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont and Herb Kohl of Wisconsin are at each other's throats.
Normal antagonists like Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and Robert
Smith, the Republican turned Independent from New Hampshire, are
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Down Pennsylvania Avenue, President Clinton is on one side and
his wife, Hillary, the all-but-announced Senate candidate from New
York, is on the other. Mrs. Clinton's likely opponent, Rudolph
Giuliani, took one position when he was merely mayor of New York,
but he changed his mind when he began running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The issue ``is all about economic self-interest,'' said
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman. That is apparent from
conversations with family farmers in the warring regions.
</P>
<P>
   David Krug, who has a 280-acre farm with about 75 cows in Owen,
Wis., that has been in his family for 105 years, calculates that if
a new pricing system developed by the Clinton administration goes
into effect, he might earn an additional $8,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But 800 miles or so to the east, in Swanton, Vt., near the
Canadian border, Paul Bourbeau, who has about 300 cows on a farm he
runs with his wife and two grown sons, figures that changes in the
system could cost him $16,000 to $18,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Krug and Bourbeau are relatively prosperous, and unlike some of
their neighbors, their farms will survive no matter how the
political questions are resolved. ``But it could make the
difference between profit and loss,'' Bourbeau said, ``the
difference in whether you keep up the buildings and replace the
piece of equipment you need.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a convoluted federal milk-pricing system that was
devised in 1937 to ensure that fresh milk was available in all
parts of the country. The minimum price that farmers can charge for
milk is fixed monthly by the Department of Agriculture. The country
is divided into 31 regions, and the set price is higher the farther
the regions are from Eau Claire, Wis., historically the center of
the dairy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Developments in dairy technology, transportation and
refrigeration have made the old system obsolete, but efforts to
change it have always failed because the stakes are so high.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1996, Congress approved a law, called the Freedom to
Farm Act, reducing and ultimately ending the subsidies for farmers
who grow corn, cotton, rice, soybeans, wheat and most other crops.
</P>
<P>
   Although the law retained the 60-year-old milk-price system, it
instructed the secretary of agriculture to develop a new, more
market-oriented system by this year. The law also permitted the
creation of the Northeast Dairy Compact, which puts a floor on the
price of milk that goes into bottles in the six New England states.
The compact is supposed to expire when a new federal pricing policy
is put into place.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Glickman offered the administration's new plan,
which would reduce, though not eliminate, the regional differences
in what farmers charge for milk. The plan will go into effect
unless Congress blocks it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safest thing for me to have done,'' the secretary said in
an interview, ``would have been to reaffirm the status quo, but I
thought it was important to have a more up-to-date policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department maintains that if its plan had been
in effect for the last 12 months, the average price farmers
received for milk would have been 58 cents higher for each 100
pounds of milk they sold, or nearly 5 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   But some farmers would have benefited more, and some would have
been hurt. The politics of the matter turn on the prevailing view
that the administration's plan would be to the advantage of farmers
in the upper Midwest and to the disadvantage of those in the East.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department has calculated that its plan would
lower the supermarket price of milk by an average of 2 cents a
gallon nationally. The Consumer Federation of America figures that
the New England compact caused the price of bottled milk to rise 15
cents a gallon. A study by the Office of Management and Budget
found that consumer prices were 5 cents to 20 cents higher than
they would be without price fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Those calculations are difficult to prove conclusively and are
disputed by organizations representing dairy farmers in the East.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Eastern lawmakers have spent the year scrambling to preserve the
Northeast Dairy Compact, regardless of what happens to the new
pricing plan. Eastern seaboard states outside New England,
including New York, want to join the price-fixing arrangement, and
Southern states want to form a compact of their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, it is almost always harder to change something than
to leave it alone, and the dairy system is no exception. A majority
appears to be in favor of blocking the administration's pricing
plan and allowing the New England compact to continue. But the
majority may not rule.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the House of Representatives voted, 285-140, to
block the new pricing plan and leave the old one in effect. But the
latest word is that a House-Senate conference committee has
decided, under instructions from House Republican leaders, to drop
the section blocking the pricing plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders say they are philosophically opposed to
putting such policy in a spending bill. Their political opponents
say that Rep. Dick Armey, the majority leader, and Rep. Tom DeLay,
the whip, both Texans, are representing the interests of Suiza
Foods Corp., the Texas holding company that is the country's
largest dairy producer.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from the Midwest and the Northeast say they will
filibuster legislation that puts their dairy constituents at a
disadvantage, and neither side seems to have the 60 votes necessary
to break a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said that if Congress approved legislation blocking his
pricing plan, he would recommend that Clinton veto it. But
campaigning in dairy counties in upstate New York, Mrs. Clinton has
opposed the administration's plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani, who used to be against propping up the prices paid
farmers on the ground that consumers in New York City would have to
pay more for milk, announced in August that he had changed his mind
and now sided with the farmers.
</P>
<P>
   All this squabbling seemed about to end this week when the dairy
compact was supposed to go out of existence. But a federal judge in
Vermont provided a respite by issuing a temporary restraining order
preventing any change in government policy until hearings in a
related lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare their farms for winter, Krug in Wisconsin and
Bourbeau in Vermont are following the developments in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about what it will mean for the younger farmers
here,'' said Krug, 60.
</P>
<P>
   Bourbeau, 40, said: ``When I started farming here 17 years ago,
there were seven farms on my road. Now there are only two left.
This could make the difference to lots of people up here whether
they stay in business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ARMSTRONG-BABY03-COX     10-02 2695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMSTRONG-BABY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lance Armstrong's wife shares their experiences with in vitro
fertilization
 &HT;    By John Maher and Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The very day Lance Armstrong and his wife,
Kristin, were in Paris reveling in his improbable Tour de France
victory, Louise Brown was somewhere in England, celebrating her
21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown became the world's first ``test-tube'' baby when she was
born on July 25, 1978. The process that helped produce Brown has
now more accurately become known as in vitro fertilization, from
the Latin term for ``in glass.'' The technique was introduced in
the United States in 1981, and an estimated 45,000 babies have been
born in this country through a variety of IVF procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The Armstrongs have been traveling that road to parenthood this
year. Lance Armstrong was rendered infertile by powerful
chemotherapy to treat his advanced testicular cancer from October
to December 1996. The couple are expecting their first child _ to
be called either Grace Elizabeth or Luke David _ on Oct. 25, which,
as coincidence would have it, is right in the middle of National
Infertility Awareness Week beginning Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly didn't plan it that way,'' Kristin Armstrong
said. ``We timed it strictly around the cycling season.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin recorded all the joy, wonder, fear, pain and uncertainty
of the IVF process in a pull-no-punches diary at the Lance
Armstrong Foundation Web site (www.laf.org).
</P>
<P>
   Kristin felt the diary, which detailed all the shots, surgeries
and doctor visits needed to have a child through IVF, was an
extension of one of the foundation's missions: improving the
quality of life of cancer survivors. Although some passages might
make some readers blush, she said the diary has helped the wives of
men suffering from testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lance got sick, he was so open about everything,''
Kristin said. ``This is an addendum to that. This whole IVF
procedure, not very many people want to open up and talk about it.
But I've had so many e-mails from wives whose husbands have gone
through cancer treatments. They are so grateful to find someone
that they can ask, `What about this and what about that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It really addressed the whole issue of survivorship. Once you
finish your medical treatment, oftentimes, the doctors get you out
the door and say, `OK, get on with your life. Everything is great
and all is well.' They just expect you to return to normal, and all
is not normal. It's altered in so many ways. Survivorship is huge.
There are so many things that go with that. Going on with your life
and having a family is one aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband never tried to keep the details of the pregnancy a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been honest about everything else,'' Lance said.
``The (details) have been beneficial to some people, at least
that's what we've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the couple's openness, it's obvious the world has come a
long way since Louise Brown's secretive birth. IVF accounts for
less than 5 percent of infertility treatments, but it is often used
by women with blocked or damaged fallopian tubes. And it also helps
cancer survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The very treatment that saved Armstrong's life jeopardized his
chances of having children. The chemotherapy drugs, such as
platinum, attack the DNA of rapidly dividing cells, such as the
cancer tumors that had grown to the size of golf balls in
Armstrong's lungs. However, such drugs also damage cells in the
stomach lining, hair, fingernails and sperm.
</P>
<P>
   There was a possibility that Armstrong's sperm would be fine a
few years after his treatment. There also was a possibility they
wouldn't. So, before he began his treatment, and before he had even
met Kristin, he had some sperm saved in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Of fatherhood, Kristin said, ``Lance is so nurturing, so loving.
It has always been his dream of a lifetime to be a father. When he
was so sick, he'd thought he'd never be a father.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin, who worked for a local advertising firm, met her future
husband at a news conference at the Four Seasons Hotel in January
1997 when Lance announced plans for his first official Ride for the
Roses weekend.
</P>
<P>
   She eventually started volunteering for the foundation. By that
June, they began dating. By October, they were engaged. In May
1998, they were married in Santa Barbara, Calif., near where
Kristin and her family spent summer vacations when she was growing
up.
</P>
<P>
   Lance was declared cancer-free in October 1997, and that's when
they started discussing starting a family. Kristin, who turned 28
in August, always envisioned herself with children, but she hadn't
given much thought to when she should have them.
</P>
<P>
   She was ambivalent at first when Armstrong broached the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how can you tell someone whose motto is `live for the day'
that you want to put it off?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has made millions during his cycling career, so the
high cost of IVF wasn't an obstacle, but it still was a surprise.
Kristin estimated the drugs and other medical procedures cost about
$15,000. The couple's insurance did not cover any of the
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge issue,'' she said. ``It's completely not
covered, and it's so expensive. We had the resources to pay for it.
But it's sad for people who have trouble coming up with that kind
of money. Having a family shouldn't be a financial constraint.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Society for Reproductive Medicine,
only about 25 percent of health plans cover infertility services,
and the cost of one cycle of IVF treatment averages between $8,000
and $12,000. Thirteen states, including Texas, require coverage of
infertility services, but few of the laws are very demanding.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DIARY
</P>
<P>
   Kristin started the IVF process in December.
</P>
<P>
   She started writing details of the treatment in her private
diary, then decided to make it public. Here are some of the
entries:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dec. 30, 1998: ``I have to say today was horrible ... Nurses
strapped me to this sliding X-ray table and stuck this torture
device inside of me that sprays dye. Then, when they take the
X-rays, they can see if you have blocked tubes or any other
problems ... I was sobbing the whole time and I wanted my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 6: An encounter with counseling. Kristin observed, ``It
was two hours of sex-ed, complete with old films of the sperm
swimming up the tubes. We've all seen it. We don't want to see it
again ... You know that you want to just get up and bolt, but you
can't find the right moment? Finally I had all my belongings packed
up, and couldn't take one more minute, so I stood up and
race-walked out of the room with Lance on my heel. We burst out of
the room, giddy like school kids, and ran to our car laughing and
out of breath. I wondered if we were fit to be parents. Then I
realized that we were absolutely perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 11: Kristin began her Lupron shots. It's often the first
fertility drug women use. It affects the pituitary gland and the
hormones it releases. ``Ten units a day until they tell me to
stop,'' she wrote. ``Lupron is a drug that prevents you from
ovulating. For someone with needle phobia, the whole daily concept
is highly unnerving. I had to administer it myself since Lance is
gone. My hands were shaking so badly and I couldn't get the tiny
bubbles out of the syringe. I finally just squished a blob of my
thigh together and swore out loud as I stuck myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 14: Kristin got a shipment from the pharmacy of another
drug, Gonal-F. ``These are the drugs that `stimulate the follicle,'
or make you lay more eggs. My body, once a temple, is now a
pincushion-henhouse. For some reason, I'm still excited about all
this. I'm starting to look at other people's babies, and they are
starting to look really cute.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later: ``Today I made the grand pilgrimage to the clinic
in San Antonio where we store what Lance calls his `frozen
tadpoles.' We pay rent on them every year, $100. I went to the IVF
office early in the morning and picked up this big frozen tank. It
filled up the passenger seat next to me and was pretty heavy. I
jammed to tunes and made it there in an hour. I lugged the tank
inside the building and up to the 13th floor. I read some House
Beautiful magazines while one of the nurses prepared my family for
the icy trip back to Austin. She even opened the tank briefly to
show me the initials LA etched into the vial. I said a silent
prayer that it wasn't some Larry Anderson and was on my way. This
time I drove very carefully and answered several inquiring calls
from Lance, checking progress. I never felt quite safe until I had
deposited the tank back into the safe hands of the IVC staff.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 16: With curious friends watching in the master bathroom,
Kristin suffered a mishap. ``Call it stage fright, call it slippery
fingers _ I drop the glass vial of Lupron on the bathroom tile and
it shatters. I stare at it, disbelieving, knowing full well that if
I miss my shot, I miss the entire cycle and have to start another
month. My eyes fill with tears and my friends help me clean up the
shards before the dog eats them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin phoned a nurse on call, looking for help and
reassurance. ``Oh dear,'' the nurse said. Kristin then desperately
tried to find a pharmacy that stocked Lupron and that was open on
Saturday night. She finally found one, and a helpful pharmacist
agreed to stay open 20 minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 19: After a sonogram, Kristin got a green light, dropping
the Lupron from 10 units to five and beginning her Gonal-F shots.
``Mixing the Gonal-F shots is hard to do. ... It comes in glass
vials in a powder form. You take a syringe with a long needle and
you draw a unit of this sterile water solution. Then you break the
tops of these vials of powder, and shoot the liquid into each vial
one at a time until your final shot has three units mixed together.
You have to flick the syringe to move this fat air bubble to the
top and squirt until the air pocket moves out of the needle. Then
you thankfully swap out the evil needle for a more familiar one and
inject it into your thigh. I'm thinking I should have gone to med
school, I'm getting so good at this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 22: Kristin had blood drawn at a 7 a.m. doctor's
appointment. ``I looked away from the needle and focused on the Far
Side cartoons taped to the wall, for other squeamish victims like
me. I wonder how the heck I'll handle childbirth if I can't even
have blood drawn without feeling woozy.'' At 4 p.m., she returned
for a sonogram that showed she had 12 eggs growing.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, Lance had an appointment with his oncologist in
Portland, Ore. ``Ironic that he is at one doctor and I am at
another one for two entirely different purposes, or maybe not _
they are, in effect, to confirm the possibility of life. A very
beautiful thing.'' That day she received a shot of human chorionic
gonadotropin, which stimulates egg maturation, exactly 36 hours
before surgery scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 30: After a night of strange dreams about knives and
henhouses, Kristin woke up at 6 a.m. to be at the day surgery
center by 7 to have her eggs harvested. She wrote, ``Nurses asked
me 20 questions and had me sign away every right ever to be mad or
vengeful if someone should screw up. The one thing I did not like
was that I signed the right to cut open my abdomen to retrieve the
eggs if the traditional way didn't work. Thankfully that didn't
happen. I walked into the surgery room and was strapped to a table.
There were extensions for my arms so I felt crucified, and was
literally when they started my anesthesia IV. My world got foggy
and I went under _ feeling and remembering nothing of the whole
procedure. Lance says that I was awake when they brought me back to
the recovery room, but I don't remember it. All I remember was
waking up on the bed and seeing his face, knowing in that instant
that everything was going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Feb. 1: Kristin wrote, ``They defrosted the frozen tadpoles
and used a procedure called ICSI (Intracytoplasmic Sperm
Injection), whereby they physically inject one sperm into each egg.
We had nine viable eggs to use. Of those nine, six are perfect, two
are possible and one broke. We decided to implant three of the six
perfect ones and freeze the other three. I'm freaking out that all
three will work and I'll be as big as a house and later a total
mental patient with three screaming toddlers scampering in
different directions. But despite that, I am beside myself with
excitement, wondering if it will work. On some level, I know that
it will.''
</P>
<P>
   According to data from the American Society for Reproductive
Medicine, only about 26 percent of the women who go through an IVF
cycle produce a baby. Of those who do, almost a third have twins
and 6 percent have three or more babies.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin went to a church and prayed, got a progesterone shot and
readied for the transfer of the eggs back into her body. ``I know
tonight is our last night of life as we know it and it feels
awesomely powerful and strange,'' she wrote. ``We are about to do
something that affects the rest of our lives, alters the very core
of our existence, and there is no turning back. From this moment on
we will never be worry-free again. The feeling is so intense, such
a rush, that I can only equate it to teetering on the edge of a
magnificent chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Kristin added, ``Today was tied for the most
momentous day of my life, the other being our wedding day.''
</P>
<P>
   The three embryos (all had eight cells) were injected into
Kristin with a syringe. Everything went fine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feb. 3: Kristin was confined to the house. Paying bills and
using the computer were the most strenuous tasks she was allowed to
do. She got ``hatching drugs'' four times a day. ``Apparently they
poked a hole in each of the fertilized follicles before they
transferred them. These drugs, along with that tiny hole, help the
embryos `hatch' out of that follicle and implant,'' she wrote while
starting an anxious, 11-day wait to see if the procedure would be a
success.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feb. 13: The Armstrongs awaited results of a pregnancy test.
``I was so nervous that I had the radio off and was praying to
myself on the way there and back. ... Just as I was taking the dog
out, the phone rang. Lance picked it up and was saying `uh huh _
yes _ uh huh,' and making notes on a paper. I motioned to him, `is
that her?' He shook his head `no.' I was about to get my purse to
get ready to go. He hangs up the phone and barrels into me with a
huge hug, his eyes filled with tears. `Babe, you're pregnant.' ...
I will never forget that hug for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Armstrongs knew Kristin was with child. But they had to wait
three more weeks to find out if she was with children.
</P>
<P>
   _ March 4: Kristin wrote, ``I have a sonogram appointment at 10
a.m. that will allow the doctor to see the heartbeat and number of
babies. They say my hormone levels are not indicative of triplets,
so that leaves one baby or a chance of twins. Lance is of the mind
that more is better. I'm unsure ...Try to picture me on an 11-hour
international flight with triplet boy babies. See also: insanity,
fatigue, catatonic state, insomnia, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   _ March 5: Kristin wrote, ``Well, we have one healthy baby! Not
twins, not triplets, but one bambino. I was relieved, but a tiny
part of me was oddly disappointed ... I couldn't ignore the vague
loss I felt wondering what happened to the other two.'' She asked
her doctor, wondering if she'd done something wrong. ``He said
absolutely not, and that there are still some things that are
natural and inexplicable _ even in a seemingly sterile, scientific
procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally on April 13, after a checkup at the end of Kristin's
first trimester, the Armstrongs figured they were ready to announce
the news to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin wrote, ``And you understand why this year, if Lance
rides like the wind, it's because Big Daddy Armstrong has a family
to support!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
