u e BC-FALL-PBS03-COX     10-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-PBS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A passion for quality ignites new PBS season
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``culture vultures'' at PBS have an ever-steeper
incline on their annual uphill battle as they face financial
cutbacks and increased competition from artsy cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   But dating back to 1990, when Ken Burns' mega-documentary series
``The Civil War'' took a chomp out of the commercial networks' fall
ratings, PBS has tackledeach new season head-on, aggressively
programming instead of limping through the barrage with reruns. The
weapon of choice has been (you guessed it) more Burns programming.
Burns' ``Baseball'' wasn't quite the phenomenon that ``The Civil
War'' was, but it attracted a sizable crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Heralding PBS's fall season this year is a double whammy: Ken
Burns' two-part ``Not For Ourselves Alone: The Story of Elizabeth
Cady Stanton &AMP; Susan B. Anthony,'' airing Nov. 7-8, and brother Ric
Burns' mammoth 12-hour epic ``New York: A Documentary Film.'' The
latter airs Nov. 14-18 with the two-hour conclusion reserved for
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Burns brothers are two of the most important documentary
filmmakers of our time,'' crowed PBS programming chief John F.
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   They've certainly popularized the documentary form and attracted
millions of people to PBS. Ken Burns is generally credited with
reinventing the form, creatively using still photos, music and
actors to give voice to letters and other historical writings.
``Not For Ourselves Alone,'' the first documentary to chronicle the
women's suffrage movement, follows a similar style and oozes with
typical Burns passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outraged that this part of history is so unknown,'' Ken
Burns seethed at a TV critics gathering in Los Angeles this past
summer. He noted that recent polls found that 74 percent of
Americans do not know what the 19th Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution is or when women won the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ric is equally enthusiastic about his in-depth history of and
ode to New York, dubbed ``the King Kong of American cities.'' The
``other'' Burns spent almost three years producing the super-long
historical documentary, which he calls a ``tragi-comic story.''
</P>
<P>
   Such passion is what makes the Burns brothers' work great.
Perhaps a little more passion scattered throughout the PBS schedule
would ignite greater interest in the fall programming as the
network celebrates its 30th year on Nov. 3. There are promising
signs in upcoming shows that the Burnses' influence is burning
brightly, especially in two other fall documentaries:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``American Photography: A Century of Images'' is a three-hour
film that showcases the role of photos in the personal lives and
public history of 20th-century America and the profound effect such
images have. (Oct. 13 at 8 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wonders of the African World with Henry Louis Gates Jr.'' is
a six-hour chronicle of the renowned Harvard professor's journey to
the ``dark continent,'' challenging Europeans' notion of a
primitive land. Gates' soft-spoken but powerful narration spins a
fascinating story of the great African civilizations that preceded
the arrival of slavers and white colonists. (Oct. 25-27 at 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   In other PBS premiere news, ``Nova'' begins its season with
``Fall of the Leaning Tower of Pisa'' (Tuesday at 9 p.m.), and
``Nature'' returns with a two-parter on ``Antarctica'' (Oct. 24 and
31).
</P>
<P>
   The title sounds like a made-for-TV movie on USA cable network,
but ``Intimate Strangers'' actually is a four-part science
documentary about microbes, the ``dazzlingly beautiful unseen life
on earth'' (Tuesday nights, Nov. 9-30).
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody out there? That's the question posed in ``Life Beyond
Earth'' (Nov. 10), a provocative two-hour special on the search for
extraterrestrial life. Host Timothy Ferris, the best-selling
science writer who created the program, believes there is life in
the universe and that the discovery of a signal from aliens could
drastically change the course of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobil Masterpiece Theatre,'' the only series that's been on
the air almost as long as PBS itself, begins its 29th season
tonight at 9 with ``A Rather English Marriage,'' a bittersweet tale
about two widowers played by Albert Finney and Tom Courtenay. Next
up on ``Masterpiece'' is ``The Aristocrats'' (Oct. 10-24), a
three-parter based on Stella Tillyard's novel about four well-bred
women in 18th-century England.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Mystery!'' continues its 20th season with Part 2 of
``Second Sight,'' a psychological thriller starring Clive Owen that
debuted Sept. 30 and concludes this Thursday. Next up will be the
sequel to ``An Unsuitable Job for a Woman'' (Oct. 14-Nov. 4),
starring Helen Baxendale as young private detective Cordelia Gray,
followed by ``Mrs. Bradley'' (Nov. 11), a stylish thriller that
allows ``Mystery!'' host Diana Rigg to exercise her acting chops as
an amateur sleuth in 1920s England.
</P>
<P>
   There may not be any exciting cliffhanger resolutions on PBS's
fall shows, but there's plenty of high-quality entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
