<HEADER>
A4480 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-QUILTS03-COX     10-02 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILTS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stitches in time
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It can blanket you and keep you cozy, bring back
fond memories and create a decorative focal point.
</P>
<P>
   A handmade quilt is a wondrous thing.
</P>
<P>
   Quilt lovers _ whether they collect them or create them _ are
delighted to share their passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great combination of function and form,'' says
Sharon Weltner, who fell in love with quilts as a child. Today they
cover the walls of her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Aunt Minnie was a resourceful old lady who came through the
Depression and saved everything,'' Weltner explains. ``She would
cut up any piece of clothing that wasn't wearable and save it. We
would visit her in her log cabin each summer in Arkansas, and when
I came home at the age of 12, I made a quilt for my bed.''
</P>
<P>
   She's been quilting ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original purpose was to keep people warm, as a blanket,''
she says. ``As human beings, we need to decorate, and that's
evident in the time-honored patterns passed on from mothers to
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can relate to fabric because we all choose clothing
based on color, texture, fabric,'' Weltner says. ``And almost all
of us have memories of sleeping under Grandma's quilts or watching
our mothers make quilts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fascination with Amish culture and quilts that led
Aullwood Audubon Farm's Executive Director Charity Krueger to come
up with the organization's annual fund-raiser _ an Amish quilt
auction that will be next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quilts are beautiful statements about art and nature
together,'' Krueger says. Amish patterns incorporate stars and
birds, flowers and plants. Amish quilts are characterized by
intricate piecing designs, quality fabrics and superb quilting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an African Violet Quilt this year and each flower is
raised off the fabric,'' says Krueger. ``It took two years for this
young mother to make it for me. In that time she had two babies.''
</P>
<P>
   When you have a quilt in your house, observes Krueger, you
instinctively slow down. ``It's a great feeling of comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   When Aullwood is filled with quilts in the weeks before the
auction, she notes, the atmosphere becomes more peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had kids who are hyperactive and adults who come for
meetings with hostile agendas,'' she says. ``As soon as they walk
in and see the quilts, they slow down and become more tranquil.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Meredith Moss at 225-2440 or by e-mail at
meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   You can learn more about quilts by attending one of these
upcoming quilting events.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ABOUT QUILTS
</P>
<P>
   _ What exactly is a quilt? It's a decorative bed cover or wall
hanging that consists of a top, batting and backing. Think of it as
a fabric sandwich, with the three layers held together with
quilting _ a series of tight stitches done in a decorative pattern
that connects all three layers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quilting can be done by an individual or at a quilting bee,
where several women work together.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many quilts have more than 470 yards of fabric.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Fantastic Irish Chain Quilt that will be auctioned at
Aullwood has more than 5,600 pieces of fabric. An Antique Log Cabin
Quilt, stitched in 1890, is made of 2,548 pieces of fabric.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to pay between $400 to $1,500 for a quality bed-sized
quilt at a quilt auction like Aullwood's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for quilts in antique stores and flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some people buy the quilt tops and have them quilted later.
</P>
<P>
   USES FOR QUILTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Quilts can be hung on a wall, used to cover a bed or displayed
on a blanket rack. Some people use them as tablecloths or stack
them in baskets or trunks.
</P>
<P>
   CARING FOR QUILTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Direct light can cause fading.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you keep your quilt folded, refold it regularly in
different patterns to avoid damage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not hang a quilt on a wall without adding a sleeve to its
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ To clean, use mild soap and wash in a washing machine. Place
it flat on a clean sheet to dry, preferably outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
