<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-UNION-ENDORSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMPAIGN IS BUOYED BY SUPPORT OF A HEALTH CARE UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the first good news for his campaign in some
time, Vice President Al Gore on Saturday received the support of a
major health care workers union local.
</P>
<P>
   In a head-to-head straw poll, Gore beat former Sen. Bill
Bradley, 55 percent to 38 percent, for the endorsement of Local 250
of the Health Care Workers Union of the Service Employees
International Union.
</P>
<P>
   With 46,000 members in Northern California, it is the
second-largest health care workers local in the country, after
Local 1199 in New York, and provides a potent army of field
workers, precinct walkers and volunteers for its endorsed
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The vote could signal support for Gore at the Oct. 12 meeting in
Los Angeles of the AFL-CIO, of which the service employees union is
a significant member. Gore had been the presumed favorite for the
endorsement, but the recent rise of Bradley, and his appeal to
minorities and labor unions, have threatened to put organized
labor's endorsement on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is welcome,'' said Chris Lahane, a spokesman for
Gore. ``It's a sign we're talking about the right issues. But while
we did well with the Northern California service employees, we're
still going to work for every single vote we can within the AFL and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Rosselli, president of the local, said the vote would help
put the union's issues ``on the front-burner, and we'll be
organized for the March primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was held after Gore and Bradley made direct appeals to
the local's membership, with Gore addressing the members live in
Oakland, Calif., by satellite from Washington, and Bradley by
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley had actually showed up in Oakland on Thursday
and was interviewed by a few members of the local, some union
members said that the video shown to the group at large on Friday
came across as less personal than Gore's interactive appearance.
</P>
<P>
   If the vote was a harbinger of things to come with labor, it may
also be a sign of how future debates may play out between the two
candidates. In their presentations, they directly attacked each
other for the first time in a shared venue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who promised recently to re-invigorate his flagging
campaign, presented Bradley to the heavily Democratic group as
disloyal to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been tempted to turn my back on the Democratic
Party,'' Gore said, referring to Bradley's brief flirtation with an
independent presidential candidacy in 1996. ``I've never been
tempted to run as an independent and divide the progressive
coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley presented his independence as a virtue, saying it would
help attract independent voters and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of nominating somebody is to win in the fall,''
Bradley told the union. ``Since January, people have come up to me,
in hotels and restaurants, and said, `I'm an independent or a
Republican and I would vote for you, and I would never vote for
him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates said they wanted to make it easier for unions to
organize workers. And both laid claim to a longtime commitment to
organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former basketball star, said he had been the shop
steward for nine of his 10 years with the New York Knicks. Gore
noted that his father had been the first labor commissioner in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also noted that he had a better performance rating from
organized labor than Bradley had, even though Tennessee has an
anti-union right-to-work law and only a small percentage of its
workers are unionized. Achieving a strong rating from a state like
Tennessee ``is a little bit harder than in a state that is
unionized wall-to-wall,'' Gore said of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he had a broader, more realistic life experience
than Gore, whom he branded a Washington insider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a life before I got into politics,'' Bradley said,
referring to his basketball days and travels with ``a multiracial
group.'' He said this gave the two candidates ``a different idea of
who the American people are and what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two agreed on most basic union issues, they drew
contrasts on several other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that he was for stronger gun-control measures than
Gore, that his health care proposal would offer broader coverage
sooner than Gore's ``incremental'' approach and that when he spoke
in support of overhauling the campaign finance system, the Gore
campaign ``attacked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wanted to improve public schools and did not
support vouchers, as Bradley briefly did. Gore said vouchers
``drain the money away from public schools at a time when we need
to do more for public schools.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
