<P>
   RUSSIA-POTATOWARS _ A crime wave of sorts has swept the
vegetable patches of rural Russia as the harvest approaches. Poor
and hungry, Russians are killing each other over potatoes. In
several Ural and Siberian towns, potatoes are being harvested early
to prevent them from being stolen. In a few cases, thieves have
been murdered by vigilant patch-tenders. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-VOTE _ CALCUTTA _ More than 600 million Indians are
eligible to cast ballots in the ongoing five-phase parliamentary
election. This year a few voting machines were introduced, but most
of the polling is done the old-fashioned way _ with ink stamps and
paper ballots. A look at the antiquated voting system in the
world's largest democracy. (Basu, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEWT-SPEECH _ Newt Gingrich's first speech since his affair was
revealed. (Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-SHOCK _ A sheriff's cruiser soared past Sheila Wildermuth
as she headed home from an afternoon of shopping for a family
vacation. The kids had been with their grandmother all afternoon.
Sheila heard the whoosh of the cruiser and thought absently,
'They're really after somebody.'' She turned into her street,
Stephens Road, transformed into a parking lot of cruisers and
emergency vehicles. As she drew closer she realized the yellow
police tape circled her yard. Sheila jumped out of her car, but
Sidney officers blocked her from entering the house. ``You can't go
in,'' they told her. ``I want to see my husband,'' she pleaded.
``You can't go in,'' the officers repeated. ``Did you know a Matt
Hensley?'' they asked. ``I know a Mike Hensley,'' she said. ``He's
someone who attends our church, someone the church was trying to
help.'' Once again, the officers barred her way: ``This is a crime
scene,'' they said. Minutes later, after she learned the truth,
that Mike Hensley had murdered four people, including her husband,
Sheila Wildermuth lost her ability to speak. For weeks she could
only mutter a few words. She has traveled an unfathomable distance
since that day. This is her story. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News).
90-100. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FORFEIT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the war on drugs, one of
the big guns is the state's forfeiture law, which gives police the
power to seize any property _ cars, boats, planes, computers, guns,
or cash _ they believe has been used in a crime. The police need
not charge anyone with a crime to take their property; in fact,
because such seizures are treated as civil matters rather than
criminal, they need even less evidence than they would to arrest
someone. Thanks to this law police in PBC have collected more than
$7 million since 1996, money they can spend on equipment, drug
treatment programs, and complex investigations. After reviewing
more than 600 forfeiture cases, we will examine how this law works.
(Hiaasen, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the first in a three-part series.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON DAILY NEWS FOSTER CARE SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Following is information about a series by the Dayton Daily News
that depicts America's foster-care system as lacking in oversight
while being driven by financial considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are available in two forms: As a CoxNet Focus page,
available by 5 p.m. Friday, that features the best of the series
reduced to one stand-alone page (see bottom of this budget for
information on how to receive that page) and as the following
separate stories, which moved Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All are for release Sunday, Oct. 3, and all have photos.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, please call CoxNet at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-PART1 _ This is the first of four parts on foster
care. This is the overview: Specialized Alternatives for Family and
Youth is an agency that finds, trains and administers a network of
foster parents willing to take in some of the nation's most
troubled youth. But it also operates with little oversight and has
little financial incentive to run quality homes.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-LANDDEALS _ Sidebar to Part 1 of foster care. Running
a multimillion-dollar private foster care agency has brought its
president, Bruce Maag, recognition among his peers. It's also
brought him money. Land deals seem to have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-MAAG _ Sidebar with Part 1 of Foster Care's Castoff
Children, a Dayton Daily News four-part series. Bruce Maag, the
founder and president of a private foster-care agency, surrendered
his license to take kids into his own home just before he pleaded
guilty in 1987 to contributing to the delinquency of a minor. (Eds:
This story originally moved last weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-PART2 _ Lead of part 2 of Foster Care's Castoff
Children series. An independent-living program administered by one
foster-care agency ended up becoming a party house. Teens had
little supervision.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-18 _ Many foster kids slip through the cracks when
they turn 18. Sidebar to Part 2 of Foster Care's Castoff Children.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-WATTS _ Sidebar to Part 2 of Foster Care's Castoff
Kids. Some kids find independent-living programs help them on the
road to self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-PART3 _ Part 3 of Foster Care's Castoff Children
focuses on how governments, agencies and families haggle over the
price of caring for kids.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-CRIMINAL _ Sidebar for day 3 of Foster Care's Castoff
Children. A criminal record doesn't necessarily disqualify you from
being a foster parent.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-PART4 _ Part 4 of the Foster Care's Castoff Children
series. U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, says governmental financial
incentives pose a ``major, major problem'' for the foster-care
system, and an overhaul is needed. But DeWine and others are
skeptical that Congress and the Health and Human Services
Department, which administers the multibillion foster-care program,
will ever bring about reform.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-REGULATION _ Sidebar to Part 4 of the Foster Care's
Castoff Children series is on the way the states handle foster care
regulation (usually a nonprofit business that operates much like a
for-profit business).
</P>
