<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-RELIG-NYT &LR;      10-02 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-RELIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: OPPOSITION TO EXHIBIT IS DEFENSE OF MARY AS ICON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Ohio, Ind.)  (With NY-MUSEUM.) 
(nk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's battle with the Brooklyn
Museum over a painting combining an image of the Virgin Mary with
elephant dung and pornographic photographs is being waged on the
emotionally charged terrain of cherished symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the museum, while citing the ideal of artistic
free expression and their rights under the First Amendment, have
been denounced as ``anti-Catholic'' for including in the exhibition
``Sensation'' a painting called ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' an object
striking (shocking to some) in its juxtaposition of the sacred and
the profane.
</P>
<P>
   The charge of anti-Catholicism is one that would cast the museum
into a dark stream of American cultural history. In its rudest
form, anti-Catholicism meant riots against Irish immigrants in the
1840s, a pledge not to hire Roman Catholics by members of the
American Protective Association a century ago and a voter backlash
against the Democratic presidential candidate Alfred E. Smith, a
Catholic, in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   R. Scott Appleby, director of the Cushwa Center for the Study of
American Catholicism at the University of Notre Dame, said
``anti-Catholicism in the United States has been a reaction to an
immigrant faith that is heavily devotional'' and perceived as
authoritarian and undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, he said, as recognition of American
pluralism has replaced the old ideal of a melting pot, those like
the Catholics aggrieved by the exhibit can appeal to a new ``rules
of the game,'' in which a group can demand respect for the
essential symbols of its identity.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said, ``They're saying, `Look, Jewish people have
successfully appealed to the integrity and the experience of their
culture to avoid defamation of their culture _ why can't Catholics
do the same?'''
</P>
<P>
   He added he did not feel offended by the painting, which he had
seen in news reports, having read that its creator, Chris Ofili,
who was born in Britain of Nigerian parents, used elephant dung in
his work as an African fertility symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the painting has continued to stir interest, others
are speaking up to criticize the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, officials of several New York religious
organizations _ representing Protestants, Catholics, Eastern
Orthodox Christians, Jews and Muslims _ released a statement saying
that while they supported the right to freedom of speech, they
objected ``to the desecration of religious symbols.''
</P>
<P>
   The key word there was symbol. Although the world's major
religions rely on sacred texts to explain their belief systems, it
is their familiar images _ the cross, the Star of David, the
crescent moon, the Hindu god Shiva dancing in a circle of fire _
that most readily convey the elements of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Mark Massa, a Jesuit priest and theology professor at
Fordham University, said that for believers, such symbols actually
share in the holiness they represent. ``There is nothing,
religiously speaking, more powerful than a symbol,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Massa, director of Fordham's American studies program, said he
did not feel shocked or offended by the portrait of Mary in the
museum's show. But he made clear that he understood how people
might perceive the painting, given the context in which the museum
placed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If indeed the image didn't shock, what would it be doing in an
exhibition called `Sensation'?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Mary, the impact would be felt considerably
beyond the Catholic world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to remember,'' the Episcopal Church's
presiding bishop, Frank T. Griswold III, said, ``that Mary is not
the exclusive property of the Roman Catholic Church, or any part of
the Christian community.'' Mary, he noted, is also revered by
Orthodox Christians and many Anglicans, including Episcopalians.
</P>
<P>
   So she is, too, by Muslims, who respect her as mother of Jesus,
a great prophet in Islam.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the Brooklyn exhibition spread, the Council on
American-Islam Relations in Washington began receiving calls. The
council had been considering a statement criticizing the
exhibition, said Ibrahim Hooper, its communications director. ``To
portray Mary in this way is just obscene,'' he said. ``Mary is
highly regarded in Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   In Orthodox Christianity, Mary is called the ``theotokos,'' a
Greek title that means the one who gives birth to God. She is
portrayed in icons closely holding the Christ child.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky, a priest in the Orthodox Church in
America, and a former president of the National Council of
Churches, said Orthodox Christians would ``feel some kinship to
those Roman Catholics'' upset about the exhibition. ``It would
certainly be seen as inappropriate and offensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Popular devotion to Mary has been on the rise during the last
two decades, emphasized by Pope John Paul II and also by trends
outside official church circles. Since 1981, tens of thousands of
people have journeyed to the Bosnian village of Medjugorje, where
several young people have claimed to see a daily vision of Mary.
</P>
<P>
   One place with insight into popular perceptions of Mary is
Dayton University in Ohio, a Catholic institution with a library
housing the world's largest collection of texts and other items
related to Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The Marian Library is home to postage stamps, prayer cards and
wine bottle labels that depict Mary. Among its small statues is one
of Mary dressed in an elaborate Japanese kimono, another in the
garb of a Dutch housewife and a third carved from ebony showing her
in African robes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas A. Thompson, the library's director, said there
has been a freedom among Catholic artists around the world in
``appropriating Mary to certain cultures and local scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, he could think of nothing to compare with
the painting of Mary on display in Brooklyn. ``I've never seen
anything like that,'' he said. ``There's always been a reverence
and a respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
