u i BC-JAPAN-NUKE-ASSESS-NYT     10-02 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUKE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: QUESTIONS FOR JAPAN AFTER NUCLEAR ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A string of embarrassingly unanswered questions
stretched long in the wake of Japan's worst nuclear accident, one
day after the crisis was officially declared over.
</P>
<P>
   Why were workers mixing vastly excessive amounts of enriched
uranium manually rather than with the plant's sophisticated
machines that were meant to ensure precise measurements? Why was no
alarm sounded at the fuel enrichment plant after an accident that
produced 10,000 to 20,000 times normal radiation levels in the
immediate area?
</P>
<P>
   Why was the plant itself not clearly marked as a nuclear
production site and equipped with a battery of anti-radiation and
security measures, even though it is situated in the midst of a
residential area? And finally, why did the government take nearly
12 hours to declare a major emergency in the area and to take
charge of the situation at the highest levels?
</P>
<P>
   But what is even more perplexing is a question underpinning
these and many other of the accident's puzzles: Why did Japan, a
nation that has long played the role of the world's only martyr of
an atomic bomb attack and has ever since made its sensitivity to
nuclear issues a cornerstone of its foreign and domestic policies,
become so lackadaisical in its own use of nuclear energy?
</P>
<P>
   For all of Japan's militant pacifism where nuclear issues are
concerned, the Tokaimura plant _ which has produced hundreds of
tons of highly enriched uranium powder over the years, more than
enough for a large arsenal of crude nuclear weapons _ was not
protected by so much as a high wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have insufficient awareness that they are handling
nuclear energy,'' said Masaru Hashimoto, governor of Ibaraki
prefecture, who likened the scant precautions against accidents to
contempt for human life.
</P>
<P>
   At a bare minimum, Thursday's accident at Tokaimura seems likely
to bring about what critics say is a badly needed, sweeping
overhaul of safety standards for a nuclear power industry that
supplies one-third of Japan's electricity. Already, however, many
here are wondering if a wariness over nuclear hazards born of this
accident will, indeed should, lead to an eventual phasing out of
the industry altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Japan's nuclear power plants were built in the late
1960s and 1970s, and within a decade or so, many of them will be
reaching the end of their useful lives. Few new plants have been
built in recent years, in large part because of growing public
concerns about their safety after a spate of other recent serious
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokaimura disaster, in which three workers were critically
injured by radiation exposure, dozens of others were exposed to
smaller amounts of radiation, and more than 300,000 people were
temporarily confined to their houses will undoubtedly strengthen
this aversion.
</P>
<P>
   If a new generation of plants is not started soon, experts say,
the de facto result will be a steady decline in the nuclear power
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Already there has been a sense of shock in much of the Japanese
news coverage of the incident, as it has become clear that
government regulators have established few safeguards and almost no
protection of the population from dangerous nuclear sites.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the Tokaimura uranium-refining plant not clearly
marked as a dangerous site but its staff lacked proper protective
shields, it had no alarm system, and it had never even been
equipped with a safety manual, according to several Japanese press
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Masajo Ujihara, a board member of JCO, the subsidiary of
Sumitomo Metal Mining Co., was quoted by the Japan Times as saying
that an emergency manual had been written for critical events, but
that no one had ever expected to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Other press accounts on Saturday focused on serious flaws in the
regulatory approval process for nuclear plants like the uranium
fuel processing unit at Tokaimura. The newspaper Mainichi Shimbun
said, for example, that the neighbors of the accident site realized
only belatedly that there were ``no legal regulations'' preventing
the construction of nuclear sites in residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Yomiuri Daily, meanwhile, said that regulatory papers filed
for the plant during construction did not include contingency plans
or a discussion of the possible dangers of a fission reaction. ``A
critical nuclear fission reaction is not feasible under our safety
precautions,'' the quoted documents stated.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance of this kind of pre-emptive assurance now seems
certain to end. But the fact that Japanese people have tolerated
having nuclear plants in residential areas _ and have so long
believed official pledges of the industry's safety even as
accidents have increased _ reflects national realities both
geographic and cultural.
</P>
<P>
   With 126 million people, Japan's territory is only about as
large as California. In a nation so mountainous and crowded,
citizens realize that finding less troublesome sites for
potentially dangerous industries is difficult, if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Japanese are overwhelmingly trustful of their
government, and of authority generally. Although anger was
abundant, voices could also be heard on Friday among the residents
of Tokaimura making allowances for the accident and refusing to
point fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that people were working very hard to fix the problem
throughout the night, so I cannot criticize anybody,'' said Shingo
Otani, a high school student who was interviewed in the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly but surely, people's reactions to things like this are
getting stronger,'' said Osamu Yatabe, a former legislator and
lawyer who has represented citizens in nuclear-related damage
suits. ``But the Japanese notion of rights is not as strong as it
is in some countries, and the national character still makes us
strongly averse to disputes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
