<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-PROFILE03-COX     10-02 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-PROFILE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A good week: McCain, maverick and straight arrow
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATESBURG, S.C. _ The posters decorating the open-air stage
behind chicken magnate Bill Amick's house Tuesday night could have
been for a movie as easily as for a presidential campaign. They
display a photo of a brash young Navy pilot decked out in flight
gear, staring at the camera with a bit of the devil in his eye and
a hint that he he'll have quite a story to tell someday.
</P>
<P>
   The same photo appears on the cover of Sen. John McCain's new
book, ``Faith of My Fathers.'' McCain still owes Random House a
third week on the book tour trail this year, which he must wedge
into his race for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It will be time well spent away from the normal requirements of
a campaign. The story of a son and grandson of admirals, a
rebellious midshipman and hard-living pilot whose character is
forged during 5 1/2 years as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam is
No. 2 this weekend on the New York Times best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator's positions on campaign finance reform and
military spending are as sharply etched as any in this year's
presidential race. But more than for anyone else in the race,
McCain's rationale for candidacy is entwined in his biography,
apart from his political record or the issues over which he differs
with his party's establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk about issues, but you've got to start with
the story,'' said media consultant Greg Stevens, describing the
campaign's upcoming ad strategy as some 2,000 South Carolinians
lined up for barbecue and politics.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case at McCain's campaign kickoff rally in Nashua,
N.H., the day before, a good sprinkling of VFW hats were spotted
among those in attendance. Veterans are a vital component of his
support, which also includes younger Republicans such as South
Carolina House Speaker pro tem Terry Haskins, attracted to his
independent style.
</P>
<P>
   This was the week for McCain to hop around the country on the
announcement tour he postponed in April because of the U.S.
military action in Yugoslavia. He had an entourage of family
members, supporters and reporters aboard a 727 dubbed Maverick 1.
Crowds were good at most stops, and events had fallen his way
before the tour kicked off.
</P>
<P>
   As if they were secretly in his employ, a group of Washington
lobbyists flew to South Carolina the week before McCain arrived to
attack him for supporting campaign finance reform. His book was
doing well. And he'd kicked up a lot of dust by publicly inviting
Pat Buchanan out of the Republican Party after reading his views
about World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The senator who inherited Barry Goldwater's mantle as the GOP's
Arizona maverick needs a lot of such media leverage. Contributions
have picked up since publication of the book, but McCain won't have
anything like the money Gov. George W. Bush and Steve Forbes will
spend in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign has focused its resources on two early-voting
states, New Hampshire and South Carolina, in hopes they can give
him enough of a boost to overtake Bush in the brief primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running for president in South Carolina like he's running
for governor,'' said Trey Walker, his campaign manager in the
Palmetto State. Tuesday, he spoke at a breakfast in Greenville,
flew to Charleston to make another kickoff speech in front of the
USS Yorktown, and on by plane and bus to Saluda County for the
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain has a strong organization headed by
popular former Sen. Warren Rudman, co-chairman of the Concord
Coalition, which shares many of his views on pork barrel spending
and ``soft money.'' In recent weeks he has placed a distant second
to Bush, with numbers in the low teens, in two of three New
Hampshire polls, but his campaign hopes it can expand his support.
</P>
<P>
   Chatting last week with reporters aboard the campaign plane,
cussing about how hard it is to get through the Atlanta airport or
joking about Marines, McCain, 63, seemed easily the most
free-wheeling candidate in a field of often stiff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   He was good off the cuff, fielding several probing questions
from voters at the Greenville breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Republicans do not have the self-discipline necessary to do
what's right, and we've got to eliminate the influence of special
interests,'' he told the GOP faithful. Asked directly about his
``relationship with Jesus Christ,'' he said a person's relationship
with God was ``between that person and God,'' but he joked that he
was the only candidate who had actually served as a preacher,
having filled that role in religious services as a POW.
</P>
<P>
   But the big announcement speech, which he delivered with slight
variations in Nashua and Charleston, was delivered word-for-word
with the text, a token of the military discipline that plays tug of
war with an independent streak in both his biography and his
political profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have passed from a young man to an old one in the service of
my country,'' he says in the closing paragraphs of his stump
speech, ``When my time is over, I want only the satisfaction of
knowing I was true to the faith of our fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   He began the week with a breakfast speech to 4,000 midshipmen at
the U.S. Naval Academy, an institution to which he remains fiercely
loyal while he expresses distaste for the hazing he went through
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whenever you have young men who have too much power
over other young men, there are going to be excesses,'' McCain said
as Maverick 1 headed for another South Carolina stop. He thinks
women have improved the tone of the place.
</P>
<P>
   The joshing, self-deprecating tone in which he talks about his
military service and ordeal as a POW keep the frequent references
to his record from seeming bombastic, and the maverick streak
allows him to come off as staunchly, but not rigidly, conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The independence that sometimes got him in trouble at the
academy has caused McCain to play a contrarian role in issues
ranging from his advocacy of campaign finance reform, on which he
differs sharply with his party's leadership, to his opposition to
ethanol subsidies, a popular expenditure in Iowa _ which, not
coincidentally, doesn't figure heavily in his campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on board with the candidate last week was Federal
Trade Commissioner Orson Swindle, a Georgia native who shared a
cell with McCain in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of McCain's supporters, Swindle argues that McCain,
with his honorable service record and support for campaign finance
reform, has the perfect combination of qualities to be the next
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has every attribute we so desperately need right now,''
Swindle said Monday night at a New York City fund-raiser hosted by
Georgette Mosbacher, McCain's national co-chairwoman, and his
finance chairman, Herb Allison. Some political scenarios have
McCain emerging as the primary challenger to Bush, the
front-runner, in large part because of his broad potential appeal.
But the attributes that cause many independents and Democrats to
say they could vote for McCain don't necessarily serve him well in
states such as South Carolina, where the Republican establishment
traditionally dominates primaries and has already gone largely to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Those attributes also make him a less likely running mate, said
Republican pollster Whit Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a vice presidential candidate, McCain gives new meaning to
the words `off the reservation,''' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Greenville breakfast, McCain referred to the campaign as
``this brief skirmish in the battle of life that we are now engaged
in.'' In a week in which he exuded a happy confidence, it was the
one wistful note, a reminder to himself that there are things
larger than a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has a long way to go, but last week, at least, things were
going his way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
