<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-HATCH-CAMPAIGN-750&AMP;AD     10-02 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATCH-CAMPAIGN-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH IS THE LATEST TO DREAM A SENATOR'S DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the last quarter-century, only one senator, Bob
Dole in 1996, has won his party's nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   But this has not been for lack of trying. Some of the most
prominent senators in both parties have tried for the nomination
and lost badly, among them the Democrats Edward M. Kennedy, John
Glenn and Henry Jackson and the Republicans Howard Baker, Phil
Gramm and Richard Lugar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when Sen. Ernest Hollings of South Carolina was running
a campaign for the Democratic nomination that went nowhere, a
reporter in New Hampshire asked him whether all senators dreamed of
becoming president. ``Every damn one, every damn day,'' Hollings
replied, an observation that he says holds true today.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the prominent senator running seemingly quixotically
for president is Orrin Hatch of Utah, a 65-year-old Republican, the
chairman of the Judiciary Committee, a fixture on the Sunday
television interview programs and a masterly deal-maker with a wide
range of legislative accomplishments over 22 years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hatch finished last among nine contestants in the
Iowa straw poll. He was second to Alan Keyes, the radio talk-show
host, in the Alabama straw poll. They were the only two competing.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has raised barely $1 million, less than 2 percent of the
$56 million collected by the front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas. Tied to Washington by his legislative responsibilities, he
spent only a few days campaigning last month.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Republican circles outside his own campaign staff
believes he stands a chance to win the nomination. Hatch concedes
that his candidacy is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   So why is he running? Here is how he answered that question in
an interview in his Senate office last week:
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most important issue is who's going to appoint the
up to five Supreme Court justices and the 50 percent of the rest of
the judiciary. I'm very concerned about having Al Gore or Bill
Bradley do that. In fact, I'm concerned about having any of the
other Republican candidates do that because none of them have any
experience in this area. I have more experience than all the rest
put together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, it's going to take a conservative with guts to
handle the nation's problems, to solve Social Security and
Medicare, and I'm the conservative with the most guts.''
</P>
<P>
   He is way behind, he said, because he started late, not
announcing his candidacy until July 1. ``Let's face it,'' he went
on, ``most people don't even know I'm in the race. I found that
some of my closest friends in California didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes heart, Hatch said, from his experience in his first
race for the Senate in 1976. When he started running, he was a
lawyer in private practice hardly known around his state. ``All of
a sudden, the dust cleared,'' he said, ``and I was the United
States senator.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, ``He's way ahead in the polls, but he's a mile wide
and an inch deep,'' said Hatch, who tends to talk about himself in
the third person. ``Orrin Hatch is 40 miles deep and 10 inches
wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch continued on Bush: ``He's a very fine person. I love his
parents. But I'm concerned because you have a man here who has four
years of experience in a constitutionally weak governorship. Does
that qualify him to go up against an Al Gore or a Bill Bradley?''
</P>
<P>
   Here is Hatch's take on some of his other competitors:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona: ``Can you name very many pieces of
legislation he's done? Has he been able to bring all sides
together? He's the author of the McCain-Feingold bill. That bill
would wreck the Republican party.'' (The bill, which McCain is
sponsoring with Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., would eliminate
unrestricted donations to political parties.)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole: ``I wish her well. I don't think there are very
many people who believe she's going to be our nominee for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes: ``I don't think money is a qualification for being
president of the United States. A lot of us have worked very hard
to make sure this party sheds the image that it's the party of the
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's chief strategist, Sal Russo, a veteran of Republican
political wars who is based in California, said front-runners in
their first campaigns for president generally faltered. Hatch's
intention, Russo said, is to be around to pick up the pieces if
Bush founders.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Hatch said, ``it's going to come down to George
Bush, John McCain and myself,'' and the party will turn to him
because of his experience.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Hatch's experience is entirely legislative, and when he
talks, he sounds more like a legislator than a presidential
candidate. This is how he described his ability to work with
Democrats:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a fellow that put together the Drug Price Competition
and Patent Term Restoration Act, the Hatch-Waxman bill. Here's a
fellow that put together the child care development block grant,
the Hatch-Dodd bill. Here's a fellow that put together the capital
gains rate reduction, the Hatch-Lieberman bill. Here's a fellow
that put together the Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act
with Tom Harkin. Here's a fellow that put together countless
legislative enactments with none other than the bugaboo of all
conservatives, Ted Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The other senator from Utah, Robert Bennett, who is also a
Republican, said legislative experience did not always prepare
politicians well for presidential campaigns. ``A campaign is an
executive-oriented exercise,'' Bennett explained. ``If you've spent
years working out deals behind the scenes, it is not the same as
making an executive decision at high noon.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why so many senators have failed to win their
party's nominations for president. Technically, even Dole was not a
senator when he was nominated. With the nomination sewed up, he
resigned from the Senate in June 1996, a month before the
Republican nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   But it should not be surprising, Bennett said, that so many
senators try to become president. ``In the Senate,'' he said, ``you
have access to people who have great power. And the closer you get
to people who have great power, the easier it is to convince
yourself that you're as smart as he is, and you say to yourself, `I
can see these issues as clearly as he can, maybe clearer, and if he
can do the job, certainly I can.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hatch, he is hedging his bet. In addition to his
presidential campaign, he is running, as Utah law permits, for
re-election to a fifth term in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
