<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Oct. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mild air will linger another day near the northeast coast as a
front marking the leading edge of a very cool air mass slows down
over the interior Northeast. Sunshine will mix with increasing
clouds east of the northern Appalachians where afternoon
temperatures will be above seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, cooler air will be accompanied by
scattered light showers near the eastern Great Lakes. Steadier rain
will fall to the north of a low pressure center as it moves east
from the central Mississippi Valley early Sunday. The rain will
spread into the Northeast and Middle Atlantic States overnight and
on Monday as the low travels along the slow-moving frontal zone.
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather will persist over the Southeast. Most areas will
have ample sun, but a few afternoon showers will develop near the
southern Appalachians as well as in central and southern Florida as
more humid air spreads into these regions.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will cover the central and northern Plains
and the Great Lakes states. Plenty of clouds, patchy showers and
cool breezes from the northeast will add to the chill of the day
across much of the Middle West. Some high-elevation snow showers
will occur where moist winds ascend the sloping terrain in parts of
the western Plains. Meanwhile, central and southern Texas will stay
sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Mild, dry air will prevail in most areas west of the crest of
the Rocky Mountains. The day will begin with low clouds near the
California coast. Otherwise, sunshine will be plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Change of Pace
</P>
<P>
   Autumn weather is a marked change of pace. Snow fell around
Denver on Tuesday, but temperatures rebounded to near 80 on Friday.
On Saturday, another chilly air mass was poised north of the Denver
area. Weather moves about twice as fast at this time of year
compared with the summer. During the autumn, the deepening arctic
chill advances southward from Canada as tropical warmth clings to
the southernmost United States. This temperature contrast is the
fuel for the jet-stream winds that steer the parade of weather
systems marching to an ever-quickening drum beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
