<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-ASTRODOME-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A NEW HOUSTON, SPACE-AGE ASTRODOME BECAME ANTIQUATED
</HEADLINE>
   (With ASTRODOME-FAREWELL, filed in ``s'' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On the night 35 years ago before the Astrodome was
unveiled to the world, Tal Smith walked onto the field and stared
at the lights twinkling beneath the great curved roof of steel and
glass. He stood inside the huge air conditioned bowl, surrounded by
nearly 50,000 empty seats, and beheld the artificial wonder of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Astrodome would later be compared to the
``working end of a gigantic roll-on deodorant.'' Never mind that
baseball purists would later blame the Dome for many of the modern
ills of the game. In an opening night exhibition with the Yankees
on April 9, 1965, President Lyndon B. Johnson watched Mickey Mantle
hit the first home run, and the nation, like Smith, seemed
astonished at the world's first indoor coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was truly a revolutionary venture,'' said Smith, now the
president of the Houston Astros. ``It wasn't just a new ballpark.
There were people who would line up to tour the building even
without an event. They would marvel at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once promoted as the Eighth Wonder of the World, the Astrodome
is now a relic, as outdated as a polyester leisure suit. On Sunday,
the Astros will play their last regular season game at the
Astrodome before moving next season to a new, state-of-the-art
downtown ballpark. Mammoth enough to contain an 18-story building,
the Dome was a monument to the Texan appetite for big things and an
emblem of a colorful era when men like the stadium's eccentric
creator, Judge Roy Hofheinz, reshaped Houston and Texas through
will and money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Astrodome will stand all but abandoned, a monstrous,
climate-controlled white elephant that has succumbed not only to
the changing economics of sports but to the changing expectations
of what a building must do to hold our attention.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the NASA Space Center, the Astrodome transformed
Houston in the 1960s from a big city backwater; the Dome became the
world's biggest stage. When Bobby Riggs challenged Billie Jean King
to the ``Battle of the Sexes'' in tennis, in 1973, only the sheer
mass of the Astrodome could do justice to the comic magnitude of
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of a sense of loss as we abandon this
thing we were so proud of,'' said Stephen Klineberg, a sociologist
at the University of Houston. ``It was the most exciting thing that
had ever happened to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium, the $250 million Enron Field, says as much
about Houston today as the Astrodome did a generation ago.
Fashioned with a retractable roof, it has real grass, and it joins
many new ballparks in evoking baseball's past.
</P>
<P>
   Named for a gas company, Enron Field bespeaks a more generic,
corporate face of Houston, the nation's fourth largest city. If the
Astrodome attracted world attention (and a sniff of scorn), Enron
Field's ambitions seem more prosaic: It will make a lot of money
for the Astros, provide a more intimate setting for baseball and,
city officials hope, spur redevelopment of the east side of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the sports industry,'' Smith conceded, ``the economics
dictate. Buildings become obsolete because they can't generate the
same revenues as in other facilities.'' He added, ``It's
regrettable, but it has been 35 years. It had a great run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome will not be demolished, the fate reserved next
year for one of its imitators, the Kingdome in Seattle. But its
future is muddled at best. The Astrodome has only one big tenant
left, the Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo, which is held each
February. But even the rodeo has hinted that it, too, might leave
if Houston attracts a new professional football team and with it, a
new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The same Astrodome where Elvis sang and Billy Graham preached
could wind up as a bloated hall for trade shows. ``I don't think
that any Hofheinz ever stood in the way of progress in the name of
nostalgia,'' reflected Fred Hofheinz, a two-term mayor in the 1970s
who was his father's chief aide during the construction of the
Astrodome. But, he added, ``I do want to see it survive.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   With its serrated skyline and knot of interstate highways,
Houston today is a vast sprawl that seems far removed from the city
that Roy Hofheinz dominated in the 1950s and 1960s. A cocksure
impresario who fancied cigars and any other totem of opulence,
Hofheinz was reputed to sleep only when bored: He was a lawyer at
19, a state legislator at 22, the Harris County judge at 24, a
millionaire in business by his 30s, and at 40 he was elected mayor,
serving two terms.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, the judge, as he was always known, took control of
Houston's efforts to attract a major league baseball team. He was
fascinated by the notion of building a cooled, domed shopping mall
and surmised that air conditioning could be the salvation for
baseball in heat-choked Houston as well. It was a toss-up as to
which local endeavor was considered more incredible: NASA's efforts
to put a man on the moon or Hofheinz's plan to build a coliseum
where men would play baseball indoors.
</P>
<P>
   He did it, adopting the futuristic glint of the space program by
renaming the three-year-old Colt 45s the Astros (the other choice
was Stars). Members of the grounds crew wore orange space suits. A
scoreboard flashing electronic lights (and advertising) dominated
the outfield. A buzzing capacity crowd watched the Astros beat the
Yankees 2-1 in extra innings as a 6,600-ton air conditioning system
chilled the arena to 72 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can ever see this,'' the judge had said the day before
the game, ``and go back to Kalamazoo, Chicago, New York, you name
it, and still think this town is bush league, that this town is
Indian territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of the Astrodome, the judge realized, was part of
the sell. He built his own five-story apartment/playhouse above
right field, complete with a two-story presidential suite, a circus
room, a medieval chapel, a barber shop and a bowling alley. He
built smaller suites, the forebears of today's luxury suites, for
rental to corporations or wealthy individuals. On opening night,
Fred Hofheinz fetched bowl after bowl of chocolate ice cream for
Johnson, a Texan, as he admired the presidential suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the quintessential salesman,'' Hofheinz said of his
father. The Astrodome ``was made up like Disneyland in order to
make it something people talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball traditionalists would come to despise the Astrodome and
the artifice it brought to the game. The field itself, initially
made of grass and later sawdust, eventually was replaced by a
carpet patented as Astroturf. To the judge, the turf was one of the
Dome's many wonders; his ground crew jauntily vacuumed it in their
space suits. But artificial turf was derided as a hazard to players
and a blaspheme against the pastoral history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Fox, an architectural historian who teaches at Rice
University and the University of Houston, said the Astrodome was an
``immensely important'' building in the mid-20th century, if mostly
as a triumph of engineering rather than architecture. ``It is one
of the great monuments of American hubris in the 1960s in this kind
of sense of no limits,'' he said, adding graciously, ``It is not a
tremendously refined work of architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox noted that the Dome played an unexpected role in the
evolution of Houston. When construction costs ran over budget, the
judge and city officials called a second bond referendum. With
opposition growing, the judge lobbied the city's growing, if
largely disenfranchised, block of black voters, promising that
blacks could attend all events at the Dome and also could work
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played a key role in the desegregation of public facilities
in Houston,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the city's population divided fairly equally among
blacks, whites and Latinos, Houston has a black mayor, Lee Brown.
Klineberg, the sociologist, noted that as Houston has matured, the
business and political climate dominated by Roy Hofheinz and a
small number of other white leaders has changed markedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a radically different kind of economy and a new kind
of business leadership and a multicultural environment where
political discussions involve a much wider range of people,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Charles Savino, an executive with the Greater Houston
Partnership, said that the judge's can-do spirit lived on in local
leaders like Bob McNair, who is trying to lure a new professional
football team and build a new stadium. But, Savino said, Houston is
a different place now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of becoming more like the rest of the country,''
Savino said, which might make an apt epitaph for the Astrodome.
Over the years similar stadiums, some larger, were built in other
cities. The awe and wonder wore off: In 1966, more than 550,000
people paid to tour the Astrodome. By 1998, the number had fallen
to 112,000.
</P>
<P>
   The judge lived in the Dome for five years after his first wife
died, but he suffered a stroke, moved out and eventually sold the
team.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, after the Astros and the Dodgers finish the game, a
ceremony is planned to honor the judge's stadium. The Astros might
make the playoffs, meaning at least one more game, but Sunday is
being treated as the farewell. Older players will congregate, and
Willie Nelson will sing ``Turn Out the Lights.'' Fred Hofheinz will
stand on the field he helped build and say goodbye as a living link
to his father. ``He was very proud of that building,'' he said.
``It was the pinnacle of his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
