<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-PEDIATRICS-NYT &LR;      10-02 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PEDIATRICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PEDIATRICS, A LESSON IN MAKING USE OF EXPERIMENTAL PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SCI-CLINICAL-TESTS) 
(nk) 
 By GINA KOLATA and KURT EICHENWALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is a model for an effective way to handle experimental
procedures, it is the world of pediatric cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In that arena, most doctors refuse to offer such treatments
outside clinical trials, insurance companies usually pick up the
tab and experimental procedures are tested quickly, before they
reach the marketplace. The result is that the procedures that work
are adopted widely; those that do not are quickly abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Why the difference from adult medicine? The credit, in large
part, goes to pediatric oncologists. They have organized themselves
into two major consortiums that enroll virtually every child in a
clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups agreed to sponsor only credible studies that
truly advanced knowledge of the field _ quashing the ``me-too''
phase 2 research that proliferates in other medical specialties.
With such quality control in place, the pediatricians were able to
successfully lobby health insurance companies to pay for medical
care in clinical trials. The companies generally refuse to pay for
experimental procedures offered outside trials.
</P>
<P>
   The pediatricians have good reason to unite behind clinical
trials. With comparatively few children getting cancer, the number
of available test subjects was already severely limited. Doctors
convinced each other that it was better for the children to test
treatments promptly than to provide them, untested, to every comer.
</P>
<P>
   The results are heartening. While just 1 percent of adult cancer
patients enroll in clinical trials, 60 percent of pediatric cancer
patients do. Cancer specialists maintain that the consequences are
clear: Progress is much faster in pediatric cancer than it is in
cancer that strikes adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine why adult oncologists don't follow the same
route,'' said Dr. Kenneth Lazarus, a pediatric cancer specialist in
San Antonio. ``If you take all the cancers that were incurable in
the late 1960s, nearly all are curable now. It's dramatic what's
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the pediatric world, even bone marrow transplants were tested
promptly. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, at the very time the
procedure was being widely sold for adult cancer patients,
pediatric oncologists began giving it to children with
neuroblastoma, a cancer of the nervous system. The cancer appears
in just 500 children each year. But its effects can be devastating,
striking toddlers from 2{ to 4 years old and often spreading to the
bones, where it can cause excruciating pain before killing the
child.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as transplants appeared as a possibility, the Children's
Cancer Group, one of the national consortiums of pediatric cancer
specialists, began a randomized clinical trial. The group began the
trial in January 1991; within five years, it had reached the
enrollment goal of 545 children. And even though there was a belief
among some pediatric cancer specialists that bone marrow
transplants would be more effective than standard chemotherapy for
these children, there was virtually no market for the procedure
outside the clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have trouble finding children to enroll,'' said Dr.
Archie Bleyer, the chairman of the Children's Cancer Group. In
fact, he said, ``the trial was actually completed ahead of
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now finished, and the results show what the doctors had
hoped _ that bone marrow transplants do improve survival for
children with neuroblastoma.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary success of clinical trials in pediatric cancer
would not have been possible without the cooperation of health
insurance companies, cancer specialists say. Unlike the situation
in adult cancer, where companies have refused to pay for patients
receiving experimental procedures in clinical trials, the same
companies routinely pay for children in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Radtky, stem cell transplant coordinator at Riley Hospital
for Children in Indianapolis, said that the insurance companies
were usually cooperative. ``In five years and 200 patients, by and
large, I have had 5 percent really problem cases, with insurance
companies denying it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance companies even go as far as to use the
reimbursement structure to push children into studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen contracts that said that if it is not a qualified
trial being offered at a qualified center, then it is not
covered,'' said Dr. Andrew Kelahan, the chief operating officer of
the Coalition of National Cancer Cooperative Groups, which
represents the major groups of medical institutions that conduct
cancer clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   One way to encourage the testing of experimental procedures for
adults might be for insurance companies to institute a similar
system, some academic doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   But insurance companies alone are unlikely to change the system
of marketing untested procedures to adults.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, working with the Coalition of National Cooperative
Groups, United Healthcare, which provides health insurance for 13
million Americans, worked out an arrangement to nudge adults into
clinical trials. Dr. Lee Newcomer, a senior vice president for
health policy at United Healthcare, explained: ``If there was a new
treatment out, we would pay for it under the trial scenario. But if
someone said they wanted to give it off of the trial we would say
no.''
</P>
<P>
   But by a year later, nothing had changed. ``It's not working,''
Newcomer said. So far, only a dozen patients have entered clinical
trials. Moreover, he added, most of those patients were never even
told by their doctors that a clinical trial was an option. They
found out about the trials and enrolled despite, not because of,
their doctor's advice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Newcomer said, ``the onus is on the physician community.''
Doctors, he said, may say they believe in putting patients in
trials, but when offered an incentive and an opportunity, ``it
doesn't happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN DESPERATE DAYS, METS KNOW THE SCORE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say this about the New York Mets: They are not a
bunch of couch potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   With their fate partly out of their control, they did not
unilaterally hunker down on the clubhouse sofas, biting their nails
and rooting for colleagues on the Brewers and the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   After 160 games of a 162-game season, the Mets woke up Saturday
depending on the kindness of fellow union members. They seemed
vaguely embarrassed about their plight, and did not want to indulge
too openly in cheering for other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so slim,'' said Robin Ventura, Friday night's hero, about
the Mets' chances. ``You don't know what's going to happen. You
just play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could not do anything about games Saturday afternoon.
The Reds would play outdoors in Milwaukee's County Stadium at 1
p.m., Eastern time, and the Astros would play host to the Dodgers
at 4 p.m. in the cavern of the Astrodome, soon to be abandoned for
a real ballpark. Then the Mets would play the Pirates in Shea
Stadium shortly after 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, once again, baseball had lucked out with genuine
old-fashioned excitement in the final weekend _ a three-way
scramble, in three vastly disparate corners of North America, with
two teams going to the postseason and one skulking home.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Mets have squandered a four-game lead for the
wild-card spot, which they enjoyed only two weeks ago, they do not
display any swaggering sense of entitlement. Everything must be a
struggle. They act as if they deserve this torture _ which they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun at times,'' Bobby Valentine said after Friday's 3-2
victory in the 11th inning. ``Nerve-racking at other times.''
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly nerve-racking Friday when Valentine could
not communicate with his bullpen because of electronic failures.
Valentine, who is constantly wired into the Internet, could not get
the telephone line or two sets of walky-talkies to operate, so he
sent bench players or staff members scurrying through the catacombs
to keep in touch. Maybe he should have sent e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard provided updates, every half-inning, from the two
vital games out of town. While Pittsburgh sent out left-handed
Scott Sauerbeck for his third inning of relief in the 11th, the
lights flickered from Milwaukee, indicating the Brewers had scored
two runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the players maintain the fiction that they do not
watch the scoreboard. Of course they do. They are a captive
audience in the dugout or the bullpen. It is their livelihood. How
could they not?
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt Franco said it was all tied up,'' Valentine conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston saw the two runs go up as he loosened up to
pinch-hit. He decided the best way to enjoy the gift would be to
get a hit, which he did, soon scoring the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Mets calmed down from their celebration, they did not
necessarily hang on every pitch as the Reds-Brewers game lurched
onward. The game, shown on several televisions in the Mets'
spacious clubhouse, had a tenuous edge, because of the sight of
umbrellas in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Mets went about their business, seemingly oblivious
to the game that would decide if they were temporarily one or two
games behind the Reds. They already were down to one game behind
the Astros, courtesy of the Dodgers' 5-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Without glancing at the television, Ventura talked to reporters.
Ventura, who has been playing with a gimpy knee, but will not
discuss it, was in demand because of his home run early and then
his game-winning single off a left-handed pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to win all your games,'' he said simply. ``You have
to show up. We've had some tough games. It's nice to win one like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Mets, who had family and friends waiting, dressed
and strolled out into the parking lot. John Franco, who had one of
his nightmare relief appearances, stood around in his skivvies,
watching the action from drizzly Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tag up, baby,'' shouted Darryl Hamilton after a Brewer flied
out with a runner on second. The runner did advance, but the
Brewers did not score in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the 10th, Marquis Grissom of Milwaukee made a
lovely acrobatic catch in center with two runners on base to end
the inning. To let off steam, Edgardo Alfonzo let out a highly
appropriate English vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the 10th, Ron Belliard smacked a single to give
the Brewers a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh,'' Hamilton shouted across the clubhouse, where no more
than 10 Mets were watching.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them were on their way home or to a late snack. They had
put themselves in this needy position, and did not want to look
like supplicants. But they knew the score. Ballplayers always know
the score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
