<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS GOD ROOTING FOR DEION TO DANCE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, TEXAS - In ``USA Today,'' No. 21 of the Dallas Cowboys
is pictured standing with feet together, arms spread, eyes turned
to Heaven. He looks like he might ascend at any moment. ``DEION'S
BACK!'' the caption reads.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer shot a glance at the FOX/NFL ad promoting today's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Jake, I asked, can you say ``Hallelujah!''?
</P>
<P>
   Plummer looked unamused.
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders is back. His toe healed, the minister of the First
United Every Pa$$ Is Mine Holy Punt Return Gospel Church rejoins
the Cowboys today and says he is praying that Plummer will throw
him the football.
</P>
<P>
   If Deion's prayer is answered, and he scores, the Cowboys
cornerback will perform his new ``Holy Ghost dance.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what a ``Holy Ghost dance`` looks like, as it's
never been attempted in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is the flamboyant star will delight Cowboys fans with
some kind of celebratory seizure that would shame Jerry Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas Morning News'' will have 14 photographers on hand
to record the moment, should it happen.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to Jake (who has thrown nine interceptions) was for
him to pray that he ``doesn't'' throw the ball to Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe Jake's prayer will offset Deion's, assuming his
prayer carries equal weight. Jake shook his head. ``Like `Who does
God like better, him or me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders is born again. He found religion a couple years
ago, about the same time his wife filed for divorce. A new man, he
turned his life around. Sanders told the world, ``Fornication is no
longer my drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But what are we to think of an athlete who prays for
interceptions? Is Deion _ Prime Time _ truly giving all the glory
to God? Or is Deion primarily promoting Deion?
</P>
<P>
   Has religiosity become his shtick?
</P>
<P>
   Sanders loves the limelight as few athletes will admit. Remember
when Deion played for the Atlanta Falcons ``and'' the Braves? One
Sunday he flew to Miami and played in an NFL game. Afterward, he
jetted back to Pittsburgh for Game 5 of the National League
playoffs. No athlete had done anything like that. Who would
``want'' to, given the inconvenience, and quality of airline food.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he pulled double duty out of his commitment and
loyalty to the Falcons and Braves. But skeptics suggested his
whirlwind stadium-to-helicopter-to-plane-to-limo-to-ballpark
odyssey was a self serving publicity stunt designed to make
national news and to satisfy his giant ego, which it did.
</P>
<P>
   Many NFL players walk the straight and narrow, witnesses for
God. After Friday's practice, about 20 Cardinals knelt in a circle
and joined hands in prayer. But no one prayed for an interception,
or 100 yards rushing. No one jumped up and danced for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   If Deion picks off a Plummer pass and scores a touchdown what
does the event mean? How do we interpret it? Was it God's Will? I
don't think so. Does God influence the outcome of games? Does he
play favorites?
</P>
<P>
   Trey Junkin, the Cardinals veteran long snapper, has a favorite
cartoon. It depicts a football player, head bowed, kneeling beneath
a goalpost. From above, a voice says, `Gee, Timmy, I'd like to help
but my money is on the ``other'' team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything in The Book about `Thou shalt kick thy
neighbor's (behind),'' Junkin said. ``The God I pray to doesn't
care about football.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's an important game. A division game. But surely
Almighty God has more important things to do this Sabbath than
watch the Cowboys and Cardinals. As Dave McGinnis said, in
agreement, ``He ain't dialed into FOX.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
