<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PLAYOFFS-100     10-02 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PLAYOFFS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE DID NOT CHANGE, BUT PLAYERS' EXECUTION DID 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Hurricane Floyd raged through eastern states last month, Jack
McKeon sat in the comfort of his office at Cinergy Field in
Cincinnati and made a bold prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a gut feeling,'' the Reds' manager said, ``that we're
either going to win our division or we're going to beat out the
Mets for the wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets, the Reds and the Houston Astros prepared Friday for
their final series of the regular season, McKeon denied that he had
made that declaration as a way of needling the Mets and their
manager, Bobby Valentine. The 68-year-old McKeon, the major
leagues' oldest manager, has been known to do things to annoy
Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you looked at the schedule,'' McKeon related, ``who did
you figure that you could beat? They had to play the Braves six
times. I was just doing some math, figuring the Braves would cool
them off. It was no disrespect for the Mets. Houston was four games
ahead of you. The best shot for you is the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day McKeon offered his view of the races, Sept. 16, his
team was three games behind the Astros in the National League
Central and two and one-half games behind the Mets in the wild-card
race. The Mets subsequently lengthened their lead over the Reds to
four games with only 12 games to play, but then they encountered
the Braves, as McKeon was counting on.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves beat the Mets three times in Atlanta, then two more
times in three games at Shea Stadium, all in the space of 10 days.
In between, the Mets lost three games in Philadelphia to a team
that had lost 23 of its previous 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is there was some carry-over effect from the Braves
series,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said of the
Philadelphia disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Their seven successive losses and eight defeats in nine games
sent the Mets plummeting out of the wild-card lead and placed them
on the precipice of extinction from the playoffs they had seemed so
certain to make.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves. They are the common denominator of the Mets'
end-of-season failures this season and last. Last season, the Mets
had a one-game wild-card lead with five games to play, then lost
two games to the Montreal Expos and three to the Braves. Last
season, the Braves beat the Mets nine times in 12 games; this
season, the Braves beat the Mets nine times in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I thought we just weren't quite good enough, but
this year I don't think that's the case,'' Phillips said.
``Everybody can come up with their own version about why it is. My
version about why it happened is guys started trying too much. Then
the question is why did that happen. I don't know the answer to
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking an explanation for the Mets' reprise of their 1998
demise, which this time also cost them a chance to unseat the
Braves as division champions, some people inside baseball and out
look for dark, hidden reasons, motivated in no small part by the
widespread dislike of Valentine. But no one was citing managerial
deficiencies in Valentine as the Mets were gaining their first 92
victories and compiling the best won-lost record in the league for
the previous three and one-half months.
</P>
<P>
   Two club officials said that in assessing the job a manager has
done, they look for signs that he changed his modus operandi during
a losing streak. In Valentine's case, they said, they found he had
not. A manager's strategy can always be questioned, but Valentine
didn't make any outrageously different moves in trying to beat the
Braves and the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can argue forever about a manager's moves,'' Mike Piazza
said. ``But whenever a manager makes a move, the guy he puts in
that place has to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   From June 6, when three of the team's coaches were fired and the
Mets ended an eight-game losing streak, to the start of the series
in Atlanta on Sept. 21, they had a 65-30 record, a .684 winning
percentage that would compute to 111 victories for an entire
season. During that long stretch, the team's regulars and part-time
players executed.
</P>
<P>
   Late in that impressive period were two series with Houston, the
Central Division leader. The Mets won four of the six games. At the
same time, the Reds played the Braves and lost five of six. The
Reds dropped only one additional game behind the Astros but tumbled
from one and one-half to four games behind the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves giveth and the Braves taketh. Three weeks later,
the Mets arrived in Atlanta only one game behind the Braves, and
they then lost seven straight with the lineup's seven .300 hitters
batting a collective .211. The Mets scored 15 runs in those games.
In the two games they played before the losing streak began, they
had scored 19 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a team whose offensive style is working the count and
taking pitches, waiting to get into a hitter's count and getting a
pitch to hit,'' Phillips said. ``The Braves don't give you the
luxury to work the count that way. They throw strikes. Because we
didn't score and didn't hit, I think we changed our approach a
little bit and got overaggressive. Even in Philadelphia, we were in
pitchers' counts all the time. We were swinging early in the
count.''
</P>
<P>
   A National League scout who has shadowed the Mets closely in
recent weeks did not agree with the general manager's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My charts don't show that,'' the scout said of the early
swings. ``I'm always looking for that. I look for patterns, and I
didn't see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the explanation, as the Mets struggled to score runs,
they began pressing more. That's a natural reaction in baseball
slumps, but it's the opposite of what players should do. ``It's
unfortunate when it happens at the end because it becomes your
legacy,'' Phillips said of the losing streak. ``Because it's the
end, it makes you feel that much more desperate to stop it. It
causes you to try harder, relax less, be more aggressive and chase
pitches. It's one of those cyclical things that feed on a club.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets struggled and staggered, the Reds reeled off six
consecutive victories, including one in Houston in the first game
of a two-game series last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would have thought we'd be sitting here
with three days to go with 95 wins,'' said McKeon, whose team's $33
million payroll is half the size of the Mets'.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected the Reds to be in any race, and McKeon has
played down their presence in both races. ``We haven't discussed
the playoffs or anything the last month,'' he said. ``We just play
day to day. All we preach is have fun, relax, go out and enjoy
yourself. We haven't mentioned the Astros and the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' plight became so grave last weekend in Philadelphia
that after their second loss there Valentine made a strange
proclamation for a manager. ``If we don't go to the playoffs,'' he
told reporters, ``I shouldn't come back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was trying to be a lightning rod for his players,
deflecting attention from them and piercing the mushrooming
pressure; maybe he was doing what he often does, making the
development about himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also tried meetings, one run by Valentine, another by
the players. Nothing worked, including most of Valentine's in-game
moves.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game in Philadelphia, the Mets led, 2-1, in the
eighth inning when Valentine summoned Armando Benitez, the team's
often unhittable closer, with two out and one runner on base.
Benitez gave up two hits, and the Mets were on their way to a 3-2
loss. Valentine critics questioned his choice of Benitez instead of
John Franco to pitch to a left-handed batter.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his selection of Benitez, the manager said Friday
night: ``Every single time the rest of my life in that situation,
Armando pitches. It's the most ridiculous thought in the world that
anyone else should pitch in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he made only one move during the streak that he
might like to have taken back. It was when he had Bobby Bonilla bat
for Rey Ordonez in the eighth inning with the bases loaded, one out
and Atlanta ahead, 3-2. Terry Mulholland, a left-hander against
whom Bonilla had batted .351 in their careers, struck him out. The
Mets did not score in the inning and lost, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the one building Rey's RBI thing the whole time, and
I just let my head take over from my gut,'' Valentine said. ``Most
of the rest of the time I've allowed my gut to rule. It was just my
eyes saying I'm not sure if this is right, but these are really
good statistics. I have to go with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-3 game against the Braves last Thursday night, the Mets
had a runner at first and two out in the 10th inning. Valentine
needed a pinch-hitter when Mulholland came into the game, and this
time he used Jay Payton, a right-hand-hitting rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a better chance of getting a hit,'' Valentine
said. ``That was my gut.'' But Payton grounded to second base for
the third out, and the Braves won the game in the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours earlier, the Mets had halted their losing
streak, emerging from their two-runs-a-game rut and crushing the
Braves, 9-2, behind Al Leiter. Afterward, it was noted that there
was a remarkable similarity to a Leiter victory over the Yankees in
June that started the three-and-one-half-month spree. Did Leiter
see a sign in the outcome?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``the sign that it started a four-game
winning streak last time, and we have four games to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets didn't duplicate the June winning streak. The loss
to the Braves dropped the Mets two games behind the Reds and the
Astros, who were tied for the wild-card spot as well as the Central
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The loss also shoved the Mets to the brink of elimination. If
they lost Friday night and the other two teams won, the Mets would
be excused from any additional October games. But the exact
opposite occurred, and the Mets, now only one game back after play
ended Friday, had life for another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
