<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS ON IDLE, SOLDIERS STALK PREY BY NIGHT; DILI IS THEIRS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ The objective was the Hotel Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Crouching in double file, halting on whispered commands, the
military patrol, part of the Australian-led international
peacekeeping force now cautiously gaining a grip in East Timor,
moved cautiously through the night, its weapons at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees lounging in looted chairs watched curiously from their
lean-tos across the street. Three youths played a tambourine in the
orange light of a street lamp. A child rode by on a tricycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, mister,'' called the child. ``How are you?'' The patrol
halted and took defensive positions outside the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a seafront cluster of single-story rooms, it
was packed with refugees and humming with the late-evening babble
of small children.
</P>
<P>
   Two armored vehicles armed with .50-caliber machine guns waited
at a short distance, their motors idling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the sites we like to keep an eye on,'' said
Cpl. Andrew Becker, the commander of the patrol. ``As you know, the
militia don't fare that well in the hills. They like to come back
to town to places like this.''
</P>
<P>
   All across Dili _ and now in an increasing number of towns
around East Timor _ patrols like this are constantly on the move as
they attempt to intimidate and flush out the irregular militias
that have wreaked havoc here.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-trained militias with their grab bag of odd weaponry
terrorized the unarmed population with little difficulty. But in
the last two weeks, they have not challenged the firepower of these
disciplined foreign soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers' commander, Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, said his
troops had moved at a careful pace to secure Dili before beginning
to fan out through the rest of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we go, we stay,'' he said. ``Where we seek to control,
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker's patrol moved into the grounds of the Hotel Dili, in
battle-ready groups of three, ducking under lines of washing,
peering into sheds and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, overcrowded rooms, stripped of furniture and doors by
looters, were filled with blinding light from uncontrolled electric
power. Their ceiling fans whirred endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, situated beside a former militia headquarters, had
been the site of two brief attacks when it was filled with foreign
journalists in the week before the Aug. 30 referendum in which East
Timorese voted to become independent of Indonesia, which invaded
this territory in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   A room was inspected. Young women giggled and a small child
burst into tears at the sight of giant men with their strange,
protruding night-vision goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the seafront road, the soldiers proceeded toward the
port, turning their heads slowly from left to right in silent
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The goggles, the soldiers said, have transformed the art of
night patrols, turning a mere man into an omniscient Cyclops.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these streets we crossed,'' said Becker. ``I could see
right down to the end of them. For example, if some guys approached
us, we could see them at 150 meters quite plainly. And they
wouldn't even know we were there until they were 20 meters away.''
</P>
<P>
   Another soldier said, ``People say the next war will be won by
the side that carries the most batteries'' for their goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Armored carriers drove up with a grunt and the soldiers
clambered aboard, nine to a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the patrol was in the outskirts of Dili, the
long antennae of the vehicles slapping and banging against
overhanging tree branches.
</P>
<P>
   Now the night was dark and silent, the air cooling as the patrol
headed into the hills, the clamor of refugees and the ugly smell of
a burned and filthy city fading behind it.
</P>
<P>
   The objective here was a prominent statue of Jesus Christ,
dedicated in this heavily Roman Catholic territory in 1996 by
former President Suharto in what many East Timorese saw as a
calculated insult.
</P>
<P>
   The statue is 89 feet high, symbolizing Indonesia's insistence
that East Timor was its 27th province. And its arms are raised not
toward the town below but toward largely Muslim Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The area around the statue provided a base for some of the most
feared of Indonesia's soldiers, a unit that liked to dress in black
and strike terror in Dili in the guise of what locals call ``black
ninjas.'' But now the hillsides seemed empty. The two armored
vehicles sped up the winding road in darkness and near silence,
their drivers guided by infrared sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Through the goggles the shimmering hillsides seemed covered in
frost. The port, now miles away, glittered invitingly, giving no
visible hint of the recent terror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
