<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ALNOTES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller slams Boston's Martinez
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   A gratifying aspect of mound maestro Pedro Martinez's
development has been his shedding his reputation as a head-hunter.
That news apparently never got to Orioles manager Ray Miller, who
went on a tirade after Martinez hit Brady Anderson in the back
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching him do it for 10 years,'' Miller ranted.
``He doesn't have the guts to walk up to anybody's face. All he
does is run behind everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Anderson became the eighth man Martinez hit all
year. And Boston franchise Nomar Garciaparra was out of uniform
that day, after being drilled the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shortstop couldn't play, that's my only response,'' Boston
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``Selective memory.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   For the all the talk that Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss
might be leaving the club to become the Brewers' manager, there
also is talk within the New York front office that he might be
fired after the season.
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   HARGROVE IN AWE OF RAMIREZ
</P>
<P>
   When Manny Ramirez reached 161 RBIs, the scoreboard at
Cleveland's Jacobs Field didn't look right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at it the other day when they put it on the
board,'' said manager Mike Hargrove. ``And I was thinking that when
I played I used to have around 70 RBI every year, which wasn't bad.
But golly, then I realized that Manny has 90 RBI more than I had in
my best year. Geez!''...
</P>
<P>
   Chicago left-hander Jim Parque was 9-6 the first half and 0-9
the second.... The Royals, who entered the weekend eight runs shy
of setting a franchise scoring record, were also two blown saves
shy of breaking the majors blown saves mark of 31.... After making
three errors in a 14-3 loss to the White Sox on Fan Appreciation
Night, Twins players handed out their game jerseys to selected
lucky fans. Said infielder Danny Hocking, ``The way we played
tonight, we should have given our jerseys away before the game. I
was embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON EYES ANGELS BID
</P>
<P>
   People close to the Angels say it won't be long before the
franchise and the Mighty Ducks hockey club will be bought by Henry
T. Nicholas III and partners at Orange County based Broadcom Corp.
And Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson is working his way into the Angels
group, which does not excite Andy Dolich.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich, a former A's executive, heads a group that includes
Jackson whose $120 million bid to purchase the Oakland team was
tabled at the last owners meeting. That was enough for Jackson, who
headed south to have preliminary talks with Nicholas about his
Angels bid. The new Angels owners seek a high-profile baseball
presence in front office management, not to mention an
African-American presence. Although Pat Gillick was an early
front-runner for the vacant Seattle GM job, Bob Watson is the only
candidate to have a follow-up interview. Gillick's name has since
also come up in Los Angeles, after the firing of Dodgers president
Bob Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
