<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Umpire earns Mets' ire
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves left New York Thursday night, the Mets seemed more
concerned with rookie plate umpire Phil Cuzzi than their own fate.
The club was primarily angry over Cuzzi's refusal to appeal checked
swing calls to base umpires, but manager Bobby Valentine was
incensed that Cuzzi had the plate at all, with veteran Jerry
Crawford calling bases all series.
</P>
<P>
   A critical checked swing call against Mike Piazza in the ninth
prompted Mets GM Steve Phillips to say, ``I was wondering if there
were political issues involved.'' Cuzzi is one of the 25 minor
league umps hired to replace the 22 veterans who were let go.
Crawford, who was at first, is president of the umpires union....
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia catcher Mike Lieberthal has this message for his
front office: ``Pitching-wise, we can't match up. I think we're
maybe only one starter away in the rotation. Relief-wise, we need
something different. A lot of teams can say they're one or two
pitchers away, but I think we need more than that. It stinks to
lose every day.''
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   RIGGLEMAN SAFE IN CHICAGO
</P>
<P>
   Chicago manager Jim Riggleman shouldn't have to wait any longer
than Monday to see if he still has a job. He could stay if he
dismisses some of his coaching staff, but his biggest strong point
is a continued positive working relationship with GM Ed Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict for so many other Cubs won't be so certain.
Essentially, the only veteran position players expected back are
Sammy Sosa, Mark Grace and Henry Rodriguez. With a weak crop of
free agents available this winter, Lynch must be ready to deal....
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden will have to see his payroll bumped
some $22 million to assume raises, bonuses and four free agent
contracts (including outfielder Greg Vaughn) to maintain his
roster. ``If we get to the World Series, I might be able to talk
our new majority owner (Carl Lindner) into a $55 million payroll to
keep the team together,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   SEASON FRUSTRATING FOR ROCKIES
</P>
<P>
   The weekend can't end fast enough in Denver, where a sour season
has festered for weeks. Jim Leyland's burnout, Larry Walker backing
out for knee surgery and the first losing September in franchise
history has made for the darkest days in Rockies history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole year has been a disappointment,'' said outfielder
Dante Bichette. ``And then we pretty much went into the tank. We've
never done that before.''
</P>
<P>
   After hiring a new manager _ and Buddy Bell remains the
frontrunner _ this roster is going to be scrutinized. Even though
Bichette has a no-trade clause, the club would like to move his
contract ($6.5 million coming over the next two years). Neither
Darryl Kile nor Vinny Castilla is safe....
</P>
<P>
   Andy Benes opened the season as Arizona's third starter but is
in danger of falling from the postseason rotation behind Omar Daal
and Brian Anderson. Don't expect the Diamondbacks to pick up his $6
million option next year.... With two saves this weekend, the
Padres' Trevor Hoffman can break Dennis Eckersley's record of 94
saves in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
