<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-CURTRIGHT-COLUMN0     10-02 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CURTRIGHT-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travis still a standard
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Williams batted .406 in 1941, and Joe DiMaggio had
a record 56-game hitting streak. But neither led the American
League in hits that season, baseball's last before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Travis did.
</P>
<P>
   Travis, a soft-spoken Georgian who grew up as the youngest of 12
children on a Fayette County farm, had 218 hits. His .359 average
beat out DiMaggio (.357) for second place behind Williams in the
batting race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost a dream year,'' said Travis, now 86 and still
living in the Riverdale area. ``But I knew all season I was on
borrowed time.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis, then 28 and unmarried, already had heard from his draft
board and was deferred from service only through the end of the
season. He received his induction notice on Christmas Eve _ 17 days
after hearing about the bombing of Pearl Harbor while on a hunting
trip with Washington teammate Buddy Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   He reported to duty in early January and was not discharged
until the end of World War II. Travis made it back to the Senators
for the last few weeks of the 1945 season. By then he had suffered
frostbite on two toes while in special services with the 76th
Infantry in France, and his baseball skills had waned. By 1947, his
career was over at age 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people say the war cost me a chance at the Hall of
Fame,'' said Travis, a left-handed batter whose .314 career average
for 12 seasons remains the best for an American League shortstop.
``But I don't think about that at all. Who knows what would have
happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, there is already too many people in (the Hall of
Fame). I've always thought it should just be for great players. I
was a good player, but I wasn't a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   However, many baseball people, think that his career _ although
shortened _ was too good to be forgotten. That's why Travis still
regularly gets autograph requests in the mail, 52 years after he
played his last game. Many letters come with old photos and
newspaper clippings. He even received a scrapbook of his career
that a fan had kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't do any of those autograph shows, but I'll sign
anything I get in the mail,'' Travis said. ``I suppose people know
old players like me don't have many more years left, so they try to
get us to sign while we can.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Travis can read the mail for himself now, thanks to
cataract surgery on his left eye this spring. Glaucoma has cost
Travis most of the sight in his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had great sight when I played, a real good batting eye,''
Travis said. ``That's what makes not seeing well so hard now. I
used to go to Braves games all the time, but now I just watch on
TV. I couldn't see if I tried to go to Turner Field, and I don't
drive anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis still lives on the land where he grew up, his 85 acres a
sanctuary from the suburban sprawl that has overtaken the area.
Evander Holyfield's estate is about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just used to be dirt roads out here,'' said Travis' wife of
57 years, Helen. ``Things sure have changed. Thank goodness we are
so far off the road. That gives us a little privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis and a son still take care of a herd of 10 cattle. ``That
gives me a little something to do each day,'' said Travis, who had
quadruple-bypass surgery about 17 years ago. ``I'm doing pretty
good for my age.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis was only 19 and had never seen a major-league game when
he made his debut with Washington in 1933 as an emergency fill-in
for an injured Ossie Bluege. Called up from Chattanooga, Tenn., he
had hits in his first five at-bats _ still a major-league record.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing to top that the rest of my career,'' Travis
said. ``I thought they just called me up to sit on the bench, and
then I get five straight hits. It's still hard to believe. I guess
I was too scared to know what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis hit more than .300 in seven of his first eight full
seasons, making the All-Star Game 1938, '40 and '41, despite having
to compete with American League rivals Joe Cronin, Luke Appling and
Lou Boudreau. ``Shortstops were expected to hit in those days,''
Travis said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis saw Babe Ruth hit his last homer as a Yankee in 1934, and
he had wet eyes like everyone else in Yankee Stadium when a dying
Lou Gehrig made his farewell speech in 1939 and Babe Ruth Day was
held in 1947. But he says his most memorable baseball meeting was
with a fellow Georgian, Ty Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Travis played in the dedication game for the Baseball Hall of
Fame in 1939 and rode on the train from Detroit to Cooperstown,
N.Y., with the legendary Georgia Peach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that he gave me one bit of advice,'' Travis said.
``He told me, `Save your money.' Of course, you didn't make much in
the days when I played. But I guess I did OK. It didn't cost much
to live back in those days, either. That was a long, long time
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   CECIL TRAVIS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 86.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married to Helen for 57 years. Sons Tony, Mike and Rick.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Had average of .314 _ best for an American League
shortstop _ in 12 seasons with the Washington Senators. Led
American League in hits with 218 in 1941 while batting. 359 with 19
triples and 101 RBIs. Missed nearly four full seasons during World
War II. Suffered frostbite on two toes in Europe. Retired after
hitting only .216 in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Debut: Had a record five hits in his first five at-bats for
Washington on May 16, 1933, during a 11-10 win over Cleveland in 12
innings, finishing 5-for-7. The Senators won the pennant, and
Travis received $500 as part of a losing World Series share,
despite spending most of the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star appearances: Played for the American League in 1938,
'40 and '41, when Ted Williams gave the AL a dramatic 7-5 win with
a three-run homer in the ninth inning at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
