<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The envelope, please
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although the Baseball Writers' Association of America
stipulates only that all ballots be in ``prior to the start of
postseason play,'' some of these choices could have been made by
the Fourth of July. Then again, others are so knotted, not another
six months of play could make them any easier to cast.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here follows one man's 1999 awards:
</P>
<P>
   MVP
</P>
<P>
   NL: 1. Chipper Jones, Atlanta. 2. Jeff Bagwell, Houston. 3. Matt
Williams, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two months, Jones made the Braves the best team in
the league. Plus, he reserved his best play for the contenders. The
two Mets series _ four homers, eight RBIs in six games _ swayed the
vote
</P>
<P>
   AL: 1. Ivan Rodriguez, Texas. 2. Robbie Alomar, Cleveland. 3.
Pedro Martinez, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   No one was as dominant both in the field and at the plate as
Rodriguez. Alomar started everything that RBI king Manny Ramirez
finished. Martinez's dominance alone got the Red Sox into October.
</P>
<P>
   Cy Young Award
</P>
<P>
   NL: 1. Mike Hampton, Houston. 2. Randy Johnson, Arizona. 3.
Kevin Millwood, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Diamonbacks scored two or fewer runs for Johnson 10
times and winning half of those would make this a runaway. But he
won just one of them. Hampton went 19 starts with just one loss.
</P>
<P>
   AL: 1. Pedro Martinez, Boston. 2. Mariano Rivera, New York. 3.
Mike Mussina, Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   If this isn't unanimous, someone's BBWAA card needs revoking.
Rivera made the ninth inning a moot point _ 43 saves in 47 chances.
The only pitcher perhaps better than Mussina was Bartolo Colon, who
worked with the Tribe run machine behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year
</P>
<P>
   NL: 1. Warren Morris, Pittsburgh. 2. Preston Wilson, Florida. 3.
Scott Williamson, Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a flat September, Morris hit .292 with 15 homers and
72 RBIs, and while Wilson might emerge as one of the game's new
power hitters, Morris' RBI production is comparable while hitting
lower in the order.
</P>
<P>
   AL: 1. Carlos Beltran, Kansas City. 2. Tim Hudson, Oakland. 3.
Billy Koch, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, the Auburn product who came out of nowhere in June,
might have won it with a full season. But Beltran had a 20-20 first
year and anchors the future of the franchise from center field.
</P>
<P>
   Manager of the Year
</P>
<P>
   NL: 1. Jack McKeon, Cincinnati. 2. Bobby Cox, Atlanta. 3. Larry
Dierker, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had this one sewn up until the Reds were ignited under
McKeon at midseason and exceeded everyone's expectation. Cox had
more players out for the year; McKeon had less talent to work with.
</P>
<P>
   AL: 1. Jimy Williams, Boston. 2. Art Howe, Oakland. 3. Joe
Torre, New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox hadn't made the playoffs in consecutive seasons
since 1915-16. Williams also lost Mo Vaughn. The A's had their
first winning record in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Comeback Player NL: Hideo Nomo, Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected by three clubs before camp broke, out of the majors for
the first five weeks, Nomo wound up going 12-8 for a team that will
finish 15 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   AL: John Jaha, Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   A bad foot and a horrible 1998 left Jaha unsigned as spring
training began. Oakland's faith was rewarded with a career-high
35-homer season. Honorable mention: Jermaine Dye, Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise Player NL: Brian Giles, Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland couldn't find a place for him and dealt him for
reliever Ricky Rincon. Giles missed the last three weeks and is
still among NL leaders in homers (39) and RBIs (115) in just 141
games.
</P>
<P>
   AL: Shawn Green, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Green gave Toronto its first 30-30 season, a nice
summer from a kid who never seemed to be able to keep a starting
job. In 1999, he went for 41 homers and 121 RBIs and leads the
league with 86 extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   Flop of the Year
</P>
<P>
   NL: Raul Mondesi, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, the majors' only 30-30 player when the weekend began,
was compelled to apologize for being a jerk around a very
freaked-out team. Somehow, his behavior has managed to make a
statesman of Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   AL: Frank Thomas, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He threw a fit about not wanting to play first. He threw a fit
over the decline of the White Sox. He threw a fit when asked about
his declining power numbers. Then he needed foot surgery. The Big
Hurt became the Big Pain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
