<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXPENSIVE PAIR OF MARINERS
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't make too much out of Nintendo CEO Howard
Lincoln's making those definitive offers ``to both Ken Griffey and
Alex Rodriguez that would make them the highest-paid players in the
130-year history of major-league baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's agent, Scott Boras, said that the pair ``are not
mere players, they must be considered capital assets like, for
instance, a ballpark.'' Before this is all done, last winter's
Kevin Brown talks will look like a bake sale.
</P>
<P>
   Initial offers to both players _ $140 million over eight years
to Griffey; $70 million over seven years to Rodriguez _ were only
opening position statements.
</P>
<P>
   TAYLOR-MADE
</P>
<P>
   When he started putting together a front-office in Tampa Bay,
general manager (and ex-Brave player development chief) Chuck LaMar
took some heat for populating his staff with a legion of ex-Atlanta
staffers. Dean Taylor, just hired away from the Braves as
Milwaukee's new GM, did the same, using his first hire for Dave
Wilder as his vice president for player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The two first worked together under John Schuerholz for five
seasons in Atlanta, Wilder in scouting and development through
1995. Wilder becomes one of the highest ranking minority executives
in the game. He had been an assistant GM with the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the leading candidate in my mind from the day I
accepted the job,'' said Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
