<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLICK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Billick shaking up the Ravens
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baltimore Ravens coach Brian Billick can sympathize
with the Falcons' injury woes.
</P>
<P>
   With running back Jamal Anderson and quarterback Chris Chandler
sidelined with injuries, and defensive tackle Travis Hall's thumb
throbbing, the Falcons will be less than full strength today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard a great deal about where they're at
injury-wise,'' Billick said. ``We're talking about (playing) a
backup quarterback, a running back that didn't play much last year
and (losing) one of their key defensive linemen in the front seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm talking about us,'' Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens, who got their first win under Billick last week,
17-10 over Cleveland, are battling injuries of their own. Starting
running back Priest Holmes has missed two games with a sprained
right knee, and defensive tackle Tony Siragusa missed last week's
win after undergoing arthroscopic knee surgery on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Billick found capable reserves in Errict Rhett, who has rushed
for at least 100 yards two games in a row, and tackle Lional
Dalton. Even without Siragusa, Baltimore held Cleveland to a
club-record 189 yards in Week 3.
</P>
<P>
   Billick, the architect of Minnesota's record-setting offense
last season, signed a six-year, $9million contract in January. He
quickly took control of the franchise, which won just 16 games the
past three seasons. In a team meeting last spring, he challenged
Siragusa to lose weight and offered him a reward. Siragusa lost 25
pounds in less than six weeks. In May, safety Ralph Staten walked
into a team meeting 20 minutes late. Billick cut him the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But his most drastic change was introducing computers to the
franchise. Every assistant coach has one now, and so do some
players. Billick uses it to dissect his West Coach offense and
break down opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything basically comes from his computer _ different
figures and stats, breakdowns of defenses we play, everything,''
quarterback Stoney Case said.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an Air Force test pilot, Billick enrolled in the Air
Force Academy out of high school, but later transferred to Brigham
Young. He played in the NFL for only two seasons, and returned to
BYU as a graduate assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he joined the San Francisco 49ers as the team's
assistant public relations director. He caught the attention of
head coach Bill Walsh, but wanted to return to coaching. Billick
left the 49ers in 1981, eventually joining coach Dennis Green's
staff at Stanford in 1989, where he coached future NFL wide
receivers Ed McCaffrey and Chris Walsh, then jumped to the NFL with
Green three years later.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Billick's offenses ranked among the top eight in
four of his final five seasons and set an NFL record with 556
points in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the reasons I came here in the first place,''
Case said. ``This is the first time I've ever had an offense-minded
head coach, somebody that can relate to the quarterback a little
bit. That's definitely a factor I like about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
