<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-GRAZIANI03-COX     10-02 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GRAZIANI03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graziani unafraid thrust in spotlight
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First things first. When Tony Graziani goes under
center today, the man suddenly thrust into the role of co-savior
for the Falcons wants fans to know something.
</P>
<P>
   They shouldn't interpret his bug-eyed gaze as evidence of fear.
</P>
<P>
   When he started Sept. 20 in a Monday night game at Dallas, TV
exaggerated his normal gaze, and he looked, well, like somebody had
startled him awake from a deep snooze.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent letters to the editor, and calls to sports talk radio
were consistent in one regard. Fans figured the third-year pro was
scared witless in his third NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   He said it just wasn't so, and it won't be today when the takes
over for Chris Chandler as the Falcons (0-3) play the Ravens (1-2)
at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 215-pounder just happens to have giant eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident and ready that night,'' he said. ``Maybe I was
a little more intense at first, and that's what the whole `Deer in
the headlights' thing was. I was really comfortable; we just
couldn't get anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani has struggled to get something going since he was a
seventh-round pick out of the University of Oregon in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before his first training camp, the person most dear
to him, his mother Debbie, died of lung cancer. She had spent his
senior season driving with Tony's stepfather from Modesto, Calif.,
to see him play.
</P>
<P>
   Tony's mom was everybody's mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team kind of rallied around me and her,'' he said. ``It
was like a family deal. It was kind of therapeutic for her. I was
numb (when she died). I still think about her every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys say this, but she really was my best friend.'''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani's only start that season was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   With Chandler hurt, Graziani got the nod Oct. 26 at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 4 of 18 passes for 24 yards and two interceptions
in the rain, and was replaced in the second half by Billy Joe
Tolliver. Atlanta lost 21-12.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander played better, but only a little, last year,
when his passer rating was 42.4, up from 3.7 as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's played better still, completing 22 of 39 passes
for 274 yards, one touchdown, and one interception. He has a
respectable 76.2 passer rating.
</P>
<P>
   That's gone largely unnoticed, however, because the team is
winless. Fan and media reaction has been unkind.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism doesn't grate like last year.
</P>
<P>
   College sweethearts who were engaged after the '97 NFL draft,
and married little more than a year ago, the Grazianis are parents
now.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Frederic entered the world Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor the dog, Daisy the cat, Jack the cat, a Valentine's Day
gift to Sarah back at Oregon, and Ben keep the quarterback
centered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben has made it easier. I can come home and not do anything
except be with him, and that makes things better,'' Graziani said.
``I think it's made me a better quarterback, too. It brings a
little calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani doesn't read defenses as well as Chandler, his arm
isn't as strong, and he tends to flee the pocket quickly.
</P>
<P>
   He's trying all the time, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only played in a handful of games... so I'm learning on
the run,'' he said two days before his fourth start. ``The more I
play, the better I'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   An avowed rebel in his college days, when former Oregon coach
and current Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, ``cut me a
few breaks,'' Graziani has mellowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's grown up a lot,'' said Sarah, who met Tony when she was a
junior and he a sophomore. ``He's become a lot more confident, too.
He was confident in college, but the transition to the NFL is huge.
He seems to be a lot more sure of his abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case last year, when Graziani was pulled at
halftime of his only start, Nov. 29 at St. Louis, an eventual 21-10
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were still in that syndrome, you know, `Chris is
hurt; we're never going to win,' and there was this cloud of
depression over everything,'' he said. ``But now, everybody is
acting normal around me. I think they have confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can win with Tony; we have to,'' wide receiver
Terance Mathis said a couple weeks ago. ``He's making better
decisions. He's a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's strained right hamstring might mean Graziani has to
play a lot more. That and the season-ending knee injury of running
back Jamal Anderson leave Graziani and running back Byron Hanspard
in new roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as high-powered as last year, obviously,'' he said.
``We can't pound 'em 30 times a game with Jamal. We got to run
play-action a little more, roll out of the pocket, change things
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani knows changes may keep coming. The team signed
quarterback Danny Kanell in the offseason, expecting him to be the
backup, before Graziani beat him out.
</P>
<P>
   Does he sense that ``cloud of depression'' coming again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not, but I think we're close,'' he said. ``There's
definitely a sense of urgency. We need to win.... and quickly, or
we're heading for some bad stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
