<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAQ-UNREST-ART-2TAKE     10-02 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-UNREST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SOUTHERN IRAQ, HINTS OF NEW SECTARIAN UNREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAJAF, Iraq _ In the dusty streets and alleyways of Najaf and
other southern Iraqi cities, inquiries about recent troubles
produce pursed lips and averted eyes, even when the questions are
asked in the most guarded of ways.
</P>
<P>
   This holy city and its shrines were badly scarred when a Shiite
Muslim rebellion swept through southern Iraq at the end of the
Persian Gulf war eight years ago, and even now the Iraqi
authorities are still tarring those they say were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Ali Mosque, the most revered in Shiite Islam, angry
captions on photographs that document the 1991 rebellion condemn
the ``mob gangs'' who ``did not spare even the house of God'' _ a
damning charge in an Islamic land.
</P>
<P>
   In Karbala, another Shiite holy city, nooses dangle from the
ceiling of one mosque. The authorities say the ropes are grotesque
proof that those who challenged the government of Saddam Hussein
had turned the holy place into a lynching ground; Shiite opposition
figures say the hangings were carried out by government loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   With the memories of that violent period still fresh, this year
tensions are again running high in southern Iraq, whose
overwhelmingly Shiite population has long harbored deep resentment
against a central government dominated by minority Sunni Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Though few people here dare to speak openly, and though
competing reports from the government, its opponents and the United
States are impossible to verify, it is clear that the region's
already explosive climate has been charged anew by recent events.
These include the killing of a leading clergyman, an attempt to
kill a top government official, and Shiite rioting and a subsequent
crackdown that may have involved bulldozing scores of homes and
turning tanks on two towns.
</P>
<P>
   Even recent public statements at high levels of the Iraqi
government have hinted that all is not well _ a veiled but rare
admission of the sectarian unrest that challenges Saddam's
stranglehold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Tariq Aziz, the deputy foreign minister, said in late September
that his government had ``not denied'' that ``security attacks''
against the government had been carried out in recent months. But
he said they were the work of ``pro-Iranian agents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And some of them are Iranians,'' he added, ``not just
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has offered a very different characterization.
In a report in September, the State Department pointed to what it
called a steady increase in the ``scale and severity'' of attacks
by the Sunni-dominated government against Shiite civilians. (The
vast majority of the world's Muslims are Sunnis; Shiites, who broke
away in the early days of Islam, live mainly in Iran, Iraq, Lebanon
and some Persian Gulf countries.)
</P>
<P>
   The civilians, the report said, had nevertheless ``continuously
resisted'' Iraqi attempts at repression _ at least since February,
when the assassination in Najaf of Grand Ayatollah Mohammed Sadeq
al-Sadr, Iraq's most prominent Shiite clergyman, appears to have
ignited long-simmering tensions.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, say several independent Baghdad-based analysts,
the assassination kindled protests by Shiite civilians, which then
led to clashes between them and security forces. The demonstrations
stretched even to Al-Thawra, an impoverished Shiite-dominated
suburb of the capital, and dozens of people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are fomenting,'' said Hans von Sponek, the U.N. aid
coordinator, who is the top U.N. official in Baghdad. He added,
however, ``We have very little opportunity to see things
firsthand.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been denials of any trouble from most local Iraqi
officials. Since the 1991 uprising, said Sayed Fadhil al-Gorabi,
chief cleric of the Abbas Mosque in Karbala, ``all Iraq has been
one and everyone is standing together.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point, a banner in the courtyard of the
mosque _ whose structure was badly damaged in the 1991 rebellion _
proclaims simply, ``We pray every Friday for Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   But as early as November 1998, the government confirmed that
there had been an assassination attempt in Karbala against Izzat
Ibrahim, the vice president of the Revolutionary Command Council,
who is in theory the country's No. 2 official.
</P>
<P>
   By the spring, it announced a shake-up in its security lineup in
the region. And throughout the year Iraq has become increasingly
vocal in its claims that any unrest is the work of Iranian
provocateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are actually dogs from beyond the borders who are given
dollars to influence the people,'' said Sheik Abdel Amir Abd Juwad,
the deputy prayer leader at the Ali Mosque, dismissing as nonsense
any talk of a real Shiite rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In both the attempt against Ibrahim and the killing of Sadr,
whose two sons were also killed, the government has announced the
arrests of suspects said to be Iranians or their agents.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, that kind of finger-pointing carries almost as much
propagandistic weight as accusing Shiite rebels of defiling a
mosque. Most Iraqis, even in the Shiite south, still revile Iran
and its Shiite Muslim government, a bitter legacy of the bloody and
protracted 1980-88 war between Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   And because Iran does provide sanctuary for Shiite rebels,
including a group known as the Supreme Council for Islamic
Revolution, the accusation of an Iranian hand in Iraqi unrest rings
true to some.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past, the Iraqi government has often proved less than
candid in casting blame. In 1991 it was not Shiite rebels but Iraqi
government forces who were judged by most experts to have inflicted
most of the damage to holy sites in Najaf and Karbala, despite
government claims since to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   In both cities, evidence suggested that much of the damage was
caused by heavy weapons used by Iraqi forces to drive Shiite rebels
from their hideouts.
</P>
<P>
   After the rebellion was put down, Iraqi forces for a time used
the Ali Mosque as headquarters, parking a squadron of motorcycle
troops in the courtyard, which is not far from the tomb of Ali, the
fourth and most revered of Shiite Islam's 12 imams.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the United States has said, Iraqi forces have
acted with a similar brutality. The State Department said in its
most recent report that the Iraqis bulldozed or gutted about 160
homes in Al-Masha village after a protest early this summer, and
that tank columns attacked Rumaitha and Khudur after similar
protests.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi government disputed several charges in that report,
but it was notably silent on those points. Still, Aziz, the deputy
prime minister, mocked what he called feigned U.S. concern over
developments in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the United States and Britain have enforced a
no-flight zone over southern Iraq, ostensibly to protect the Shiite
Muslim population there from Iraqi repression. There is another
such zone in the north to protect the Kurdish minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans have decided to have an obsession with the
Shiites in Iraq,'' Aziz said in a two-hour conversation in Baghdad.
``They have decided to have a love affair. But isn't it a funny
thing that they have not shown the same feeling for the Shiites in
Lebanon or Iran?''
</P>
<P>
   Government regulations prohibit foreign journalists from
traveling unescorted in Iraq beyond the Baghdad city limits, and
official interviews must be arranged by the Ministry of
Information.
</P>
<P>
   Even foreign diplomats and international officials who are based
in Baghdad operate under restrictions that have made it impossible
to confirm specific details of any recent clash. The diplomats and
international officials spoke about the unrest on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, some contended in interviews that the State
Department had greatly exaggerated the case against Iraq and seemed
to rely on claims of Iraqi opposition groups with uneven
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Most clashes, they said, involve hit-and-run attacks by Shiite
guerrillas. But, they added, it was clear that the response from
the government had been harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Those skeptical about the Iraqi claim that Iranian forces were
behind the assassination of Sadr have noted that he was merely the
latest Shiite clergyman to be killed or to die in mysterious
circumstances. Grand Ayatollah Abu al-Qasim al-Khui, Sadr's
predecessor as Iraq's highest-ranking Shiite clergyman, died in
government custody in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Max van der Stoel, the special rapporteur for Iraq of
the U.N. Commission on Human Rights, issued a report expressing
fear that the killings might have been carried out by Iraqi
officials as part of a systematic attack on the independent
leadership of Shiite Muslims in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before his death, Sadr was said to have encouraged
Muslims to attend Friday prayers at their local mosques rather than
watch them on television _ a message thought not to be appreciated
by the authorities, who tend to discourage large gatherings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
