<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-NYT     10-02 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. TROOPS HAVE SHIFTING ROLE IN ENFORCING PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. strategy for dealing with regional
conflicts has undergone a significant shift, as shown by its new
involvement in Kosovo and East Timor, and a third mission under
consideration in Sierra Leone, U.N. officials and other diplomats
say.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the United Nations deployed its own blue-helmeted
force, drawing on troops contributed by countries like Sweden,
Canada and Fiji that had no geographical interests at stake and
were usually placed in situations where peace had already been
established and merely had to be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, however, the world organization has
been faced with a more dangerous job _ peace enforcement, or
stopping fighting _ and has begun leaving that task to regional
military groups, like NATO in Kosovo, an Australian-led force in
East Timor and a West African force of mostly Nigerian troops in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo, East Timor and Sierra Leone are good examples of how
peace enforcement missions are undertaken by regional forces,'' a
U.S diplomat said. ``It's very much the trend that the U.N. is not
in position to do peace enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo and East Timor, the United Nations, besides creating a
civilian administration and aid operation, provides a political
framework and peacekeeping legitimacy for the troops already there.
It would assume a similar role in Sierra Leone under a British
draft resolution circulating among Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. official familiar with peacekeeping said that a robust,
well-equipped military intervention must exist on the ground before
peacekeeping can work. The regional forces fill this role.
</P>
<P>
   The change in strategy dates back to the strained credibility
that the United Nations suffered trying to bring peace to Bosnia.
By 1994, an official said, the United Nations had nearly 80,000
blue-helmeted troops deployed on missions around the world. Once
the peace accord was reached in late 1995, thousands of European
troops there moved under NATO command. By contrast, there are no
plans so far to put the NATO troops in Kosovo under U.N. authority.
</P>
<P>
   Finances also became a consideration in relying on regional
forces. Joseph E. Connor, the under secretary for management, said
in an interview that there are no reserve funds for peacekeeping,
because the United States, which is assessed 31 percent of
peacekeeping costs, owes more than $1.5 billion in unpaid dues and
other arrears. This means that before any new peacekeeping
operation can begin, the funds to pay for it must be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans look at every new operations through one lens,
the budgeting lens,'' another U.N. official said. ``Can they get
the money through Congress? If not, they'll resist it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some U.N. officials admit being uncomfortable with relying too
much on regional military forces. One official said the United
Nations was conferring its authority on countries with a vested
interest in influencing the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs of failing to intervene can run much higher,
another official said. He referred to the genocide that paralyzed
Rwanda in 1994, when the United Nations could not persuade
countries to contribute troops. ``The world failed to respond to
genocide in Rwanda, so we had a million refugees in Zaire,'' the
official said. He estimated that the costs of caring for the
refugees exceeded $1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
