<SLUG> BC-WORLD-EXPO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICAL OF TOP GORE AIDE ON SPENDING IN GOVERNMENT ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Portugal)  (bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A report soon to be issued by State Department
investigators is critical of management and spending at the 1998
World Exposition in Lisbon, an event whose U.S. participation was
overseen by Tony Coelho, now Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The department's Office of Inspector General reviewed the U.S.
Information Agency's planning and management of the exposition,
known as Expo 98, which ran from May 22 through Sept. 30, 1998.
Investigators working for Inspector General Jacquelyn
Williams-Bridgers said they uncovered several problems.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said planning for Expo 98 had started too
late, leading to needlessly high construction and operating costs.
They said the poor planning and execution by the Information Agency
had exposed the U.S. government unnecessarily to possible financial
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also said the U.S. pavilion at Expo 98 had
been poorly managed. For example, the pavilion's restaurant was
shut down before the end of Expo 98, at least partly because of
lawsuits filed by a subcontractor against the primary construction
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The report specifically criticized the commissioner general of
the exposition, a title held by Coelho, a former Democratic
congressman from California who is of Portuguese descent. He did
not return a telephone call on Friday night seeking comment on the
report, but he did rebut some of the criticisms in a letter to U.S.
Information Agency officials last April, after seeing a draft of
the document.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the criticism was useful and some was based on
misunderstandings that might not have arisen if investigators had
talked to him, ``which they never did.'' Coelho said there was a
surplus of $100,000 when Expo 98 closed, and he suggested that some
of the possible financial liabilities for the United States existed
mainly on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The report was obtained by the Center for Public Integrity,
which made it available to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   While planning for Expo 98 was going on, many members of
Congress were becoming reluctant to finance such international
events.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of Expo 98, with Coelho at the helm, hoped for
significant private contributions.
</P>
<P>
   But when it became clear that private money would be
insufficient, Coelho used his old connections on Capitol Hill and
in the Clinton administration to get taxpayers' money to finance
much of the U.S. participation in Expo 98, the Center for Public
Integrity asserted.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimates that 80 percent of the cost of U.S.
participation in Expo 98 came from government money. The total cost
may exceed $10 million, it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
