<HEADLINE>
TRACK WORK ON SUBWAYS NEAR MUSEUM DELAYS SOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-MUSEUM-OPENING and NY-MUSEUM-RELIG) 
(bl) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Could the timing have been worse?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not for thousands of Manhattan residents who boarded
subways Saturday for the Brooklyn Museum of Art, only to learn that
their return trip would be complicated by suspended service at
subway stations close to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that getting to ``Sensation,'' the year's most
passionately debated art show, was easy, at least for those coming
from Manhattan, but that for many, getting home was not.
</P>
<P>
   Signs said the stations were closed to Manhattan-bound traffic.
Transit officials said the suspension was necessary for track work
in three stations on the 2 and 3 lines that had been planned for
months. A spokeswoman for New York City Transit, which operates the
city's subways and buses, said signs announcing the suspension were
posted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency did offer an alternative, free bus shuttle service
from the museum to the Atlantic Avenue Terminal, 12 blocks away, as
a last-minute concession to the large crowds expected to attend the
exhibit. Signs announcing that service were still being put up soon
after noon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The transit spokeswoman, Melissa Farley, insisted that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's opposition to the exhibition was unrelated to
the maintenance schedule, an assertion that some museumgoers
greeted with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously an effort to torpedo the exhibition,'' said
Irwin Greenberg, 67, a retired lawyer who lives on Manhattan's
Upper West Side and traveled by subway Saturday morning to see the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like starving people when they want to eat,'' said
Chrissy Sereno, 22, of East Meadow on Long Island, who was also
waiting to get into the show.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has no direct control over the transit agency, which
is a subsidiary of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority. While
the authority is influenced most directly by Gov. George Pataki,
who appoints the chairman of its board, it has made political
concessions to Giuliani in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farley said the Brooklyn track work had been planned for
months and was dictated mainly by things like the weather and how
long it takes concrete to dry. ``This is not a fly-by-night
operation, and it has nothing to do with the museum,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Service was suspended for Manhattan-bound trains at the Eastern
Parkway Station, with an entrance directly in front of the museum's
main entrance, and at two of the closest stations for
Manhattan-bound riders, the Grand Army Plaza Station and the Bergen
Street Station.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farley said that track work at the stations began in June,
and that schedules for the most disruptive parts of the project _
including this weekend's closings _ had been determined months
before that. Beginning Friday night and ending before the stations
were to reopen for Manhattan-bound riders early Monday morning, she
said, crews were pouring concrete and laying new track in the three
stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really weren't expecting this big thing at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art,'' Ms. Farley said. ``If we don't get this job done
now, it might have to be put off until after the first of the year,
and that could create a safety problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
