<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-POLICE-BIAS-NYT &LR;      10-02 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-STATE POLICE CHIEF SAYS HIS DISMISSAL WAS REVERSE
DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. _ The man who was fired as superintendent of
the New Jersey State Police after making public comments linking
minority groups to drug crimes said Saturday that his removal was
an example of reverse discrimination and that Gov. Christie Whitman
had planned all along to replace him with a minority-group member.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public remarks since his dismissal, former
Superintendent Carl Williams, 59, said he had been used as a
political scapegoat and unfairly branded a racist simply because he
made comments about racial profiling that ``were the truth'' in a
newspaper interview with The Star-Ledger of Newark in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reputation was blackened,'' he said Saturday in his
lawyer's office here, with his wife, Eloise, beside him. ``I want
my reputation back because I didn't do anything wrong. I am the
victim in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks came one day after his lawyer, Clifford Van Syoc,
filed a civil lawsuit in Superior Court in Camden, asserting that
Williams had been wrongfully dismissed for his comments and
discriminated against for being a white man.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses Whitman and former state Attorney General
Peter Verniero of firing him ``in order to replace him with a black
superintendent'' to further their political goals. Williams'
successor, Carson Dunbar, a former FBI agent, is black. His
appointment was confirmed by the state Senate in September.
</P>
<P>
   Pete McDonough, a spokesman for the governor, said he would not
comment on pending litigation, ``no matter how baseless or
boneheaded it is,'' and that he had not seen the lawsuit. Verniero,
who is now a judge on the state Supreme Court, could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Williams touched off a storm of criticism last February by
telling the Star-Ledger in an interview that certain crimes were
more routinely committed by certain racial and ethic groups.
Williams was quoted as saying: ``Two weeks ago, the president of
the United States went to Mexico to talk to the president of Mexico
about drugs. He didn't go to Ireland. He didn't go to England.
Today, with this drug problem, the drug problem is cocaine or
marijuana. It is most likely a minority group that's involved with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, the same day that his remarks were published,
Whitman dismissed him, saying that the state needed to enhance
public confidence in the police. Williams had been under fire for
weeks over charges that state troopers unfairly singled out black
drivers on state highways, a practice known as racial profiling,
and that he had refused to acknowledge what critics called a long
history of racist procedures by his force.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams called profiling a ``time-honored tool'' of
police work in the interview, he condemned it and said it was
unacceptable. But he also was quoted as saying, ``It would be naive
to think race is not an issue in drug trafficking.'' Minority-group
leaders reacted swiftly and furiously to his printed remarks and
called for his dismissal hours before the governor announced it.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Leroy Jones, D-Essex County, said at the time: ``His
views are dastardly, his thoughts are ill and sickened, and he's
unfit to hold such a critical and important office. He's a racist
of the worst kind, because he doesn't even know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Saturday, however, that his remarks had been
honest, not racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My remarks in the Newark Star-Ledger were the truth,'' he
said. ``That's the way it is.'' When asked whether he thought they
had been insensitive, he responded: ``I suppose we could play
semantics. What is insensitive?''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says Williams ``was required on occasion to answer
questions from the media, and did so truthfully in accordance with
his nickname, Carl ``The Truth'' Williams. Williams said that state
troopers had given him the nickname years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think back and you're brought up throughout life to
tell the truth, and you always tell the truth, and then you get
your life taken away from you for telling the truth, it's quite a
shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says, ``There was nothing whatsoever `racially
insensitive' about the statements plaintiff made, which were
truthful and accurate, such that plaintiff was entitled, under the
New Jersey constitution, to make those statements without fear of
adverse consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which seeks compensatory and punitive damages, does
not specify an amount. His lawyer, Van Syoc, said that the
Williamses might sue some of the minority-group leaders for
comments they regarded as defamatory.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was often praised for his devotion to the state police,
which he joined in 1963. He cruised the highways as a trooper for
years, then, rising through the ranks, worked in the criminal
investigation, organized crime, intelligence, internal affairs and
narcotic units. He was appointed by Whitman early in 1994 to the
$89,963-a-year job of supervising 2,600 troopers and 1,000
civilians.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said Saturday that the ``equity'' he had built up over the
years had been destroyed by his dismissal, and that while he had
sent out five resumes seeking other jobs, he had received no
responses. That did not surprise him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being called a racist by some black individuals,'' he
said. ``I'm being called insensitive by the governor and the
attorney general of New Jersey. It gives the impression that
there's something wrong with me.''
</P>
<P>
   But most painful, he said, was the damage to his reputation, one
he had built through 35 years of service. ``It, more or less,
submarined my integrity,'' he said in a quavering voice as his wife
wept silently. ``It put an emotional hurt on myself and on my
family, and, most of all, it hurt the state troopers who are out
there protecting the public.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that his burden would have been unbearable if not for
the show of support from his family and from the state troopers,
who often dropped by, called, and sent cards and letters. ``I just
think I should be treated fair, and I wasn't treated fair,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
