<HEADER>
A4551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-OLYMPICS-IOC-1003-COX     10-02 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-IOC-1003-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanctions Unlikely in Atlanta Olympic Probe
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens, Greece - The International Olympic Committee official
who directed the committee's bidding scandal investigations said
Saturday that he doubted revelations about the Atlanta campaign
will lead to disciplinary action of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, the IOC vice president who led the investigation of
the Salt Lake City bidding scandal, also said apparent abuses in
the campaign for the 1996 Games fall short of the violations
committed in the Utah city's bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Six IOC members were expelled and four resigned in the Salt Lake
vote buying scandal. IOC members and their relatives were paid $1.2
million in cash, college scholarships and other inducements.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said his reading of the Atlanta report contained no
suggestion that IOC members accepted such large gifts. ``I don't
believe there is anything in that report that would lead to any
further action,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that there was an awful lot of offers pushed
upon IOC members (by the Atlanta committee) and were not
accepted,'' he said. ``Even the Bell report said these were
excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   A new report prepared by former attorney general Griffin Bell
details the expensive gifts, personal favors and travel offered by
Atlanta lobbyists to IOC members in the two years leading up to
Atlanta's surprise selection in 1990. The report includes accounts
of Atlanta bidders' offering college scholarships, job assistance
and other perks to IOC members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is anything in that report that would
lead to any further action,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   The report has been handed over to the IOC's ethics commission,
which is expected to make a final determination within the next few
weeks. The Bell report was prepared for Congressional hearings into
the Atlanta bid scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a year of enduring the embarrassment and abuse
produced by the Salt Lake City scandal, the IOC is eager to close
this lamentable chapter in the 105-year-old organization's history.
Despite sporadic allegations about the behavior of former bidding
teams and IOC members, the committee has shown little appetite for
following leads beyond Salt Lake City. Additionally, the IOC has
concerned itself only with the conduct of its members and not
bidding committees. Many of the IOC members implicated in the
Atlanta report have already been either removed or disciplined for
their actions in the Salt Lake City affair.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the IOC will hold a special session to enact
sweeping reforms intended to clean up the process for selecting
host cities. Also, the committee is looking forward to the 2000
Sydney Games, which seem to be shaping up to be a success.
</P>
<P>
   Despite months of claims by former Atlanta lobbyists that the
campaign for the 1996 Games was free of improper gift giving and
inordinately lavish entertaining, the report suggests that the
Atlanta bidders employed methods that were similar to those used by
the Salt Lake bid. Indeed, Salt Lake City officials have often said
they were only emulating what had worked for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Commerce subcommittee for Oversight
and Investigations, Rep. Fred Upton, R-Michigan, has invited IOC
President Juan Antonio to testify. Upton, who has been critical of
the Olympic bidding process, has threatened to subpoena Samaranch
if he does not agree to appear voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old president is wrestling with whether he should
appear but is expected to make his decision known as early as
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members are deeply worried about the prospect of being
compelled by U.S. authorities to testify as well as separate
concerns about being questioned by FBI agents investigating the
Salt Lake City scandal. These concerns are leading to an awkward
situation in which IOC members are reluctant to travel to the
United States, the biggest and most powerful member of the Olympic
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nervous,'' Pound said. ``They don't really understand
this. It's as if they were going to Brazil and worrying that the
Brazilian police might grab them.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC executive board, which is chaired by Samaranch, may drop
plans to go the United States in February to meet with Salt Lake
and U.S. Olympic Committee officials.
</P>
<P>
   However, an IOC spokesman has attributed this to scheduling
conflicts rather than members fears that they may be greeted at the
airport by officials bearing subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
