<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOORAY FOR RYDER CUP CELEBRATION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a platform near the 15th green on Saturday during last
weekend's Ryder Cup matches at The Country Club in Brookline,
Mass., a young British voice was heard saying, ``Stay out, Davis,
stay out,'' as he listened to a radio description of Davis Love
III's birdie putt on the 18th green. Suddenly he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stayed out,'' he said happily.
</P>
<P>
   Two middle-aged men nearby were not smiling. One of them turned,
glared at the young Briton and growled: ``So what are you laughing
about? You're in Boston. We'll throw you over the railing.'' They
didn't, but that's what the Ryder Cup is now: a nationalistic event
that stokes emotions that can burst into flame and incinerate some
of golf's genteel traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Even the traditions of the Ryder Cup golfers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Golf has always wanted to be as popular as baseball, football,
basketball and hockey in America, and now that it is as popular on
the Ryder Cup weekend every two years, golf has to learn to accept
that, for better or worse, it's going to attract the same sometimes
indelicate devotion of those who attend other sports, just as it
turned the U.S. Ryder Cup team into the 1980 Olympic hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   When Justin Leonard's 45-foot birdie putt disappeared into the
hole on the 17th green last Sunday for what the American Ryder
Cuppers considered the clinching one-half point in a comeback
14{-13{ victory, several golfers (as well as wives and officials)
celebrated with Leonard on the side of the green.
</P>
<P>
   In golf, you're not supposed to do that when another golfer
still has to putt, as Jose Maria Olazabal did. After composing
himself, the two-time Masters champion missed his 20-footer for a
halve and the Americans had clinched.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ryder Cup is not golf so much now as it's a crusade to
prove whether American or European golfers are better; the
Europeans had held the cup after five of the previous seven
matches. So when Leonard's putt fell, the American Ryder Cup
contingent celebrated. It was not proper golf etiquette, but it was
understandable. It was simply human spontaneous combustion.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans use the words ``sad'' and ``ugly'' to describe the
celebration, but can the Europeans honestly say they would not do
the same thing in the same situation: one of their golfers holing
an improbable 45-foot putt for the likely winning half-point at The
Belfry near London, where the 2001 matches will be played, or at
Valderrama in Spain, the site of the 1997 matches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Valderrama wasn't exactly a cakewalk for us over there,'' Tom
Lehman said. ``Their fans were pretty interesting, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Tom said, memories are short,'' Love said. ``There's been a
lot of celebrating on a lot of holes in a lot of Ryder Cups.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro golfers are not accustomed to being part of a team. When a
golfer wins the U.S. Open or the Masters, he's the only one who
celebrates. But in the Ryder Cup, the golfers are no longer
individuals; they're a team. And when the American team won, they
celebrated just as the 1980 Olympic hockey team did. And because it
was the U.S. team, most of the spectators in Brookline were rooting
for the Americans as devotedly as they do for the Red Sox or the
Celtics or the Patriots or the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, that the Americans were about to win it all,
which is more than the Red Sox have done since 1918, more than the
Patriots have ever done.
</P>
<P>
   That does not excuse the improper Bostonian who, according to
the wife of Mark James, the European captain, spat at her. But it
does explain the rude remarks that hecklers directed at Europe's
best golfer, Colin Montgomerie, throughout the three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the Americans root for the Americans,'' said
Jesper Parnevik, the Swede who lives in Florida but was on the
European team. ``But it should never get personal. Not in golf.''
</P>
<P>
   As if it never had until last weekend, as if there was never a
discouraging word anywhere else for any other golfer. As if the
word ``choker'' has never been heard in a gallery. As if nobody
yelled ``Fat Jack'' or ``Ohio Fats'' at Jack Nicklaus in the years
when he was dethroning Arnold Palmer. As if nobody at Valderrama
tossed racial epithets at Tiger Woods two years ago. But the Golden
Bear just ignored the taunts. So did Tiger. They let their clubs
answer.
</P>
<P>
   That's usually what Montgomerie does too, or at least has tried
to do, not only last weekend but whenever he has played the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it now as a motivating factor,'' said Montgomerie, the
world's No. 3-ranked golfer behind Woods and David Duval. ``I treat
it as a compliment because I must be good at this game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Montgomerie's body language sometimes betrays his annoyance,
provoking his hecklers even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, too, was disgusted with some of the actions and some of the
name-calling and the heckling that goes on with Colin,'' said Payne
Stewart, who played him in Sunday's singles. ``That's not what this
event is about. I appreciate the gallery we had here, but it's a
golf event. I don't know how many of these fans have been to golf
events before.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely the point. Now that the Ryder Cup is so much more than
a golf event and now that Tiger Woods has spread the gospel of golf
to so many others, all golf events will be attracting more and more
spectators unaccustomed to what is considered, perhaps too
reverently, to be golf etiquette. Let the gallery yell more. Not in
a golfer's backswing or when someone is about to putt. That's
unfair. But in general let the gallery yell more and, yes, even let
the gallery heckle.
</P>
<P>
   Golf and golfers need to adjust to it, and golf and golfers will
be better for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ASTRODOME-FAREWELL-2T     10-02 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRODOME-FAREWELL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRODOME IS BOWING OUT AFTER A STORIED 35 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (With HOUSTON-ASTRODOME) 
 (Eds: Sam Blair was a writer and columnist for The Dallas Morning
News for 41 years.) 
 (rk) 
 By SAM BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mickey Mantle set the mood for everything to come in
the Astrodome in the first baseball game played there, an
exhibition on April 9, 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees superstar smashed the first home run far beyond the
center-field fence, then described the strange sensation of playing
in sport's first major indoor stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it reminds me of is being in a flying saucer off
somewhere,'' Mantle said.
</P>
<P>
   But time also flies. Now the Astros are closing out their 35th
and final season in this storied stadium, battling to make the
playoffs before record crowds filled with stretch-run anxiety and
Astrodome nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season ends Sunday afternoon against the Los Angeles
Dodgers, but two all-time Astros hope that their team will still be
lighting up the Astrodome in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to win the World Series here, then dig up home plate
and take it with me,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, 53, would be entitled. Signed as a rangy 17-year-old
pitcher by the old Houston Colt 45s in 1964, Dierker has spent much
of his life in the Astrodome as athlete, broadcaster and manager.
And when he collapsed in the Astros' dugout with a grand mal
seizure in the eighth inning against San Diego on June 13, it was
feared he also might die there.
</P>
<P>
   But Dierker underwent a 5 1/2 hour brain operation and returned
to the same dugout July 16 after missing 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   If this Astros season ends as happily as Dierker hopes, his
first-base coach, Jose Cruz, would gladly help him carry home plate
out to his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some thrilling memories, but after all these years we
never have played in the World Series,'' said Cruz, 52, whose
heroics as an outfielder earned his No. 25 a place high in the
Astrodome along with the numbers of pitchers Jim Umbricht (32), Don
Wilson (40), Mike Scott (33) and Nolan Ryan (34). ``It's time we
bring a championship here.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a grand way for the prime tenants to say goodbye
to their old showcase. But whatever happens, the Astros will head
downtown in April 2000 to a new ballpark that will offer a lot that
the Astrodome does not: a much cozier stadium designed purely for
baseball, with games played on natural grass outdoors. Or indoors,
when Houston's notorious heat and humidity or an occasional
cloudburst dictates use of a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to change downtown Houston like nothing has in the
last 50 years,'' said Drayton McLane, the Astros' owner since '93.
``On summer nights the roof will be closed when the game starts,
but by 9 p.m. the roof will roll back and the fans will have the
stars and downtown Houston around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Hofheinz, the first Astros owner and the godfather of the
Astrodome, called his pleasure palace ``the Eighth Wonder of the
World,'' but its glass-paneled roof hasn't moved in all these
years. The Astrodome, named in tribute to the fledgling space
program at neighboring NASA, has been host to football, basketball,
track, championship fights, rodeos, revivals and such memorable
events as the Billie Jean King-Bobby Riggs ``Battle of the Sexes''
tennis match.
</P>
<P>
   King won on Sept. 20, 1973. Houston resident George Bush won the
Republican presidential nomination there on Aug. 20, 1992. And Feb.
4-6, 1966, one of the most bizarre events in Astrodome history _
bloodless bullfights _ drew 107,257. The popular logic at the time
was that the bulls had no-cut contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Over these last 35 years, the Astrodome has left its imprint on
the world, helping change Houston from a sprawling oil boomtown to
a city renowned for high-tech industry and heart transplants. Its
marquee names have ranged from Billy Graham to Evel Knievel, from
Elvin Hayes to Elvis Presley, and, getting back to Astros managers,
from Leo Durocher to Larry Dierker. But now the 54,370-seat
Astrodome is too big, too drab and simply wrong for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   So it's farewell to the Big Bubble on the Bayou, built by Harris
County for $31.6 million, and on to $250 million Enron Field with
42,000 seats and 162 lucrative luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to play there,'' said Jeff Bagwell, the All-Star
first baseman and a veteran of nine Astro seasons. ``I was born in
Boston and I still like those old, traditional ballparks where the
players are close to the crowd, like Fenway Park and Wrigley Field.
Our new park will be like that and that closeness will help us and
our fans. They're just too far away from us in the Astrodome.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane, a folksy, good ol' Texas boy, put it another way: ``The
Astrodome doesn't have any personality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' president, Tal Smith, remembers when it was livelier
_ and louder. ``The Astrodome lost its personality when the county
pulled out the exploding scoreboard and put in 10,000 upholstered
seats to accommodate Bud Adams,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, the Houston Oilers' owner, had threatened to move his
National Football League team to Jacksonville, Fla., if the dome's
football capacity wasn't greatly expanded. So, down came the
celebrated 474-foot scoreboard, which saluted home team home runs,
touchdowns and victories with an animated display combining Fourth
of July fireworks and the thunderous roar of a Wild West show.
</P>
<P>
   Up went 10,000 seats in 1989 in that strange gaping space
stretching from above the center-field wall around to right field.
And then Adams ultimately did move his club _ to Tennessee three
seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were more fans,'' Smith said of those who stayed for
baseball, ``but their reaction to things was just polite applause
instead of the raucous cheering that was typical of Astrodome
crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Harris County owns the Astrodome, but the Astros' owner always
has operated the stadium for all events under a long-term lease
agreement. Hofheinz frequently seemed to function like an emperor,
however. A former Houston mayor and Harris County judge, Hofheinz
liked to operate in a grand style. For a while he made any visit to
the Astrodome rare and exciting entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A latter-day P.T. Barnum,'' Tal Smith said of his old boss.
But Hofheinz enjoyed being the Big Cigar. And this sometimes caused
conflicts, disputes and bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Astrodome opened in '65, Hofheinz and oil
billionaire R.E. ``Bob'' Smith, his longtime friend and business
partner, parted company. Smith wanted to concentrate first on
building a strong baseball franchise and consider peripheral
projects later. Hofheinz wanted to move quickly to build Astrohall
and Astroarena adjacent to the dome, plus the Astroworld amusement
park and a group of hotels across the road.
</P>
<P>
   Hofheinz hustled hard to buy Bob Smith out and helped to raise
the needed $9 million by selling his home and moving into a large,
luxurious suite in the Astrodome. But as years passed, the Astros
struggled competitively and Hofheinz struggled financially. In May
1970, he was felled by a stroke. By 1979, the Ford Motor Credit
Corp. controlled the club and the Astrodome and was delighted to
sell everything to John McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen didn't know baseball and often ran the club by long
distance, but he made Nolan Ryan of nearby Alvin the sport's first
$1 million player as a free agent. The Astros came frustratingly
close to bringing the World Series here in 1980, losing the final
game of the National League Championship Series to the Phillies in
10 innings; and in 1986, losing Game 6 to the Mets in 16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   But today McMullen is remembered mainly for firing Tal Smith in
1980 after Smith was voted baseball executive of the year and for
running off Ryan in 1989 after trying to cut his salary 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Ryan to join those upstate upstarts, the American
League Texas Rangers. Ryan's arrival led the Rangers to unexpected
riches and respectability and eventually into a new
state-of-the-art stadium.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, who brought Tal Smith back as club president in 1994,
will sell the remaining 23 years of his Astrodome lease back to
Harris County in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astrodome can't be the type of stadium we need for the
21st century,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
