u a BC-NY-PATAKI-TRAVEL-500&AMP;     10-02 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-TRAVEL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPSICO GAVE TO SPONSOR OF PATAKI TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pepsico, which regularly lobbies in Albany on tax and
other issues, says it donated $5,000 to a nonprofit trade group in
1995 just before the group paid for a trip to Hungary by Gov.
George Pataki, his family members and aides.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico is the third major New York-based corporation with
business before the state to detail its ties to the nonprofit
group, the Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce USA, which
sponsored Pataki's visits in 1995 and 1996 to Hungary, the homeland
of his paternal grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Brown, a spokesman for Pepsico, said Friday that the
company contributed the $5,000 just before the September 1995 trip,
adding that he did not know who had solicited it. Asked whether the
company gave specifically to finance the visit, Brown said, ``I
would guess that it had something to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on information from the governor's staff, the state Ethics
Commission ruled before the trips took place that they were legal
because the chamber did not have business before the state. Under
state law, the governor and members of his administration are
barred from accepting gifts of $75 or more from companies with
business before the state, even through third parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethics Commission has said it did not know about the
donations to the chamber made around the time of the trips. It is
now considering whether to open an inquiry into the trips to
determine whether the donations violated the gift rules.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the governor have said he and his aides were not
aware of any donations to the chamber and played no role in its
fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber was established in 1992. Brown said Pepsico, which
has operations in Eastern Europe, had donated to the chamber before
1995, but never more than $1,000 annually. Since 1995, the company
has not contributed in some years and has given $1,000 or less in
others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pepsico executive, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said the company's decision to increase its donation in
1995 was directly related to the governor's trip. The executive
said that shortly before the trip, it appeared that the chamber was
having money problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they could barely afford the cost of the
trip,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported last week that Philip Morris, the
cigarette giant, had sent $10,000 to the chamber a week before the
first trip, $10,000 a few weeks before the second trip and another
$10,000 a year later. Philip Morris had not donated to the group
before 1995. It has said its donations were not linked to the
trips. The chamber has also cited Bristol-Myers Squibb, the
pharmaceuticals conglomerate, as a big contributor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the chamber's tax records, which summarize its
finances without giving details, the donations from Philip Morris
and Pepsico shortly before the 1995 trip made up nearly 40 percent
of the chamber's total revenues for its fiscal year. It is unclear
how much Bristol-Myers Squibb donated, and when.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Philip Morris and Bristol-Myers, both headquartered in New York
City, also sent senior lobbyists to Hungary to take part in some of
the events on one of the trips. Brown said Pepsico arranged for the
governor to tour a company bottling plant in Hungary on the 1995
visit; it did not have a lobbyist accompany him.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies have significant interests before the state
government and were among the few to donate $25,000, the maximum,
to the private corporation that Pataki established to pay for his
first inauguration in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's trips to Hungary were a mix of family vacation
and trade mission. On the 1995 trip, he was accompanied by three
relatives, four aides and two security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Pepsico donation, Charles Deister, a spokesman
for Pataki, read a statement that said: ``Pepsico is a New
York-based company that employs 3,490 New Yorkers. It's in the
governor's interests to promote New York companies worldwide. We
were proud to tour Pepsico's Hungarian plant, and would gladly do
so again.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the governor have said he and his aides did not
ask the chamber about its backers and were not required to do so
under state ethics rules. The governor has declined to release
information about how much the chamber paid for the trips. He has
said he will not ask the chamber to make details of its finances
public.
</P>
<P>
   Monika Szarka-Elling, the chamber's president, did not respond
to two phone messages left at her office on Friday. She said last
month that she would not discuss the trips or the chamber's
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, which is headquartered in Purchase, N.Y., has
maintained warm relations with Pataki since he was a state
legislator representing Westchester County. A few months before the
1995 donation, Pataki and the Legislature approved a cut in soda
and beer taxes in response to a lengthy lobbying campaign by the
company and others in the beverage industry.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Pepsico spokesman, played down the $5,000 donation.
``If a Hungarian official were to use the Hungarian-American
Chamber of Commerce for a trip to the United States,'' Brown said,
``then we would very readily might have contributed and would most
certainly have looked to providing a tour of a factory here.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of the rules on gifts to administration officials, he said,
``There is absolutely no nexus between our participation in the
Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce and any issue which may have
impacted our business in Albany.'' He called back later to say that
with respect to the $5,000 donation, ``it is our understanding that
those funds went to the general operating budget of that
organization and there was no specific earmark on any of that money
having to do with any specific project.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
