<HEADLINE>
A MARTINEZ DOUBLE; HISTORY REPEATS; COLOR THEM BROWN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his league-leading 23-4 record, 2.08 ERA, 312 strikeouts
and .206 opponents' batting average, Pedro Martinez of Boston will
be the unanimous winner of the American League Cy Young award. But
will he be voted most valuable player as well by the 28-member
panel of the Baseball Writers Association?
</P>
<P>
   He will have competition from a gang of position players: Nomar
Garciaparra, his teammate; Ivan Rodriguez and Rafael Palmeiro of
Texas; Roberto Alomar and Manny Ramirez of Cleveland; Derek Jeter
of the Yankees. Before anyone proclaims Martinez the favorite
because of his spectacular pitching performance and what it has
meant for the wild-card Red Sox, a history lesson is in order.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Ron Guidry of the Yankees had a 25-3 record, a 1.74
ERA, nine shutouts and a .193 opponents' batting average. He led
the league with all of those numbers. His 248 strikeouts were
second to Nolan Ryan's 260. Guidry's ERA was 46 percent of the
leaguewide 3.76. Martinez's ERA is 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Martinez's pitching has been instrumental in the Red Sox
advance to the post-season, Guidry was greatly responsible for the
Yankees' division championship that season. But Guidry was not
named the AL MVP. Jim Rice of Boston was. Rice received 352 points
in the balloting, Guidry 291; Rice was named first on 20 ballots,
Guidry eight.
</P>
<P>
   Rice played for the team that the Yankees overtook and beat in a
playoff for the AL East title. He led the league with 46 home runs,
139 runs batted in, a .600 slugging percentage, 406 total bases,
213 hits and 15 triples. He was second in runs scored with 121 and
third in batting average with .315.
</P>
<P>
   Of this season's AL hitters who are among the leading
candidates, Ramirez most closely resembles Rice among the league
leaders, though he leads only in runs batted in and slugging
percentage. He also ranks high in home runs, batting average, total
bases, runs scored and on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   History Repeats
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine is apparently consistent, if nothing else. When
the Mets' manager used five pinch-hitters in an inning in a recent
game against Atlanta, the second of the Mets' disastrous seven-game
losing streak, he was merely repeating a pinch-hit strategy he
employed in a game against Montreal last September. That game, too,
was the second of a Mets collapse. Last year the date was Sept. 23,
this year Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning last year, the Mets were losing, 2-0, and
had runners at first and second with no one out. Jay Payton batted
for Lenny Harris and walked, loading the bases. Butch Huskey was
announced as batting for Carlos Baerga, but when reliever Mike
Maddux replaced Tim Young, Matt Franco batted for Huskey and popped
out. Todd Hundley then batted for Rey Ordonez and struck out. Luis
Lopez did the same when he hit for Bobby Jones. The Mets didn't
score, and they lost, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Braves this month, it was the eighth inning and the
Braves were leading, 3-2. Again the Mets had runners at first and
second with no one out. Melvin Mora batted for Benny Agbayani and
sacrificed the runners to third and second. Shawon Dunston was
announced as batting for Darryl Hamilton, but Russ Springer
relieved Mike Remlinger so Franco was sent up to hit for Dunston
and was walked intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Payton got into this inning, too, but as a runner for Franco.
Then Bonilla batted for Ordonez and struck out, and Todd Pratt hit
for Orel Hershiser and knocked an inning-ending grounder to second
base. The Mets again didn't score, and again they lost, this time
5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is bizarre, no doubt about that,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   Color them Brown
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hot it might get in Pittsburgh during the baseball
season, the Pirates won't have to worry about a brownout if they
maintain their current roster. For one game last week, in fact, the
Pirates had a Brown in, or more precisely three Browns in. Gene
Lamont's batting order had Browns in the first three spots _
Adrian, the center fielder; Emil, the left fielder; and Brant, the
first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   That game was not against Los Angeles, so Kevin Brown did not
pitch against the Brown trio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-02 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN   FLORIDA, A NEW CAMPAIGN BUT THE SAME REFRAIN;   REPUBLICAN
WOES IN CALIFORNIA;   AN IDAHO WEDDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Calif., Idaho) (js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., announced last March that he
would not seek re-election, it seemed for a while that just about
every politician in the state would jump into the contest to
replace him. But the race began to take some shape as the political
dance by candidates and would-be candidates subsided, and by
midsummer Bill Nelson, the insurance commissioner, had emerged as
the leading Democrat and Rep. Bill McCollum Springs as the leading
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   There was a possibility that McCollum might have to fend off a
primary challenge by Tom Gallagher, the education commissioner. But
by fall the general expectation was that the election to replace
Mack would be a knock-down, drag-out Nelson vs. McCollum fight,
with both national parties dumping gobs of money into the battle as
part of a larger war to control the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Logan, a man with a long memory, foresees a knock-down,
drag-out Nelson vs. McCollum vs. Logan battle. Logan is a black
state representative who is also a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his 16th in the House, his Democratic colleagues made
racial history in Florida by electing him minority leader, only to
make more history shortly thereafter by ousting him on the grounds
that he was not spending enough time raising money for the party.
He vowed to get even.
</P>
<P>
   And he did, in a way.
</P>
<P>
   During last fall's governor's race, he sided with the Republican
candidate, Jeb Bush, and urged the state's many black voters, most
of them Democrats, to do likewise or, at the least to stay away
from the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won, though it is difficult to quantify just how much Logan
contributed to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Logan have in mind for Election 2000?
</P>
<P>
   When he jumped into the Senate race, last week, he jumped in as
an independent, not as a Republican. Political parties have become
``irrelevant to the average voter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What he did not say was that no matter which party label he
wears, he has little chance of succeeding Mack. But as a black
independent, he stands to pull more votes from the Democratic
candidate than the Republican, meaning that in a close race, which
this one bids to be, he could end up handing the Republican the
winning edge.
</P>
<P>
   Same song as in the 1998 governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Different words.
</P>
<P>
   California: Republican Tremors
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party of California, once the mightiest in the
land, has been in a free fall since the last election, which saw
Democrats capture not only the governor's office and just about
every other top state job but also control of both houses of the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State Republicans remain in a black mood, demoralized, in
debt and divided by issues like abortion and gun control. A
gathering of top party members in Anaheim last weekend was by all
reports almost as much a civil war as a convention.
</P>
<P>
   And here's some more bad news, straight from the heart:
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, that sprawling, sun-splashed suburb south of
Los Angeles that once was considered the most Republican of all
Republican strongholds in the country (Anaheim is there),
Republican registration has fallen below 50 percent for the first
time in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Orange County Registrar of Voters, it slipped
to 49.98 percent just before the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican percentage has been going down in the county for
some time, as more and more Hispanic voters, who tend to lean
Democratic, have moved in and as more and more voters in general
have begun to register as independents, in Orange County as in the
rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year twice as many Democrats as Republicans have
registered in the county, and Democratic registration now stands at
32 percent. The county now has a Democratic congresswoman and a
number of Democratic state legislators, and the mayor of Anaheim is
a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   As for the independent vote, it has almost doubled over the past
decade, to around 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even at just under 50 percent, Republicans still hold a
reasonably comfortable registration edge over Orange Democrats. But
big trouble looms in elections in which the independent vote swings
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a wake-up call,'' John McGraw, the chairman of the
California Republican Party, said of the new registration figures.
``Orange County is very important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   How important?
</P>
<P>
   A decade and more ago, the Republican vote in the county was
almost twice as big as the Democratic vote, so heavy that
Republican candidates running for statewide office depended upon it
to help give them the edge needed to overcome Democratic domination
elsewhere. But in the 1998 governor's race, the Democratic
candidate, Gray Davis, carried the county, thanks to the growing
Democratic vote and to an independent vote that swung Democratic,
and that victory in turn helped him carry the entire state and
become the first Democratic governor in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho: A Wedding on a Political Scale
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Helen Chenoweth of Idaho doesn't do things in a small way.
</P>
<P>
   She is about as conservative as Republicans come in Congress.
And as outspoken as any legislator on Capitol Hill, Republican or
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it should come as no great surprise that she invited
11,000 people to her marriage Saturday in Meridian, Idaho, to Wayne
Hage, a rancher.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, love.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it should come as a surprise since only 1,200 people
could fit into the church.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, politics.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation list, it turns out, contained the names of not
only friends of the bride and groom but also the names of any and
all who have contributed time, money and effort to the Chenoweth
cause over the past five years, including the Chenoweth PAC,
Helen's List.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chenoweth _ make that Ms. Chenoweth-Hage, she now asks _
will be leaving the House next year, because she took a term-limits
pledge to serve no more than three two-year terms. But she hasn't
taken any pledge not to run for the Senate in 2002, given all the
talk in Idaho that the incumbent who will then be up, Larry Craig,
a fellow Republican, is pondering whether to retire.
</P>
<P>
   About the Chenoweth-Hage wedding cake ...
</P>
<P>
   It was a four-layer job, made of cream cheese, buttermilk
batter, pecans and coconut by Richard Langston.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Richard Langston whom The Idaho Statesman
calls ``cakemaker to the stars,'' the Richard Langston who when
J.R. Simplot, the potato king, turned 90 came forth with one cake
shaped like a sack of fertilizer and another that looked like a
spud.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
