<HEADLINE>
NO LOVE LOST BETWEEN PIPPEN AND BARKLEY 
SPREWELL IN COURT 
RETURN OF THE DUNK CONTEST 
OUT OF RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Barkley once called a future Hall of Fame player a
``big, old crybaby,'' a comment that stung his teammate and seemed
to ensure that the two would never play together again. But two
years later, Barkley and that teammate, Hakeem Olajuwon, were
coexisting on the same frontline, trying to summon their strength
for one more playoff run with the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen never had that kind of tolerance or patience for
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's words helped force his trade to the Portland Trail
Blazers on Friday night, a wild seven-player deal that brought the
Rockets six players, not one of them a starter: Kelvin Cato, Stacey
Augmon, Walt Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Houston's Frontline for the Ages had become worthy of
a Jack Lemmon and Walter Matthau sequel. Who would have thought?
Pippen and Barkley, Grumpy Old Ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Pippen have spent the last few years critiquing the
kids in the league who apparently don't respect the game or their
teammates, talking about Michael, Larry and Magic and the good old
days _ as if Charles and Scottie belonged in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was a genuine clash of personalities: two egos and
talents unable to play together. Maybe Pippen saw the Rockets for
what they are: Olajuwon, Barkley and a young malcontent named Steve
Francis, trying to resurrect some lost glory from 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you would think two of the greatest players of their
era would bow out gracefully. Instead, they have become more
petulant than some of their teen-age peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to want to leave after one year, it disappointed me
greatly,'' Barkley said last week, responding to Pippen's hint that
he wanted to play for former Bulls coach Phil Jackson in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen went on the offensive, and then some. ``I probably
should've listened to Michael a year ago when he said that Charles
will never win a championship because he doesn't show any
dedication,'' Pippen said in an ESPN interview. ``He's a very
selfish guy. He doesn't show the desire to want to win. That's my
reason for wanting to get away from playing with him, because he
just doesn't show the dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would apologize to Barkley for asking out of
Houston, Pippen said: ``I wouldn't give Charles Barkley an apology
at gunpoint. He can never expect an apology from me. If anything,
he owes me an apology for coming to play with his sorry fat butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping Shaquille O'Neal and Tim Duncan knock both Barkley
and Pippen out of the playoffs with the desire and passion those
two used to show before they became so sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   SPREWELL MAY BE DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how soon his civil trial over an auto accident ends
in the Bay Area, Latrell Sprewell may or may not make the first day
of Knicks training camp in Charleston, S.C., tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks guard is being sued by Arnulfo Perlas, 55, and Irma
Feliciano, 54, two Antioch, Calif., residents who were injured when
Sprewell's car struck theirs in March 1998, causing it to flip.
During his testimony in Contra Costa County Superior Court,
Sprewell admitted he caused the accident when he tried to get back
on the freeway from an exit-only lane.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he made a mistake, he answered, ``Without a
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it comes to Sprewell, it is all about perception, as
The Contra Costa Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprewell said that he was going as fast as 90 mph on the
bridge and then between 75 mph and 80 mph just before the
accident,'' the paper said. ``During the eight to 10 miles from the
bridge to where the accident occurred, Sprewell testified that he
changed lanes between five and 15 times, that he was driving faster
than the flow of traffic and that he passed every car he came upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprewell said he believed he was driving in a safe and
cautious manner.''
</P>
<P>
   DUNK CONTEST SET TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year hiatus, the slam dunk contest is returning to
All-Star Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league official, the National Basketball
Association has decided to add the event to the 2000 All-Star
Saturday festivities in Oakland, Calif., next February. Kobe
Bryant, who won the last contest during the 1997 weekend in
Cleveland, is expected to defend his title against six of the
game's most prominent skywalkers, including Toronto's Vince Carter
and Tracy McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   The competition was discontinued because league officials felt
it had deteriorated into a stunt show and because several
high-profile players backed out of it, reducing fan appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A REASON TO CARRY ON
</P>
<P>
   In less-rewarding times, a player with old legs and limited
skills retired because, frankly, he could not play anymore. With a
minimum salary of less than $300,000, it made sense to go out and
get a television analyst job and save your body. But with the
10-year minimum salary at $1.1 million, it apparently pays to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers last week signed John Salley and Benoit Benjamin,
neither of whom played in the league last season. Salley, 35, has
not played for three seasons. Benjamin, 34, has played for eight
teams in 14 seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
