<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-HOSPITALS-AR     10-02 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-HOSPITALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC HOSPITALS SEEK STRENGTH IN NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trouble with being St. Vincents Hospital was best
illuminated last month, when Cardinal John O'Connor found out he
had a brain tumor. The cardinal did not seek care at St. Vincents
but rather at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   While it was perhaps surprising that the cardinal _ who
technically oversaw St. Vincents as archbishop until recently _
chose to get care elsewhere, the choice underscored the basic
reality that high-profile patients have never been the hospital's
bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the central mission of all the region's Roman Catholic
hospitals has historically been quite unambiguous: to serve their
neighborhoods and to treat the very poor. Competition from the
city's prestigious medical centers was hardly a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, St. Vincents Hospital and Medical Center, the
jewel among the city's Catholic hospitals, has found itself facing
the same problems that public hospitals face: lower reimbursement
rates from government programs and managed care companies, shorter
hospital visits by patients, and increased competition from the
city's most renowned hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The choice became clear: merge with others and become more
cost-efficient, or perish. So last summer, the hospital, along with
Sisters of Charity Healthcare on Staten Island, agreed to merge
with the Catholic Medical Centers of Brooklyn and Queens.
Overnight, the region's largest Catholic health-care system was
born, with eight hospitals and scores of other services under its
wing.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will be the first of many acquisitions, the
executives involved in it said. When the city is left with a
half-dozen or so consolidated systems, as most health experts
expect, these executives want to make sure that one of them is
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of merger reflects what has been happening in health
care generally,'' said Robert Field, the director of the graduate
program on health policy at the University of the Sciences in
Philadelphia. ``Only religious institutions thought they could hold
out longer. But in the past four to five years, it has been more
and more difficult for them to resist the pressures of operating
like businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   While the new entity will face many of the challenges inherent
in any hospital merger, like ironing out who gets to run various
clinical departments and trying to haggle with managed care
companies, it will also face its own curious conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the merger was arranged ostensibly to help each
hospital continue to serve the city's poorest and sickest
residents. On the other, to compete as a behemoth among prestigious
academic medical centers, the new system will have to attract many
more higher-paying patients. As Adler said, ``You can't serve the
poor without a margin.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives of the merged entity, to be known as St. Vincents
Catholic Medical Centers of New York, are grabbing high-priced
talent left and right. (Non-Catholics are welcome to apply.)
</P>
<P>
   They hope to draw wealthier patients by continuing to build
clinical centers, like the spanking new cancer center at St.
Vincents, and a cardiac care unit that is already making inroads,
the executives said. The idea is that the smaller hospitals will
still serve as primary care centers, referring patients with more
complex problems to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic hospital consortiums have been formed in other parts of
the country for the same economic reasons that secular hospitals
have merged: to consolidate management of payrolls and to gain more
negotiating power with suppliers, laboratories and, most notably,
managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic medical executives have also decided that to protect
their values, especially regarding opposition to abortion and
assisted suicide, they are better off sticking together when
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice to be in health care; it is part of who we
are,'' said the Rev. Michael Place, president and chief executive
of the Catholic Health Association of the United States. ``And we
will continue to adapt while preserving our traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The church is no stranger to changes in health care; in many
ways, it was ahead of the consolidation curve. Its role in American
health care began 272 years ago when nuns and religious laywomen
took it on as part of their mission to help immigrants, and
church-sponsored hospitals resulted. Over the years, different
religious orders built large health-care systems, often stretching
across broad swaths of territory.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's largest groups, Catholic Healthcare West,
based in San Francisco, has been rapidly acquiring hospitals. The
consortium, which has 37 hospitals, has met with some success. Last
summer, for example, it was able for the first time to persuade
Blue Cross of California to increase its reimbursement rates for
all of the group's hospitals, after threatening to drop the
insurer.
</P>
<P>
   But attempts to merge hospitals from far and wide have also had
problems. Some have not performed as well as had been hoped, and
when the distances between a consortium's parts are great, one
hospital may have trouble referring patients to another. What is
more, cost savings, which at first can be substantial, tend to
dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental problem of operating such a large organization
is continuing to achieve the economies of scale and economic
benefits,'' said Laura Jacobs, a vice president of the Camden
Group, a health care consulting firm in El Segundo, Calif. She
added: ``Catholic systems by and large are financially strapped to
begin with. They have less wiggle room.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Cantu, the spokeswoman for Catholic Healthcare West,
said it ran into speed bumps in its rapid growth. ``We doubled in
size between '95 and '99; that kind of expansion really takes its
toll on individuals,'' she said. Many employees had no idea whom
they were working for, for instance. ``You tend to let things go
because you are too busy working on the next big deal,'' Ms. Cantu
said. ``We need to pay attention at each instance of what happens
after the merger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1651EDT &QL; 
