<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MTA-EXPANSION-500&AMP;     10-02 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MTA-EXPANSION-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTA'S CAPITAL PLAN GOES BEYOND SECOND AVENUE SUBWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The plan for a new Second Avenue subway got most of
the attention, but the Metropolitan Transportation Authority's
$17.5 billion, five-year capital plan includes a host of other
improvements stretching across the New York region.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, adopted on Thursday by the authority's board, would
provide the first major investment in decades _ $3 billion _ in new
tunnels, tracks and trains that would expand the region's subway
and commuter rail network.
</P>
<P>
   And while the plan immediately provoked protest over the $700
million that would be provided for the Second Avenue subway, an
amount many riders and Manhattan officials say is too little, the
ensuing debate may have diverted attention from the plan's breadth.
It calls for large investments in subway platforms and train
stations, and would lay the groundwork for the construction of
other new lines far afield from Second Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do things that would improve the economy as well as
improving the ride for our customers,'' Christopher P. Boylan, the
MTA's deputy executive director, said on Thursday as he described
what may have been one of the plan's biggest surprises _ $20
million for a new Metro-North station at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That station would only be built ``once lease discussion between
the city of New York and the Yankees is complete,'' according to
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Another project is a new tunnel extending the No. 7 subway line
from Times Square to the far West Side, providing access to what
some Manhattan officials envision as an expanded Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center. If such an expansion takes place, ``we stand
ready to move,'' said E. Virgil Conway, the MTA chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 7 subway project is presented as one of the most
tentative on the authority's wish list, with money provided only
for preliminary engineering and environmental studies. The plan
allocates $75 million for it and two other long-range expansion
projects: One would reconfigure tracks to give Metro-North trains
access to Penn Station, the other would provide new express service
by subway or Metro-North from Grand Central Terminal to lower
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Second Avenue subway isn't getting built until 2015, I
wouldn't expect these others until 2050,'' said Gene Russianoff,
staff lawyer for the Straphangers Campaign, a riders' advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Another major subway construction project was given higher
priority, and more financial backing, than many transit experts
outside the MTA had expected. That is the plan to provide direct
subway access to La Guardia Airport, probably through an extension
of the N line in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The plan provides $645 million for the project, including $500
million widely believed to have been added at the insistence of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Queens Borough President Claire Shulman,
both of whom have advocated the La Guardia subway link. It
stipulates that the new line would be completed, at least to the
boundary of La Guardia, by 2004. Connecting the line to airport
terminals would take longer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Obviously the mayor and borough president have been pushing,
but nobody is quite sure what the project will be,'' said Jeff
Zupan, a transportation analyst for the Regional Plan Association,
a nongovernmental planning group. There are several open questions,
including whether to build a new underground branch of the N train
or an elevated line through densely populated sections of Queens,
where residents have already voiced opposition to an elevated
structure.
</P>
<P>
   With such a broad assortment of projects, the MTA for now faces
its biggest test in Albany, where proponents of a larger Second
Avenue subway project have a powerful ally in Sheldon Silver, the
speaker of the Assembly, who represents the Lower East Side of
Manhattan. As one of four members of an oversight committee with
veto power over the capital plan, Silver has promised to block any
version that does not provide far more money for a Second Avenue
project.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, reflecting criticisms by many on the East Side, said
last week that a Second Avenue subway from the Bronx to the Battery
was needed to relieve crowding on the Lexington Avenue line,
something that would grow worse because of the largest project
provided for in the MTA plan. That project, budgeted at $1.6
billion, would provide access to Grand Central Terminal by the Long
Island Rail Road, in turn drawing new riders to the Lexington
Avenue line.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes several other projects that seemed likely last
week to survive any compromise forged in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The largest are improvements to existing rail and subway
stations, including a $225 million renovation of the Jamaica
Station, which serves the subway and the LIRR. That project, to be
completed by 2004, has been designed to upgrade the station as a
transfer point serving the new shuttle trains to Kennedy
International Airport that are planned by the Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Another project, budgeted at $75 million, would be at the
Atlantic Avenue station in Brooklyn, another hub for subway lines
and the LIRR. Throughout the subway system, the plan calls for
improvements ranging from new elevators and platforms to cosmetic
repairs at 64 stations in all five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also provides $140 million to maintain and expand fare
collection systems of New York City buses and subways, in which the
Metrocard has overtaken tokens as the preferred method of payment.
While upgrading the electronics of the Metrocard system, Boylan
said the authority will explore other technologies like a ``Smart
Card'' that could be used like the ``E-ZPass'' at highway toll
booths, enabling customers to charge their fares to a credit card
account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
