<SLUG> BC-NY-MIDTOWN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE BEWILDERED BY SHOOTING NEAR RAP STAR'S MIDTOWN STUDIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police said Saturday that they remained puzzled
by a shooting outside a building in midtown Manhattan that contains
a recording studio owned by Sean Combs, the rap star better known
as Puff Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting, which occurred shortly after 1:30 a.m. on Friday,
left the lobby door of the building at 321 West 44th St &UR; . &LR; 
shattered, the police said, and a trail of blood was found leading
to Combs' second-floor studio, Daddy's House.
</P>
<P>
   While they originally thought that the intended target had fled
there, the police said Saturday that it now appears the blood came
from a young woman who had been standing near the doors when the
bullets pierced them and who was injured by flying shards of glass.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose name and age were not released by the police,
received 35 stitches at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center before
being discharged, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   A man, Stan Johnson, 24, of Welch Street in the Bronx, was
arrested nearby after the shooting, but the police did not charge
him in connection with it.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, Johnson was sitting in a red Mercedes
with two other men when officers arrived to investigate the reports
of shots being fired. The officers approached the car when they
noticed Johnson was driving away without turning on his headlights,
they said, adding that he was arrested after he allegedly tried to
run over the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson faces charges of attempted assault, assault on a police
officer and reckless endangerment, the police said. Two passengers
in the car fled into a nearby building and have not been found,
they said. Although a 9-millimeter handgun was discovered in the
building, the police said they have not yet been able to link it to
the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Slovis, a lawyer who represents Lil' Cease, one of the
rap performers in the studio at the time of the shooting, said the
gunfire apparently followed a fight between two men at a nearby
bar, but he added that neither man was associated with Combs'
recording studio or with the people who were there that night.
</P>
<P>
   Slovis said the only reason the police went to Combs' studio was
because the woman cut by shards of glass had fled there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They detained Lil' Kim, Lil' Cease and Junior Mafia thinking
that a shooting victim was in the studio,'' Slovis said. ``But the
police eventually let them go, because the police know nobody was
shot in the building and that the tape they took from the entrance
of the studio shows nobody but the girl going inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
