<P>
   BBO-CURTRIGHT-COLUMN _ Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941 and Joe
DiMaggio had a record 56-game hitting streak. But neither led the
American League in hits that season. Georgia farm boy Cecil Travis
had 218 hits for the Washington Senators and batted .359 _ second
in the league. But it was to be Travis' last big season. He got his
induction notice on Christmas Eve, spent nearly all of World War II
in the army and never regained the batting stroke that gave him a
.314 career average. By 1947 he was out of baseball and back on his
Riverdale farm, where he still lives at age 86. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
