<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-FOSSETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHALLENGE TO YACHTING'S TRANS-ATLANTIC SPEED RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Fossett sets sailing records the way Mark McGwire crushes
home runs _ with startling regularity. In 1978, Fossett, buoyed by
a growing fortune in the securities market, began to make up for an
idle boyhood with forays into mountain climbing, marathon swimming
and triathalons. But it was not until 1991 that Fossett got truly
serious about his fun.
</P>
<P>
   That year, looking ``to find some interesting things to do,''
Fossett decided to take up long-distance ballooning and offshore
sailing. And the records in those endeavors soon began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the 55-year-old Fossett is planning to steer his
latest, wildest toy _ the grand, powerful 105-foot catamaran
PlayStation _ into New York Harbor in advance of his attempt to
topple one of yachting's most elusive marks: the 6-day-13-hour
trans-Atlantic speed record from New York to the English Channel,
set by the French cat Jet Services in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a window here where, for the next year, we'll
certainly have the fastest sailboat in the world,'' Fossett said in
a telephone interview. ``We want to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fossett's trans-Atlantic trip is just the opening scene
in a three-act play. In February, PlayStation is scheduled for an
all-out assault on the 71-day, nonstop round-the-world record. And
on Dec. 31, 2000, the boat will again try to conquer the planet in
an epic contest for unlimited sailboats called, simply, The Race.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation claimed the title of world's fastest sailboat in New
Zealand last March when Fossett and crew nailed a 24-hour run of
580 miles, the quickest ever under sail. ``Our top speed was 36.5
knots,'' Fossett said. ``But we can go faster. We hope to top 600
miles in a day. We're just beginning to explore the boat's
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   That potential was nearly dashed forever several weeks later
when the vessel's bank of experimental electric automobile
batteries caught fire and torched the resin-rich carbon-fiber hull.
The fire was soon under control, Fossett said, ``but we actually
had to cut the boat in half and build a whole new 26-foot section
of hull and splice that back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossett's resilience has been tested countless times. In 1999
alone, hopping from one vessel to another in his three-boat fleet,
Fossett added course-record victories in the Chicago-Mackinac and
Montego Bay races and a new record for the Newport-Bermuda passage
to his list of 10 speed sailing records and 8 race records.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his 40-hour singlehanded dash to Bermuda aboard his
60-foot trimaran Lakota, Fossett said, ``As a matter of personal
pride and self-esteem, I like to do one solo event each year so I
can do all the sailing and people can see that I can sail without
my crew.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the trans-Atlantic voyage on PlayStation, Fossett will
be just one of 11 seasoned crew members. In addition to the
co-skipper Ben Wright and his longtime allies Brian Thompson and
David Scully, the stellar cast includes the prominent West Coast
ocean racers Peter Hogg and Stan Honey; the boat's designers, Gino
Morelli and Pete Melvin, and one of Fossett's buddies from his
ballooning circles, Richard Branson, the Virgin Airlines chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard's had a long association with trans-Atlantic
endeavors,'' Fossett said. ``He had the powerboat record at one
time, and he still has the ballooning record. So I thought he'd
very much enjoy it if I invited him on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   From their base at Chelsea Piers, the PlayStation crew will
spend about two weeks in Manhattan on final preparations. They plan
to set out as soon after Oct. 25 as possible. First, they will need
the perfect forecast. Perfectly miserable, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to latch on to the spiraling low-pressure systems
that truck off the coast and across the North Atlantic and to ride
their westerlies for all they're worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The favorable wind must be from angles which produce the
fastest speeds and persist for as much of the crossing as
possible,'' said the meteorologist Chris Bedford, who will provide
shoreside routing assistance. ``We actually will be looking for
moderate, rather than strong winds, for the fastest crossing. We
want to make sure that the favorable pattern will hold for the
entire trip and not disappear at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   If PlayStation gets and holds the right breeze, the record will
be in serious jeopardy. Fossett would have it no other way. ``I
keep the book with all the world records for sailing right with
me,'' he said. ``I'm very aware of them all. And I'm looking for
opportunities to break them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
