</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL DAVIS RESTYLES THE RAIDERS;  
 LEWIS EXCELS 
ANOTHER CHANCE 
SPANISH INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   As difficult as it may be for some people in the National
Football League to hear, there is a man who may deserve an apology.
You know who he is. He wears those horrific white suits and
funny-looking glasses. He hates the league office _ and the people
in it hate him. He is Al Davis, owner of the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have flopped in recent years, and along the way
Davis has been called many things, including wacky, out of touch,
even a loser. There were some in the league who believed Davis
would never again be a winner. Harsh words for a man of such pride.
</P>
<P>
   So, as hard as this may be ... well, sorry for the unkind words,
Mr. Davis. You may finally have your act together. Your team is
good again. There. Was that so hard?
</P>
<P>
   Oakland is 2-1, and though that is not a reason to celebrate _
the Raiders still have plenty of time to self-destruct _ Davis has
recently made a number of astute moves to get his team back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Raiders' becoming one of the league's up-and-coming
teams is that Davis may have taken a hard look at himself. In some
ways he has not changed. He is still heavily involved in every part
of the organization. He still sues everyone except the local
grocer. But Davis, once wedded to the vertical passing game, has
finally entered into the modern football world. No team survives on
deep routes alone. The Raiders have drafted better, emphasized the
running game and focused on upgrading their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a talented team now and a strong foundation for
the future. If it were not for a miraculous, last-minute victory by
the Green Bay Packers in the season opener against them, the
Raiders would be 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have made several smart decisions in recent years.
Davis hired  &UR; c &LR; oach Jon Gruden, a move criticized by some in the
news media because he was unproven. But he has grown into a solid
leader, and Gruden hired one of the top coordinators in Willie
Shaw, who has turned the Raiders' defense into a solid group.
</P>
<P>
   While the Raiders have rushed for 424 yards and five touchdowns
on 91 attempts, their opponents have only 159 yards rushing and no
touchdowns. The Raiders also have six interceptions to one for
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland has built its impressive defense around two solid draft
picks: Darrell Russell, a first-round selection from Southern
California in 1997, and Charles Woodson, their top pick in 1998 who
won the Heisman Trophy while at Michigan. Russell has one and a
half sacks, and Woodson inspires the same kind of fear that Deion
Sanders once did. Teams rarely challenge Woodson, which is why he
has no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have even been able to get something out of running
back Tyrone Wheatley. After failing with the Giants and being cut
by the Miami Dolphins, Wheatley has found a home on the West Coast.
He leads the team in rushing with 176 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   And quarterback Rich Gannon has demonstrated an accurate arm
along with his good feet. Gannon has completed 63.6 percent of his
passes and has a quarterback rating of 93.4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At last, the pieces seem to be falling in place for the
Raiders. Because they have the league's toughest schedule, there
will be times this season when they stumble. But the Raiders
definitely have a playoff-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   So, Mr. Davis, more apologies may be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS EXCELS WITH PACKERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Based on the Packers' first three games, in which they have
shown an offensive explosion, the league owners no longer have any
excuses. If there is a head-coaching opening at the end of this
season and Green Bay's offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis does not
get it, then the people who claim that the league is racist will
have more ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis arrived with Mike Holmgren when he became the coach in
1992 and presided over the Packers' offense. But Holmgren called
the plays.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last season, Holmgren left for the Seattle
Seahawks, and now Lewis exclusively runs the offense. In Green
Bay's first three games the Packers have averaged 402 yards
compared with 352.3 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has also put his stamp on the offense. Holmgren tended to
be more conservative; Lewis likes to throw deep more.
</P>
<P>
   There could be five or more head-coaching openings at the end of
this season, and again the focus will be on the lack of black head
coaches, as it has been for years. But this year the situation is
different. If the Packers make the playoffs _ almost a guarantee _
and Lewis improves the offense after Holmgren's departure, then
every possible excuse not to hire him is gone.
</P>
<P>
   EMPATHY FOR UNDERWOOD
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins are prepared to give defensive lineman
Dimitrius Underwood, who recently attempted suicide, a chance to
play next season, assuming he undergoes successful counseling.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Underwood, a rookie, was arrested on a warrant
accusing him of nonpayment of child support, he was treated in a
Lansing, Mich., hospital. The police say he cut his neck with a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood's problems do not seem to shake Miami Coach Jimmy
Johnson, whose plan was to have Underwood receive extensive
therapy. But can Johnson, known for his ability to get the most out
of his players, salvage the career of the troubled Underwood?
</P>
<P>
   A SPANISH INFLUENCE
</P>
<P>
   Eight NFL teams have games broadcast on Spanish radio stations
in their markets. Professional football has become so popular in
the Latino community that the NFL has launched pro sports' first
Spanish-language Web site for news media covering games. ... The
struggles of Minnesota wide receiver Randy Moss continue. He has
only nine catches for 123 yards in his first three games. ... A
Tennessee victory against San Francisco Sunday would make the
Titans 4-0 for the first time in the franchise's history, including
as the Oilers. ... San Francisco general manager Bill Walsh has
ordered the team's office staff to wear 49er jerseys, bearing No.
99, on Fridays before home games.
</P>
</TEXT>
