u w BC-COX-COALITION03     10-02 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COALITION03 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scent of victory lures Christian Coalition
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes told
Christian Coalition members Saturday that he, not Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, should be their choice for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In a ballroom filled with his supporters, Forbes recited a
litany of positions that makes him a better fit for the coalition
than Bush, whose address on Friday was well received.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Forbes' list was his commitment to choose federal
judges and a vice presidential running mate who oppose abortion
rights. ``The front-runner won't promise to appoint pro-life
judges,'' or a pro-life running mate, Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   His direct attack on Bush also included a warning that
Republicans should not let Bush avoid debates with his rivals until
just before caucus and primary voting begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party deserves to know its nominee,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest applause lines came when he noted that, ``in
477 days, Bill Clinton will no longer be president.''
</P>
<P>
   But that statement also called attention to what makes Bush so
attractive as a candidate, even among voters who are more
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to elect a Republican president in 2000, after eights
years of Clinton, seems to have triumphed over ideological purity
in the minds of many conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer Forbes. I think he's a great guy,'' said John
McBride of Richmond, Va. ``But I guess I think Bush is the most
electable.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Anita Chase of Lugoff, S.C., sported Forbes stickers
and also spoke highly of GOP candidate Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   But Anita Chase said, ``We feel like Bush will be the
front-runner, and we'll vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband chimed in, ``We won't have any choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson voiced a similar
sentiment during the coalition's two-day political convention when
he said, ``If we aren't in the field in this coming election, then
the Republicans are going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He identified five states, Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey, Ohio
and Pennsylvania, in which a strong turnout by coalition members
could swing the election, in a close contest, to the Republican
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The 2 million-member organization has slipped in its
fund-raising and lost many of its most experienced hands during the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson exclaimed, ``We're back!'' when he spoke on
Friday, and predicted the group would raise enough money to
distribute 75 million voter guides in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Watson, a professor of religion at Florida State
University and author of a book on the coalition, doubted that
Robertson could restore the organization's luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger sense of dissatisfaction with the direction of
American culture is still there,'' said Watson, who listened to the
weekend's speeches. ``But this particular vehicle has run out of
gas, and I don't see anything that will really galvanize these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the program included seven candidates for president and
the top Republicans in Congress, evidence that religious
conservatives remain a significant Republican constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
