<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MORTGAGES-REAL-1200(3     10-02 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGES-REAL-1200(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASING THE RULES FOR MORTGAGE APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN S. OSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sisters Arlene Jones and Judith George are close.
They grew up together in the Virgin Islands, and after they arrived
in Brooklyn in 1978, when they were in their early 20s, they lived
in apartments two blocks apart.
</P>
<P>
   They long hoped to own homes near each other, and this year they
achieved that goal. They moved into side-by-side two-family houses
on Elton Street in the East New York section of Brooklyn, each
paying $175,000 for a house newly built through the New York City
Housing Partnership program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to find it,'' said Ms. Jones, who is an
executive assistant at Keyspan Energy, the parent company of
Brooklyn Union Gas. When they were house-hunting the builder still
had adjoining houses available in a development of 40 houses that
were in construction.
</P>
<P>
   They were lucky for a less obvious reason as well. In
considering them for a mortgage, Chase Manhattan Bank let them
count most of their prospective rental income in a way that
qualified them for the loan they needed. They would not have
qualified for their loans if the bank had used traditional
underwriting standards.
</P>
<P>
   The less restrictive standards have come into wider use in
recent years in the sales of homes that have at least one rental
apartment. They have had the effect of allowing creditworthy
borrowers with somewhat lower incomes _ usually close to the median
family income in New York City of $50,000 a year _ to buy houses.
Ms. Jones and Ms. George have incomes in the $40,000-a-year range.
</P>
<P>
   The basic change is that in determining the borrower's ability
to afford the loan, a large portion of the rent that will be
collected is applied as an offset to the monthly costs the borrower
will bear. Buyers for years have thought that they were doing that
by getting a rental tenant or two.
</P>
<P>
   But the principle had not been generally embraced by mortgage
lenders in loan underwriting. Instead, a portion of rental income
was merely added to the buyer's gross income to determine
eligibility. This creates a higher ratio of housing costs to income
than the new method does.
</P>
<P>
   For buyers who can afford a 5 percent down payment, the new
method makes it more likely they will qualify for a loan of 95
percent of the purchase price of a two-family house.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant number of two- to four-family home buyers have
benefited from this approach,'' said Wesley Wainwright, senior vice
president of Chase Manhattan Bank in charge of residential lending
in the Community Development Group.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, the major banks supporting the New York City Housing
Partnership's program of new-home construction for moderate-income
buyers have used this approach in qualifying purchasers. But it got
greater impetus in 1994 when Fannie Mae, the nation's largest
purchaser of mortgages from banks and other home-mortgage
originators, introduced pilot programs to stimulate the home sales
market in New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae packages these loans with other mortgages as
securities for sale to investors. Creating a market to which
mortgage originators can sell their loans encourages them to lend
more.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Fannie Mae pilot program, the houses may be either
newly built or previously occupied. The purchasers do not have to
be first-time buyers, although most have been. The buyers must live
in the house they buy, and if they formerly owned a home, they have
to have sold it before they close on the new one. There are no
income restrictions on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical situation, a creditworthy buyer with an income of
about $45,000 in wages and the ability to make a 5 percent down
payment would qualify for a 95 percent mortgage on a two-family
house costing about $200,000, Fannie Mae said. This assumes that
the apartment would rent for about $800 a month. Previously the
same buyer would probably have needed $55,000 a year in income to
qualify for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pilot program began, it has been used in about 10
percent of all the loans for two-family to four-family houses in
New York City that Fannie Mae has purchased, the company said. Last
year, Fannie Mae's total purchases of New York City two- to
four-family loans was 4,200 _ with an aggregate value of $788
million _ and 11 percent used the pilot underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be having its greatest effect in Brooklyn and
Queens, and especially for two-family homes,'' said Naomi Bayer,
director of the New York office of Fannie Mae, which was
established in Manhattan four years ago. She also said that most
buyers may not need such financing, because they have higher
incomes or can make a higher down payment. They also may not know
about it, she said, so they may not ask their lender about it.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly payment that a home buyer makes to a lender covers
not only the principal and interest due on the mortgage loan but
also contributions to escrow accounts for real-estate taxes and
insurance, and, in many cases, private mortgage insurance on that
portion of the debt that exceeds 80 percent of the value of the
house. Bankers refer to the monthly payment they receive for these
obligations as the ``PITI'' payment, an acronym for principal,
interest, taxes and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pilot program, the bank, in calculating how large a
loan it will offer to the purchaser of a two-family house, uses 75
percent of the buyer's anticipated rental income as an offset to
this monthly payment. The minimum down payment is 5 percent, and
the buyer must have at least $1,000 a month in additional income
after the monthly payment is made.
</P>
<P>
   The standards are slightly different for three- and four-family
houses, but the principle is the same. These buyers must put down
at least 10 percent, and the income they have left after their
monthly payment must be higher _ at least $1,250 for a three-family
loan and $1,350 for a four-family.
</P>
<P>
   In standard underwriting of residential mortgages, rental income
is considered too. But it is added to the buyer's gross income
rather than deducted from monthly costs for purposes of calculating
how large a loan the borrower can afford. The standard approach
leads to a more conservative loan.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program has been been used by buyers spending over
$300,000 for a two-family house, bankers say. The national 1999
limits on loans that Fannie Mae will buy _ $240,000 for a
one-family house, $307,100 for a two-family, $371,200 for a
three-family and $461,350 for a four-family _ apply to the pilot
program as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae requires that first-time buyers get counseling both
in home ownership and in acting as a landlord, before it will buy
these loans. In resale housing only landlord counseling is
required.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McEnerney, president of Bank of New York Mortgage Co &UR; .,
 &LR;  said that it is only in the last year or year and a half that the
new Fannie Mae standards have become widely available in
three-family and four-family sales, although in two-family sales
they have generally been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always take a little time for the lending community to get
comfortable with new standards,'' McEnerney said, ``and we're only
beginning to get enough data on the performance of these loans to
the threes and fours.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One older house was bought recently by Dimitriy Bobkov, 23, an
information specialist with IBM, who arrived in the United States
from Ukraine five years ago, and his brother Vitaliy, 31, who is a
self-employed computer technician. Their combined income is about
$80,000 a year, Dimitriy Bobkov said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers bought a three-family house for $194,000 in the Sea
Gate section of Brooklyn a year ago with a Bank of New York
mortgage, and also spent about $25,000 to improve it, doing much of
the work themselves. They are getting $500 a month in rent from a
tenant, a friend who agreed to rent the apartment before the
brothers bought the house. They received a $174,600 mortgage at
conventional rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Possibly we could have gotten another loan but it would have
been much more trouble,'' Dimitriy Bobkov said. ``We would have had
to put 20 percent down instead of 10 percent.'' And the rent
calculation would have been less favorable.
</P>
<P>
   More liberal underwriting also carries risks, for both the
lender and the borrower. Nowadays many lenders are offering
subprime loans, for example, which go to less creditworthy
borrowers and carry higher-than-normal interest rates. Presumably,
during a period of prosperity and high employment borrowers in
general will be successful in carrying this debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   But many lenders and housing specialists caution buyers about
becoming too dependent on rent. What happens in a recession, and a
weakened housing market, when both buyers and renters may face a
loss of income? If the tenant cannot afford the rent, will he leave
quickly and be replaced by another tenant at the same rent? If the
owner has to seek an eviction in housing court, will he get quick
action or have to go for months with no rent collections?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fannie Mae program is a fabulous thing if it's used
correctly and not abused,'' said Keith Kantrowitz, president of
Power Express, a mortgage company in Great Neck. He said that about
20 percent of the resales of two- to four-family houses that Power
Express finances in the city use the Fannie Mae pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the program were not there, many buyers would be forced to
use subprime loans to buy their house, if they could buy at all,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some buyers overlook potential problems that mortgage
underwriting does not take into account, he said, and then they
lack the resources to deal with them. There can be overoptimism on
the rents that can be obtained and unanticipated problems with
basic housing systems. Heating costs and water and sewer charges
may turn out to be beyond expectations, and the cost of gardening
and cable service may have been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Kantrowitz said he had already seen evidence of negative
effects. Over the last five years, there have been seven
foreclosures in loans Power Express financed, more than would be
expected in an upward market, he said, because buyers facing
foreclosure might be expected to sell and move. In one case, a
borrower of $211,000 made 40 payments on time and then abruptly
stopped paying for a full year, Kantrowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tenant simply stopped paying the rent, and the owner can't
get him out,'' he said. ``And the house isn't salable. Who would
buy a house when the tenant's not paying?''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a 1996 buyer of a three-family house in the
Canarsie section of Brooklyn with two tenants in place made only
three payments on a $221,000 loan. ``She moved into an area where
the cost of child care was much higher than she expected,'' he
said, ``and then the cost of heating buried her.'' It was winter
and she was getting heating bills of $600 a month. She had budgeted
$150 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go into a house in December on a budget that uses
average year-round heating costs,'' Kantrowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   In new housing, some of these problems are minimized. The owner
gets to select the tenant _ many times a family member _ and
operating costs are more clearly foreseeable. Tax abatements for
new home construction, which are passed on to buyers, also are a
big help. ``For a novice in home ownership, the new house has great
advantages,'' Kantrowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage for any owner is a healthy rental market.
Rising rents may help the home buyer even in the early years of
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   In the Highbridge section of the Bronx, Isabel Santos has had a
positive experience with tenants. She said she was well aware of
the risks she was taking on when she bought a new three-family
house on Woodycrest Avenue through the Partnership program for
$322,000 five years ago. ``I was worried about my ability to find
responsible tenants,'' said Ms. Santos, who is in her 50s and is a
field worker for a union, earning in the high $40,000-a-year range.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out out, not only has she had regular rent
collections, but also the rents have risen _ from a total of $1,640
for the two apartments to $1,725, which fully covers her monthly
housing costs. ``I didn't even have to advertise for tenants,'' Ms.
Santos said. ``They're both friends of mine, and one is a colleague
at work.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Housing Partnership program, nonprofit organizations
working with lenders provide budgeting and landlord counseling. The
Partnership itself, in collaboration with developers, provides
instruction on home maintenance, and it expects in the future to
take on both aspects of owner education.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 14,000 Partnership home buyers since 1986, and
more and more of the newer houses are three-families. Nowadays the
loans are normally sold to Fannie Mae, and the underwriting for
them follows Fannie Mae's standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't be developing two- and three-family houses without
the Fannie Mae underwriting,'' said Gale Kaufman, vice president of
the Housing Partnership. Rental income is a secure form of income,
she said, and the renters are often the owner's relatives. Loans
made under the Partnership program have a default rate of less than
1 percent, Ms. Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   But as in any home purchase _ whether a new house or a resale _
buyers are responsible for their own decisions. The obvious
precaution they are advised to take before they buy the house is to
have it inspected. This is often done in a cursory way, however, by
buyers eager to save money or lock in the purchase with a contract
so as not to lose out to another buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays there's pressure being put on buyers to go into
contract within 10 days,'' said Donald Siracusa, whose
home-inspection business, Absolute Building Inspections Ltd., is
based in Bay Terrace. Buyers are often not willing to take the time
or pay the price for a proper inspection by a professional
certified by the American Society of Home Inspectors, in Des
Plaines, Ill., said Siracusa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a lack of knowledge.'' he said. ``Many buyers
don't even read the report when they get one. Or they hire people
unqualified to make them, who are too close to the sales broker.''
The cost of a proper inspection for a two-family house on Staten
Island has been about $350, Siracusa said. The reports that he
gives to customers, with photographs, are in narrative form.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae made the following comparison to explain how the
pilot program would make a two-family home purchase affordable
while conventional underwriting would not.
</P>
<P>
   In Fannie Mae's conventional underwriting for two-family home
loans nationally, buyers must make at least a 10 percent down
payment (but only 5 percent in New York City, and 3 percent for
single-family houses). In addition, 75 percent of the owner's
rental income from the rental apartment would added to the buyer's
annual income to calculate eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   So if the house costs $200,000 and the buyer earns $44,000 and
can collect $850 a month in rent, the buyer's income would be
considered $51,644 a year. Three-quarters of the rent _ $637 a
month, or $7,644 a year _ would be added to annual income.
</P>
<P>
   Although this buyer might be able to make a 5 percent down
payment, his application to borrow $190,000 would probably be
denied. A 30-year loan at 7.5 percent interest, plus payments to
escrow accounts for taxes and insurance, would bring the
applicant's monthly payments to about $1,660, or $19,920 a year.
This is 38 percent of the buyer's gross annual income of $51,650.
The normal limit in affordable-housing programs is 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot program, no more than a 28 percent ratio of housing
costs to income is allowed (but 33 percent for new houses in the
Partnership program). The $44,000-a-year buyer would find the
$190,000 loan affordable. His monthly obligation would be only
$1,023 after deducting 75 percent of the rental income ($1,660
minus $637). On an annual basis, net housing payments would be
$12,276 ($19,920 minus $7,644), or 27.9 percent of his income.
</P>
<P>
   After all the calculations are made, the lender would take into
account the buyer's residual income after his monthly payments, to
ensure that the borrower is not overly dependent on rental income.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Jones, who bought the house in East New York next door to
her sister Judith, a Board of Education employee in downtown
Brooklyn, said that they had advertised in the Amsterdam News for a
renter and received about 60 phone responses.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the Brooklyn Neighborhood Improvement
Association, which assists moderate-income home buyers, interviewed
three of these respondents. Only that number were willing to risk
$50 for an interview and credit check.
</P>
<P>
   One tenant was selected by Ms. George. Ms. Jones readvertised
and then found one. The rent levels turned out to be higher than
those used in the underwriting, by $50 a month in one case and $80
in the other, Ms. Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters have been in their homes for two months. Ms. Jones,
who has four daughters ranging in age from 7 to 22, said her family
had lived for 20 years in an apartment that had only one bathroom.
Now she has two. She also has her own parking place, on her own
property right next to her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
