<HEADER>
A4634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-COX-850(2TAK     10-02 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COX-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COX'S TWO WORLDS UNITE SENSITIVITY WITH PLAYER RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ If you thought the Jets were getting an undisciplined,
angry man when they plucked Bryan Cox out of oblivion 14 months
ago, talk to the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a different opinion, talk to his children.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just last Sunday night he practically cried when he took
his wife, La Tonia, and their three children to the airport and
sent them home to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But this Sunday, he will revert to the intense linebacker who
nearly went into the stands after a fan the last time he played in
Denver's Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cox loves both worlds, and coexists in remarkable harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Broncos, the competitive _ some might say angry _
side of Cox is sure to surface. This is a clutch game, as important
as any he has played with the Jets. They are 0-3 and the Broncos
are 0-3 in this first meeting since the championship game matching
them last January. In that game, the biggest one the Jets have
played since 1982, Cox led the team in tackles.
</P>
<P>
   In big games, Cox has been superb, especially since becoming a
Jet. He has taken on the role of leader with his actions in
pressure situations. He is the one who grabbed the rookie Jason
Wiltz by the face mask in the season opener when Wiltz failed to
get onto the field in time. And he scolds teammates on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mo Lewis and Marvin Jones are more veteran linebackers,
Cox is the one who gets the players' attention, not only with his
demands, but also with his signal-calling. He makes sure the
defense is lined up correctly. And he is the one whom the news
media lines up for when the locker room is opened before practice.
Reporters stand three-deep waiting for him to say something.
</P>
<P>
   Cox has more than backed up his mouth. He is the only Jet to
intercept a pass this year _ he returned it for a touchdown in the
opener against the Patriots, giving the Jets a fourth-quarter lead.
In this demoralizing start, he has knocked down three passes _ the
same number as the Pro Bowl cornerback Aaron Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   In the game at Miami last year that the Jets needed to win to
clinch a playoff berth, Cox led in tackles, returning to the city
where he had starred and gone to the Pro Bowl three times. A week
later he led the defense against the Bills in Orchard Park, N.Y.,
where he had once fought with an opponent and jawed at fans whom he
said were racist. The Jets clinched their first division title
since the American Football League days with a 17-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the 31-year-old Cox why he performs so well in the clutch,
and he does not hesitate in offering a reason. It has to do with
being raised in a tough town, East St. Louis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to grow up in a place like that,'' he said,
``having to work, go through the struggle. If you grow up in a
rich, white neighborhood, and preppy, your father's head of a
company _ when something bad happens, you fold.''
</P>
<P>
   So, adversity had honed him?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. He grew up in a private home with a two-parent
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I had four parents,'' Cox said, ``a stepmother and a
stepfather. I spent weekends with my father. My stepfather was
college-educated as a sociologist. My father was a hard-working man
until he was stricken with arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was strong, I was protected. I had everything _
maybe I couldn't get a pair of Jordan's.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the streets attracted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You live in a concrete jungle,'' he explained. ``I never hurt
people. I did some things. When I go back to East St. Louis, I see
the same guys. Some of them tell me, `You shouldn't be seen around
us.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Cox said he would never desert the friends he had when he
was young. ``There are times on the football field I feel the same
way about my teammates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And his family, he might have added. He brings them to New York
when the Jets have a 1 p.m. Sunday game. And he sees them off to
Atlanta on Sunday night. On Saturday nights, the Cox clan stays in
the hotel with him. He and La Tonia have two children. A third
child is hers from a previous marriage, and he also has a teen-age
daughter in East St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   There have been moments on the field when Cox has looked more
like the East St. Louis street fighter of his youth than a model
football player, let alone father. There was his tirade in Orchard
Park, another one in Chicago against officials. There was, to a
lesser degree, his actions as a Jet last year at Tennessee, when in
one quarter he clubbed running back Eddie George and quarterback
Steve McNair. He was fined $10,000 a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   His children _ Lavonda, 15, Brittani, 7, and Bryan Jr., 5 _ are
aware of his wild side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they laugh,'' he said. ``Sometimes they tell me I'm
an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't believe that is so strange because, he said: ``My
kids are my friends. But you know, they're just like all kids.
They're sort of embarrassed to be with me. We'll go to the mall,
and they say, `Dad, can you just walk ahead?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Part idiot, part friend, this is the Bryan Cox the Jets rescued
from oblivion in August 1998, the day after the team learned Jones
would be lost for the year with a knee injury. The Bears had
dropped Cox following an acrimonious two seasons in which he
complained about management and, on occasion, teammates. But from
1991 to 1995 he had starred for the Dolphins, before becoming a
free agent upon the arrival of Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had known Bill Parcells for years. Both own thoroughbred
horses. When Cox was in high school he worked in the kitchen of
Fairmount Park racetrack in Collinsville, Ill. He always loved
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is it eases my mind,'' he said. ``If I can't hook
up with my kids, I go to the track or watch horses train in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   When he became a Dolphin, he played a round of golf with someone
who had a partial interest in a horse. Cox bought a piece of the
horse _ and it won the first race for him.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Cox owned several, calling his stable Freakman Stables. A
mutual friend introduced him to another man who owned horses:
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had known Cox for years before Jones was injured. It
was an eye-raising move, however. The volatile Cox coming to the
overscrutinized Jets? Parcells never wavered. Within a few weeks,
Cox was a starting outside linebacker in the Jets' 4-3 scheme. This
year he has moved to the inside in a shift to the 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells recently reflected on some of the top players he has
coached and mentioned the Giants' Lawrence Taylor, the Patriots'
Sam Gash _ and Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a very determined, honest player,'' Parcells
said. ``I've got a lot of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronco fans don't have the same opinion of Cox, but despite last
January's incident Cox is cheerful about his return to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going back to the place where I got hit in the face with a
beer can,'' Cox said, adding good-naturedly: ``But the police did
such a wonderful job. They beat him up. I didn't have to take it in
my hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
