<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAN CELEBRATES 100TH BIRTHDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- You sit down and talk to Henry Rabow on his 100th
birthday Friday, and you don't know whether to congratulate him or
console him.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, he's glad to still be around, he says _
considering the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   As Henry looks around him these days, he doesn't see many faces
he recognizes anymore. All his pals and older relatives are long
gone, and it gets a little lonely not having anybody to talk to
who'd been with you back in the old days, Henry says.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you start feeling a little sorry for him, one of
the 61 women living over at the Wedgewood, an upscale retirement
home in the Tarzana community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley,
comes walking by with a wink and a birthday card.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when Henry Rabow _ one of only a handful of men
living there _ gets this smile on his face that says, OK, so maybe
I'm not all that lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, if he could do, he would do,'' says Evelyn Morton,
administrator of the Wedgewood. ``He's the most popular guy
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too bad for 100.
</P>
<P>
   Funny the things you remember when you look back over a century
of life, Henry says.
</P>
<P>
   Like the times when he and his buddies would stand on the
sidewalk in Toronto, his hometown, waiting for one of those new
contraptions called the horseless carriage to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd take off our caps and throw them in the middle of the
street so we'd get the gas fumes on the caps after the carriage
went by,'' he said. ``That was a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the time his mother _ a widow raising five children by
herself _ took him to his first day of kindergarten and sat him
down on one of the three-legged stools all the kids were sitting
on.
</P>
<P>
   He fell off and started crying, Henry said. Not because he was
hurt, but because he didn't want his mother to leave him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how she managed to raise us all by herself,'' he
says. ``I still don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knew he'd have to get a job, like his brothers, and help
out. So he did _ working in the grocery business in Toronto before
coming to New York in 1928 to learn the retail clothing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my brothers and I worked for the same company for 35
years, and we wound up buying it, but we went bankrupt in 1963,''
Henry says.
</P>
<P>
   It was pretty traumatic at the time, going belly up in business,
but when you've had 37 years to reflect on it, it becomes just
another little milestone along the way you remember on your 100th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the biggest men in this country have failed at times,
including Henry Ford,'' Henry Rabow says. So there.
</P>
<P>
   If he had his way, he'd still be living on his own _ still be
back in the home he shared with his wife, Dolly, before she died in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   They were happy together there, and even after she died, he
didn't mope around for very long, Henry says. His niece Lola Rabow
wouldn't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   She got him volunteering at the place she worked, the
Organization for the Needs of the Elderly, and before long, Henry
was one of the busiest, most popular volunteers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of years ago, his family thought it would be best
for him to move into the Wedgewood because they didn't want him to
be living alone at 98, even though his health and faculties were
good.
</P>
<P>
   So, that's where Henry is now, celebrating his 100th birthday _
only a few months shy of living in three centuries. The most
popular guy there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Birthday, Henry,'' says another female resident of the
Wedgewood on Friday, stopping by to give Henry a birthday card and
a wink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' he says to the woman, putting the card with the
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was in the millinery business so I'm comfortable
around women,'' he says, looking around to make sure none of the
women are within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to tell you the truth, I'd rather be sitting around with a
bunch of men. Trouble is, there are none my age around anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, you just don't know whether to congratulate or console
Henry Rabow on his 100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
