<HEADLINE>
TRANSFERRING A HOME TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., N.Y.)  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers who specialize in estate planning say that one of the
more effective methods of passing real estate to the next
generation _ while keeping a home of one's own for as long as one
needs it and perhaps avoiding probate _ is the life estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A life estate usually works nicely,'' said Linnea Levine, a
lawyer who specializes in elder law in Purchase, N.Y., and
Stamford, Conn. ``And it usually works nicely on several levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levine explained that a life estate _ or ``life use'' in
Connecticut _ is a legal arrangement whereby title to real estate
is held by two entities, a ``life tenant,'' who has the right to
use the property for life, and a ``remainderman'' who obtains full
ownership of the property upon the death of the life tenant.
</P>
<P>
   With a life estate, she said, the life tenant can live in the
property, leave it vacant, or rent it to others, but cannot sell
the life tenancy without the consent of the remainderman. Moreover,
Ms. Levine said, the life tenant is responsible for paying the
costs of owning the property _ including mortgage payments,
property taxes, and hazard insurance premiums _ as well as for
maintaining the property by doing things like shoveling the walk
and keeping the heat on in winter so the pipes don't freeze.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, Ms. Levine said, most life estates occur
in the context of a parent or parents conveying title to a property
to a child or children while retaining a life tenancy in the
property for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you put the property in the names of the
children before you die, but you've set things up so they can't
sell the property out from under you while you're still alive,''
Ms. Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that if a life estate is not used, and title to a
house is transferred from parents to children using the more common
form of ownership, called ``fee simple,'' it is conceivable that
the children could evict the parents from the house if there is a
falling-out between the parties at a later time.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Siev Belson, an elder-law lawyer in Stamford, said that
another advantage of using a life estate as opposed to a fee simple
transfer when putting a house in the names of one's children is
that with a life estate, the life tenant can remain in the house
for life even if creditors obtain judgments against the children.
</P>
<P>
   If the house is put in the names of the children without using a
life estate, Ms. Belson said, it is possible that a creditor who
obtained a judgment against a child who is the fee-simple owner
could force the sale of the property and the eviction of the parent
if the child did not satisfy the judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of using a life estate to transfer property to
children, Ms. Belson said, is that doing so makes it unnecessary
for the property to be transferred through probate when the last
surviving parent dies. She explained that probate is the process
whereby title to certain property of a deceased person passes to
that person's heirs or beneficiaries _ either by will or by
operation of law _ subject to court supervision.
</P>
<P>
   With a life estate, she said, title to the property is deemed to
have passed to the children while the parent was still alive,
thereby eliminating the necessity for probate _ at least with
respect to that property.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason for using a life estate rather than a fee
simple transfer is that with the former form of ownership, the life
tenant remains the owner for purposes of qualifying for tax
benefits available to the property owner.
</P>
<P>
   Among those benefits are property-tax exemptions and credits
that are available to certain individuals _ such as veterans and
homeowners 65 years or older who qualify for the STAR (School Tax
Relief program) tax exemption in New York by having annual incomes
of $60,000 or less. The program gives varied exemptions, depending
on location of the property, on the assessed value of a house, the
basis of reckoning taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Belson pointed out that the fact that a life estate transfer
of property is not subject to probate does not shield it from
federal gift and estate taxes. Generally speaking, she added,
roughly the same amount of taxes will ultimately be paid whether or
not a life estate is used.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, under current law, the first $650,000 of an
individual's estate _ or of gifts made during the individual's
lifetime _ is exempt from such taxes. The exemption amount
gradually increases to $1 million in 2006.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The use of a life estate, however, could result in a reduction
of capital gains taxes that may be due upon the ultimate sale of
the property.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Treacy, a Rutherford, N.J., lawyer who specializes in
estate planning, said that if a homeowner transfers title to the
property to a child without payment, the transfer is considered a
gift for tax purposes. In such a case, he said, the original
owner's tax basis _ typically the cost of the property plus amounts
spent in purchasing, selling and improving it _ becomes the tax
basis of the new owner.
</P>
<P>
   That means that when the new owner _ in this case, the child _
sells the property, the entire difference between the original tax
basis and the ultimate sale price is likely to be considered the
child's taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Treacy said, when a life estate is used, the
transfer is considered an ``incomplete gift'' for tax purposes
because the passage of title doesn't become ``complete'' until the
death of the life tenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that the child receives the same tax benefit as if
the property had passed to him or her upon the death of the last
surviving parent,'' Treacy said, explaining that in such a case,
the beneficiary receives a ``step-up'' in basis to the market value
of the property at the time of the life tenant's death.
Accordingly, he said, when the property is sold, only the
difference between the sale price and the value of the property at
the time of the life tenant's death is considered taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Another somewhat controversial benefit of transferring property
using a life estate is that doing so makes it possible to shield
the house from creditors _ including those who are seeking payment
for medical services, nursing-home care and reimbursement for
Medicaid payments that have been provided.
</P>
<P>
   Treacy explained that under current law, it is possible for a
homeowner who has received Medicaid benefits _ or who has run up
significant medical bills or who requires nursing-home care _ to be
forced to sell a home to reimburse Medicaid or cover those other
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible _ and allowable under current law _ for such
a person to transfer a house to a child or children using a life
estate and thereby avoid the possibility of having to sell the
house, or lose it to creditors, to cover later medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you follow the rules and do everything the right
way, it's a perfectly legal estate-planning strategy,'' Treacy
said. For such a transfer to successfully survive the scrutiny of
Medicaid officials, he explained, it must have been made a
sufficient amount of time before Medicaid benefits were applied
for. As a general rule, he said, three years or more between the
date of the transfer and the application for benefits will always
be considered sufficient. Less than three years may also be
considered sufficient, depending on the individual circumstances
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of folks, the only thing they have to leave to their
children is their house,'' Treacy said. ``So for a lot of older
people, the most important issue for them is protecting their only
real asset _ their home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
