<SLUG> BC-MAINE-GOLF-REAL-795(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF COURSES INCREASE MAINE HOME SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Maine _ Taking a cue from Southern states, developers
in Maine have begun to emphasize the availability of new golf
courses and the expansion of existing ones in their sales of new
homes to a market made up increasingly of vacationers or retirees.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen new or expanded golf courses have recently been
completed or are being built, bringing the state's total to about
130. The new or improved ones have had a major effect in increasing
housing starts, especially in vacation destinations like Belgrade
Lakes, York and Old Orchard Beach, said James Plumer, president of
Construction Data of New England, which tracks industry activity.
</P>
<P>
   These houses are typically traditional Colonials and Cape Cods,
with clapboard siding, peaked roofs and enclosed porches with wood
paneling and stone fireplaces inside. The prices vary with the
local real estate market; most houses do not abut golf links, but
sales have benefited from the development of courses nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, a secluded, picket-fence town about 20 miles north
of Augusta with 15,000 acres of waterfront property stretching
along a chain of six north-south lakes, a new year-round house near
the water costs $130,000 to $350,000. In the woods away from the
water the cost is about half as much.
</P>
<P>
   But in bustling York, 150 miles to the south on the ocean, new
waterfront estates sell for $1 million to $4 million, while houses
inland start at around $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sales to vacationers and out-of-state buyers have accounted for
a large part of the resales of existing housing, said Valarie
Lamont, director of the Institute for Real Estate Research at the
University of Southern Maine in Portland. Last year, 10,080
existing homes were sold statewide, a rise of about 30 percent from
a year earlier. The activity was stoked by people looking for a
resort lifestyle in which golf plays a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the buyers were out-of-staters over 45 who are moving
into houses for vacations now and retirement later,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Mainers build such homes near, but not on, the links.
However, with demand for vacation-style houses growing, houses are
going up along the fairways at a few courses, among them the
Dunegrass golf course in Old Orchard Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The activity in Belgrade Lakes, one of the three villages in the
town of Belgrade, is a leading example of the use of a golf course
as an amenity for vacationers and potential home buyers. Lake
fishing has been the main attraction that has drawn generations of
families to its whitewashed cottages and rustic lakeside cabins.
Now the new $12 million Belgrade Lakes Golf Club in the center of
town is another draw for buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Just completing its first full year of operation, the public
18-hole course sits 200 feet above a chain of crystalline ponds.
Its presence has extended the local vacation season from the
traditional three summer months to six months or more, brokers say.
</P>
<P>
   It's also helping to increase sales and raise prices, according
to Gail Rizzo, owner of DeWolfe Belgrade Lakes Region Real Estate.
Last year, when the course opened in stages, her agency sold 82
single-family vacation homes, up 33 percent from a year earlier.
Throughout Kennebec County, almost 900 existing homes were sold, a
47 percent increase from 1997, according to the Maine State Housing
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The average sale price last year for Ms. Rizzo's agency was
$155,000, up 10 percent from 1997. ``We think that having the
course here adds about 10 percent to property values,'' said Ms.
Rizzo, who has also developed 54 houses on three lakeside sites
here in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Kelly, 44, a cabinetmaker who was raised in this
region but now lives in Marblehead, Mass., last year completed
renovations on an 1,800-square-foot, year-round lakeside cabin for
family vacations. This summer he bought another cabin to convert
into a rental property. ``I did it because the golf course makes
Belgrade Lakes a more attractive place to buy and invest,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The housing investment builds on the growing popularity of golf.
Last year the Maine State Golf Association handicapped 24,000
golfers, up from 17,000 in 1994. And young people are increasingly
being drawn to the links. Last year, 1,000 people under 17 competed
in tournaments, compared with 400 four years earlier, said Nancy
DeFrancesco, director of the state golf association.
</P>
<P>
   For construction, 1998 was a record year, with 2,388 housing
starts, up from 1,959 a year earlier in Maine's busy southern
region, from Lewiston to the Massachusetts border. So far this year
there have been 1,140 starts and the average selling price is
$133,404, up from $125,544 in the first half of 1998, according to
Plumer of Construction Data.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the fastest-growing southern Maine communities is York,
where two new privately owned courses opened last year, the Ledges
Golf Club and the Highland Farm Golf Club. The Ledges is open to
both members and the public, but Highland Farm is for members only.
Since development on the courses began a few years ago, the pace of
home construction doubled to about 130 houses a year, said Stephen
Burns, the town planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we're seeing people buy old cottages, tear
them down and build new dream houses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles L. McKenzie, a 41-year-old member of the Ledges, did
exactly that. This summer he paid $850,000 for a 20-year-old house
overlooking York Harbor. It was demolished by burning and in its
place will rise a 4,000-square-foot, four-bedroom house that will
be the primary residence for his family of three.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, McKenzie moved to York from the Boston suburb of
Lexington, where golf opportunities are fewer and house prices are
double or triple those in York. Now, his daily commute to
Harborview Asset Management in Boston is 15 minutes longer, but he
is minutes away from three 18-hole golf courses. In his decision to
move, he said, ``I must admit, golf was a big appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   On Old Orchard Beach's Dunegrass Golf Course, about 40 minutes
farther north, Carolyn and Stephen St. Pierre, native Mainers in
their 40s, are building an 1,800-square-foot house on a half-acre
site, together valued at about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that being on the course adds 20 percent to our
property value,'' said Mrs. St. Pierre, who expects to spend
summers there and winters in Florida when she and her husband
retire.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-square-mile Town of Belgrade became a popular resort area
in the 1890s, with hotels for families from Boston and New York,
rustic two-bedroom cottages in the woods called ``camps'' and
several children's summer camps, said Robert Early, the town
manager of Belgrade. Its year-round population of 3,000 rises to
7,000 in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, its only golf course closed and the two hotels
went out of business, one because of fire. While many tourists went
elsewhere, some families kept coming back, and some were ready to
invest in a replacement golf course.
</P>
<P>
   One benefactor was Harold Alfond, the founder of Dexter Shoe
Corp., who has long summered here. Recently he bought land for a
town recreation area and invested in the new 240-acre golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is part of our campaign to bring back Belgrade
Lakes,'' said Ms. Rizzo, the developer and broker, who also
invested in the golf course, which is almost hidden on a wooded
glacial ridge off Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   The course was one lure for James and Anne Rooney, both 75. They
have a winter home in Naples, Fla., and a summer place in Cape May,
N.J., which became too crowded for them.
</P>
<P>
   They had vacationed here before and last June they paid $150,000
for a new 1,400-square-foot, three-bedroom house at Ms. Rizzo's
development called Snug Harbor, on Great Pond. The two-acre site
was once a fishing camp.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are six vacation homes on the site, built in a
semicircle facing the pond. But though the houses are close, the
setting is serene enough to induce Rooney to rent out his Cape May
cottage in the summer and come to Belgrade, where golf has been one
of the attractions for him. ``The course has spectacular views, so
you can really appreciate it, even if you don't play that well,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
