<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PRIVACY-NYT &LR;      10-02 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DISCLOSURE AS FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Oct. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Although former Speaker Newt Gingrich has left the House of
Representatives, a nasty private lawsuit involving two members of
Congress, and arising out of the House ethics investigation of
Gingrich, churns on.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court panel, by a 2-1 vote, recently decided
to revive a suit filed by Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, against Rep.
Jim McDermott, D-Wash., under the Electronic Communications Privacy
Act. The panel's ruling poses a serious threat to press freedoms,
and if upheld could make it harder for anyone to bring to light
truthful information of public importance.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy act bars the interception of cellular calls, and
prohibits anyone from intentionally disclosing the contents of
intercepted calls.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, a Florida couple, John and Alice Martin,
illegally taped the contents of a cellular phone conversation in
which Gingrich, Boehner and other Republican leaders were heard
discussing matters related to Gingrich's ethics case. The Martins
gave their tape to McDermott, who passed it on to the House ethics
committee. News organizations, including The New York Times, also
published transcripts. McDermott has not said how the press
obtained the tape.
</P>
<P>
   The Martins were prosecuted under the federal statute and fined
$500 each. Boehner sued McDermott under the same law for $10,000
and punitive damages. A U.S. district judge dismissed the case on
grounds that the statute violated McDermott's free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott was not a party to the taping, and did not acquire the
tape illegally. Prior Supreme Court rulings have established the
clear principle that government may not punish the disclosure of
truthful, lawfully obtained information of public significance
absent a showing of a state interest of the highest order.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court fails to follow those principles. The
implications for press freedoms are grave. As Judge David Sentelle
argued in dissent, if McDermott can be punished for disclosing
information based on how his source obtained that information, then
the news media that published the information could well be found
liable too.
</P>
<P>
   This lawsuit began as a grudge match between two bitter
political opponents. But if allowed to go forward, it may restrict
the right of the press to publish truthful information even about
official wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
