<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-FOREIGN-FILMSALES-2TA     10-02 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-FILMSALES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GOES GLOBAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Bond. James Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase voted the single-most memorable movie line will again
greet moviegoers this winter when the 19th Bond movie _ ``The World
Is Not Enough'' _ opens in November. It will also greet moviegoers
across the globe, albeit slightly differently: ``Mi nombre es Bond.
James Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   What's at stake is not just Bond saving the world once more
despite deadly explosions, fast cars and women with names like
Christmas Jones. The larger battle is much more significant:
Hollywood's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Because as the Bond franchise proves more than any other set of
movies, Hollywood's livelihood increasingly depends on selling
films not so much in Burbank but in Bolivia and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hollywood, studios continue to benefit from
being reliable suppliers of entertainment that can be understood
anywhere on the planet. The clearest example came last year when
``Titanic'' grossed a record-setting $600 million domestically and
then took in a stunning $1.23 billion overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, foreign customers last year accounted for better than
three of every five dollars of total worldwide grosses. That's an
astounding reversal from only a decade ago when the rule-of-thumb
was the United States generated 60 percent of total box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign film executives feel their audiences now consider
American movies as accessible as native films,'' said Robert
Marich, senior editor with industry tracker Baskerville
Communications. ``They've become used to seeing Tom Hanks and
Venice Beach and hearing our idioms. And between the Internet and
TV, we're seeing more overseas business keyed off American hype and
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend, quite simply, is that the rest of the world is
starting to copy the United States in both culture and in how it
shows movies. Analysts believe the drive to build new multiscreen
theaters _ showing mostly American movies _ will accelerate into
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville Communications' 1998 survey estimated global box
office would grow 34 percent by 2007 from $18 billion to $24.2
billion by the year 2007. The U.S. market share will fall from 39.2
percent ($7.06 billion) to 36.4 percent ($8.74 billion); Europe's
share will rise to 29.5 percent from 25.1 percent and Latin
America's market will increase to 7.2 percent from 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bond can thank that foreign audience for his very existence.
Without the foreign market, owner Kirk Kerkorian would have
undoubtedly pulled the plug on Santa Monica-based
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer years ago. Only two Bond films have topped $100
million domestically; nine have crossed that milestone
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``What male on Earth wouldn't want to be a dashing, debonair
secret agent, even if you're living in Calcutta?'' asked
entertainment analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners.
``Bond has a very basic appeal that cuts across all geographic
groups that every male can identify with. And it's very engaging
for women _ the romantic notion that her path would cross with
James Bond's.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after a six-year absence, MGM revived the Bond
franchise with ``GoldenEye'' and grossed an acceptable $106.6
million domestically. The foreign gross, however, was more than
double that at $244.3 million and ranks as the 23rd highest ever.
Just to show it was no fluke, two years later, ``Tomorrow Never
Dies'' grossed $125 million domestically and $211 million overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bond is the quintessential Englishman, ownership of
the right to make and distribute Bond movies resides in Santa
Monica. Bond's value is such that MGM sued Sony Corp. over plans to
start up its own series and reached a favorable settlement earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt ``The World Is Not Enough,'' which has an
estimated $110 million price tag, will succeed. Key elements
include the trademark explosions, fast cars, femme fatales and
gadgets; Pierce Brosnan, star of the last two films; and an opening
sequence that is, at $5 million, the most costly ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a further reflection of the power of foreign markets, the
19th Bond movie will open in many key markets within a few weeks of
the Nov. 19 U.S. opening, rather than three or four months later,
which used to be the norm. UIP, a joint venture which handles MGM,
Paramount and Universal films overseas, will open it six days later
in Australia, followed by the United Kingdom on Nov. 26, France on
Dec. 1 and Spain on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the quicker roll-outs have to do with the world
becoming more homogeneous,'' said Phil Garfinkle, an analyst with
ACNielsen EDI. ``When something does well at the box office here,
everyone in the rest of the world knows about it instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has relied on its so-called ancillary markets _
foreign, TV, video and merchandising _ for decades but their
importance has been growing significantly in recent years as costs
escalate, analyst Chris Lanier of the Motion Picture Intelligencer
noted. ``If the studios had to survive on U.S. rentals alone, the
average movie would have lost over $40 million,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: over $40 million,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   To put it bluntly, the customers in Cordoba, Spain, count as
much those in Chatsworth. Major theater chains, facing cut-throat
competition domestically as megaplexes gain popularity, have
started shifting their construction focus toward less-crowded
overseas markets and those customers have responded, Garfinkle
noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as in the United States, when you give people a better
place to go see movies, you see significant gains particularly in
markets that have been stagnant with older theaters,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Marich said many foreign markets are a long way from being built
out. ``The upgrading of the international infrastructure is going
to continue with modern-style megaplexes replacing older large
single-screen inner-city theaters with no parking that were built
in the 1920s and 1930s,'' he added. ``We're about halfway through a
30-year process of rebuilding overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious beneficiaries are the action-adventures that don't
need a lot of translation. Even though neither is anywhere near the
end of its foreign run, ``Star Wars: Episode 1'' has already
grossed $351 million overseas, ``The Mummy'' has topped $221
million and ``The Matrix'' is well over $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the slam-bangers that travel beyond American
borders. If a comedy or drama succeeds in America, it's a
springboard for success overseas such as ``Notting Hill'' ($184
million), ``There's Something About Mary'' ($183 million overseas),
``Dr. Dolittle'' ($146 million), ``You've Got Mail'' ($128 million)
and ``City of Angels'' ($105 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``Taste has been shifting in foreign markets, where it used to
be only action films,'' Garfinkle said. ``Now, everything from the
United States has a chance. And comedy, in particular, travels much
better than it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend is fueling optimism over MGM's offbeat
religious-horror film ``Stigmata.'' It's expected to top $50
million domestically, and will probably hit $100 million overseas
after going into foreign release in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys at UIP have been very hot for `Stigmata' since Day
One,'' said director Rupert Wainwright. ``The old perception is
that the international marketplace is full of strange people who
only like car crashes. But the truth is that there's a very
enthusiastic market for thought-provoking films. The reception so
far indicates that the market is primed for it, particularly
Catholic countries.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the growing influence of foreign markets,
Wainwright decided to tweak the Brazilian release by changing the
references of the prologue's events from Brazil to Mexico, where
the scenes were actually shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil's a huge marketplace so we want to respect that and not
have them feel insulted by an element in the film that they might
know isn't from Brazil,'' he explained. ``The point is that, these
days, people care very much about what goes on in each individual
market. In the old days, it might have been more like, What the
hell, why bother changing it if it's only Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FOREIGN-FILMSALES-2TA     10-02 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-FILMSALES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GOES GLOBAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
