<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-KOREA-NYT &LR;      10-02 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ATROCITY ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen has now ordered a ``complete and
thorough review'' of fresh allegations that U.S. soldiers
machine-gunned hundreds of helpless South Korean civilians under a
railroad bridge nearly 50 years ago during the first desperate
weeks of the Korean War. A description of the massacre, complete
with eyewitness reports from retired U.S. servicemen, appeared in a
startling report by The Associated Press that landed on the front
pages of many newspapers Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has two important obligations. One, of course, is
to get to the bottom of what actually happened. The other is to
find out why the U.S. and South Korean governments have never made
a serious effort to investigate the matter, despite repeated pleas
from South Koreans who describe themselves as survivors of the
massacre and who have asked for compensation. Time and again, these
survivors have been rebuffed by their own government and by the
Pentagon, which as recently as last March asserted that there was
no information in military archives to substantiate their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen now concedes that the Pentagon failed to give these claims
proper attention. Unlike the AP, Army investigators made no effort
to locate and interview former GIs who were at or near the scene.
The investigators limited themselves to Army records at the
National Archives in Maryland, but even there they appear to have
done a miserable job. Though there is no single document describing
a massacre, the AP found copies of orders authorizing U.S.
commanders to fire on South Korean civilians, as well as other
clues pointing to the possibility of a massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Though their stories differ on certain details, the GIs
interviewed by the AP corroborate, in most respects, the narrative
provided over the years by the South Korean survivors. According to
this narrative, the trouble began when U.S. soldiers, anticipating
a North Korean attack, ordered hundreds of villagers to leave their
homes. At some later point, while they were resting in a clearing,
the villagers were strafed by U.S. planes _ whether deliberately or
accidentally is not clear _ and took refuge in culverts under a
railroad bridge near the village of No Gun Ri. There they were
mowed down by U.S. machine gunners over a three-day period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wholesale slaughter,'' a former rifleman, Herman
Patterson, told the AP. ``We just annihilated them,'' recalled
Norman Tinkler, a former machine gunner. Another American veteran,
Eugene Hesselman, remembered his commanding officer as saying:
``The hell with all those people. Let's get rid of all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the veterans gave the same justification. U.S.
soldiers, they said, had been instructed from the beginning of
America's involvement to regard all South Korean civilians with
suspicion. The fear was that North Korean troops would try to
penetrate American lines disguised as refugees. Indeed, according
to one document unearthed by the AP, the American troops had been
told shortly before the firing erupted that ``no _ repeat no _
refugees will be permitted to cross battle lines at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   A full inquiry will take time and money, but it is vital to see
whether an injustice has been done and whether its victims are due
reparations or compensation of some kind. With relatively limited
resources, the AP has been able to raise some important questions.
With its much greater resources, the Pentagon ought to be able to
answer them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
