<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-02 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS DID COWBOYS A FAVOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that silly talk about revenge _ it was heard everywhere last
week at Valley Ranch. The playoff embarrassment of nine months ago
hit home again because Arizona returns today to Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't count owner Jerry Jones among the still angry.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was steaming last January after a feeble performance by
the Cowboys in a 20-7 loss to the Cardinals. ``But all my heat was
aimed at myself,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a useless exercise of getting mad and then plotting
to get even, ``I was thinking about us getting better as a team,''
said Jones. ``I blamed myself that day for having allowed things to
slide at certain positions, creating deficiencies that eventually
caught up with us. I vowed then it wouldn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality now says it was a local blessing when Arizona beat up on
a Cowboys team that was supposed to win that particular game. But
what if the Cowboys had won, then gone to Atlanta in the second
round of the playoffs, only to be ousted by a better club?
</P>
<P>
   Would receiver Rocket Ismail be on the field today? Would center
Mark Stepnoski? Without the humiliation dealt by the Cardinals,
would the free-agency urgency from Jones have been the same in the
off-season?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, answered Jones. But what Arizona did was remove the
``maybe.'' It became a Jerry crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of that loss being a personal kick in the butt for
Jones, it was more like a swift shove from behind. That meant he
was moving forward, and as it turned out, moving in the direction
of, say, Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   It is far too early to get carried away about Rocketman, one
reason being Ismail's seven-year NFL resume, which has B-U-S-T
stamped all over it. But ...
</P>
<P>
   Based on the limited exposure of two games, that B-U-S-T can
also be viewed another way. As in, here's a speedball who is on the
verge of becoming a bust-out kind of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Think hard. When was the last time the Cowboys owned such a
potential game-breaker? Do you have to go all the way-way-way back
to Bullet Bob?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are ecstatic over the return of Stepnoski and how he
has provided an anchor for the offensive line. But that's no
surprise. That was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail, however, was considered an iffy acquisition by a
majority of NFL talent scouts. There was no long line to bid for
his free-agency services, certainly not for what Jones eventually
paid _ $21 million over seven years with a $5 million bonus. Ismail
became, by far, the Cowboys' highest paid receiver ever. Only
Carolina, where Rocket played last season, challenged the Cowboys
for his services.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the Arizona game nine months ago. ``I walked off the
field that day thinking first about what we had to do at center,''
said Jones. ``It was obvious we had to zero in on getting back
Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   But the second free-agency priority became a speed receiver, and
Ismail was coming off a better-than-expected season for a bad
Carolina club.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cardinals winning the playoff game in Irving was
certainly an upset, it wasn't exactly a shock. The Cowboys' offense
had slumped badly throughout December. Top receiver Ernie Mills had
been lost in November due to injury. Tight end David LaFleur went
down in early December, eliminating another air-game option.
</P>
<P>
   The offense lined up against Arizona with a struggling Michael
Irvin, who later admitted he didn't even know the playbook, plus
Billy Davis, Patrick Jeffers and Jeff Ogden. Davis would be
released after the season, and Jeffers signed with Carolina as a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting back Mills and LaFleur for this season was going to
help,'' said Jones. ``But we also needed that additional weapon.
The speed weapon. Our homework on Rocket became as intense as any
we've ever done around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones heard first from the club's longtime film-graders, Bill
Hitt and Jim Dodson, both former high school head coaches in the
area. Those two recommended Ismail based on film study. So did
Larry Lacewell and the pro personnel department. Jones also had
former NFL receiving great Paul Warfield study the Rocket.
Warfield, who is a paid adviser for Jones, gave the thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there, it was a matter of Chan liking Ismail,'' said
Jones. ``And he did. Very much so. Then it became the same as
college recruiting, but, fortunately, Rocket liked the idea of
playing here as much as we liked the idea of him being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's defensive secondary will hardly recognize the
receivers it faces today, when compared with January. And the
Cardinals have only themselves to blame for making the Cowboys much
better.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
