<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 10/02/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-3, 10-2 --
Protesters at the Brooklyn Museum of Art object to a painting of
``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' which was created by Chris Ofili, a
British artist of Nigerian descent, using elephant dung. The
painting is part of an exhibit entitled ``Sensation'' which opened
Saturday. Although some art experts say the painting actually
venerates the Virgin Mary, noting that dung is a symbol of growth
in the African culture, many Catholics view it as blasphemous.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SWANTON, Vt.. -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- CONGRESS-MILK-FEUD,
10-2 -- Paul Bourbeau, 40, who has about 300 cows on a farm he runs
with his wife and two grown sons in Swanton, figures that changes
in the milk pricing system could cost him $16,000 to $18,000 a
year. With the livelihoods of tens of thousands of dairy farmers
are at stake, the issue has provoked a civil war between lawmakers
from the East and those from the Midwest. ``When I started farming
here 17 years ago, there were seven farms on my road. Now there are
only two left. This could make the difference to lots of people up
here whether they stay in business,'' says Bourbeau. (Paul O.
Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- HATCH-CAMPAIGN, 10-2 --
Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah concedes that his candidacy for the
Republican nomination is a long shot, but says his plan is to pick
up the pieces if Gov. George W. Bush of Texas falters in his bid
for the Presidency. Hatch has raised barely $1 million, less than 2
percent of the $56 million collected by the front-runner, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. ``Let's face it,'' he says, ``most people
don't even know I'm in the race. I found that some of my closest
friends in California didn't know it.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- CATHOLIC-HOSPITALS-2, 10-2
-- Dr. Nicholas Campion, left, and Dr. Mohammed Khan, at the Mary
Immaculate Hospital Division in Queens, which is part of a merger
involving eight Catholic hospitals in New York, including St.
Vincents, the jewel among the city's Catholic hospitals. On the one
hand, the merger was arranged ostensibly to help each hospital
continue to serve the city's poorest and sickest residents. On the
other, to compete as a behemoth among prestigious academic medical
centers. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- CATHOLIC-HOSPITALS-1, 10-2
-- St. Vincents Hospital and Medical Center in Manhattan, the jewel
among the city's Catholic hospitals, is facing new pressures,
including falling reimbursement rates from managed care and
competition with the city's most renowned hospitals. As a result,
the hospital, along with Sisters of Charity Healthcare on Staten
Island, has merged with the Catholic Medical Centers of Brooklyn
and Queens, making it the region's largest Catholic health-care
system. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- NY-ART-DEALER-ARREST, 10-2 --
Mary Boone, a New York art dealer who was arrested Wednesday on
charges of distributing live ammunition and displaying two working
guns at a show in her Fifth Avenue gallery. Ms. Boone says she
spent the night in a rancid precinct jail cell with a broken toilet
and a narrow bench, and the entire next day in a group holding cell
with prostitutes and drug addicts in the infamous Manhattan
Detention Complex known as ``The Tombs.'' ``I was in shock and
terrified,'' says Ms. Boone. ``The whole idea is that you're guilty
because they say you are.'' (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) GREENWICH, England -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- MILLENIUM-DOME,
10-2 -- The $1.2 billion Millennium Dome in Greenwich, England,
just under three months from its completion and gala inauguration
by Queen Elizabeth, was once labeled ``The millennium fiasco,'' by
the British press. With expectations of attracting 12 million
people during the year 2000, the dome is now awash in corporate
logos representing Britain's largest companies and has become a
beast that Britons seem eager to climb aboard for their ride into
the new century. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BREMERTON, Wash. -- Oct. 2, 1999 --
BOX-BATTLE-OF-SEXES-2, 10-2 -- Margaret MacGregor, 36, right, who
will take on Loi Chow, left, in a four-round fight in Seattle that
is sending waves through the boxing world. After the state of
Washington declared that its gender-equity laws give it no
authority to prevent the match, what is billed by its promoters as
the nation's first officially sanctioned bout between a man and a
woman is scheduled for October 9. ``Once we get in there and start
going toe-to-toe,'' says Ms. MacGregor, ``Loi Chow is going to
realize something. He's going to have to go to work.'' (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-2, 10-2 --
Protesters opposed to New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's crusade
against the Brooklyn Museum of Art, line the streets outside the
museum, as the new controversial exhibit entitled ``Sensation''
opened on Saturday. As the museum began to harvest the financial
benefits of ``Sensation,'' an exhibition of contemporary British
art that has spun New York City into a political, cultural and
religious uproar, polls show a majority of the public in
disagreement with Giuliani's actions. Giuliani has withheld the
museum's monthly city subsidy and has started eviction proceedings.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-1, 10-2 --
Protesters outside the Brooklyn Museum of Art, as the new
controversial exhibit entitled ``Sensation'' opened on Saturday. As
the museum began to harvest the financial benefits of
``Sensation,'' an exhibition of contemporary British art that has
spun New York City into a political, cultural and religious uproar,
polls show a solid majority of the public in disagreement with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's crusade against the museum. Giuliani has
withheld the museum's monthly city subsidy and has started eviction
proceedings. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BREMERTON, Wash. -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- BOX-BATTLE-OF-SEXES,
10-2 -- Margaret MacGregor, 36, who will take on a man, Loi Chow,
in a four-round fight in Seattle that is sending waves through the
boxing world. After the state of Washington declared that its
gender-equity laws give it no authority to prevent the match, what
is billed by its promoters as the nation's first officially
sanctioned bout between a man and a woman is scheduled for October
9. ``Once we get in there and start going toe-to-toe,'' says Ms.
MacGregor, ``Loi Chow is going to realize something. He's going to
have to go to work.'' (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DETROIT -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- SCI-CLINICAL-TESTS-3, 10-2 --
The stem cells of Catherine Porter, 44, which were reinfused into
her body in an experimental bone marrow transplant to combat her
spreading cancer. Known within the field as high-dose chemotherapy
followed by bone marrow transplant or stem cell rescue, the
experimental treatment is based on a simple concept: If a little
chemotherapy killed some of the cancerous cells in a woman's body,
a lot might kill them all. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DETROIT -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- SCI-CLINICAL-TESTS-2, 10-2 --
Catherine Porter, 44, recuperating in her hospital room after an
experimental bone marrow transplant at the Barbara Ann Karmanos
Cancer Institute last month, to combat her spreading cancer. The
transplant took place more than a decade after the procedure first
showed promise. Yet the painful transplants have not been proven
any better than standard therapy. ``Something has got to be done,''
says Porter, ``So we don't have to keep going through this.''
(Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DETROIT -- Oct. 2, 1999 -- SCI-CLINICAL-TESTS-1, 10-2 --
Catherine Porter, 44, the night before she received a bone marrow
transplant in September at the Barbara Ann Karmanos Cancer
Institute, to try and fight a recurrence of breast cancer. Now, she
waits at her home in Imlay City, Mich., wondering if the
experimental treatment she received will help her, and why medical
science still cannot answer that question for so many thousands of
women. ``Something has got to be done,'' she says, ``So we don't
have to keep doing this.'' (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
