<HEADER>
A4672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-PURDUE-MICHIGAN-N     10-02 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PURDUE-MICHIGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN SNAPS PURDUE'S STREAK AND ITS SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ It was the final indignity Drew Brees
suffered on an afternoon brimming with them: an interception early
in the fourth quarter. Brees, the Purdue quarterback, had already
been sacked twice, hurried and buried in the wet sod another
half-dozen times, and his receivers were frightened into dropping
10 passes.
</P>
<P>
   Brees shuffled nervously in the pocket and popped the ball to
the left side of the field, where Michigan linebacker Larry Foote
easily stepped in front of it and caught it at the Wolverine's 22.
</P>
<P>
   Brees was not back on the sideline long when his counterpart,
Tom Brady, made the Boilermakers pay once more for sloppy play.
Brady, a senior co-captain, rifled a bomb 44 yards in the air that
Marcus Knight corralled and took 10 more yards to the 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Wolverines were confident enough to let a
third-string fullback have some fun. And B.J. Askew did, pinballing
into the end zone to give No. 4 Michigan a 35-12 lead en route to a
38-12 victory over an outclassed and humbled Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second week in a row, haughty talk about a Heisman
Trophy was shoved down the hopeful's throat by a savage Michigan
defense.
</P>
<P>
   From the first series, the Wolverines punished the Boilermakers
with hard, clean hits that were met with empathetic winces from the
111,468 at Michigan Stadium. They could feel the Boilermakers'
pain.
</P>
<P>
   But not as much as Brees, who finished 20 of 49 passing for 293
yards and one touchdown to go with the interception. He was
thoroughly outplayed by Brady, who was 15 of 25 for 250 yards and
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Boilermakers briefly demonstrated that
the Wolverines had not totally kicked the life out of them. On
Michigan's 34-yard line, facing second down-and-eight, Brees
dropped back, moved left and uncorked a bomb down the left sideline
that Vinny Sutherland, behind cornerback James Whitley, raced under
down the sideline for a 66-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   When Michigan was penalized for offsides on Travis Dorsch's
extra point, coach Joe Tiller decided to take the point off the
board and attempt a 2-point conversion to narrow the score to
21-14. But once more Brees' receivers failed him. His pass to an
open Randall Lane in the end zone bounced off the wide out's
stomach and left the score at 21-12.
</P>
<P>
   Brady and Anthony Thomas (23 carries for 116 yards) answered the
threat again. This time on a 10-play, 75-yard drive that was capped
by Thomas' second touchdown of the day, a 5-yard squirt through the
middle to put the Wolverines ahead, 28-12. A 24-yard Jeff Del Verne
field goal with less than five minutes left gave the Wolverines
their final margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 11 Boilermakers came to Michigan Stadium ready to topple
all sorts of history in their football program. A victory over
Michigan would mean Purdue would have matched an 11-game winning
streak set from 1928 to 1930. It would mean a 5-0 record for the
first time since 1945. It would mean a spot in the top 10 of the
Associated Press poll for the first time since finishing No. 10 at
the end of the 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, beating Michigan would serve notice that the
Boilermakers were Big Ten title contenders not to be taken lightly
by such upcoming opponents as No. 12 Ohio State, No. 14 Michigan
State and No. 2 Penn State. It was clear early, however, that
Purdue's ancient history would stay intact and that in its coming
big games the team must settle for being a spoiler rather than a
champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines ran up a 21-6 first-half lead, showing they were
a better and more efficient passing team than Purdue. Michigan did
not need Tiller's spread offense; it just needed a modest running
game to set up some play-action passing. The Wolverines didn't need
the gaudy numbers of Brees, a Heisman hopeful; they just needed a
pair of quarterbacks _ Brady and Drew Henson _ who took what was
given to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers started well enough when, on the second play of
the game, tackle Matt Mitrione stripped Thomas of the ball and
Purdue's Adrian Beasley recovered it at the Michigan 36-yard line.
Brees quickly moved the Boilermakers to the 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wolverines' secondary _ which began the day allowing 168
yards a game passing _ valiantly thwarted three of Brees' attempts
to get into the end zone. First, DeWayne Patmon got to the ball
before tight end Tim Stratton. Then, Brandon Williams smothered
Chris Daniels on a corner route. Finally, cornerback Todd Howard
nailed Daniels, separating him from the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers settled for a 28-yard field goal from Travish
Dorsch and a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-hitting stand set just the right tone of intimidation.
Three more times the Boilermakers were deep in Michigan's
territory, but could not make it into the end zone during the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   On first-and-10 at the 16-yard line, Brees mishandled a low snap
in the shotgun formation that Michigan's James Hall recovered on
the 31. On another drive, to the Wolverines' 24, Dorsch missed a
42-yard field goal. Finally, with 1 minute 5 seconds left in the
half, Michigan's Thomas fumbled again and Purdue linebacker Mike
Rose snapped it up at Michigan's 16-yard line. But a penalty and
more tough play from the Wolverine secondary stranded the
Boilermakers there for a 31-yard field goal by Dorsch.
</P>
<P>
   That concluded an awful half statistically for Brees: 11 of 27
passing for 131 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
