u i BC-YUGO-PROTEST-430&AMP;ADD-     10-02 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PROTEST-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PROTEST IS HELD IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Serbian police in riot gear blocked a
march of anti-regime demonstrators on Saturday evening, but both
sides avoided confrontation and the protesters returned to the
central Belgrade square from which they started.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 people showed up _ a disappointing turnout for a
Saturday night _ for a walk intended to reach a city hospital where
some of the wounded remain from police baton charges Wednesday and
Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The police were determined to keep the marchers in the central
city, where they have a permit to rally. However, the police did
not charge the demonstrators but walked slowly toward them, and
they retreated.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic insisted that the retreat
was a victory. He said in an interview that the idea was to force
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``to show the violent face of
the regime,'' but at the same time ``to avoid violence if we can.''
</P>
<P>
   In another variant of the opposition's changing strategies,
Djindjic said that these rallies would continue until mid-October,
``and after that, maybe we can organize a large final rally and
maybe after that ask for early elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The stated position of the Alliance for Change is that no fair
elections are possible with Milosevic still in power. But on
Saturday again, Djindjic appeared to be moving closer to his rival,
Vuk Draskovic of the Serbian Renewal Movement, who has scorned the
past 12 days of rallies and called instead for early elections to
undermine and then oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled media continued to scorn the rallies as
unsuccessful and their organizers as dupes of NATO. The official
newspaper Politika, ominously perhaps, contained a large section
explaining the details of the legal requirements for holding
rallies and marches. Besides outright police violence or arrests,
Milosevic's government has often used selective application of
Serbia's communist-style laws to curb opposition efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics enhance the fear that many Serbs have of losing
their jobs or forfeiting other benefits if they join opposition
groups, or marches.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been using such requirements to justify their
use of force to block demonstrations from moving outside the
central Belgrade Square of the Republic where the rallies begin and
end.
</P>
<P>
   The police have used harsh tactics, clubbing unarmed protesters
to drive them back. But the Interior Ministry accused demonstrators
of provoking police ``performing their regular duties of directing
traffic and monitoring public law and order.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A police investigation into the ``perpetrators and ringleaders''
of Wednesday's violence continues, and Djindjic said the government
would have to develop its own strategy and decide whether to seek
the arrest of himself and other opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in another ominous note, the Serbian Radical Party of
ultranationalist Vojislav Seselj, the Serbian deputy prime
minister, issued a statement that was read on state television,
accusing ``hooligans'' of the Alliance for Change of setting fire
to the Radical Party headquarters in the Belgrade suburb of Zemun.
</P>
<P>
   The party said that if such an incident happened ``just one more
time,'' then the Alliance for Change would find that it no longer
had any offices of its own anywhere in Serbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
