A4674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-VOTE03-COX     10-02 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-VOTE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    India enacts dry days for voting
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA, India _ A sign outside the Chowringhee Bar of the posh
Grand Hotel turns disappointed customers away: ``Dry Days, Oct.
1-3. We regret the inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Friday, alcohol stopped flowing all over Calcutta and
in every other Indian city, town or village participating in
today's balloting, the last of a five-phase election process that
began Sept. 5. The temporary prohibition is designed to keep voters
sober and guard against any unnecessary raucousness.
</P>
<P>
   But elections in India often erupt in violence, and this year is
no exception. So far, more than 55 people have been killed in
election-related violence. There also has been evidence of ballot
box stuffing and rigging in earlier phases of the five-stage
general election. The independent Election Commission has had to
order hundreds of ballot centers to repeat earlier votes.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing more violence and corruption in the last phase of
India's elections, authorities have ordered police to shoot on
sight anyone who attempts to disrupt the polls, the Times of India
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the tranquillity of the Grand Hotel, flag-draped
three-wheelers equipped with megaphones blast deafening campaign
slogans as they parade through Calcutta streets, often disrupting
the already chaotic traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even God doesn't buy the argument that Sonia Gandhi is a
videshi (foreigner),'' blares a Congress Party slogan, referring to
the Italian-born widow of the late Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and
the party's candidate for prime minister. Gandhi's dual citizenship
and heavily accented Hindi have been made a major campaign issue by
the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Hindu nationalist BJP's election campaign has
failed to address the country's most pressing issues of poverty and
economic reform. Instead, it has focused on whether the
foreign-born Gandhi has the right to take up India's highest office
and also on the war this summer in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The mudslinging between political parties comes to an end 24
hours before the polling begins.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of privately owned buses and minibuses lined
Calcutta's streets and will carry personnel and material to and
from polling stations across the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Saurav Ain, 43, who has been a presiding elections officer since
1980, has an important job in a country where millions of voters
cast ballots by placing a rubber stamp on a paper ballot carrying
symbols of the different parties: a lotus, a cow, hammer and
sickle. Several districts experimented this year with a handful of
electronic push-button voting machines, but most Indians _
illiterate and unused to gadgets _ will exercise their most
fundamental right the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Automation will eliminate mistakes that often occur in manual
voting,'' Ain said. ``In the manual system, voters may stamp the
ballot paper in the wrong place or fold it incorrectly. Automation
will eliminate such errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the benefit of voting machines, polling officers mark
the index finger of the voter's left hand with indelible ink to
avoid duplicate voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless someone tries to chemically remove it immediately after
application, it usually stays for two to three days,'' Ain said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 1903EDT &QL; 
