</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-REACT-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN LEADERS VOW TO RESIST RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Chechnya's president vowed on Saturday to
repulse a Russian invasion that he said had already been launched,
saying the fighting forces of his republic were united and far
stronger than in the two-year war that ended in 1996 and dealt a
humiliating blow to Russia's once-proud army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has begun,'' Chechen leader Aslan Maskhadov declared
to foreign journalists. Dressed in camouflage fatigues, he called
for international pressure to end what he said was daily Russian
bombing of villages and towns throughout his breakaway republic,
and pleaded for just 30 minutes alone with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin to avert full-scale war.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have pounded civilian areas for a month, hitting
some 40 villages, three hospitals, factories and bridges, Maskhadov
said. ``They are blocking humanitarian aid, they have cut the
electricity and gas supplies, and every minute continue rocket
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces had moved into two villages just inside
Chechnya's northern border Friday but were quickly repulsed by
Chechen forces, he said. Chechen commanders reported that they had
destroyed two tanks in fighting overnight.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, in an open radio conversation with
Maskhadov's headquarters, a field commander reported that Russian
forces were continuing to shell their positions, making it
impossible to estimate casualties. ``But there are wounded, we know
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny, a city still in ruins from the 1994-96 war, was quiet
Saturday, with civilians leaving, joining thousands who have
already fled.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov ordered a full mobilization of Chechen fighters after
fighting broke out in neighboring Dagestan last month, and Russian
forces engaged Chechens for the first time since the end of the war
in 1996. He said Saturday that his forces stood at five times their
previous strength and did not lack weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Militarily speaking, we are stronger than before,'' he said.
``More men want to fight. They have experience, a fighting spirit,
and the last war showed people what would happen if Russian troops
come into our land and people get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Chechen fighters were also solidly behind their
president, accepting his orders, after commanders and community
leaders met Saturday and agreed to set aside any differences.
</P>
<P>
   Even the renegade field commander Shamil Basayev, who led the
Chechen incursion into Dagestan last month against Maskhadov's
wishes, and so sparked Russia's sharp retaliation, would fight
under him, the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that any Chechens, including Basayev and his comrade
in arms, the Arab fighter known as Khattab, were involved in the
bomb blasts that rocked Moscow and other Russian towns and killed
some 300 people last month.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb blasts he blamed on Russian secret services who he said
were playing a dark and sinister game to retain power in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than wait for Russian troops to storm Grozny, as happened
in 1994, he said the Chechen leadership had decided to resist at
the borders. ``If they break through,'' he said of the Russian
forces, ``which I do not rule out, and reach the city, then we will
fight in the city; if in the woods, then the woods; if in the
mountains, then the mountains.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His speech echoed the style of the late president Dzhokhar
Dudayev, the former Soviet general who was killed in 1996 during
the last war. Dudayev had frequently insisted that he could have
averted the war in 1994 if he had just had 30 minutes together with
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was heading for trouble if it tried to annex a northern
part of Chechnya and install a loyal puppet government, he said.
That policy would spark a conflagration across the North Caucasus,
where the polices of Soviet leaders left many outstanding
territorial claims cutting through ethnic communities in
neighboring Ingushetia and Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia tried to annex northern Chechnya as far as the Terek
river, once the Russian frontier, then Chechnya had the right to
reclaim land from Dagestan that was once part of a greater
Chechnya, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
