<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUGBY-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM OFF TO ROUGH START IN RUGBY WORLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ ``You're going to get hammered,'' said an
elderly Irish gentleman standing outside Lansdowne Road stadium
with a ticket in his hand and an impish look on his weathered face.
``You know that don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   If the subject had been football, or basketball, or even the
once-exotic sport of soccer, it would have been difficult for an
American visitor to agree with this confident Dubliner. But this
was a rugby match the Americans were about to play against the
Irish: a World Cup rugby match, to be precise, which made it all
the more meaningful to the home team and all the more potentially
painful for a team whose country does not often get to play the
role of underdog internationally.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans most decidedly were underdogs as the opening
round of the World Cup got under way Friday and Saturday in Great
Britain, France and Ireland. There are 20 teams in this five-week
competition, a quadrennial event that was first contested in 1987.
And according to Rugby World, one of the leading publications that
covers the sport, the Americans had the least chance of winning of
any team: 2,500 to 1. Those odds put them slightly below Uruguay
and Namibia in a pecking order that was topped by New Zealand and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're expecting to kill us, and they're probably right,''
said Jimmy Whited, a 30-year-old from Dallas with an American flag
tied round his waist and a tartan cap with red wig atop his head.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no surprises on the field, as the Irish won
convincingly and predictably, 53-8, in the opening match in Group
E. The Irish, one of the five perennial powers in European rugby,
scored seven tries to the Americans' one; they dominated play in
the scrums and line-outs that are so critical to rugby success, and
they handled the ball with a great deal more assurance than their
skittish, occasionally frantic opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it could have been worse, as it was last month at
Twickenham in London, when in an international test match the
Americans were beaten by the English, 106-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of places you can go to get your confidence
inflated,'' said the American coach, Jack Clark. ``But the fact is,
if you want to be international rugby players, you need every
experience you can get, including some that are bad. England was an
embarrassing experience. Tonight was not.''
</P>
<P>
   What made it a big improvement for Clark was the constant effort
his overmatched team demonstrated against a team that is, along
with Australia, is one of the two favorites to advance to the
quarterfinals from this four-team group that also includes Romania.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get into one of those David and Goliath things and
decide that effort is a variable, and then it can really get away
from you,'' he said. ``And I can remember a night in Twickenham
when that happened, but tonight it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish led, 3-0, after three minutes and by 10-0 after seven
minutes and would probably have built on that lead in a hurry if
not for a very unexpected bounce. Irish fullback Conor O'Shea was
running hard with the ball near midfield when he was sandwiched by
two American players. The ball popped loose, straight into the
hands of an American, scrum half Kevin Dalzell, who scooted left
around the surprised Irish for the lone American try of this chilly
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Fly half Mark Williams then missed the conversion, but it would
not stay 10-5 for long. The Irish would lead by 24-8 by halftime
and by 31-8 after the first three minutes of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the Americans are in the World Cup again. After
competing in 1991, they failed to qualify for the emotional and
symbolic competition in 1995 won by the South Africans in South
Africa. Much has changed in the Americans' absence. Rugby union _
the 15-man version of rugby played in the World Cup _ is now
professional throughout much of Europe and in the Southern
Hemisphere. As a result, the standard of training and play
worldwide is rising, and the beer consumption of the teams is
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the 15 Americans who started Saturday night play
professionally, including the captain, Dan Lyle, who is a star in
the English premier league. The others are amateurs who juggle
rugby and part-time or full-time jobs as mortgage brokers or
software salesmen or graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the game went open, it's hard for U.S amateur rugby to
stay in touch,'' Clark said. ``It won't get easier in the short
term, but in the long term we think it will be good for American
rugby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
