<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CRIME-SHOCK03-COX     10-02 3962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-SHOCK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slain father's spirit lives on through family, friends
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A sheriff's cruiser zoomed past Sheila
Wildermuth's car as she headed home from an afternoon of shopping
for a long-overdue family vaca-
</P>
<P>
   tion.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila heard the whoosh of the cruiser and thought absently,
'They're really after somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned onto her street, transformed into a parking lot of
cruisers and emergency vehicles. As she drew closer she realized
the yellow police tape circled her yard, and a red paramedic truck
was parked in her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila jumped out of her car, but sheriff's deputies blocked her
from entering the house where she lived with her husband Brett and
their three children. ``You can't go in,'' they told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see my husband,'' she pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go in,'' the officers repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know a Matt Hensley?'' a deputy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a Mike Hensley,'' Sheila said. ``He's someone who
attends our church, someone the church was trying to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the officers barred her way: ``This is a crime
scene,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Dazed, Sheila noticed Julie Hensley _ Mike Hensley's wife _
leaning against Brett's red Geo Prism, staring into space. Sheila
approached Julie, whom she knew from church, but gleaned only one
fact: Mike had shot Brett.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing if Brett was alive or dead, Sheila turned back to
the house only to see paramedics leaving. ``That's not a good
sign,'' she told herself. She felt shock, dread, an eerie sense of
unreality, all at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff told me to go over and sit down; he didn't take me
off by myself,'' Sheila said. Then, matter-of-factly, ``he told me
on the front lawn in front of some of my neighbors that my husband
was no longer with us.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, said Sheila, ``I lost my speech in front of
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks following the murder of her husband, on Thursday, July
8, 1999, Sheila Wildermuth could speak only a few simple words at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors rallied round with their cell phones, asking, ``Who do
you want us to call?'' Her brother was the only person Sheila
called directly, because her fingers remembered the number when her
mind could not.
</P>
<P>
   It was another two hours before she was allowed in the house to
see her husband. But she couldn't do what she really needed to do:
to touch him, to hold him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why,'' she said softly. This was one more thing
Brett's killer had robbed from her: She could not say goodbye to
her husband because the body of the man she loved had become
``evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crime scene,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   It was 9 p.m. by the time Sheila reached her mother-in-law's
house. About an hour later, she faced her most painful task:
telling the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gathered them around and of course we were all bawling,''
she said. ``They couldn't understand what was going on with my
speech; I couldn't put a lot of words together like I'm doing now.
I didn't lie to them; I told them what I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, surrounded by grandparents, ministers and close friends,
the children said a prayer for their lost father.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Mike Hensley stands charged with the murders
of Brett Wildermuth and three teen-agers murdered earlier that day
at Hensley's home: Tosha Barrett, Sherry Kimbler and Amy Mikesell.
</P>
<P>
   How could it have happened? Why was Brett Wildermuth shot by the
very man to whom he had opened his home and his heart? Why did it
happen just as he turned his back to Hensley, to prepare a place to
pray?
</P>
<P>
   If the tragedy of Brett Wildermuth's death raises an agonizing,
unanswerable Why?, the example of his life raises a question even
more fundamental: ``Am I my brother's keeper?''
</P>
<P>
   You are your brother's keeper. It is a truism so familiar, so
worn, we gloss over it as reflexively as we pass a panhandler on
the street, without making eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   We don't often think how radical it is to live a life of faith _
until something happens to remind us.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Wildermuth's death _ but most of all his life _ can remind
us.
</P>
<P>
   At Brett's funeral, mourners pieced together this account of the
tragedy:
</P>
<P>
   Brett was the only one home that day when a call came from a
friend, telling him there had been ``trouble on Queen Street,'' and
asking him to pray for Mike and Julie. ``I'm on my knees,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Mike and Julie pulled up. Julie told Brett
they were running from an occult group. ``Come in; let's pray,''
Brett said. Hensley shot Wildermuth after he turned his back to him
to prepare a place to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Julie refused to flee with her husband. She called for help and
held Brett's hand, praying, ``God, please don't let him die.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Brett lay dying, he reassured Julie, ``Don't worry, it
will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be OK. It is important that those words came from Brett,
not a minister, said Pastor Ben Davis of the First Church of God in
Sidney, where both the Wildermuths and Hensleys worshiped. ``Brett
was praying for them before they got there, and he continued to
pray,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   After the tragedy, a detective pulled Davis aside and said this
about Brett Wildermuth: ``I've seen a lot of crime scenes and they
are ugly, hard things, but there was something different about this
young man. I had never seen so much peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The observation comes as no surprise to close friend Tom Looker.
Brett never forgot _ or even questioned _ that he was his brother's
keeper, Looker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One example is the way he reached out to Mike. Brett knew God
could change anybody, and that's the truth of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While some members of the congregation knew Hensley had a
``rough past,'' Looker said, no one was afraid of him. Hensley
attended a world religions course Brett and Looker taught together.
``He talked about the draw of the enemy and of Satan, but there
were holds on his life he wasn't telling us about,'' Looker said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila didn't worry about Hensley, either; Brett had taken
greater risks while living in New Jersey in the early '80s,
volunteering with homeless men.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildermuths didn't really know the Hensleys outside of
church, nor did they belong to the same small prayer group that met
every week at various families' homes. When Brett opened the door
to the Hensleys that day, Mike and Julie Hensley entered the
Wildermuth home for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildermuths were far more closely involved with another
woman in the congregation, a single mother trying to get back on
her feet, who lived with them for six weeks. Brett and two of his
friends _ ``The Three Skinny Guys Moving Company,'' they dubbed
themselves _ helped her move into her new home.
</P>
<P>
   The church's involvement with Hensley began late last October,
when Pastor Davis received an urgent, early-morning call from Mike
and Julie Hensley. Julie was a congregation member who had married
Mike in April 1998. ``Mike said he wanted to walk a new life in
faith,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At the First Church of God, people call each other ``brother''
and ``sister'' without a trace of irony. When Mike Hensley came to
the church seeking a new life, they opened their arms to him.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley was active in the church, attending marriage counseling,
Sunday school, and small prayer groups in the home. ``I've met a
lot of people trying to scam me and go through the motions, but
Mike was sincere,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the killings that Davis learned of Hensley's
previous arrests for public indecency, or of the reports of Cheryl
Kai, mother of 16-year-old victim Sherry Kimbler, that Hensley was
luring girls to his house with offers of cash to watch him
masturbate.
</P>
<P>
   Davis knew nothing of Hensley's apparent double life. But after
his years as a pastor, he knows something about human nature: ``I
believe in spiritual warfare. It's within every individual; we all
have to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those forces,'' he added, ``were great in Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley told Davis and the congregation of past involvement with
an occult group. Davis isn't sure now if that was the truth, but he
believed it then.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation paid a high price for its open-heartedness. As
Hensley fled, a suspect in the murders of Wildermuth and the three
teen-agers, some in the congregation were told to go into hiding,
including Davis and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of fear in the congregation,'' Davis said.
``We stayed away from the house for several nights. It took three
weeks before I could sleep at night without listening for
footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hensley returned to Sidney for a final wild rampage, he
terrorized another family in the congregation, John and Kathy
Bruce. At 2:30 a.m. July 13 _ the morning after Brett Wildermuth's
funeral _ Hensley pounded on the Bruces' door, firing a shot
through the door when Bruce refused to open it.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley surrendered two hours and 15 minutes later after taking
three people as hostages at the Sidney Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Has Davis second-guessed himself? Should he have protected his
congregation by refusing to minister to the likes of Mike Hensley?
</P>
<P>
   That might be the way a corporation looks at things, but not a
church. ``Our job is not to investigate,'' Davis said. ``When
Christ forgives a past, we begin to work on a future. You believe
in what a person is becoming, and treat them as if they're already
there. We did the same for Mike as we would have done for anybody
else. If someone has been divorced and remarried five times, we
just look at them as being in a new life and a new start. That is
the gospel; that is what Brett believed, and what we still
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Wildermuth tries not to spend too much time rewriting the
past. What if she had come upon the scene 20 minutes earlier? What
if the children hadn't been with their grandmother that day? These
are the thoughts she banishes from her mind. ``There are all kinds
of things that I think, `If this or if that happened,''' Sheila
said.
</P>
<P>
   She does't allow herself to stay despondent. She misses her
husband desperately and she has days _ after a church family
picnic, where Brett's absence is palpable _ when she feels as if
she's back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   A close friend stayed with her the first month after the murder,
and she despaired when it came time for her to leave. ``I realized
we were going to be here just the four of us, without him here to
help with things or do the things we normally did, and it all just
came back _ the fear, the feeling, `How am I going to do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   With her sky-blue eyes and direct, honest gaze, Sheila has the
serene, natural beauty of a woman in a Vermeer painting. Like her
husband, she is sustained and transformed by her faith: ``I feel
tremendous peace; people expect me to be lying in bed all day or
bawling at the drop of a hat,'' she said. ``God doesn't want us to
stay there. He gives me strength to get through each day. I have
responsibility for the children. Brett would not want me lounging
around being depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would call that denial. Davis calls it faith.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila has traveled an unfathomable distance since the day she
lost her ability to speak, on her front lawn, in front of her
family and neighbors. Today, she is the one encouraging people to
talk _ the children especially. ``We were all just such a family,''
she said. ``How could anybody not talk about that? Half of us is
gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila battles against any attempts, however well-meaning, to
transform her husband into Saint Brett, an icon, instead of a man
of flesh and blood, a man who loved fast motorcycles and fast cars
(though he drove a sensible Prism). At church gatherings he was
known for his goofy Elvis impersonations, complete with wig and
sequined jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could see all this, he'd say, `What are you guys doing?
Don't put me on that pedestal,''' Sheila said. ``He was a great
guy, but he was a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brett, July 8 started as every Thursday did: with orange
juice, cereal and 5 a.m. fellowship with Tom Looker. It was a
weekly event in which the friends met before work to pray, discuss
Scripture, to share what they had written in their journals or in
the margins of their Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   They picked the red-eye hour because it was least likely to
interfere with family time, and to skip it altogether would be
unfathomable. ``If there were a struggle or tension in his life, I
noticed a change in perspective after they were together,'' Sheila
said. ``They had such a neat and deep relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendship began in 1991, when Looker was seeking a weekday
Bible study class. Brett was seven years older, married, already a
father, ``and initially it was more of a mentoring relationship,''
Looker recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the friendship evolved into what Looker described at
Brett's funeral, quoting a verse from Proverbs 27: ``As iron
sharpens iron, so does one man sharpen each other.''
</P>
<P>
   They consulted each other not only about spiritual issues but
also about major decisions such as job changes. ``Tom used to bring
girlfriends to meet us for approval,'' Sheila joked. ``Pam's the
only one who passed the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker believes it was no accident that he and Brett met that
morning. ``It was meant to prepare Brett, to prepare both of us,''
Looker said. ``We were meant to have a meaningful time that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was also a special day for the Wildermuth children_
Joel, 9, Hannah, 7, and Naomi, 5 _ the day they normally spend with
their grandmother, Jean Wildermuth, a librarian. Sheila decided to
use that Thursday to do some ``serious shopping'' for an upcoming
family trip to Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ the first family vacation for
the extended Wildermuth family since the death of Brett's father,
Jake Wildermuth, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a rough few years for the family, and the vacation
was to have been a step toward healing. ``Last Christmas, we agreed
we'd have no Christmas gifts, and we'd call this trip our
Christmas,'' Jean recalled. ``It was time to go out and have fun
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of Jake and Jean Wildermuth's three sons, Brett was
born with a sunny, tenderhearted disposition and a daredevil
streak. ``He must have had a guardian angel,'' Jean said, laughing.
``When he was a boy, he built a ramp and made like Evel Knievel. He
was just fearless when it came to doing things with his bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett also showed an early musical talent that would later
become the core of his lay ministry. As a child he fashioned a toy
guitar out of string and cardboard and rubber bands, ``and he made
it sound just like a guitar,'' his mother said. As a teen-ager he
starred in musicals at Anna High School.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildermuth boys _ Kevin, Gregg and Brett _ reveled in
growing up next to their grandparents' farm in Anna. They shared
their father's passion for cars and motorcycles, and were
constantly working on restoring cars. ``I was always walking over
car parts in the basement, but I didn't dare move a thing out of
place,'' Jean recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't complain, since it brought father and sons closer.
``Brett was a good father,'' Jean said. ``He had a good example;
his dad was a good dad, too. He spent a lot of time with his
sons.''
</P>
<P>
   On Father's Day 1995, Brett wrote a long letter to his father,
recalling an incident in which Brett, while trying to lay a roof,
lost his temper and quit the job: ``You came after me that day to
tell me you were sorry. You'll never know how important it was to
me to know I mattered more to you than that roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett had grown up in a religious home, but it was during his
years in the Coast Guard, which he entered at 18, that his faith
caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   He met Sheila several years later, in July 1985, the summer
between her sophomore and junior years at Wright State University.
``There's a new guy in Bible study,'' Sheila's friends announced.
It was Brett, and in short order, he asked her out, inviting her to
go water skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never been on water skis in my life,'' Sheila said.
``And I said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple were married Aug. 2, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila endured two miscarriages before Joel was born in 1990.
Her difficulty in carrying children brought her closer not only to
Brett but also to the First Church of God congregation. ``I had
never prayed so hard for anything,'' Sheila recalled. It helped to
know that her church was praying with her.
</P>
<P>
   After Joel was born, Sheila stayed home as they had always
planned: ``We had him at last, and I wanted to see him in all the
stages.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah was born in 1992 and Naomi in 1994. Brett continued to
reach out to couples who suffered miscarriages, making special
musical tapes for them and mailing away for books. ``It was healing
for them,'' Sheila said. Brett loved to make musical tapes for
people, to mark special occasions or console them in times of
trouble. He wrote love songs to Sheila, songs honoring the births
of each child.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before his death, Brett told his mother he enjoyed his
work as a computer programmer, ``but ministry is my life.'' He
dreamed of a career in ministry.
</P>
<P>
   His family was his other top priority. Last spring, Brett
accepted a new job, taking a nearly 10 percent cut in pay, so he
could devote more time to family and church. His office was so
close he usually came home for lunch, helping the children _ who
are home-schooled _ with their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the little things I miss,'' Sheila said. ``His manner.
The way he would sit in his rocking chair. The way he would play
hide-and-seek or wrestle on the floor with the kids, acting as if
he were a slightly bigger kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She misses the big things, too _ shared parenting decisions and
joys, dreams for the future. ``I loved him very much, and we were
going to grow old together and watch our kids get married,'' Sheila
said. ``Brett would have written a song for each of their weddings.
We talked and prayed about our kids' future spouses. He was looking
forward to being a grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   The children are all heartbroken about the loss of their father,
Sheila said, but Joel _ the oldest _ has been the most reluctant to
talk about what he is feeling. During their nightly devotions, she
asks the children to remember things they did with their father.
She tells them, ``Daddy's safe in heaven and there's no more pain
and he's not sorrowful any more.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent family evening, the kids shyly shared their
favorite memories. Joel, 9, says he loved it ``when we worked on
the car. He taught me how to rotate the tires and change oil and
check fluid.'' Hannah, 7, a born performer, misses ``singing songs
together at church.'' And Naomi, 5, remembers fondly, ``He took us
for ice cream. Once he blindfolded us and took us for ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel also enjoyed the family singalongs, particularly when his
father and great-aunt Sally would perform a duet of ``The Railroad
Song.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel thinks he understands the lyrics: ``When you go through a
storm or darkness, just follow through and keep your eyes on the
rails.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Joel ever needed to follow that advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Joel said, his eyes thoughtful behind his Harry Potter
glasses, ``when my grandfather passed away. And when my father
passed away.''
</P>
<P>
   One of hardest things for the kids to understand, Sheila noted,
is how ``one of daddy's friends could have done this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long before the shooting, the Wildermuth family had gone to
a gathering at the Hensleys', where the children played with
Hensley's son Devin. ``It was a nice social time,'' Sheila
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi asked her mother recently, ``Mommy why would he do this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, honey,'' Sheila answered. ``Only God and Mike
know why he did this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Brett's death, Sheila hasn't missed a service at the First
Church of God. Members of the Hensley family also continue to
worship there, including Julie Hensley and her mother. It is hard
on both families, Davis acknowledges: ``People here are close to
Mike, and some find it hard to believe he had done this,'' he said.
``There is the guilt and hurt and pain of Mike's family, knowing
Brett's gone and will never be back.''
</P>
<P>
   How has his congregation managed to do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Graciously,'' Davis says, ``and that means literally with the
grace of God. There is real love and acceptance. No one blames any
of Mike's family members for what has happened. We know they had
nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Sheila, ``Their church family is the same church family as
mine. If they feel comfortable, I feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of the world, the situation may seem extraordinary.
In Sheila's eyes, it isn't. ``It's possible because of who Jesus
Christ was,'' she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is proud of his congregation, but his feelings go beyond
pride. ``It's not natural, it's not of man, that this could
happen,'' Davis said. ``This love for one another is the ultimate
in Christian faith. The apostle Paul says love never fails. This is
living proof that love is able to bear troubles even as great as
these.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila visited Julie Hensley once when she was in protective
custody, because Sheila needed to know what happened in the house
that day.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the things Sheila knows she cannot tell, because of the
pending trial. Many things she will never know, until it no longer
matters. ``By the time I am there with Jesus, I won't need to try
to make sense of what is senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila knows she has friends to whom she can turn for support,
advice, help with the kids. Friends who pray for her every day.
``This has changed our lives,'' Pam Looker said. ``We are committed
to this family, and life will never be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila is consoled by letters she has received from all over the
country, some from people who never knew Brett, but felt compelled
to write. She pores over a letter from a woman who had known Brett
only briefly, during his Coast Guard years, but who had always
cherished the tape he made for her. ``Here's this person he only
met briefly, yet he had an impact on her life,'' Sheila marveled.
</P>
<P>
   The woman wrote, ``He truly had a life that mattered, which is
all most of us want in this life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila knows Brett's spirit lives on in his friends, his family,
his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good already is coming from this,'' Looker said.
``People are looking at how they're handling their families,
parents are having better discussions with their kids, couples are
taking their relationships with each other more seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long before he died, Brett promised the children he would
build a treehouse from the dying elm in the back yard. He and
Looker planned to put their talents together to finish the project
after the Wildermuths returned from their Pigeon Forge vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Tom and Pam Looker and several other friends _ Lee and
Sandi Trisler, Dave and Noelle Schwieterman, and Chris and Tonia
Butler and Michael Clayton _ came together to finish the treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   For two Saturday afternoons and one weeknight they labored,
fulfilling Brett's promise to his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a part of each other,'' Looker said. ``You don't leave a
legacy in a house or a car. It's an eternal legacy. Seeds are
planted in people, and now it's continuing. That's the neat part.''
</P>
<P>
   After construction was finished, Sheila brought out a cake to
celebrate Hannah's first tooth coming out and the treehouse going
up.
</P>
<P>
   In her thank-you notes, Sheila described her feelings as she
watched their friends build a treehouse:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like I could see Brett out there working with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
