<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-HOTLINE-1STLD-     10-02 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HOTLINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO VERSION OF HOT LINE LETS COLD WAR FOES EXPAND JOINT NUCLEAR
SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS 3rd and 4th grafs with agreements) (rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The United States and Russia, updating the ``hot line''
concept between leaders of the world's most heavily armed nuclear
powers, opened a new state-of-the-art video-conferencing center
Saturday that will enable Russian and American nuclear officials to
see, as well as talk, to each other during a nuclear-related
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   At a ribbon-cutting ceremony Saturday afternoon, Bill
Richardson, the American secretary of energy, and Yevgeny Adamov,
Russia's minister of atomic energy, said that the nuclear accident
in Japan last week showed the need for such real-time lines of
communication in the event of a nuclear crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and Adamov signed an agreement that expands uniform
procedures for a Department of Energy project in Russia to protect
nuclear weapons and fissile material against theft or diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the two energy agencies had also agreed to
conduct joint tests on potential year 2000 computer software
problems. The tests will start in November, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the accident in Japan ``unsettling,'' Richardson said
that the opening of a joint crisis center showed that if a nuclear
incident takes place, leaders will be prepared to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the accident at the reprocessing plant near Tokyo, in
which 35 people were exposed to high levels of radiation,
Richardson and Adamov made an unprecedented offer of joint
technical assistance to Japan. Adamov said Saturday that Japan had
not accepted the offer so far and had informed his ministry that
``the situation is under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that had he been in Washington during the
accident and if the crisis center had been open, he and Adamov
undoubtedly would have used it to work out the details of their
offer to help Japan deal with the accident, the worst in Tokyo's
troubled history with nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
   But paradoxically, Richardson was in Russia when the accident
occurred and visiting Sarov, a closed nuclear-weapons city an
hour's flight away from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the sleek center on the second floor of the
Minatom building in the heart of Moscow is another indication of
the growing cooperation in critical nuclear matters between Russia
and the United States. The new system links Russia's atomic agency
with the Energy Department's Emergency Operations Center in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson toured once-closed nuclear weapons and energy sites
throughout Russia last week. He said Saturday that he was ``very
encouraged'' by the tangible evidence he had seen of what he called
the ``growing partnership'' in nuclear affairs between Moscow and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The center, with its spare gun-metal steel support beams, its
glass partitions, oversized black leather chairs around an oval
conference table, resembles a set from the ``Star Trek'' television
serial.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's contribution was a giant video-screen that covers
one of the room's walls and $500,000 worth of video conferencing
equipment. The Russian federation spent roughly an equal amount
designing and constructing the sound-proof facility.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the secure telephone line that links the White House and
the Kremlin, over which the Russian and American leaders can
discuss the most secret information, the crisis center linking
Minatom and the Energy Department is not equipped to provide for
such secrecy. But Russian officials hope to eventually be able to
link the center with all its key civilian and military nuclear
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The center will allow real-time communication between the two
energy agencies in times of nuclear or environmental emergencies
such as accidents at nuclear power or fuel facilities, the
accidental release of radioactive materials, or the theft or
diversion of nuclear weapons or other nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
   The center's first order of business Saturday, however, involved
not a nuclear crisis, but a humanitarian one. At the early morning
ceremony Saturday, Richardson announced that his agency and the
American-based Children of the World Foundation were sending two
Russian children to New York's Westchester Medical Center for
life-saving heart surgery. American technical experts learned of
the children's plight while working on projects monitoring nuclear
sites in Siberia, and worked out the arrangements with the
foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
