<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUND FIGHTING RESUMES   AMID CHECHEN THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Sounding defiant as his tiny republic plunged
into a new war Saturday with Russia, Chechnya's president
threatened to kill any Russian soldier who sets foot in the
breakaway land.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment the battle is under way. This is war,''
President Aslam Maskhadov, dressed in combat fatigues, said from a
heavily guarded compound in his bombed-out capital of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to journalists as Russian troops, backed by tanks and
artillery, fiercely clashed with rebel fighters inside the
breakaway republic and seized one Chechen village. The ground
fighting occurred after 10 days of devastating airstrikes and just
three years after the end of a conflict here that claimed the lives
of tens of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   What Russia calls a campaign to crack down on terrorists,
Chechens see as a continuation of Moscow's centuries-long attempt
to dominate the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Russian occupant steps on a centimeter of Chechnya
territory, he will be destroyed,'' said Maskhadov, a former Russian
army colonel who commanded the rebels to victory during Moscow's
disastrous 1994-1996 campaign to end Chechnya's independence bid.
``If it's in the city, we will fight in the city; in the woods, we
will fight in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov also appealed for talks with President Boris N.
Yeltsin, saying that ``We can resolve all our differences in 30
minutes.'' There was no immediate Russian response.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen leader said Russian troops and tanks had moved
several miles into Chechnya, where they were met by Chechen troops
in two districts close to the Russian border 60 miles north of
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fierce battle in the Naursky and the Shelkovsky
regions,'' said Maskhadov's chief of staff, Apti Batalov. ``Sunday
they came in with a full-scale operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian General Valery Manilov, one of the planners of the
Russian military operation, confirmed that Russian troops had
clashed with insurgents in several areas in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov said the Russian forces in and around Chechnya,
estimated at 50,000, would set up a security ring around the
separatist republic to prevent infiltration by Islamic rebels into
neighboring regions.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that Russia was planning a major ground operation, but
the mayor of Naursky, one of the towns near the fighting, described
in a conversation by walkie-talkie a battle involving many Russian
tanks and troops. He said the fighting was too heavy to count
wounded, but said two Russian tanks had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   After a heavy artillery bombardment, Russian troops occupied the
village of Borozdinovka, just over the Chechen border and 60 miles
north of Grozny, according to Abdul Magomedov, a spokesman for the
Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Russian warplanes again bombed Grozny Saturday, the 10th day of
airstrikes Moscow says are aimed at crushing the Islamic rebels,
whom Moscow blames for recent fighting in the neighboring region of
Dagestan and a series of bomb blasts in which nearly 300 people
died.
</P>
<P>
   But video footage shown to reporters in Grozny Saturday that the
Chechens say was shot last month and accounts from numerous
refugees from the violence indicate that the bombing is
indiscriminate and aimed at civilians. In one village, a woman
sitting in bombed-out ruins wails ``mama''; other footage shows
torn and burned bodies laid out in a street.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov said 40 villages had been flattened and said over 400
people had died in the air raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand the Russians,'' Maskhadov said.
</P>
<P>
   While Maskhadov has called for talks, Yeltsin has remained in
the shadows, and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has dismissed the
need for negotiations. On Thursday, Putin said leaders of a former
puppet government set up by Moscow during the last war were the
only legitimate authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have forgotten that Yeltsin sent me a telegram
congratulating me when I was elected,'' said Maskhadov, who won
over 60 percent of the vote in a 1997 election.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the ground fighting forced more refugees to flee the
capital for Ingushetia, the mainly Muslim Russian region west of
Chechnya that has allowed more than 80,000 Chechens into its
territory since the fighting began.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who have not left have been forced to live without
electricity and gas. But outside of the widespread damage, most of
it left over from the last war, there was little sign of
preparation for a new war. In Grozny, street markets operated under
the bombed-out hulls of apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better in paradise than in Ingushetia,'' read graffiti
on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens are nothing if not confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more experience this time,'' said Mogamed Khambiyev,
Maskhadov's defense minister. ``Everyone knows how to fight. We
know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Khambiyev said he had 50 diversionary squads that were ready to
attack Russian troops on Russian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Russian generals' assurances that they had learned
from the mistakes of the last war, he said: ``They have no new
tactics _ for 500 years they have had the same tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian armor continued to move along Chechnya's
western border with Ingushetia. But some of the tanks looked old
and battered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians intend to fight with that?'' said Azamat
Nalgiyev, a member of the Ingush parliament, as he watched a tank
tow an armored personel carrier. ``God help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Russian politicians favor a tough line against Chechnya,
where hundreds of Russians and foreigners are believed to be held
hostage by ransom-taking abduction rings. Journalists have also
been victims; Saturday a busload of reporters brought into the
capital were under constant guard by commandos toting machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin offered Saturday to be a
hostage in Chechnya if 180 people held by kidnappers there were
released, Interfax reported in Moscow. Stepashin was chief of
Russia's security agency during the Chechen war and played a large
part in planning the disastrous campaign. This time, he has come
out against the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have said they intend to occupy the area north of
Grozny, set up a pro-Moscow government, and isolate the rest of
Chechnya. But the resistance of the Chechens at the first Russian
incursions indicates that they are not ready to let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov was asked if Chechnya would accept a partition of
their territory, letting the Russians have the northern part.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because this is where I was born,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has been struggling to maintain control over other
Chechen commanders, including the mastermind of the Dagestan
operation, Shamil Basayev. Some Russian observers have questioned
whether Maskhadov can count on Basayev's support now.
</P>
<P>
   But Maskhadov said he had won a vote of support at a congress of
key political and public leaders Saturday in Grozny. He said
Basayev would also obey. While he said he did not agree with
Basayev's tactics, he denied that the invasion of Dagestan amounted
to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian volunteers fought in Kosovo, but no one called that
international terrorism then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov appealed to the West to speak out against the Russian
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The United States urged Russia on Friday to use ``restraint and
wisdom'' in its drive against the rebels. It denied any similarity
between Russia's offensive and NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time, the West practically gave the Russians the right to
destroy Chechnya,'' Maskhadov said, referring to incidents like the
1996 press conference where President Clinton compared Yeltsin to
Abraham Lincoln. ``Hopefully this time the West will realize they
cannot allow this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
