<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MUSEUM-FLAP-BOS &LR;      10-02 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-FLAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM FUSS DRAWS CURIOUS TO BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Mayor Rudolph Giuliani were a paid publicist for
the Brooklyn Museum of Art, he couldn't have done much more to turn
out the crowds for opening day of its controversial exhibit called
``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Crimi, a truck dispatcher from Queens, was one of the first
in line Saturday morning. ``I absolutely would not have come had
the mayor not attacked it,'' she said. ``I came only to show my
support for the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   D.J. Samuelson, a railroad worker who took the 6:43 train from
the Hamptons said, ``I'm here to see what the fuss is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Young, a college instructor who drove in from Long Island
mused, ``I see my presence here as a form of meaningful voting.
It's a vote for freedom of expression and maximum tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks now, they and hundreds more who stood waiting in
line had been savoring the moment when this show _ which has
attracted more fear, loathing, and lawsuits than any art show the
past decade _ finally opened.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidewalk, cordoned off by police, a group of Catholics _
200 at most _ had been waiting with equal eagerness to protest the
exhibit. They railed against the museum's directors, chanted
prayers, and held signs reading ``Bigotry Is Not Art,'' ``Evil
Trash,'' and ``Shame!''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen animal-rights activists were on hand to protest the use
of dead mammals in some of the show's installations. ``We think
there's nothing creative about animals suffering,'' said Mia
MacDonald, one of the activists.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, nearly 1,000 had gathered outside the museum
for a free-speech rally to denounce Giuliani, cheer the museum, and
hold such signs as ``Censorship Is an Obscenity,'' ``Next: Burning
at the Brooklyn Public Library?'' and ``Don't Pooh-Pooh Our Pooh
Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, featuring works by young British artists, includes
such provocations as a dead shark floating in formaldehyde, a
sliced-up pig, and _ most notoriously _ a painting of the Virgin
Mary with clumps of elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, after looking through the catalogue two weeks ago,
blasted that work in particular as ``disgusting'' and
``anti-Catholic.'' He cut off the city's subsidy to the museum and
filed a lawsuit to evict it _ and its vast holdings of ancient and
modern art _ from the city-owned building that it has occupied for
more than a century. In turn, the museum is suing the city,
demanding the restoration of its subsidy on First Amendment
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   When the museum's doors finally opened Saturday at 11 a.m. and
the crowds filled the halls, a pattern seemed to emerge. Of two
dozen people interviewed, some liked the show, others didn't, but
they all expressed one basic sentiment: What's the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   William Parsons, a retired math teacher, stood with a crowd of
people gazing at the center of the controversy, Chris Ofili's
``Holy Virgin Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the rays emanating from her head, like a halo,'' he
said. ``I think it's magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Pelletier, a costume designer, agreed. ``She's really
quite lovely,'' she said in a tone of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of this painting have appeared in newspapers and on
TV newscasts for weeks now. But neither the photos nor its
reproduction in the museum catalogue _ which so angered Giuliani _
capture what it looks like.
</P>
<P>
   This Mary, who more resembles an African earth goddess, is
draped in a luminous blue gown against a gold backdrop that
glistens.
</P>
<P>
   The huge canvas does sit on two clumps of elephant dung, and a
highly molded and polished clump of dung represents her breast. But
elephant dung is prominent in three other Ofili paintings, which
have nothing to do with religious themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought from the newspapers that dung was going to be
smudged all over the thing,'' said Edward Moran, a Brooklyn-based
writer. ``It's not that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said nothing about a potentially more shocking
aspect of this work _ that pasted all around Mary are photos of
bare female backsides that Ofili had cut out of porn magazines.
Then again, these fragments, shaped like angel wings, are so small,
he might not have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few inside the museum seemed bothered. ``I guess the
artist is saying she was a woman at one point,'' said Rick Casey, a
designer. ``Clearly a lot of good feeling went into this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Williams, a transit worker said, ``I don't understand the
point of the buttocks. But it isn't upsetting. The painting doesn't
look to me like someone trying to denigrate her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did many seem repelled by Damien Hirst's infamous
installations _ a sliced-up pig, a cut-up cow, and a large sealed
cage filled with hundreds of flies and maggots, a cow's head, and
an electronic zapper. The flies breed, feed on the head, then die
on the zapper. Most people get the joke _ a brutal play on the
cycle of life.
</P>
<P>
   More were upset by works of the Chapman Brothers _ tangled
life-sized sculptures of little girls in perverse positions, many
with faces made of sex organs.
</P>
<P>
   But, contrary to the publicity, the vast bulk of ``Sensation''
has nothing to do with sex or religion and much more to do with
post-modern explorations into the meaning of art _ some funny, some
shocking, a few beautiful, most flatly old hat.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blimey!,'' his book about the contemporary British art
scene, Matthew Collins writes, ``Young British art is really a
movement of everything mixed up and everyone chopping and changing
between different mediums and styles.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a few museum-goers Saturday were bothered, more than
anything, by this self-conscious stylishness. ``Don't any of these
artists care about anything outside themselves?'' sighed Deborah
Kapell, an epidemiologist. ``There's no passion. It's so pointless.
It's so cool, so ironic, so detached, I don't find it very
meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   Back outside, the protesters _ most of whom said they had no
intention of seeing the show _ were finding it all too meaningful.
William Donohue, head of the Catholic League, called it hate speech
and said to much applause that the museum ``should have a couple of
Catholics on their board of directors _ then they'd understand the
real issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's critics have accused the mayor of making such
an issue over the museum for political motives. He is the likely
Republican candidate in next year's US Senate race, and New York
statewide elections often hinge on the Catholic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Doyle Blackwall, one of the protesters, said, ``We're
sending money to Giuliani's campaign. He's standing up for what's
right. Some politician said the biggest sleeping giant in American
politics is the Catholics. Maybe it's time we woke up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0194 </DOCNO>
