u a BC-BOX-BATTLE-OF-THE-SEX     10-02 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BATTLE-OF-THE-SEXES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A MAN MEETS A WOMAN (IN THE RING)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (DELETES sentence about phone call not being returned in 3rd to
last graf) 
(ATTN: Nev., Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREMERTON, Wash. _ Both fighters are brashly predicting a
knockout, which is nothing new in boxing. But some of the other
pre-bout banter is certainly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if this guy feels at all hesitant to get out in the ring
and hit a girl, well, I'll belt him enough to get him upset and get
him going,'' explained 36-year-old Margaret MacGregor, who will
take on a man, Loi Chow, in a fight in Seattle that is sending
waves of discomfort through the boxing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get in there and start going toe to toe,'' Ms.
MacGregor said, ``Loi Chow is going to realize something. He's
going to have to go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   After the state of Washington declared that its gender-equity
laws give it no authority and indeed no reason to prevent the
match, what is billed by its promoters as the nation's first
officially sanctioned bout between a man and a woman was scheduled
for Oct. 9 at Seattle's Mercer Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The four-round fight between Ms. MacGregor and Chow, both
expected to weigh in at around 125 pounds, is on the undercard to a
longer fight between two men. But it has stolen all the attention,
generating considerable publicity and talk-show fodder here in the
Seattle area and prompting sharp criticism from boxing officials in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is very simple in the state of Nevada,'' said Marc
Ratner, executive director of the state's Athletic Commission,
which regulates fights. ``We feel that men should fight men, and
women should fight women.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Sugar, editor of Fight Game magazine and one of the sport's
most respected historians, was one of several boxing experts who
concurred that indeed, the Seattle bout was the first official
intergender match-up. But, he quickly added, that hardly makes it
momentous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a circus, it's a sideshow,'' said Sugar, echoing what
seems to be the prevailing view among boxing officials. ``It's an
old carnival act, updated for the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. MacGregor says she is angered by the suggestion that she
does not belong in a ring with Chow, of Vancouver, British
Columbia. She is 3-0 fighting other women in the ring and 8-0-1 as
a professional kick boxer, including four victories by knockout,
two in which her female opponents were out on a 10-count and two
more in which the referee stopped the fight. Chow is 0-2 in fights
against men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody could come up with a really good reason why this
fight shouldn't happen, that would be nice,'' said Ms. MacGregor, a
part-time landscaper in this blue-collar shipbuilding city an
hour's ferry ride from Seattle, who was drawn to study martial arts
in part, she said, because of the ``helpless'' way she felt when
her husband at the time hit her during an argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just vowed, `No man will ever do that to me again unless I
let him,''' said Ms. MacGregor, who has a new boyfriend, Mike
Hopkins, a truck driver with whom she hopes to have children some
day. As for her boxing, ``he's very supportive,'' and will work her
corner of the ring in the upcoming fight, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, most men are stronger than most women, but there
are exceptions,'' added Ms. MacGregor, after a workout at Twin
Tigers Gym here. At 5 feet 5 inches, she enjoys a three-inch height
advantage over Chow, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   War between the sexes is, of course, nothing new, and the United
States crossed some sort of sports rubicon in 1973, when Billie
Jean King, the women's tennis star, defeated an older male player,
Bobby Riggs, in a much-publicized contest.
</P>
<P>
   But an official match inside the ring is clearly breaking new
ground. Even as some state boxing commissions insisted that they
would never allow it, Washington officials said they ignored gender
altogether as a factor in sanctioning fights here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't discriminate against anybody on the basis of
gender,'' said Suzanne Taylor, a spokeswoman for the state's
Department of Licensing. Her agency, which also oversees drivers'
licenses, took over boxing regulation when the state's boxing
commission was disbanded three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at height, weight, prior experience,'' Ms. Taylor
said. ``What we're concerned about is the safety of the fighters,
and we wouldn't approve the fight if it was not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The department's approval was described as ``absolute madness''
by a former head of the boxing commission, Dale Ashley, in a recent
letter to The Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department of licensing will not stop until they kill
someone,'' Ashley wrote. ``They have program managers with no
boxing experience, who don't know a left hook from a jab.''
</P>
<P>
   Even officials with the International Female Boxers Association,
based in California, have objected to the MacGregor-Chow bout, for
which each fighter will receive $1,500, saying it could detract
from the big strides that all-female boxing has made. The Seattle
fight will occur one night after Muhammad Ali's 21-year-old
daughter, Laila, is scheduled to make her professional debut in a
fight against another woman at the Turning Stone Casino in Verona,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   About 12 percent of the fights sanctioned in Nevada each year
feature two women in the ring, said Ratner. Rounds are two minutes
long, rather than three as in men's fights, but otherwise the rules
are pretty much the same, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there are knockouts, women get cut, certainly their
eyes do get swollen,'' Ratner said. ``It's all a part of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The promoter of the Washington fight, Bob Jarvis, said the idea
of the man-woman match-up really arose by accident, when he could
not find a woman for Ms. MacGregor to fight and jokingly brought up
the idea with Ms. MacGregor's trainer, Vern Miller, who also
teaches kung fu and tai chi here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women don't want to fight guys,'' Jarvis said. ``But this
one, she really, really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. MacGregor was originally to fight another Vancouver boxer,
Hector Morales, but he pulled out after becoming uncomfortable with
the idea, promoters said, and Chow stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Jarvis professed dismay at all the attention the
fight is getting, even if it does sell tickets, because it has
detracted from the focus on his fighter, Martin O'Malley, whom he
described as a 10-0 phenom with huge star potential in the
lightweight division. The fighter is scheduled for a 10-round fight
with Tito Tovar of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm serious,'' Jarvis said. ``No one is even talking about
Martin O'Malley anymore. And he's not real happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chow, a jockey and a weightlifter, has predicted that the fight
will be over in less than a minute, with Ms. MacGregor succumbing
to the first left-right combination he lands.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. MacGregor, who sported a yin and yang earring as she
sparred in the ring Friday with a male friend, Juan Rodriguez,
warned her opponent not to underestimate her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he thinks he's getting a cream puff, he's in for a real
jolt,'' she said. ``I'm going to rock his world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
