<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins get low-stakes win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beyond everything else, it was a beautiful day at the
ballyard on Saturday, even if the stakes were nonexistent and so
were the runs when the Braves and Marlins met for the
second-to-last game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Not until Cliff Floyd hit a home run off Derrin Ebert to right
field in the 10th inning was there a score in this game and a
finish, 1-0 Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we wanted to do except win the ballgame,''
said Braves manager Bobby Cox, who got a couple of at-bats for the
starters, at-bats for just about every player on the bench, and
rest for the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   With the defeat, the Braves lost their chance at finishing with
their best record yet at Turner Field _ they needed wins in their
last two games to hit 57 for the season. But that was about all
that's left to play for as the Braves await the finish of the
wild-card race to find out who they will play Tuesday in the
Division Series. It'll be either the Reds, who lost their second in
a row on Saturday, or the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the last few postseason roster spots are all that's up
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen is one of the question marks. He has an outside
chance at making the postseason roster as the Braves' 10th pitcher,
and made a case for it on Saturday, allowing one hit over six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first start since a July 28 loss to the Brewers, Chen
struck out six and didn't walk a batter. Floyd lined a single to
center off him in the first inning and that would be all off Chen
for the Marlins, who struck out 15 times against John Smoltz and
company Friday, only to follow it with another 13 strikeouts on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Between those two Floyd hits, the Braves retired 26 consecutive
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's season has been mostly about disappointment as he failed
in repeated chances at becoming the Braves fifth starter. But it
didn't end that way. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Chen said. ``If I don't make the postseason
roster it's like my season ends. I don't feel like it's over. I
feel strong. I feel good.... I thought I was going to be the fifth
starter and things didn't go my way. I'm glad I was able to stay
and finish the season strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
