<SLUG> BC-FBC-LSU-UGA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucky Dogs win again
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The NCAA doesn't keep it as an official statistic,
so it's difficult to verify. But based on its play the past two
games, Georgia might be the luckiest team in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs on Saturday dodged a bullet again. More accurately,
the bullet was batted away by linebacker Will Witherspoon with 18
seconds left. He went airborne to knock away Josh Booty's two-point
conversion pass for Tommy Banks, thus preserving the 10th-ranked
Bulldogs' 23-22 victory over beleaguered LSU.
</P>
<P>
   The week before, Georgia's one-point victory over Central
Florida was made possible when a Central Florida point-after
attempt hit an upright and the Golden Knights were called for
offensive interference in the end zone in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're a team of destiny,'' Witherspoon said. ``And
your destiny is what you make of it. We're 4-0, 2-0 in the
conference. That's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stroke of luck _ Florida's overtime loss to Alabama on
Saturday _ means the Bulldogs head to Knoxville on Saturday to take
on No. 7 Tennessee as the first place-team in the SEC East. The
Vols have beaten Georgia eight consecutive years. But Georgia takes
them on with an identity: a team that makes the most of good
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise we're not trying to do this,'' coach Jim Donnan
said. ``We understand we're very fortunate to be 4-0. We are lucky.
But this is a young team, and we're looking to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to give the fans their money's worth,'' joked
defensive tackle Marcus Stroud.
</P>
<P>
   A loss would not have been funny. The Bulldogs seemed in control
of the game and could have avoided the last-second stress. But Hap
Hines failed to convert a 31-yard field-goal attempt in the third
quarter, and Donnan elected to go for a first down on fourth-and-2
at the LSU 5 later in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But after stuffing the Tigers all of the third and most of the
fourth quarter, Georgia let them fly down the field and score on a
39-yard pass from Booty to Reggie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   LSU coach Gerry DiNardo, under heavy scrutiny after the Tigers'
collapse last season, did not hesitate going for two. ``I thought
it'd give us the best chance to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Witherspoon intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something you always dream of doing,'' he said. ``You
want to make the big play in a big game. I knew if I missed it,
(Banks) was right there behind me. It was the greatest feeling in
the world to make contact with that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
