<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-RETURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME RETURN FOR COWBOYS' SANDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Sitting in his truck outside the Cowboys
headquarters a few days ago, Deion Sanders took a timeout from the
hysteria surrounding today's return of Prime Time.
</P>
<P>
   That the team's resident cornerback/punt returner/preacher and
his surgically repaired great left toe will make their season debut
when the Cowboys (2-0) and Cardinals (1-2) kick off at noon today
has sparked more national interest than a certain Dallas
championship team opening its season this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Ma,'' Connie Knight, will even be in the stands at Texas
Stadium to watch her first game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a football mom,'' Knight said. ``I love football. But the
game isn't good unless my baby is playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And her ``baby'' is yearning to return in typical Prime-Time
fashion _ with a big play for a touchdown and a new ``Holy Ghost''
dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My toe is not 100 percent,'' Sanders said. ``I don't know what
percent it is. But it's the best possible shape it's been in a long
time. I feel like I can play on it. When I say play, I mean play.
You are going to know I'm out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my time. You might call it a flair for the dramatic. I
just see myself doing what I've always done. I take care of my
moments. I see this as one.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Sanders, 32, swayed to the gospel music on the truck
stereo system, he acknowledged that the time away has also allowed
him to see that the moments will one day disappear. He said he's
nowhere close to retirement, joking that he would like to play
until his 5-year-old son, Deion Jr., reaches the NFL. But he also
understands that his Hall of Fame-destined career is turning the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes there will be a life without Prime Time, the
flamboyant superhero-like cartoon character he created at Florida
State to maximize his profile and earning potential. Prime Time is
Deion's alter ego, the guy he sees returning interceptions for
touchdowns on ``Monday Night Football''.
</P>
<P>
   And while he plans to continue to don his Prime-Time cape on
game days, he said it's time to end things as he started: with
Deion Sanders, not Prime Time, playing the larger role.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my career is over, the cartoon character dies,'' Sanders
said. ``I can't allow that to happen with my true self. I'm about
bringing people in the kingdom now. I must allow people to know
me.'' \Nsubheds:Who is Deion Sanders? For the bulk of his 11-year
career, the attention-grabbing persona of Prime Time, though a
marketing bonanza, turned Sanders the person into a public enigma.
He's generally portrayed to fans as a me-first, team-second prima
donna by critics in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Making the 6-foot-1, 195-pound Sanders even more of a conundrum
is that teammates and coaches throughout his career don't see him
as a selfish player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion is a good dude,'' safety Darren Woodson said. ``People
don't understand what type of guy he is because you can't see from
the outside in. The only reason people think he's selfish is
because when he comes on the field, he turns into the
attention-getting Prime Time. When he's in the locker room he is a
different guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin might relate to Sanders better
than anyone, on and off the field. Irvin knows about exposure as a
``prime time'' player on the field and a controversial image off
it. He said Sanders' confident swagger is crucial to his success at
cornerback because of the alone-on-an-island nature of the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to do his thing,'' Irvin said. ``The position he
plays you have to have a confident mentality. He's got to do it.
Outside of that, I don't know how else to put it. It's incredible
to play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who play with him are here because of Sanders, and
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones uses this as evidence of Prime Time's
team-oriented nature. He said Sanders was the point man in the
Cowboys' free-agent signings of linebacker Broderick Thomas a few
years ago and defensive end Alonzo Spellman this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the assistant personnel guys,'' Jones said
Sanders. ``He's always looking for guys that might help us out. The
only way that relates is that he's constantly thinking about team.
And even when he's not on the field, he's coaching his teammates,
helping them get better. Along with his obvious God-given physical
skills, Deion is one of the most intelligent players I've been
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders blames part of his negative image on cultural
misunderstandings regarding his flashy demeanor, in part because of
his own reluctance to open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at fault, too, because Prime Time is all I've showed to
some people,'' Sanders said. ``Let the truth be told, Deion is very
boring to the public. He's a lot more serious. He's honest real and
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he became more true to his teammates and family
when he became a born-again Christian two years ago. Connie Knight
said she and her son have always had a brother-sister bond. The two
became closer when he started living for Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Time, the one with all the mouth, was just on the
field,'' Knight said. ``Deion was always quiet. But he's very
different now. He has a lot more patience and we have a lot more to
talk about now.''
</P>
<P>
   What puzzles Sanders is that critics remain. People question
whether his faith is legitimate or just another Prime Time sales
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's funny is that nobody knew my life was a mess,'' Sanders
said. ``I told everybody. I told everybody I was whoring. I told
everybody I was suicidal. It's not like somebody found out.
Everybody thought I had it going on. How are people going to
persecute me for coming clean? How are you going to judge me for
telling the truth? But I don't worry about it. I have joy in my
life.'' \Nsubheds:Defining Prime Time Though Sanders is frustrated
that his on-field persona has sometimes drawn criticism, he has no
regrets for its existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal coming out of college was to take care of my
momma for the rest of my life, to secure her and retire her,'' said
Sanders, who grew up in a drug-infested neighborhood in Fort Myers,
Fla. ``Prime Time helped do that by all means. I didn't need a big
ad agency. I didn't need a firm to put my stuff out there. I did it
on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did was secure unprecedented national acclaim for a
formerly overlooked position. Thanks largely to Sanders, who
coupled standout play with an attention-getting personality,
cornerback has turned into one of the NFL's glamour positions. The
megamillions in salaries invested in Sanders has paved the way for
Denver's Dale Carter, New England's Ty Law and Atlanta's Ray
Buchanan to sign huge free-agent contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The original intent was about business, but Sanders said what
you see during games is pure enjoyment for the game of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Time comes out for a couple of hours a day for a child's
game,'' Sanders said. ``He plays with joy like he played with as a
child. Prime Time is like a kid playing in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   To be even more truthful, the root of the Prime Time nickname
was never about the way Sanders played football _ though he has
been ``dancing and high stepping on the football field since I was
7 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   ccording to]Knight said the nickname actually started because of
her son's exploits on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said Sanders, an all-star performer in football,
basketball, track and baseball in high school, helped his team win
a game with a last-second shot. One of his teammates said ``It was
a Prime Time play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it started,'' Knight said. ``It was Prime Time. He
was like that in all sports. He's not just a football player. He's
an athlete. My baby is an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Cowboys just want standout The name is not important
to the Cowboys' defense, just the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   And they want the same standout play from the person wearing No.
21 that they were getting in 1998 before he went down with a toe
injury against the Cardinals in November.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who made the Pro Bowl as a punt returner and cornerback
despite missing the last five games, said he wouldn't have come
back at all if he couldn't live up to his past standards.
</P>
<P>
   His return certainly bolsters the Cowboys' hopes of making a run
at a fourth Super Bowl title in the 1990s. Already a solid
contender this season because of their offense, the Cowboys see
Sanders' impact on defense as possibly being the difference in
making a title run.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are ranked 31st in the league in pass defense and
have allowed 11 pass plays of more than 20 yards in two games this
season. Sanders' presence should allow the Cowboys to mix up their
pass coverages and be more aggressive with the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He allows us to dictate to the offenses instead of them
dictating to us,'' linebacker Dexter Coakley said. ``Deion is a guy
who is pretty much going to take away half of the field, which
allows us to do some things on the other half.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he doesn't need the other half _ the Prime Time guy
_ or football anymore.
</P>
<P>
   His past two contracts with the Cowboys have totaled $87
million. He's a newlywed, and he and his wife, Pilar, are expecting
their first child _ Deion has two from a previous marriage _ early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have already started building on his 35,000-square-foot
dream home on a ranch in Prosper, north of Fort Worth-Dallas. His
ministry is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he continues playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always played for the love of the game,'' Sanders said.
``Along with loving the game came perks. If you work hard you
should be able to play hard. My family has been able to play hard.
I can walk away now and be financially secure. There are no
pressures to be out there anymore. I'm here because I love the game
and it comes easy to me, like I'm on the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like he did before there ever was a Prime Time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
