<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudd revisiting role in hot seat
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ The heat is on Ricky Rudd at today's NAPA
AutoCare 500, but not like it was in last year's race at
Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran driver, who starts in the eighth position today,
hasn't registered a victory this season. With seven races
remaining, Rudd is in danger of ending Winston Cup's longest active
streak of winning at least one race per season, which spans 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd was in a similar situation at the .533-mile Martinsville
oval last year, needing a win to extend the streak. In one of the
most memorable races of the season, Rudd overcame extreme
temperatures in the cockpit and severe burns to earn a drive down
victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that it was physically the toughest race I
have ever been in over the years,'' Rudd said. ``I remember some of
the race but don't remember all of it. Winning or losing simply
came down to survival.''
</P>
<P>
   An unusual set of circumstances put Rudd through the torturing
day. With 93-degree temperatures near the start, he decided to cut
holes in the upholstery in an attempt to flow in more cool air from
the car's ventilation system.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd dressed in a new cooling helmet-and-suit combination and it
malfunctioned on the second lap. As the temperatures rose in the
cockpit for Rudd, his crew tried to help on pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first stop they gave me a little glass of water down my
back and I said, `Man, I need more than (this), I need a garden
hose,''' Rudd recalled. ``I guess they weren't paying attention and
the hose laying in the sun on the asphalt was about 150 degrees and
it just cooked me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the race continued, so did the problems for Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The metal of the seat was burning through my uniform and I had
burns all over my legs and back _ I had blisters all over,'' he
said. ``The heat was the kind of stuff you jump away from, but I
didn't have anywhere to go unless I wanted to sit on the steering
wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hut Stricklin was on stand-by to be a relief driver, but Rudd
defiantly insisted on staying in the No. 10 Ford because it was
running so well. He fought off challenges from John Andretti and
Sterling Marlin to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so drained that if somebody spun, I wouldn't use up the
energy trying to turn _ I'd just ricochet off them,'' Rudd said.
``My plan was to take the checkered flag and then just drive
straight to the infield (medical) center and park there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, the detour to victory lane was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Richard Petty (18 years) and David Pearson (17) have longer
season streaks in history than Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
