<SLUG> BC-FBC-ECAROLINA-ARMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST CAROLINA REPELS ARMY FOR 5-0 START
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Unbeaten East Carolina did not need a
dramatic comeback Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, who are ranked 19th in the Associated Press poll of
news media after coming from behind last week to upset Miami, this
time had to withstand a two-touchdown rally by Army in the final
quarter before prevailing, 33-14, at Michie Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Army, those two touchdowns _ the first the
Cadets have scored in the fourth period in four games _ were, in
effect, negated by two costly miscues.
</P>
<P>
   After Army had pulled to 19-7 on a 6-yard run by fullback
Michael Wallace with 9 minutes 33 seconds remaining in the game,
quarterback Joe Gerena was sacked, the ball came loose, and the
bounding ball was recovered by 295-pound tackle Norris McCleary,
who rumbled 40 yards for a touchdown that put the Pirates (5-0)
ahead, 26-7, with 5:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   Army responded with a 65-yard drive that was capped by a 1-yard
run by Gerena to cut the Pirates' lead to 26-14.
</P>
<P>
   But Army's onside kick after the score proved disastrous.
Halfback Marcellus Harris scooped up the squib kick at the Army 46
and, behind a covey of blockers, sprinted down the right sideline
for a touchdown that sealed the victory for East Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring on four of its first five possessions, the Pirates
surged to a 19-0 lead on field goals of 30, 29, 52 and 42 yards by
Kevin Miller along with a 62-yard touchdown pass from quarterback
David Garrard to wide receiver Arnie Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw at least three missed tackles on that play,''
Army coach Bob Sutton said in referring to Powell's run after his
catch at the Army 35. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another superb passing performance by Garrard, who threw for 338
yards against Miami, and East Carolina's containment of an Army
rushing attack that had been ranked first in Division I-A were the
keys to the Pirates' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Army (1-3) had come into Saturday's contest averaging 339 yards
rushing, but was held to 184 yards, even fewer than it gained
passing, something that rarely happens for the Cadets' run-oriented
wishbone offense. Still, the Cadets outgained East Carolina, which
could amass only 52 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But Garrard, well protected throughout, made up for that
disparity by completing 24 of 34 passes for 300 yards as he
repeatedly found his receivers wide open. Gerena, meanwhile,
connected on 10 of 20 passes for 196 yards. All but one of those
passes were completed in the second half after Gerena hit on only
one of seven passes during the first two quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
