<SLUG> BC-POACHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POACHERS POSING A LARGE THREAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A multibillion-dollar poaching industry is threatening big-game
animals in North America and the rest of the world, according to a
three-part series in Outdoor Life magazine. And, quoting the World
Wildlife Fund, the magazine says that the profit margin in this
endeavor is third only to that in illegal trade in narcotics and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the series, in this month's issue, suggests ways to
deal with this problem, including more funds for financially
strapped federal and state fish and game agencies, stiffer fines,
jail penalties and loss of hunting rights, and even, as has
happened, recruiting reformed poachers to the anti-poaching cause.
</P>
<P>
   Also noted are the increasingly sophisticated tools used to
catch outlaw hunters, including laboratories with DNA-identifying
capabilities. And in a developing trend, nine western states have
banded together and agreed that a poacher who loses his right to
hunt in one of those states automatically loses that right in all
the others.
</P>
<P>
   The series points out that only a tiny fraction of the millions
of hunters in the United States defy the law, but most wardens also
believe that only between 5 and 10 percent of the violations are
detected. Trophy antlers of such animals as mule deer, whitetail
deer and elk account for much of the poaching in North America. A
rack from a whitetail buck large enough to be included in the Boone
and Crockett record book can fetch as much as $25,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
