<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESSIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSIER NOT READY FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, Oct. 2 _ The jaw juts out as menacingly as ever when
Mark Messier hears something he does like. He may be 38 now and
coming off an injury-plagued 59-game season, the fewest he has ever
played in a regular season in his brilliant career. But mellowing?
Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, hours before the debut of Messier's 21st
National Hockey League season _ which came here against the
Rangers, no less _ Messier was asked if any thoughts of his own
ceremony had crossed his mind in Edmonton the night before, as
Messier took part in the retiring of Wayne Gretzky's number.
</P>
<P>
   Messier had been recalling the ceremony. Upon hearing the
question, his eyes narrowed as he fixed his gaze on the questioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even looking or thinking along those lines,'' Messier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the question was totally out of line. Messier, after
all, is in the final guaranteed year of the deal he signed with the
Canucks, after the Rangers let him _ more like forced him _ to walk
away from them and Gretzky two summers ago. Messier signed a
guaranteed 3-year deal with Vancouver that paid him $6 million each
season, including this one. Next season, the Canucks must decide
whether to pick up the first of two $6 million options or pay
Messier a $2 million buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The woeful Canucks are perennially rebuilding. It is highly
unlikely they will pick up the option. And that means Saturday
night could be the beginning of Messier's final season.
</P>
<P>
   But Messier, who helped lead the Oilers to five Stanley Cups
before captaining the Rangers to their first Cup in 54 years in
1994, does not like hearing any insinuation that he might be
joining Gretzky in retirement after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's necessary to try to predict that,'' Messier
said. ``Obviously, one day, I'm going to get up to do it and I
won't want to do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, said Messier, that is not nearly how he feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you never know,'' Messier said, finally cracking wide one
of his trademark grins. ``I just might go fishing and never come
back one day.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a shame. How would the Oilers, and eventually the
Rangers, be able to honor Messier and retire his number if he was
out on his yacht somewhere, incommunicado?
</P>
<P>
   Messier, of course, would rather not think about that just now.
But he did allow himself to reflect on Gretzky's ceremony, and the
one for Gretzky in New York last April, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, from a selfish standpoint, it was just a sad time,
both times,'' Messier said. ``Everybody, we weren't going to be
able to see Wayne play anymore. But you take that out and yesterday
had to be a happy day.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of all those great Oilers from their dynasty years who
participated in the ceremony, only Messier is still actively
playing. Gretzky is retired. So is Jari Kurri. Kevin Lowe ushered
in his NHL coaching career in Edmonton with a 1-1 tie with the
Rangers after the Gretzky ceremony. Craig MacTavish stood beside
Lowe on the Oilers' bench as his assistant. Esa Tikkanen was
sitting up in the press box, dressed in a suit, hoping the Oilers
would change their minds after they did not offer Tikkanen a
contract after he worked out for them all preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Messier? He flew back to Vancouver after the second period to
prepare for Saturday night's game. But not before he joined
Gretzky, Lowe, MacTavish, Dave Semenko and others reminiscing about
their years in Edmonton in Lowe's office before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing time,'' said Messier, whose Canucks play the
Rangers at Madison Square Garden later this month, on Oct. 24. ``We
can get in a room like that and nothing seems to change. It was
just a comfortable feeling. It was a good night.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17,100 fans on hand for the Gretzky ceremony at Skyreach
Centre (formerly known as Northlands Coliseum) obviously felt the
same. When Messier walked out on the ice, the fans showered him
with his old nickname: ``Mooooose!''
</P>
<P>
   Messier said he couldn't remember the last time he had heard
something like that. His nickname was Mess in New York, but he was
called Moose during his Oilers days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That nickname was given to me by my brother'' _ Paul _ ``when
I was 17 or 18,'' said Messier, 6 feet 1 inch and 210 pounds. ``To
show you how much times have changed, then, I was a strapping left
winger. Nowadays, I'm a shifty little centerman. I guess it tells
you where the game has gone.
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested that the fans might have been booing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they were,'' Messier said, knowing full well they were
not. Someone else suggested that Messier had heard the Moooose call
here, in his first game with the Canucks two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, those were boos,'' Messier said, the broad grin returning
to his face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
