r s BC-BBA-VELARDE-LADN     10-02 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VELARDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ANGEL VELARDE FEELS A MEASURE OF GUILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Randy Velarde knows what it looks like.
</P>
<P>
   He complained. He was traded. Things got tough and he packed his
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Angels' dysfunction was plunging to a new depth,
Velarde high-tailed it for a young, contending team in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone from a losing team expected to win, to a winning
team expected to lose,'' said Velarde, who was traded along with
pitcher Omar Olivares for prospects on July29.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Velarde can't help feeling a measure of guilt for the
Angels' implosion _ one that has resulted in casualties to manager
Terry Collins and general manager Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   It was an implosion Velarde helped to detonate.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde murmured the first public complaints in June,
criticizing Collins for a perceived lack of aggressiveness. He took
specific issue with Collins not allowing him to steal when Mo
Vaughn was at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it seems rather trivial. But it was just a small
portion of Velarde's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people can bottle that stuff. I couldn't,'' Velarde said.
``It was literally killing me inside. I had to vent it. I couldn't
let my poor wife listen to it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even remember who the reporter was. I just got caught
at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, it was leaked that the Angels were discussing a
contract extension for Collins, and that several players _
represented by Vaughn _ aired concerns to Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde, with his week-old comments still reverberating, became
cast as Mutinous Angel No.1
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the only one who had something to say,'' Velarde
said. ``I was just the first one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't the last. Darin Erstad called his teammates soft.
Gary DiSarcina questioned their heart. The ripfest came to a
cacophonous climax four weeks ago when Mo Vaughn and Troy Percival
held a very loud and very public shouting match across the visiting
clubhouse in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   By the time all the dirty laundry had been aired, Collins took
the clothesline and hung himself.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde wasn't there to witness the fallout. He had been with
Oakland for more than a month when Collins resigned on Sept.3.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the guilt comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out I'd been traded, I was disappointed, to be
truthful,'' Velarde said. ``I see myself as a faithful person. I
signed a contract to play here. When you're traded, your initial
sense is that maybe you didn't do your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys might think I'm crazy, but that's the way I am.
If a problem's in front of me, I don't run away. And I know that's
what it looks like _ that I'm running away from my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   His former Angels teammates don't believe Velarde ran out on
them. They don't harbor any resentment. Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and
Garret Anderson joked and chatted with Velarde near the batting
cage on Tuesday when the A's began a three-game series at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   An usher leaned against the photographers well and watched the
scene with interest. ``A week ago when Terry Collins was here,'' he
said, ``only the coaches went up and said hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde can't feel bad about his on-field performance. If he had
stayed with the Angels through the season, Velarde would have been
the team's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   With two games to play, Velarde was hitting .316 with 16 homers
and 74 RBI. He topped the 100-run mark for the first time in his
career. He was three hits short of 200. He had seven triples, 23
doubles and had stolen 24 bases in 32 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time since 1996, he was injury-free the entire
season. No stiffness in his surgically repaired elbow. No strains
or sprains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have health on your side, you have an opportunity to
produce,'' Velarde said. ``Without it, you're a cheerleader. I
always said I'm not a very good cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde has played even better since the trade, batting .331
with Oakland, and while the youthful A's came up short in their
inspired playoff run, Velarde provided a much-needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   He made enough of an impression that Oakland GM Billy Beane
already has contacted Velarde's agent about a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   He'll listen to other offers. And no, he doesn't expect any from
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what (the Angels) are going to do,'' he said.
``That's not my problem. That's their problem. I take care of what
I can between the white lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``... And I'm glad it's not my problem, because they've got
their hands full.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
