 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL _ In the fall of 1944, near a battle front in central
France, an American G.I. named Bob DeHeer was told his services as
an Army mechanic were no longer required. Roughly half of DeHeer's
outfit had been wounded or killed in a German artillery barrage,
and now the enemy was advancing on their position. Since retreat
was not an option, the job for which DeHeer had been trained _
maintaining the company motor pool _ became superfluous. ``So, I
volunteered for machine gun duty,'' he said. By E.J. MONTINI. Story
will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
