<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ARMEY-BO     10-02 2789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ARMEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY'S RECRUITS FORTIFYING RAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Warner is the talk of the NFL at the moment, and, as usual,
the man who discovered him is in the shadows. But he may not be
there for long.
</P>
<P>
   If Warner continues to throw passes the way he has the past two
games and his St. Louis Rams continue to win the way they have
these past two games, the man who discovered the passer and helped
rebuild the team may finally be recognized around the NFL for just
what he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley Armey is the best there is,'' Rams head coach Dick
Vermeil said of his team's vice president for player personnel.
``How could you not enjoy working with him? Charley knows football
players. There are only eight players left from when I got here (in
1997). We have rebuilt this thing together along with (college
personnel director) John Becker into what we believe will be a good
football team. But when it comes to Kurt, I credit Charley Armey.
He's the reason Kurt's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, the former Patriots assistant director of personnel, may
have made his greatest find not long after his arrival in St. Louis
when he signed Warner on Dec. 26, 1997. At the time, Warner was an
Arena Football legend about whom most people knew little or
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Warner had been cut three years earlier by the Green Bay
Packers. After playing only one year at Northern Iowa and then one
summer in Green Bay and making no impression on a team that already
counted Brett Favre, Mark Brunell, and Ty Detmer among its
quarterbacks, Warner moved off to toil in football obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many young men who come unheralded into the NFL, Warner
was gone before he had a chance. He landed back in Iowa in an
oddball indoor league, where he passed for 10,164 yards and 183
touchdowns (including a remarkable 93 in 17 games in 1997). He
supplemented his meager income by working with at-risk kids for a
local YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Armey suggested to Vermeil that maybe they should sign this kid,
and Vermeil took his advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coach at Northern Iowa (Mike Kolling) was my first high
school quarterback when I started in coaching in Graceville,
Minn.,'' Armey recalled. ``I was grateful for that job, and now I'm
grateful to him. He told me the kid could play, and I went to watch
him. He burned up the Arena League and we sent him over to NFL
Europe, and when I saw him there, I knew he was good enough to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner led the Amsterdam Generals to a 7-2 record by completing
165 of 323 passes for 2,101 yards and 15 touchdowns, numbers that
left Armey confident he had done the right thing. After watching
Warner the past two preseasons, that belief was confirmed to his
satisfaction, even when disaster struck in training camp this year
as big-money free agent Trent Green went down for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel we had to run out and sign somebody else,''
Armey said. ``I really had a lot of confidence in Kurt Warner last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner stepped in for Green, and instead of panicking, the Rams
are prospering. Last Sunday, they slapped the defending NFC
champion Falcons silly, and they have given Vermeil every reason to
believe in both Armey's evaluations and his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the end of last season, I've never said anything other
than we'd be a good football team,'' Vermeil said. ``I said a lot
more behind closed doors. Now it's only two games. We haven't done
anything yet. But it's not like we're unlikely performers. We have
good players here.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason they do is Armey, who not only imported Warner but
was instrumental in recommending trading for running back Marshall
Faulk and passing on talented Georgia defensive back Champ Bailey
to select wide receiver Torry Holt in the first round of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey looks like he may become a star one day, but Holt has
been just as impressive and far more valuable to the Rams, who were
already solid at cornerback but without a threat at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The speedy Holt has combined with veteran Isaac Bruce to give
the Rams two dangerous deep threats, while Faulk has picked up
where he left off a year ago in Indianapolis, when he rushed for
more than 1,300 yards and caught passes for more than 900. Handed
those weapons and a solid offensive line to protect him, Warner has
thus far been nothing short of brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt Warner is Larry Bird,'' Rams defensive tackle D'Marco
Farr said in a burst of overzealousness. ``He has the Larry Bird
look. We lost Trent, and they told him, `You're our guy for the
season,' and there was no batting of an eye. Nothing but calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but calm and a 108.6 quarterback rating after two games,
a number Warner reached by completing 45 of 69 passes (65.2
percent) for 584 yards and 6 touchdowns. Vermeil admits no one
could have predicted that, but he quickly adds that one man at
least predicted he could play.
</P>
<P>
   That man is the tall one in the shadows, the one who left New
England with some people in that organization questioning his
ability to evaluate talent. This is a guy who in two years has
brought in Faulk, Holt, Warner, guard Adam Timmerman, young wide
receiver Az-Zahir Hakim, and ex-Patriot linebacker Todd Collins,
players who have become the backbone of the revitalized Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a science,'' Vermeil said of personnel work. ``You
have to be lucky. But Charley Armey helped build a team in New
England that went to the Super Bowl, and he came here and really
liked this kid Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after Trent was hurt and we started to talk about
bringing in a veteran quarterback, Charley was one of the people
who said Warner could do it. We didn't want to confuse the issue
with Trent later by bringing in a veteran, so we assumed Kurt could
step up and we'd grow with him.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the Rams have, with a quarterback from the Arena League
and a personnel director who got his start in the USFL, two guys
left too long on the outside with something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   If they prove it, the world will hear of Kurt Warner soon
enough. A few folks might even hear about a guy who proves his
stuff when players he knows have the right stuff show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of weapons here now,'' said Armey, modestly
neglecting to mention he's one of the guys ordering the armaments.
``The running back is phenomenal. Timmerman has made a huge
difference solidifying the line. (Orlando) Pace is playing tackle
as good as anybody. Todd has come in and really helped our defense.
We're pretty solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the guy who brought them in.
</P>
<P>
   Easing off a little
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil has made a small concession to those who felt the Rams
were practicing too long and too hard since he took over. Although
they still practice more than 2 1/2 hours a day, once the run
defense portion of practice is finished, he allows players to take
off their shoulder pads and finish the drills in shorts and shirts.
``I don't do as much full pad work now because we're further along
as a team,'' Vermeil explained. ``I've figured out if the guy isn't
good enough to make you a playoff-caliber team, longer practices
aren't going to change that. It's my third year back (in coaching)
and I'm trying to do it better. I'm more realistic. The players are
bigger and faster than they were when I was coaching the Eagles.
They hit harder, so it takes a little more out of them and they
need more time to recover.'' . . . There will be something on the
line Sunday when the Rams face the Bengals, even though the two
have been NFL doormats this decade. The loser will be the first
team to reach 100 defeats this decade. St. Louis is 47-99, the
Bengals 48-99 . . . Just to prove that pro football is not a family
business, we point out this fact. Since Bengals founder and
legendary coach Paul Brown died, Cincinnati has gone 39-102 with
his son Mike running the team. Being 0-3 is nothing new to the
Bengals. It is the fourth time this decade they started off that
way . . . If you wonder why they've had so many problems in
Cincinnati, you got a good example this past week, when Brown
released popular starting fullback Brian Milne while he was
rehabbing a sprained knee. That led not only to a grievance but
also to some angry players in the locker room. ``People are going
to look and say, `Man, hard work doesn't pay off,' '' tackle Willie
Anderson snorted. A day later, Brown put hard-luck running back
Ki-Jana Carter (dislocated kneecap) on injured reserve for the year
without telling him. He learned by watching ESPN that he'd suffered
his third season-ending injury in five years . . . Carter has
missed half of his 64 games in a five-year career because of injury
. . . Cowboys owner Jerry Jones is looking to join NASCAR. Well,
sort of. Jones is negotiating to have two cars carry the Cowboys'
colors in the DirecTV 500 at Texas Motor Speedway next April 2 and
at least one car in the Texas 300 a day earlier. Jones has been
negotiating with Action Performance Co., which has licensing deals
with more than 300 drivers. His representatives have spoken with
the sponsors of Bobby Labonte and Rusty Wallace. This would be a
first for an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Things to do in Denver
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional speech last Wednesday, Denver guard Mark
Schlereth got up in front of his battered teammates and spoke about
the team's 0-3 start and his belief that they were feeling sorry
for themselves and many had become selfish. The speech reportedly
had a deep impact on Schlereth's teammates, who could not question
his dedication since he's had 21 operations and a kidney stone
procedure during his professional career. Schlereth reportedly told
his teammates, ``I've got three (Super Bowl) rings and I'm on my
last leg in this league and I've got 13 more weeks left and I'm
here and I'm going to be out here _ we're going to be out here _
doing it right.'' Whether it makes a difference when the 0-3
Broncos take on the 0-3 Jets in an odd replay of last year's AFC
Championship game is another matter. No defending champion has
started 0-3 and returned to the Super Bowl . . . For the Broncos to
turn things around, they're going to have to get a lot more out of
their offense, which has gone from one of the highest-scoring
machines the last two years to No. 27. Despite the insistence of
head coach Mike Shanahan that this is not because of the retirement
of John Elway, Tampa Bay defensive end Chidi Ahanotu finally said
last weekend that the reason for Denver's sputtering offense is
obvious: Brian Griese. But Shanahan is supposed to be a genius, and
in his genius he pulled veteran Bubby Brister before training camp
was over and installed Griese, causing a crisis of confidence on
several levels. The veteran Brister felt betrayed, many of his
teammates privately supported him, and now the young Griese has not
come through . . . Speaking of offensive ineptitude, how much worse
can it get for the Eagles? Of their 40 offensive possessions, 33
have ended with a punt (25) or turnover (8). Only three of those
drives have gone 35 yards or longer . . . Eagles fullback Kevin
Turner is contemplating his football mortality after suffering a
stinger injury last weekend, when he pinched a nerve in his neck
making a block and his arm temporarily went numb. Turner left the
game and will not play against the Giants. He has had such burning
sensations at least once a game of late and visited a specialist
this past week. Although Turner had talked earlier in the year
about his free agent possibilities next winter, he's now wondering
whether he'll continue to play at all . . . Bears offensive
coordinator Gary Crowton is having a field day with his offense.
The innovative Crowton, former head coach at Louisiana Tech, has
brought his high-powered, multi-pronged attack to the NFL, using
quick counts, no-back formations, shotguns, and no-huddles. ``They
remind me of a high school offense we used to play against in San
Diego,'' said Saints defensive tackle La'Roi Glover. ``They run 100
different formations, and each formation has 100 plays.'' . . . A
week ago we mentioned that John Elway had 18 fourth-quarter
comebacks by the end of is seventh season, while Drew Bledsoe had
14 with 14 games to go in his seventh season. Bledsoe actually had
14 when the season began, so the two this year increase his total
to 16, making him even more likely to pass Elway before this year
is out.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman is bearing up
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Spellman has found a second life in Dallas, where he will
start this weekend at defensive tackle, a position he had never
played before this season. His ex-coach with the Bears, Dave
Wannstedt, was among those who recommended the Cowboys give
Spellman a second chance despite his problems in Chicago, where
Spellman was an underachiever who walked out on the team after he
was finally benched, and then had a nervous breakdown . . . Don't
expect a wave of instant-replay challenges after the results so
far. Of 61 challenged plays in 63 exhibition games, only 14 were
overturned. That ratio is unchanged after three weeks of real play.
``It's still a little rough,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll.
``There's still some question marks about it, but I think everyone
on the coaching end is tolerating it, hoping it will eventually
right some wrong down the road this season. I've never been a
proponent of replay because I felt they make the call the best they
can, and that's part of the game. It evens out. But I went with the
numbers on it when we voted and hoped it would work out. They have
a very difficult job making those calls, and now they have a
difficult job ruling with the replay. We had one (in an exhibition
game) where (Vincent) Brisby made a catch in the back of the end
zone we thought was good for a touchdown, and our guys watching the
replay flopped three times on it. If our guys are having that kind
of problem deciding, what is it like for someone with no vested
interest to make a decision? I've always understood those officials
had a very difficult job, but that Brisby play reminded all of us
how hard it is.'' Dallas coach Chan Gailey believed he would use
the challenge system with some regularity, but after going 0 for 5
in challenges in the summer, he changed his approach. ``I will
challenge a lot less than I thought I would have,'' he said. ``I
did not see many overturned in preseason. Whether that was on
purpose to discourage us from challenging or whether it was just
the way it fell, I don't know. Whatever the reason, it happened. It
got to me. I'm not going to challenge very many.'' . . . The main
reason Barry Sanders's agents are making all this noise about
paying back the $5.6 million signing bonus to the Lions is that the
players' union informed Sanders's father last week he has no legal
chance of keeping the money because of a clause in his contract
that covered a non-injury-related retirement. As good a guy as
Sanders is, his reputation is taking a beating over this because
he's acting like a spoiled, manipulative brat instead of the
honorable man he's always been. Have we seen this before in sports?
. . . Buffalo general manager John Butler knows the injury problems
that decimated the Jets will be difficult to overcome but he also
knows it's much too early to write anybody off. ``We haven't heard
the last of the Jets,'' Butler cautioned. ``Sure it's terrible to
lose a key player so early in the season, especially when he's your
quarterback (Vinny Testaverde). That changes things for them, but
this is where a team's character and leadership comes in. They have
some good players there like Bryan Cox and Keyshawn Johnson and
they have to step up and they will, because invariably with a good
team when something like this happens early they bind together. It
can bring a team together if you have the right players and I think
the Jets do. They realize it's still a long season to go and a lot
of things can happen and now they don't wait on someone else to
make a play. They make the plays. They're like wounded dogs now and
that's a very dangerous animal.'' According to Butler, the Jets
also have time on their side. ``Things can change so much in a few
weeks,'' he said. ``It's not like the other sports because each
game is so much larger a part of our season. You see a team winning
for a few weeks and they seem to be one thing and by the end of the
year, it's the complete opposite. So while the injuries certainly
hurt the Jets, it's too early to say it finished them. Who in the
hell thought Vinny or Doug (Flutie) were going to do what they did
last year? A quarterback is only as good as the talent around him
and the Jets still have a lot of talent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
