<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PIPPEN-B     10-02 1974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PIPPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN WEARS OUT ANOTHER WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen got his wish, sort of. He's free of his newly
minted adversary, Charles Barkley. But he still loves LA, although
it may be an unrequited passion.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, Pippen signed with Houston and then, in an
article in ESPN Magazine, detailed at length how different it was
from his years of purgatory in Chicago. Now, he's in Portland after
bad-mouthing Barkley, who, lest we forget, worked for the NBA
equivalent of bag-boy money last year so Pippen, whose signing he
endorsed, could get the big payday.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Pippen wanted out of Houston, and the Rockets
could accommodate him in this salary cap-strangled league, is a
minor miracle in and of itself given Pippen's age (34), health (on
again/off again), performance from last year (mostly off again),
and recent cheesy behavior (bad form). After Barkley delivered a
mild, shut-up-and-play dictum, Pippen went on ESPN and brought out
the Big Berthas. He invoked the name of the sacrosanct Michael
Jordan, who, Pippen said, told him Barkley would never win a title.
(Pippen appparently doesn't know what Jordan has said about him
behind closed doors.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad mix for Pippen in Houston. It wasn't a great mix
for any of the Jordanaires who went elsewhere after title No. 6.
Steve Kerr couldn't get off the bench in San Antonio. Jud Buechler
was still a one-dimensional role player. Dennis Rodman, well, never
mind. The Bulls' diaspora created a lot of wealthy guys who
struggled to find themselves in new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was the most visible. He had a new team, loaded with
veterans, which never got in sync. There was a new system to adjust
to after a lockout. There was a huge sense of expectation that
never materialized. Pippen always felt unappreciated in Chicago and
now, finally free of that ogre Jerry Krause, he was going to win
and be happy in Houston. The Rockets lost and he lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's in Portland _ at least for the time being. How's he
going to feel watching Damon Stoudamire hog the ball? The
expectation there will be every bit as great as it was in Houston;
the Trail Blazers will be the team to beat. He may have to learn to
play fewer minutes on the deep Blazers _ maybe even come off the
bench, for goodness sakes _ and this will be his third coach and
system in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen wants LA and Phil Jax and the triangle and the presumed
greener grass. He still could get it; Portland GM Bob Whitsitt, who
unloaded half of the Willamette Valley to get Pippen, loves Glen
Rice. The holdup may well be Jerry Buss's reluctance to take on
Pippen's diamond parachute (four years, $68 million), which is mere
pocket change for Blazers owner Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of this story is that if you whine long enough and
loud enough, and if you're good enough, something's going to
happen. We thought we had seen the last of the Scottie Pippen who
wouldn't go into a game because Toni Kukoc was getting the last
shot. Apparently, that evil twin is back. The Rockets recognized
rightly that to bring Pippen back would have been untenable. He had
made it thus. Now, he's someone else's headache.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettable bottom line
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McHale was in the most jovial of moods this weekend. Who
could blame him? He went into the Hall of Fame. He had his friends
and family along to share the moment. He even got to ramble on for
the media about a number of topics.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone asked him about managing the Timberwolves and the
losses of Stephon Marbury and Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was supposed to be a fun weekend,'' he quipped.
``You trying to depress me?''
</P>
<P>
   He then went on about how players have a lot of options these
days and how the real challenge is to keep what you have and build
on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But until these guys buy into the concept of team success,
you've got no chance,'' he said. ``Basketball has become too
individualized. It's not an individual game.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, he sounds like Mozart. To others, he sounds like a
fingernail across the blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   McHale paints the agents as the villains in the mess. (He must
have loved seeing David Falk this weekend; Falk was on hand for his
friend and client, John Thompson.) You don't have to prod very hard
to get his take on the negotiating process, which, you probably
know by now, is quite unappealing to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these guys are lawyers,'' he said in a separate
interview before his induction. ``I watch `Matlock' and `Perry
Mason,' but that doesn't mean I know anything about law. How does
watching those shows make me a lawyer? But these guys will tell you
`my guy can do this' and `my guy can do that,' and I say, `Your
basketball background is? Stanford Law School? Oh, I can see why
you know so much.' It drives me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agents will tell you what their guy averaged and how
much he helps the team and so forth, right, Kev? He clearly was on
a roll about one of his favorite topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know everything about basketball, and their basketball
background is none,'' he said. ``I'm thinking, `How can you be so
smart and never play?' But if they have leverage, the agents will
just try to kill you. If they have no leverage, they want to be
fair. My thing is, why don't we start out with being fair?''
</P>
<P>
   He recounted his recent negotiations with Bill Duffy, the agent
for Terrell Brandon. The Wolves re-signed Brandon for $60 million.
McHale and Duffy roomed at Minnesota and are close friends; when
McHale thought he was about to be drafted by Golden State, he
called Duffy, who was living in Northern California at the time,
and told him to clear out the guest bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked with Billy (about Brandon), I said, `Let's try
something unique: I won't lie to you, and you don't lie to me.' And
everything went smoothly,'' McHale said. ``But the problem is that
these guys all lie to you and you're forced to lie to them, and it
becomes a big B.S. fest.' One agent told me about his client. I
said, `What number is that guy? I haven't seen him. He's been on
our team for two years? I must have missed this guy. He plays on
our team and he does all this? That's pretty impressive. Where have
I been?' ''
</P>
<P>
   McHale has a new nucleus built around Kevin Garnett, who, he
says, does not share the selfish, me-first, how-many-did-I-score?
attitude of many of today's young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin loves to play, first of all,'' he said. ``A lot of these
guys love to get paid. I keep on telling them, `You're supposed to
love to play. I know it sounds like pay, but it's different.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a burning desire to be the best player in the
league,'' McHale said. ``I don't think he wants to accept anything
less than that. That's refreshing. It's fun to see a guy play that
way. He understands he's at a level where he's such a highly
talented, multidimensional player that he'll be judged on how his
team does, not how he does. When you understand that at an early
age, you become a lot better player. When your only focus is to win
the game, it's very easy to play. Then you're willing to do
whatever it takes to win that game. If your focus is to score 25
points, where does winning the game come into that? He's not into
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave's world
</P>
<P>
   McHale's various moves around the basket have become a staple on
the international scene. ``I've been really struck by that,'' said
his former boss, Dave Gavitt, whose travels take him to remote
outposts all over the world. ``Kevin's low-post repertoire is the
primer, worldwide. All those duck-unders and things he used to do,
they're studied internationally. It's an absolute primer on how to
do it, and it's amazing that one player could have such an
impact.'' Gavitt, by the way, said he did talk with McHale about
remaining in the Boston organization after retirement. McHale said
he might have stayed had anyone offered anything, but no one did.
``I wanted to talk him into waiting to make it official until the
season was behind us for a month,'' Gavitt said. (McHale, of
course, made it official on the floor of the Charlotte Coliseum
after the Celtics were eliminated by the Hornets.) ``But I had no
success with that. Kevin was Kevin. He wasn't going to step back.
Our ownership situation at the time was very unsettled, and I think
he looked at that and said, `No way.' He was really of a mind that
he wanted to go home. We knew Jack (McCloskey, the Wolves' GM)
wasn't going to stay around much longer, and I think it was just
more comfortable for him to go back home. With him and Larry
(Bird), it's harder to do it where you played. They both went back
to where they're from.'' . . . The man McHale keelhauled in the
1984 NBA Finals, Kurt Rambis, has a new job with his old team.
Rambis will be a front office adviser for the Lakers, focusing on
the business side. ``I want to get back into coaching,'' he said.
``But this will give me an opportunity to know the business
operations a little better. (Owner) Jerry Buss gave me this
opportunity to learn, and I'll continue to learn. I don't see how
that can be a bad thing.'' Asked about McHale's defense, Rambis
said, ``I wouldn't say he was up there as one of the top defenders
I faced. But I also wouldn't say stopping me was any great feat.''
. . . Free agent Rick Mahorn, meanwhile, is waiting for the phone
to ring. ``I'm not too stressed about it,'' he said. ``I'd love to
play one more year. I'd love to play up in Boston, to prove to
those young guys that you can be old and competitive.'' Mahorn
played for the Sixers last season, and Larry Brown loved his
locker-room presence. The Sixers have no room for him this year, it
seems. Mahorn said if he does not get a job, he'd like to get into
coaching, although a player/assistant position might be the best of
both worlds. ``That's basically what I was last year in Philly,
anyway,'' he said . . . The Celtics will christen Conseco
Fieldhouse, the retro/avant garde home of the Indiana Pacers.
Indy's home opener against Boston is Nov. 6. Of the five arenas
opening this year _ Philips Arena in Atlanta, American Airlines
Arena in Miami, Staples Center in Los Angeles, and the Pepsi Center
in Denver _ the Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis is the only one
opening with a basketball game. However, of those five arenas, only
Indiana's is not shared with a National Hockey League team. Still,
you've got to love Indy to open the building with a basketball
game. The only thing better would have been the Kingston Trio.
</P>
<P>
   Flunking one test
</P>
<P>
   While we noted McHale's many achievements and highlights this
past week, one of the lowlights was his inability to win the state
high school title. His senior-year team in Hibbing, Minn., advanced
to the title game against Bloomington-Jefferson, whose big man,
Steve Lingenfelter, had a cup of coffee in the NBA. Well, Hibbing
High had the lead at the half and couldn't hold it. McHale got into
foul trouble, and the picture on the front page of the Hibbing
paper the next day showed cheerleader Lynn Spearman in tears. She
eventually married McHale. ``At the time, it was one of the most
disappointing things that ever happened to me,'' McHale said. ``A
lot of stuff happened after that that put it in perspective.
Lingenfelter's mom was dying and she was at the game. He knew it.
The guys on the team knew it. We should have won, but other forces
were at work that day. We were a better team, but we didn't win.''
His high school coach and Hall of Fame presenter, Gary Addington,
remembers it the same way. ``Have I replayed that game? Many, many
times to see if I would have done things differently. That was one
of the great frustrations of my coaching career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
