<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL DAFOE REALLY GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps we have seen the last of Byron Dafoe in Boston black and
gold, but I don't think there are many people around here _ fans,
media, management, or Dafoe himself _ who believe that.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In disgust, Dafoe banged the table with his last possible trump
card last week, asking to be dealt, saying he had no alternative
when Boston boss Harry Sinden suggested a $4 million-a-year deal
could lead to the club's financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe hasn't been here long enough to receive Sinden's bankrupt
bombast with the same deaf ear that all of New England has learned
to apply by now. Of course, I'm not the one stuck between a $9
million and $12 million payday, so it's easy for me to chuckle at
it all. Sinden's assertion that Dafoe's dollars could lead the
Causeway cash cow to bankruptcy is nothing more than standard
Sinden posturing, in a sense a variety of British comedy (if you're
not sure it's a joke, just laugh, and keep on negotiating).
</P>
<P>
   Sinden now suggesting that the two sides hand the issue to an
arbitrator _ a process he has always loathed _ is proof that the
budget has room to meet Dafoe's figure. Otherwise, Sinden wouldn't
dare put his budget at risk, no matter how firmly he believes that
the arbitrator will side with management's figure.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, following the Dmitri Khristich situation, Sinden said
the arbitrator didn't understand terminology referring to teams
skating at full strength. Ouch. The next arbitrator might not
understand the term ``Stanley Cup winner.'' Then what? Dafoe gets
awarded $5.2 million a year?
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe and his agent, Ron Salcer, have one far better alternative
than seeking a trade or entering ``back-door'' arbitration: come
back to the table with focus, targeting a two-year contract, and
sit in the room until the deal is done. How bad could it be? Worst
case: two years, total $5 million plus incentives? Maybe better?
</P>
<P>
   Given the NHL calendar, a two-year deal would expire in about 18
months. Dafoe would be back at the table in the spring of 2001,
armed with the leverage that he would become an unrestricted free
agent only a year later. No-brainer. If he still has the goods, his
impending free agency and the natural spiraling inflation that is
built into the game should make him rich beyond imagination. And
again, that's only a year and a half down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Now, failing that, what happens? If Dafoe remains out, there's
true risk on both sides, because goalies too easily lose their
stuff (edge, magic, whatever you want to call it). A goalie in
mothballs quickly can become a dwindling, dated asset. We saw that
only last season with Felix Potvin, who sat out in a contract
dispute with the Leafs and ultimately got traded to the Islanders,
only to find he couldn't stop a beachball (11 games, 2-7-1, 3.66
goals-against mark) when he got back in net.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of others have lost it, even without sitting around to
atrophy. Let us not forget Blaine ``Let 'em in'' Lacher and, even
more frightening, ex-Vezina winner Jim Carey. Lacher is back in
Medicine Hat, Alberta, and when last contacted, he was happy to be
out of the puck-stopping business. He wasn't alone in that feeling.
Only 25 years old, Carey wasn't offered an invitation to anyone's
camp this fall and is now in Madison, Wis. (where his wife is
taking college classes), hoping that an employment opportunity
comes his way.
</P>
<P>
   According to his agent, ex-Bruin Brian Lawton, Carey had nibbles
from Carolina and Tampa Bay over the summer, but ultimately neither
club extended offers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton, reached Friday at his Minnesota office, was asked how
Carey was feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's he feeling? Oh, I don't think he feels great about the
whole thing,'' said Lawton. ``He's been down a rough road, and he
feels like he's been beaten up some. Those things can burn the
passion out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bought out by the Bruins last season when he was in Providence,
Carey was picked up by St. Louis, where he was 1-2-0 with a 3.86
GAA in four games. He got bought out there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Could Dafoe suddenly become another Lacher, another Carey? Not
likely. But who thought Potvin would be elite one day and in deep
retreat the next? Lacher was a key one minute, a Keystone Kop the
next. It can happen. And fast.
</P>
<P>
   From that perspective, the Bruins never will get more for Dafoe
in trade than today. From that perspective, perhaps the gregarious
goalie might want to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden has made hasty, emotional trades in the past. Tom Fergus
essentially asked out in October '85, when he said he wouldn't wear
the Boston sweater again, angered that Sinden refused to
renegotiate his contract (he was making $125,000 a year). Within
days, Fergus was dished to Toronto. In the exchange, the Bruins
acquired veteran pivot Bill Derlago, who lasted all of 39 games
before he was dealt to Winnipeg for Wade Campbell, a young
defenseman who ended up playing only 28 games in black and gold
over three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fergus, 23 when he left Boston, went on to play six-plus seasons
in Toronto, where he three times broke the 20-goal plateau, and he
finished up his NHL career with a couple of seasons in Vancouver
before a two-year farewell tour in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden believed at the time he was getting fair value in return.
History proved otherwise. From Boston's standpoint, it was a total
bust. Fergus also believed he'd be better off elsewhere. His money
improved, but he was never as effective as he was in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is in neither party's interest right now for Dafoe to go. The
Bruins almost assuredly wouldn't get equal value, and there are a
lot of teams in the Original 28 today that wouldn't offer Dafoe the
supporting cast he has right here in the Hub. He has to realize the
fact that, in part, he can boast strong numbers because of the
solid front-to-back defense that surrounds him. How do you suppose
his numbers would read in Nashville?
</P>
<P>
   Emotions have collided again on Causeway, leading Sinden to fall
back on his dyed-in-the-wool laments over his budget and sending
Dafoe into a pay-me-or-trade-me tizzy that puts him in an
impossible situation with the fans, few of whom can fathom what it
would be like to fret over such mountainous sums. Time for them
both to ask for a line change _ get Id, Ego, and Superego off the
ice _ and sit down with a realistic vision of what a two-year deal
should look like.
</P>
<P>
   Hawgood is back
</P>
<P>
   One of Boston's more entertaining alums, Greg Hawgood, caught on
with the Canucks (a one-year deal worth $450,000). Hawgie Hockey is
back. ``I have a different appreciation for it now,'' said Hawgood,
who started his career in the Hub and played a couple of years here
before being dealt to Edmonton for Rosie Ruzicka. ``I've been in
the NHL, gone to the IHL, back again now with Vancouver. When you
are away for a while, you just see things in a different way. A lot
of guys make decent money in the `I,' it's good, but it's not close
to the NHL. The money, really, doesn't matter to me as long as it's
fair, and the Canucks have been nothing but honorable and extremely
fair. There's really no such a thing as a bad contract in the
NHL.'' . . . Mixed results for a bunch of ex-Bruins looking to
catch on with training camp tryouts. It appeared Randy Burridge had
a job won with Detroit, but he was one of the Winged Wheels' final
cuts. Sandy Moger and Steve Leach failed to catch on with the
Penguins, although GM Craig Patrick expressed interest in finding a
spot for Leach in the minors, just to keep him around as insurance
(the role Leach filled late last season for the Coyotes). However,
Cam Stewart won a spot with the Panthers after convincing
management to give him a look with the condition that, if he didn't
crack the big lineup, he could return to Houston, where he was a
key contributor to the Aeros' IHL championship last season. But
Stewart's grittiness _ especially his willingness to work the
corners _ impressed head coach Terry Murray, and he'll start the
season on a line with Rob Niedermayer and Radek Dvorak. Stewart's
last fling in Boston was a 15-game run in the ill-fated 1996-97
season, leading him to Houston . . . The season opened Friday night
with 25 Group 2 free agents (similar to Dafoe) unsigned. That
doesn't include some previously highly compensated players who
remain in search of work: Ulf Samuelsson, Mark Tinordi, Joe Juneau,
Joe Murphy, Ray Sheppard, and Pat Verbeek. Sameulsson's chance of
landing back with the Rangers all but disappeared Thursday when the
Blueshirts acquired Kevin Hatcher for Peter Popovic. Hatcher will
pull down $3.1 million this season, as opposed to Popovic's $1.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Clymer hooks on
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Bruins draft pick Ben Clymer, selected 27th overall in the
'97 draft, took a tryout fling with Tampa Bay and Friday was
rewarded with a three-year deal that his agent, Lawton, said is
worth $2.5 million (slightly ahead of what the Bruins gave Nick
Boynton). According to Lawton, Boston never got beyond offering
Clymer, a 6-foot-1-inch, 200-pound defenseman, more than $100,000.
The Bruins were headed to arbitration with Clymer this fall (after
classifying him a defected player), but, according to Lawton,
finally released him as a free agent at the start of September.
Clymer will start the year with the Detroit Vipers (IHL) for
seasoning. ``I can't understand what Boston was thinking,'' said
Lawton. ``Ben really wanted to be a Boston Bruin, but for $100,000?
What choice did we have? I asked (assistant GM) Mike (O'Connell)
for something, anything, to get it done _ maybe $400,000 or
$500,000. I mean, a No. 27 pick for $100,000? But, hey, that's the
Bruins. I'd say they lost out, but they'd probably say they made
out best, if I know them.'' . . . Washington GM George McPhee, an
on-ice brat in his playing days, sucker-punched Chicago coach Lorne
Molleken following a Capitals-Blackhawks game last week in
Columbus, Ohio. McPhee felt Molleken loaded his lineup with thugs
and then delivered his objection with the poke to the coach's
kisser (leaving Molleken with lingering double vision). And you
thought ``Slap Shot'' was an exaggeration. The league cuffed McPhee
with a $20,000 fine and told him to stay away from his own team for
a month _ never mind anyone else's squad. Loved these remarks from
Blackhawks owner Bill Wirtz, good friend of ex-con Alan Eagleson:
``There's a code of conduct . . . You just don't do things like
this . . . The problem is, not enough people realize what this
whole game's about.'' Do you suppose Wirtz was reading from the
Europeans' postgame script at the Ryder Cup? Gentlemen, please, a
little etiquette. And, oh, game on!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
