<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTBREAK IN CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Their orange helmets are blank, making them the only
team in pro football without a logo on their heads. This is a
mistake. What the Cleveland Browns should do immediately is find a
picture of a teary-eyed blues singer and make that their official
emblem.
</P>
<P>
   If not that, the Browns should become the first team to have a
detailed hologram on their helmets. View it from one angle and
you'd see a happy couple holding hands. View it from another and
you'd see a lawyer between the couple trying to figure out who gets
the car and who gets the house.
</P>
<P>
   The heartbreak theme is a natural in this city. You know how
some people throw rice at the end of weddings? Not here. They
shower newlyweds with divorce lawyers' business cards, just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know. You don't have to tell me. I am miserable. I can't
help it. This happens every time I return to this city by Lake
Erie, 30 miles from my hometown. All the old memories will start to
circle me Sunday afternoon when the Browns play the Patriots at
Cleveland Browns Stadium. By 4 o'clock, when Drew Bledsoe will have
thrown for 400 yards and five touchdowns (47-10, Pats?), the
memories will have me pinned against a wall, taunting, ``Look,
chump. We'll never let you forget us. Never. Understand?''
</P>
<P>
   Forget? Please. Want to know how old I was when I first had my
heart broken by the Browns? Three, I think. I learned Al Green
lyrics before I learned my ABCs. My first writing assignment didn't
come in school; I think it was the following exchange with Ann
Landers.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ann:
</P>
<P>
   I am 3 years old. Most people in my family are Browns fans.
Because of this, they all trade depressing heartbreak stories.
Husbands come home, see their wives and say, ``What are you doing
here? I thought you would have left me by now.'' I don't want to
live like this. Ann, my love, take me away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bummed Out By The Browns &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bummed:
</P>
<P>
   It's too late. You're ruined. Stop stalking me.
</P>
<P>
   There still is plenty to like about Browns history. The great
Jim Brown spent his entire career here. By the time I was 10, I
could recite all of Brown's quirks, even though I never saw him
play. For example, he used to get up slowly after being tackled,
making people wonder if the hits had dazed him. He then would go
back to the huddle, take the ball on the very next play and flatten
a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brown, one of the game's top innovators, started the
franchise. If you think the war between Robert Kraft and Bill
Parcells is significant, you should have seen Brown-Art Modell.
Parcells went to coach an existing team when he couldn't get his
way. Brown founded a team _ the Bengals _ when he and Modell could
not coexist. If you approach a stranger in Cleveland and say you
love Paul Brown, you are almost guaranteed to have a peaceful
conversation. If you say you love Modell, there's a good chance you
will be the plaintiff and the stranger the defendant on ``Judge
Judy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Browns should have the climactic scene from ``Romeo
and Juliet'' on their helmets, a reminder of how close they have
been to bliss. They never have been to the Super Bowl. They thought
they were going after the 1986 season. A local band even took the
words from ``Louie, Louie'' and made ``Bernie, Bernie'' in honor of
quarterback Bernie Kosar. But John Elway drove the Broncos 98 yards
in the final minute of the fourth quarter to win the AFC
Championship game that year. The next year, in a conference title
rematch with the Broncos, running back Earnest Byner fumbled as he
was crossing the goal line and the Browns were denied again.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, the Browns always knew how to produce a coaching
drama that would twist your mind and confuse your heart. That's
because your overly sentimental heart told you, above all, that you
loved the team. But the facts were that Modell divorced himself
from established head coaches like Brown and Marty Schottenheimer
and raved about an unproven one, Bill Belichick, who was hated here
even after his team made the playoffs. I'll never forget stories of
fans burning their season tickets and picketing the team's offices
when news broke that Kosar was released by Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Modell tried to move the Browns in 1995. He couldn't. He moved
the team, but he was prevented from taking the name, colors, and
history. And even though he is a New Yorker, Modell is haunted by
Browns memories, too. If he is ever seen in the stadium, it won't
be Art imitates life; it will be more like Art running for his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, fans by the Great Lake of Heartbreak will
witness a different kind of pain. It's one thing to have your
dreams taken from you suddenly in a playoff game. But this Browns
season shows the cruelest way to crack a heart: You know the wins
won't come, but you still have to wait for the end of the season
for the emotional wreckage to be official. By January, the Browns
may have a couple of wins, but even the players know a win will not
come Sunday. The fans know it, too. You get that kind of insight
when you've been heartbroken for years.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this _ through baseball _ shortly after
arriving here this weekend. My grandmother, who still refuses to
forgive Jose Mesa for failing to protect a (Game 7) World Series
lead in '97, wanted me to watch the Indians-Blue Jays game with her
Friday night. The Indians had a 5-2 lead in that game. ``They're
going to lose,'' my grandmother said.
</P>
<P>
   They lost, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   I think a fractured-heart logo would look interesting on a
helmet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
