<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BC-NU-BOS &LR;      10-02 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-NU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT AN A-1 JOB BY BC? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston College's inability to win a football game in October
seemed as though it had become a rite of autumn. The last two
seasons, at the first sign of turning leaves and a chill in the
air, it seemed the Eagles would head south for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But not Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles (4-0) averted another October collapse by delivering
third-year coach Tom O'Brien his first BC victory in the month, a
hard-fought yet flawed 33-22 decision over Division 1-AA
Northeastern (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   Playing before an Alumni Stadium crowd of 42,032 on a
resplendent afternoon, the Eagles snapped an 0-for-8 October skein
with an effort that was good in some parts but certainly ugly in
the final summation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Northeastern a lot of credit,'' said O'Brien,
whose team travels to Philadelphia to play Temple next week. ``They
came in today and played an outstanding game. They did a good job
against us. Looking at our play, heck, obviously we didn't play
well. We didn't finish the game well.''
</P>
<P>
   The good part was that the Eagles scored 33 points, their most
so far this season. The bad part was that BC's offense, which
generated just one touchdown and 307 yards total offense (to NU's
401), gave away three fumbles and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   If the Eagles had not converted three of five Northeastern
turnovers into touchdowns _ Frank Chamberlin's 12-yard fumble
recovery, Ralph Parent's 15-yard return of a blocked punt, and
RaMon Johnson's 27-yard interception return _ BC likely would not
have survived its dogfight against the hungry Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we didn't play well today, but at the same time
they did a great job on defense,'' said BC junior quarterback Tim
Hasselbeck, who completed 11 of 26 passes for 113 yards and was
victimized by two interceptions (one in the end zone by Brian
Whitman) and three sacks (including two by Zach Falconer).
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tip your hat to them because of what they did. But
maybe it's a reality check for us a little bit, and maybe we're not
as good as we thought we were.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, it was apparent the Huskies had arrived not
only ready to play, but ready to win. William Griffin returned the
opening kickoff 58 yards to the BC 39 and, one play later,
quarterback Jason Quinlan found Dave Klemic with a 39-yard
touchdown on a flea flicker to give Northeastern a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to the game today and I told our seniors at the half,
that we're not coming for a moral victory,'' said NU coach Barry
Gallup, a BC graduate (Class of '69) and assistant under former
Eagles coach Jack Bicknell. ``We came to win the football game and
I am proud of our effort. We made some mistakes and they took
advantage of it, that's why they're 4-0.''
</P>
<P>
   After NU's flea flicker staggered BC _ ``I don't think it put
any more pressure on us, but it woke us up, that's what it did,''
said senior free safety Pedro Cirino _ the Eagles answered with a
10-play, 73-yard march that was highlighted by Hasselbeck's 34-yard
completion to Derrick Crittenden. The drive was capped one play
later by William Green's first collegiate TD on a 2-yard plunge.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time BC's offense would score on the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Senior John Matich rallied BC to a 13-7 lead by converting field
goals of 37 and 45 yards. But the Huskies went 71 yards in eight
plays to take a 14-13 lead on Quinlan's 1-yard plunge with 4:12
left.
</P>
<P>
   However Chris Hovan stripped freshman tailback Tim Gale and
Chamberlin recovered to score on a 12-yard return, enabling BC to
take a 20-14 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, and this is to take nothing away from Northeastern, we
played tight,'' O'Brien said. ``We dropped balls. We did things
that we don't normally do. I've been a part of this game where you
play Division 1-AA teams and there is something psychological about
it. These kids pressed.''
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless third quarter, the Eagles got two more scores
off turnovers when Parent gathered in Bessette's blocked punt and
scored a 15-yard TD that made it 26-14. Johnson seemed to put the
game out of reach with 8:49 left when he intercepted Quinlan (21 of
39, 205 yards, 2 interceptions, 1 TD) and scored on a 27-yard
return, but BC fumbles on two of its last three possessions
resulted in one last Northeastern score when Fred Vallett found
Michael Mack with a 24-yard pass with 3:26 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our team was just as up for this game as any other
game. You could see it in guys' faces in the locker room and you
could see it when they took the field,'' Hasselbeck said.
``Northeastern, their intensity was the same thing and they just
did a good job. Maybe Northeastern thought it had something to
prove, but they proved they're a good football team today, in my
eyes and everyone else's, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
