<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-EUROPEA     10-02 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-EUROPEANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS ARE NO ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The answer is: Miguel Angel Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Why did Europe win the Ryder Cup in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: It wasn't that celebration on the 17th green.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Why did the United States win the Ryder Cup in
1999?
</P>
<P>
   Now keep last week's competition fresh in your minds as we go
back two years to the shameless incident involving Martin. He had
earned a spot on the European Ryder Cup team, however disappointing
that was to captain Seve Ballesteros, who deemed Martin unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   So what a stroke of good fortune it was for Ballesteros when
Martin injured his wrist. The European captain seized the
opportunity, which became all the more important when Jose Maria
Olazabal could make it only to 11th in the standings. Ballesteros
demanded Martin prove to him he could play in mid-August, a month
before the matches at Valderrama, but Martin objected. He needed
more time.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, said Ballesteros, that proved Martin was not ready.
Hiding his smile, Ballesteros said it was unfortunate, but he would
have to dismiss Martin and elevate Olazabal. Shame on European Tour
officials for going along with it. With Olazabal a qualifier, the
captain could still pick Jesper Parnevik and Nick Faldo. The
Europeans won, though dignity was not part of the package, forsaken
at the expense of Martin's honor. Who can ever forget the two team
photos, one with, one without Martin?
</P>
<P>
   Move forward to 1999 and Justin Leonard's dramatics at The
Country Club's 17th hole. The pileup on the green was excessive and
in poor taste, and the Americans rightfully apologized. The
European players shouldn't be alone in their condemnation of the US
team's behavior; any dignified golf fan should be appalled.
Olazabal still had a makeable putt that could have halved the hole
(see: 1999 Masters, 13th hole on Sunday), so how in the name of
Robert Tyre Jones Jr. could we sink to a level of celebrating putts
that clinch at least a tie for a hole when the match is still on
the line?
</P>
<P>
   A British golf writer suggested Ben Crenshaw should have done
the sporting thing and conceded Olazabal's birdie putt. That would
have been an incredible measure given the circumstances (this was
not Jack Nicklaus-Tony Jacklin 1969, i.e. a short putt with the
outcome already decided), so it's understandable why such an act
was not taken.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Ballesteros's handling of the Martin affair, which
two years later still smells, the incident at the 17th green was
spontaneous, not calculated. It may have dropped a towel of bad
taste over the event, but it should not cover up this fact: The
Europeans had their hands on the Ryder Cup and dropped it like a
2-year-old trying to handle a wet glass.
</P>
<P>
   Mark James, bless his wit and personality, rode seven players
hard and gained a two-day lead, perhaps the only logical strategy
he had. Alas, the strategy backfired because five of them _ Lee
Westwood, Darren Clarke, Sergio Garcia, Parnevik, and Miguel Angel
Jimenez _ had nothing left for Sunday's singles; they won just one
hole each on the front. Europe could not let the US build momentum,
but it did, long before Leonard's putt at 17.
</P>
<P>
   There is much second-guessing that could be done. Why didn't
James put Colin Montgomerie out first or second to get a point
early and prevent the steamroll that evolved? Why put Garcia (he's
great, but he's still just 19) 11th, where there was too much
pressure on him? Why pick Andrew Coltart if you didn't have
confidence in him? Surely, Bernhard Langer or Faldo could have
offered something for a team match and allowed a stalwart to rest.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides are guilty of taking this precious event a bit
too far. The golf was sensational last Friday, Saturday, and
Sunday, and tens of thousands in person, and millions more on TV,
got to view a thrilling competition.
</P>
<P>
   It should concern all golf fans that we're spending too much
time talking about the behavior, not the play, inside the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance isn't bliss
</P>
<P>
   So what to make of all these complaints about spectators at The
Country Club? Only this: If you desire to be a major sport and
attract a wider audience (and governing bodies of golf everywhere
must answer yes on both counts), then you have to take the good
with the bad.
</P>
<P>
   The good being big TV contracts, and large, excited galleries,
97 percent of which are excellent.
</P>
<P>
   The bad being that 3 percent, like the moron who reportedly spit
at James's wife, Jane; those who hurled crude remarks at
Montgomerie; or the guy who stood near the 17th green in falling
darkness last Friday, heckling Tiger Woods and David Duval. No
Montgomerie basher was as rude as this guy standing there chanting
``0-for, 0-for, 0-for,'' as the American players were about to lose
their four-ball match with Westwood and Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   At first, there was pity among the crowd for Woods and Duval,
being heckled by a man who no doubt had stopped in at The Country
Club on his way to a WWF engagement. Faith was quickly restored
when some folks told the guy to shut up. He didn't, of course; but
thankfully he also didn't ruin a once-in-a-lifetime experience for
97 percent of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Pro tournaments are now attracting a larger number of spectators
who have never been to golf events. Players are learning to deal
with these sad souls (Montgomerie doesn't deserve it, nor does
Woods), but governing bodies can't expect to open up gates to
40,000 people and not get a handful who think they're at a hockey
or soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   Chef surprise
</P>
<P>
   One of the more pleasant Ryder Cup stories belongs to Frank
McClelland, owner and head chef of L'espalier on Gloucester Street
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It seems he got a call from Michael Jordan, who wanted to come
in with some friends for dinner Friday night. No problem, said
McClelland.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, however, Jordan called to say they weren't coming.
No problem, said McClelland, who praised the superstar for his
consideration: ``It was gracious of him to call before we had
started our dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, however, must have thought it an inconvenience, and he
wanted to make it up to McClelland. Would the restaurant owner like
to be Jordan's guest at the Ryder Cup?
</P>
<P>
   His reply? Yes, in a split-second, and at 7 Saturday morning, a
limo picked him up and took him to the house in Brookline that
Jordan was renting. McClelland, Jordan, and former NHL great Mario
Lemieux watched the morning portion of Saturday's competition (John
Elway had departed a day earlier).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to leave (for work) at 12:30, but I stretched it to
1:30, I was having so much fun,'' said McClelland.
</P>
<P>
   McClelland said he witnessed Jordan decline a TV interview and
shy away from autographs, not drawing a lot of attention to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there for fun, to be with his buddies and talk
sports,'' said McClelland. ``I thought it was remarkable that he
wasn't the spectacle. He didn't want to take away from the event.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, McClelland said he didn't want to impose upon Jordan,
so he never even asked to have a picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   He may get that chance, because Jordan told McClelland he'd stop
in for dinner when he's in town next time.
</P>
<P>
   Immortal words
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass grows greener, the trees bloom better, there is even
warmth in the rocks that you see about here. And I don't know,
gentlemen, but somehow or other the sun seems to shine brighter on
The Country Club than on any other place that I have seen.''
Crenshaw after the US rallied to win the Ryder Cup? No, that was
Francis Ouimet, addressing a crowd at the club's 50th anniversary
dinner, April 21, 1932 . . . The folks running this week's Dunhill
Cup have to be ecstatic. In the wake of the Ryder Cup, they get a
US team with Payne Stewart, Mark O'Meara, and Tom Lehman, not to
mention a Spanish contingent of Olazabal, Garcia, and Jimenez, the
English trio of James, Westwood, and David Howell, and Scotland's
entry of Montgomerie, Paul Lawrie, and Gary Orr. Pairings won't be
announced until Wednesday, but the delicious possibilities are
endless . . . Speaking of Olazabal, take a guess what he did on the
first hole Thursday at the German Masters? Yes, he drained a
30-footer for birdie . . . Small consolation for Europe: Its
youngsters dominated the Junior Match at New Seabury CC in Mashpee
last week. A mini-version of the Ryder Cup, the event featured 12
European teenagers (six boys, six girls) against a dozen of
America's finest. The US had won the previous two encounters, but
this time around it was a different story. Europe breezed, 10-2 . .
. Nice start to the collegiate golf career of Brent Wanner. The
Wake Forest freshman, out of Nauset Regional, has the best stroke
average (72.3) through two team events and helped lead the Demon
Deacons to a victory at the Cavalier Classic in Virginia. Indeed,
that match featured Wanner and James Driscoll, two of the more
heralded amateurs from Massachusetts recently. Wanner shot
71-71-72_214, tied for third at 2 under with Driscoll (70-71-73),
the University of Virginia senior from Chestnut Hill. At Johnson
City, Tenn., Wanner shot 73-72-72_217 to finish tied for fifth,
Wake Forest's top player, in the Ridges Intercollegiate Classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
