<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG A TRUE EVERYDAY PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Sunday's game probably won't be as compelling to New
Englanders as the three before it were. The consensus is that the
Patriots should throttle the expansion Browns and move on to Kansas
City next week for a real test.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday will be a special moment for Bruce Armstrong. When he
steps onto the grass of the new Browns Stadium, he will
freeze-frame the moment in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   It will be his 184th start, more than any other player in team
history. On the surface, that may not seem so extraordinary; but
consider that he will pass Hall of Famer John Hannah, arguably the
best offensive lineman ever to play in the NFL. Consider that 773
players are listed on the team's roster for the past 40 years, and
that Armstrong, 34, in his 13th season, has started every game he's
ever played in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me,'' said Armstrong. ``As an offensive
lineman, I'm not going to have any stats when I'm done, so it's
important to me that I've left a legacy here somehow. I feel I've
played at a high level for a long time, and so it's in the back of
my mind that I started in all of these games, more than anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a kid out of Louisville who was a 240-pound tight
end before Howard Schnellenberger converted him to tackle three
days into spring drills of his junior season. The last ``stats''
Armstrong had were the seven catches for 103 yards he made in his
first five games of the 1985 season at Louisville. Then the stats
stopped and the heavy lifting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches always tell you that your career could be over in
one play, but you don't really believe that until it almost happens
to you,'' said Armstrong. ``When you're younger, you don't ever
think about it or realize that you could be one play away from
never playing again. When it almost happens to you, you have a
better perspective of the game and when it does happen to and
you're able to make it back, you start to appreciate things and the
game more.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Armstrong suffered what appeared to be a
career-threatening knee injury during a Nov. 1 game at Buffalo, the
midpoint of the season. He missed the remainder of the season but
came back strong and started every game in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who played right tackle his first three years,
remembers 1987, his first season, when the Miami Dolphins, his
hometown team, came to play at Foxboro Stadium. The Patriots won
that game, 27-21. He remembers the tingles down his spine on Dec.
28 of that season, the final regular-season game, when he walked
into the Orange Bowl, a place that was hallowed ground for a kid
who had attended Central High in Miami. What followed was a
rare-for-the-time 24-10 win at the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was special and important to me because it was in
Miami,'' recalled Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, he has protected quarterbacks Steve Grogan, Doug
Flutie, Tony Eason, Marc Wilson, Tommy Hodson, Hugh Millen, Scott
Zolak, Scott Secules, and Drew Bledsoe. He's blocked for running
backs Tony Collins, Reggie Dupard, John Stephens, Mosi Tatupu,
Craig James, Robert Perryman, Marvin Allen, Terry Allen, Leonard
Russell, Jon Vaughn, Kevin Turner, Sam Gash, Marion Butts, Leroy
Thompson, Curtis Martin, Dave Meggett, Corey Croom, Robert Edwards,
Sedrick and Harold Shaw, Lamont Warren, and Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   He may have seen more people come and go than any other player
in Patriots history. But he remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I get the record for starts, I want to increase that to
200 games and beyond,'' said Armstrong. ``In this era of free
agency and because there isn't that much loyalty in the game any
more, with guys not spending so long on one team, it could be a
record that stands. The only one here who really has a chance to
break it is Drew.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe will be making his 94th start Sunday, about halfway to
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong got a new kick on life in the NFL in the offseason.
After a miserable '98 season, when he played with a fractured leg
all year and allowed 10.5 sacks, he wondered about his future. But
he decided that he was going to get into the best shape of his
life. When he walked into camp at Smithfield, R.I., he was at 290
pounds, his playing weight as a rookie. Now Armstrong speaks like
someone who will play out the remaining three years of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be overly retrospective at this point because
we're 3-0,'' he said. ``I'm really looking to play 2-4 more years.
The more games we win, the better I'm going to feel. Things are
good here right now. This team has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the game was fun again, Armstrong said, ``Now it is.
From this point on, it will be. I feel like I'm just getting
started. It's been 184 games, but for me right now, it feels like
my first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
