</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ONCOLLEGEFOOTBALL-BCEAGLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES HELD THAT (BOTTOM) LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are Tom O'Brien and you wake up Sunday morning with mixed
feelings abut your Boston College football team.
</P>
<P>
   You know a few facts.
</P>
<P>
   You are 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   You have won your first game in October, ending a winless streak
in the first full month of autumn that dated back to Oct. 19, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   You have just beaten cross-town neighbor and Division 1-AA
opponent Northeastern, 33-22.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, your stomach churns over the things that
you don't know as you prepare for the next two games, which most
people believe your team should win: at Temple, vs. Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   You worry about an offense that has been spotty all year. You
wonder about the psyche of a team that seems to need adversity to
perform at its best, such as coming from behind to win games
against Baylor, Navy, and most recently and surprisingly,
Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   You worry about a team that turned the ball over five times
against Northeastern, a performance that surely would have been
more costly against a more talented, more opportunistic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   You worry about the sloppiness _ penalties, breakdowns, and
other assorted misdeeds _ that made Saturday's game a contest
almost until the final gun.
</P>
<P>
   What most expected to be an Oktoberfest celebration of Eagle
superiority over a less-talented but not less-determined Husky team
turned into a nail-biting, upset-stomach type of game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relieved,'' was all BC athletic director Gene DeFilippo could
offer as a reaction after watching the Eagles get off to their best
start since 1992, when they opened 7-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo had as much reason as O'Brien to be concerned. He
scheduled the game, not only to promote college football in New
England, but to give O'Brien one more win in the quest for the
six-win minimum NCAA requirement to be bowl-eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Division 1-AA teams is often a no-win situation for
Division 1-A programs.
</P>
<P>
   If you win, the reaction is, ``So what. That's what's supposed
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If you play poorly, or heaven forbid, lose, then you can ruin a
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played 1-AA teams before,'' said O'Brien. ``I know what
that's about.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he knew now about his team that he didn't know a
week ago, O'Brien shook his head and grinned slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know more,'' he said. ``But it's of a negative nature.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is a typical reaction. Coaches worry, even
after the most impressive of wins, which was not the case against
Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien should worry. His team has played four games without
a loss and he still is not sure of what he has.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game should have an asterisk attached to it because
the Eagles did not have their normal pregame mindset. ``We played
tight,'' said O'Brien, acknowledging that his team read the papers
and listened to the talk about how the heavily favored Eagles
should blitz a Northeastern team that wasn't even .500 at the 1-AA
level, entering the game with a 1-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   But Northeastern coach Barry Gallup had a lot of good things
going for him, including a game plan that included trick plays
(resulting in a first-offensive-play touchdown on a flea flicker)
and an underdog feeling that relaxed his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something psychological about it (playing 1-AA
teams),'' said O'Brien. ``They (the Eagles) thought they were
supposed to kill them. I tried to tell them that those things
weren't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't. Had the Eagles played Navy, Temple, Rutgers, or
any other 1-A team on their schedule this season and gotten the
same result, the Eagles probably would have had more of a sense of
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   But instead there was more a sense of relief from everyone
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outplayed us in pretty much every aspect of the game,''
said BC safety Pedro Cirino. ``We were lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky and good enough.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien knows that as much as anyone. But he also knows the
bottom line is etched in ink, not pencil.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week from now, all that matters is that we're 4-0,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. When November arrives and the victories are tallied,
this win will be just as important as the win over Rutgers a week
ago or any future victories the Eagles might post in their quest
for a bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the way we played,'' O'Brien said. ``I'm
ecstatic that we won.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all that really matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
