<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ONBOXING-MICKYWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARD A WARRIOR IN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ As Micky Ward rose to meet the night's final
challenge and possibly his career's last chance Friday, there was
no mistaking who he was.
</P>
<P>
   With a 2-inch gouge out of his left cheek and with a deep cut on
the edge of his lip, one didn't need a trained eye to understand
his profession.
</P>
<P>
   On wobbly legs a warrior stood, bloodied but unbowed. Resolute
but reeling. Tired but tireless. At that moment, with 1,801 people
screaming inside a smoky arena, Micky Ward stood to fight.
</P>
<P>
   No one could mistake what he was.
</P>
<P>
   Across the ring, a man from Maryland named Reggie Green stood to
do the same. Holding a lead on the cards of two judges and the
belief that he could survive Ward's assaults for one more round,
Green ached from a pounding to the ribs and kidneys but his head
was clear and his heart strong.
</P>
<P>
   His chest heaving, Green also was at the point of exhaustion,
but he was different from Ward. Both had come to a spanking new ice
hockey rink to stand nearly naked and fight for their lives, but
there was one small difference. In a sport of desperation and
delusion, Ward had more of both than Green.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime fight trainer and boxing commentator Teddy Atlas knew
what he was looking at. He knew what was in the hearts of these men
and what was deeper. More important, he knew the price each had
paid and would continue to pay long after Ward dramatically saved
his career and his self-image with one last crushing hook to the
body that undid Green and a final flurry that ended the fight with
only 20 seconds to spare when one final hook to the head that came
from the only place Ward could summon it drove Green into
helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That truly was fighting,'' Atlas said after Ward stopped Green
at 2:40 of the 10th round to keep alive faint hopes of a last title
shot. ``That was not entertainment. That was not business. That was
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a barbaric thing at the core of it. It ain't always
pretty but it's real. Like the mobsters say, that was a real guy up
there. When it came down to what a fighter is about, Micky Ward was
it. That is what a fight is and you don't see it too often no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the first time your parents took you to the zoo
and they said, `That there is a lion,' and you look and he roars
and you think, `Yeah, that's a lion.' Tonight, if you never been
there before, that was a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fighter had carried the day but two fighters had been in
there. Two men who knew bravery and a mastery of brutal skills. Two
fighters in a place where only one could survive and it was the kid
from Lowell, Mass., who is a kid no longer who did.
</P>
<P>
   Ward (34-9) turns 34 this week, a fighter past his prime but one
whose heart had remained robust through more trials than most
athletes could endure.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, two fistic accountants named Oscar De La Hoya and
Felix Trinidad boxed for millions in Las Vegas but they never
fought. De La Hoya was paid more than $23 million and took the
final four rounds off.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad earned $8.5 million and did less fighting in 12 rounds
than Green or Ward did in two. Ward was paid $15,000 before
everyone else took a piece of his blood money and Green got $20,000
before the same thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Micky and Reggie are guys who need managers,'' Atlas said.
``Guys like De La Hoya and Trinidad need accountants. There's an
urgency about what they do. There's no list of options for them.
The only option is to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other thought than getting through tonight. It's
not about a moral victory and `I fought a good fight.' Not if you
come from where (Ward) comes from. It's about winning because if he
don't, it's back to `almost' again and almost ain't good enough
when you got no other options.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the will,'' Ward said. ``He dazed me once, but with my
heart I wasn't going down. I knew the body shots were getting to
him. Even the ones on the elbows (that were blocked) were takin' a
price. I think he just said, `Enough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The price Ward was willing to pay showed when it was over and he
sat bleeding and exhausted in his locker room. Then even the touch
of a water bottle to his lips caused him to wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some stitching to do tonight, Micky,'' Dr. Brian
Claussen said after he had peeled Ward's lip back to expose a wide
gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighter had won. His career was alive. But the pain was
there, too, and it would not go away as fast as the small money
he'd earned enduring it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're remarkable!'' screamed Hall of Fame trainer Angelo
Dundee, who had worked another fighter's corner earlier in the
evening. ``That was magnificent!''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Dundee left for an Italian restaurant to
dine with friends. Ward left for a hospital with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, even the Fighter has to leave the arena and go to a
hospital. Pain waits for him there just as it was waiting for Green
when he got back to his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The pain would be there long after the fans and most of the
money had disappeared, but they can live with that. It was a choice
they made long ago, the first time they chose to do what few people
can.
</P>
<P>
   To be lions for an evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
