<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     10-02 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 10)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; VIRGINIA WOOLF &LR;  By Hermione Lee. Vintage, $18. This biography,
selected by the editors of the Book Review as one of the best books
of 1997, rescues Woolf from her iconic stature and restores her to
human dimensions. The result is ``a book worthy of its subject _
graceful, astonishingly well researched,'' Daphne Merkin wrote in
The New York Times Book Review. ``Brimming with intelligence and
excitement, it sets before us the idea of an electric mind, of
indisputable greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FARMING OF BONES &LR;  By Edwidge Danticat. Penguin, $12.95.
This sobering novel by a Haitian-American writer takes place on the
island of Hispaniola in 1937, when the longstanding hostility
between Haiti and its neighbor, the Dominican Republic, threatens
to erupt into bloodshed. The narrator is a young Haitian servant in
a Dominican household, whose small personal world is shattered when
the country's Haitian minority is targeted for slaughter.
``Danticat knows the value of understatement in bringing
nightmarish scenes to life, and a spare, searing poetry infuses
many of the book's best passages,'' Michael Upchurch wrote in The
New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY DOG TULIP &LR;  By J.R. Ackerley. New York Review, $12.95. In
recalling his shared life with an elegant German shepherd,
Ackerley, a British writer and editor, unsentimentally portrays two
distinct personalities and two species. ``It is also a love story,
with all the hard truths, anguish and heightened sensibility that
such is likely to contain,'' Gene Baro wrote in 1965. ``A
masterpiece of empathy, this book is likely to be read again and
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; MY FATHER AND MYSELF &LR;  ($12.95),
an account of Ackerley's distant relationship with his father, who
led a secret double life, and his own struggle for identity as a
gay man. ``Written in lucid, exact prose,'' the memoir is
``constructed with the greatest skill, planned like an elaborate
mystery story,'' Michael Holroyd wrote in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TWO CITIES &LR;  By John Edgar Wideman. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$13. This novel is about two wounded souls who fall in love under
the pressure of urban warfare in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.
``Through Wideman's masterly narrative the reader learns how to
accept hopelessness without giving up hope,'' Walter Mosley wrote
last year. ```Two Cities' is as enjoyable as it is important.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GIRL IN THE FLAMMABLE SKIRT: Stories &LR;  By Aimee Bender.
Anchor/Doubleday, $11.95. Many of the young heroines in this
insouciant first collection are single and not too happy about it,
even if they don't quite know what to expect from men or from life
itself. ``Bender's stories are powered by voice ... and a
restrained sauciness,'' Lisa Zeidner wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING OF THE WORLD: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of an American
Hero &LR;  By David Remnick. Vintage, $13. The author blends athletic
and political history as he traces the arc of Ali's life inside and
outside the ring, from hyperconfident youth to ecumenical spiritual
ambassador. ``It doesn't read like the case history of a man ...
but of a comic and cosmic superman,'' Budd Schulberg wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THIS BLOODY MARY IS THE LAST THING I OWN: A Journey to the
End of Boxing &LR;  by Jonathan Rendall (Ecco, $15), a British boxing
fan tells of his troubled love affair with the sport, both as a
journalist and as an adviser to the featherweight champion Colin
``Sweet C'' McMillan. In 1998 one critic called this ``a little gem
of a book, immensely readable, laugh-out-loud funny and intensely
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERTRUDE OF STONY ISLAND AVENUE &LR;  By James Purdy. Quill/Morrow,
$13. In the author's 16th novel, an aging Chicago woman researches
the life of her dead daughter, a famous artist whose flamboyant
sexuality was a source of mystery to her emotionally estranged
mother. ``Purdy is a powerful writer'' and a ``singular American
visionary,'' Bruce Bawer wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HEART OF THE ANTARCTIC: Being the Story of the British
Antarctic Expedition, 1907-1909 &LR;  By Ernest Shackleton. Carroll &AMP;
Graf, $16.95. The explorer chronicles his voyage in search of the
south magnetic pole, a harrowing journey that brought him within 97
miles of his goal. His illustrated narrative ``is unquestionably of
great scientific value, but it is primarily a story _ a story whose
realism, never forced, is so poignant as to make a Jack London tale
look pale and anemic in comparison,'' The New York Times wrote in
1909.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UTZ &LR;  By Bruce Chatwin. Penguin, $11.95. Kaspar Joachim Utz is a
cultivated Mitteleuropa aristocrat imprisoned in his apartment in
Communist Prague by his priceless collection of Meissen china
figurines amassed during World War II. ``This short novel ...
represents Chatwin at his most erudite and evocative,'' Robert
Stone wrote in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPOSSIBLE SAINTS &LR;  By Michele Roberts. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$13. The unusual tale of St. Josephine is alternated with brief
accounts of 11 other female saints. The result is a ``fascinating
novel'' that suggests ``that everyday life is both more sacred and
more bizarre than we might imagine,'' David Guy wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
