<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL HURT AS YANKS CLINCH HOME-FIELD ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ One game remains in the regular season
and the American League playoffs are set to begin Tuesday, and the
Yankees have been pushing hard, to play better, to win enough games
for the home-field advantage. But Paul O'Neill's galloping pursuit
of a foul fly Saturday night ended in a collision with a wall and
O'Neill on the ground in pain.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill bruised his right side and lower back and left the game
grimacing; it's too early to know how the injuries will affect his
swing or his mobility. But the Yankees (98-63) do know they will
possess home-field advantage throughout the American League
playoffs, a right they earned Saturday night after edging Tampa
Bay, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the Yankees will play Texas in the best-of-5
division series, but there remains a chance they could face
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who the Yankees play, Orlando Hernandez will pitch
Game 1 Tuesday, Andy Pettitte will start Game 2 Thursday, and Roger
Clemens and David Cone are scheduled to throw Games 3 and 4,
respectively. Hernandez would pitch if a fifth game became
necessary. Torre told his starters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two more milestones were achieved in Saturday night's game:
Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center fielder, drew his 100th walk
of the season, making him the first Yankee since Lou Gehrig to
accumulate 200 hits and 100 walks in the same season. The victory
was the 400th of manager Joe Torre's tenure with the team; only
twice before have the Yankees won 400 games in a span of four years
_ they won 408 from 1961 to 1964, and 409 from 1936 to '39.
</P>
<P>
   Cone shut out the Devil Rays through five innings Saturday
night, allowing just one hit. But in the bottom of the sixth
inning, umpire Joe Brinkman replaced Derryl Cousins behind home
plate after Cousins pulled a muscle in his back. Cone's domination
quickly stopped: he walked four in a span of six hitters, the
Yankees' 3-0 lead shrank to 3-2 and Cone was removed with one out
and the bases loaded. Cone seethed as he departed, after
questioning Brinkman about some calls.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley relieved Cone and retired Bubba Trammell on a
short line drive to left, with the runner at third holding. Herbert
Perry worked the count full, and Grimsley was one pitch away from
walking home a run, one pitch away from losing the lead, one pitch
away from ending any chance Cone would get his 12th victory.
</P>
<P>
   Perry lifted a long foul down the right-field line, the ball
angling toward the stands, and O'Neill charged for the catch,
knowing that an out would end the inning. The ball fell out of his
reach, O'Neill brushed against a fence in front of the stands that
is about four feet high, lost his balance, spun around _ and
slammed onto his right side on the edge of the wall. He then
slumped to the ground, holding his torso.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's teammates, Torre and the Yankees trainer Gene Monahan
rushed to check on him, and O'Neill stayed on the ground for
several minutes before walking off the field without assistance,
but in apparent pain. Grimsley got out of the inning, and the
relievers who followed maintained the lead, but the Yankees' first
concern was for O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has the best record of all members of the Yankees'
rotation, at 17-9, and all year, he has been Torre's most
consistent starter. He registered quality starts (three runs or
less in six or more innings) in 23 of 33 games, which is among the
highest percentages in the AL. And Torre constantly mentions
Hernandez's exceptional performance in Game 4 of the AL
Championship Series last year, when, on 15 days of rest, Hernandez
pitched a spectacular and precise game to beat Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said: ``It was a big surprise, because of the
established pitchers we have around here. I'm pretty happy. I'm
pretty excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte seemed to be the front-runner to pitch the second game
all along, because Yankee Stadium always has favored left-handed
starting pitchers, and Pettitte has never been comfortable pitching
in Texas, where he and much of his family resides.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had always been the ace of whatever team he pitched for
in the past. But Clemens has been erratic this year, sometimes
dominating, often struggling for his command, particularly in the
early innings. Torre considered starting Clemens in Game 1 because
of his stature, and because Torre could better regulate Clemens'
rest. Clemens generally pitches better with four days' rest, and
now he will have eight.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has always been a pitcher Torre has relied on to pitch the
crucial Game 3 _ in the World Series of 1996, in the playoffs and
World Series last year. But Cone will start Game 4, and if the
unexpected happens and the Yankees are swept in the division
series, they would do so without Cone throwing a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a sweep was on Cone's mind Saturday, after he
spoke with Torre. ``I hope I don't have to pitch in the first
round,'' said Cone, referring to the chance the Yankees would win
the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Joe can go wrong,'' Cone added. ``We would have
to feel good about the fact that in Game 3 and Game 4, Roger
Clemens and me would be going.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
