<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH FERN WINS YELLOW RIBBON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ The Breeders' Cup finally gets in the spirit of Title
IX this year, running a $1 million turf race for fillies and mares
on its championship program Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park near Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It's a change that comes not a moment too soon for Bobby Frankel
and his latest turf starlet, an Arab-owned 4-year-old filly named
Spanish Fern who knocked off the big names under a timely ride by
Chris McCarron in the $500,000 Yellow Ribbon Stakes before 37,292
fans at Santa Anita on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel trained consecutive female turf champions Possibly
Perfect, Wandesta and Ryafan earlier in the decade _ and said he
``should have had four with Toussaud'' _ but had nowhere to run
them in the Breeders' Cup. That's one reason the 58-year-old Hall
of Famer is 0 for 30 on the richest day of the thoroughbred season.
</P>
<P>
   But if Spanish Fern is as good as she looked Saturday in running
the fastest Yellow Ribbon in seven years and leaving Fiji, Tuzla
and Tranquility Lake out of the money, she just might help Frankel
break through in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had (foot injuries) at Hollywood and then she got sick on
me,'' Frankel said of Spanish Fern, who beat Caffe Latte by 1\
lengths, covered 1\ miles in 1:59.52, and seemed to earn a
Breeders' Cup trip. ``But everything happened for the best, because
I have a fresh filly for the end of the year and that's where the
money is anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Spanish Fern, coming off a troubled third in Del Mar's Ramona
Handicap, rallied from second to last in a field of seven fillies
and mares under McCarron, who took over from Alex Solis (out of
town) and Kent Desormeaux (injured).
</P>
<P>
   Fiji, the 1998 female turf champion making her first start of
'99, having been held out with a muscle pull and illness, ran an
understandably tiring sixth under Jerry Bailey. Trainer Neil
Drysdale said Fiji will use the Oct. 15 Vinery First Lady Stakes at
Keeneland as a further Breeders' Cup prep.
</P>
<P>
   The mild upset by Spanish Fern ($7.40) helped to produce a
carryover on a day when the Oak Tree association guaranteed a $1
million pick-six pool. Fans bet $978,261 and an insurance company
made up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everybody's ticket was dead after the first pick-six
race, when Santovito sprang an $84.20 surprise under Eddie
Delahoussaye, riding for the first time since a Del Mar shoulder
injury. Favorites wound up 0 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   After the $9,260 payoffs for fans picking five of six, the
carryover for today's 12:30 card is $561,810.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Alex Solis rode Ecton Park ($8.80) to victory in the
Super Derby and odds-on Menifee made it an exacta for trainer
Elliott Walden in Louisiana Downs' $500,000 race for 3-year-olds.
Ecton Park, 12th in the Kentucky Derby, won his first Grade I in a
near-track-record 2:00.59 for 1\ miles. ``The key was the
(stalking) position Alex had,'' Walden said.... Bonapartiste (Chris
McCarron) is the 5-2 morning-line favorite for today's Oak Tree
Turf Championship.... Winning aboard Golden Tassel at Santa Anita
on Saturday moved Laffit Pincay within 40 of Bill Shoemaker's
career-record 8,833.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      10-02 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS IMPROVE POSITION WITH WIN OVER PIRATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their fate and mood had been flipped end over end in
little more than 24 hours, the New York Mets solemnly staring
elimination in the face and then suddenly sticking their tongues
out like disobeying children who refuse to go to bed when they're
told.
</P>
<P>
   With a feisty resurgence as stunning as the collapse that
necessitated it, and a brilliant pitching performance by one of the
players haunted by last year's collapse, the Mets beat the Pirates,
7-0, Saturday night and are _ unbelievably, incredibly _ tied with
Cincinnati for the wild-card spot heading into Saturday
regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   The byzantine mathematics of baseball have suddenly turned in
the Mets' favor: there is only one scenario by which they will be
eliminated Sunday: if they lose and the Reds win. If the Mets win
and the Reds, who have lost three in a row, lose Sunday, or if both
win and Houston loses to create a three-way tie, the Mets will have
grasped the wild card like someone who has fallen off a cliff only
to spot a tree branch on the way down. If Houston wins and the Reds
and Mets are tied at the end of the day, they will play a one-game
playoff in Cincinnati on Monday at 2:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the team meetings, the lineup shake-ups, the forlorn
Bobby Valentine's statement that he should be fired if the Mets
don't make the playoffs seem quaint, as if they occurred in another
era. Perhaps they did.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets have not exactly battered opposing teams to get
back in the race, they are playing with a renewed vigor and
confidence, and they are getting otherworldly pitching, all
jet-propelled by the slight missteps of the Reds and Astros,
slippages that were just long enough to allow the Mets to catch
them.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the Mets' treacherous slide into near oblivion,
their starting pitching kept them from being humiliated in every
game as the offense wallowed in a miserable slump. Saturday night,
Rick Reed, who only a month ago seemed in danger of losing his spot
in the starting rotation after coming off the disabled list with a
finger injury, was utterly dominant, giving one of the most
masterly _ and most critically timed _ pitching performances of the
season and, probably, the greatest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Reed lost one of the games during the collapse that kept the
Mets from winning the wild card almost exactly a year ago, and he
had been miserable about it during the winter. And Reed seemed
unhappy again when Valentine was less than enthusiastic about his
mediocre first starts back from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed has been superb in his last three starts. Against
Atlanta Sept. 21, Reed held the Braves to just one run _ a Chipper
Jones homer _ but the Mets lost when Dennis Cook gave up Jones'
second homer of the game. At Philadelphia last weekend, Jones
allowed just three runs on three hits, but the Mets were, by that
time, frantically tight and unable to hit with men in scoring
position, and Reed took the 3-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   None of that compared with Saturday night, though. Using a
dazzling curveball and a fastball clocked near 90 mph, Reed had
complete command of this game. He struck out 12 _ his previous best
this season was six _ allowed just three hits and gave up no walks
in the complete game for his 11th victory. He struck out the side
in the third, and, at one point, he got four of the five hitters he
faced to strike out looking.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a Keith Osik pop-up that Rey Ordonez ranged into
shallow center to grab in the fifth, just one out was recorded in
the outfield through seven innings. Reed allowed just one base
runner after the fourth inning. When it briefly appeared as if
Valentine was going to pinch-hit for Reed in the bottom of the
eighth _ Matt Franco was in the on-deck circle warming up to
pinch-hit for Melvin Mora before Reed jogged to the plate _ the
crowd booed.
</P>
<P>
   And they went positively berserk when Reed stroked a two-run
single that gave the Mets a 4-0 run lead. After Reed scored the
Mets' fifth run, he finished off the ninth to pitch just the fourth
complete game of the season for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets do make it to the playoffs _ and is everyone's
stomach turning from this roller-coaster ride? _ they will go in
with a suddenly strong rotation. They needed 119 games to get their
first complete game, but, with the season hanging in the balance,
the pitchers have given the Mets four straight spectacular
performances in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Mets have halted their skid, they have been
unable to score bunches of runs. Except for Wednesday's thrashing
of Greg Maddux, which ended with a 9-2 victory, the Mets had not
scored more than three runs since they beat Philadelphia, 8-6, on
Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   If they do make it to the playoffs, the lack of production will
be a cause for concern. Against Pirates starter Francisco Cordova,
who had an 11.57 earned run average in his two previous starts
against the Mets this season, the Mets were 0-5 with runners in
scoring position through the fifth inning. Particularly painful was
the second inning, when the Mets had the bases loaded with just one
out. But Ordonez and Reed grounded out to end the inning, and the
Mets did not have another serious threat until Aramis Ramirez
committed a throwing error that ignited the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud walked to being the inning, and Mike Piazza followed
with a broken-bat chopper that Ramirez fielded. Perhaps distracted
by the bat shard flying toward him, Ramirez overthrew second base,
and both Olerud and Piazza were safe. Then Robin Ventura, hobbled
by a bad knee and slumping at the plate, came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   He had the game winning hit Friday night _ the hit that may go
down as the one that saved the season _ and now, he stroked a
doubled off the right field wall to score Olerud. After Darryl
Hamilton lined out and Roger Cedeno was intentionally walked,
Ordonez hit a looper to Kevin Young at first. Young fielded the
ball, and looked up to see Piazza way off third base. Young threw.
_ all the way to the camera pit in foul territory. Piazza, who
would smack a home run _ his 40th _ in the eighth, furiously ran
home for the 2-0 lead. Two errors, two runs. No great bombast, but
good enough to allow the Mets to not only exhale, but to puff out
their chests a bit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
