<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVILS-THRASHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS RUIN DEBUT OF THRASHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The National Hockey League returned to this city
Saturday night for the first time since 1980 with a team named the
Thrashers. The new team was introduced amid fireworks and was met
with a rousing ovation from a sellout crowd at newly built Philips
Arena in its season opener, against the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The electrifying atmosphere from the opening ceremony continued
into the opening face-off, which the Thrashers won thanks to the
experienced Ray Ferraro, who played for the Islanders and the
Rangers. It was also fitting that the Thrashers got the first goal
in their history from their captain, Kelly Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   But the Thrashers played like an expansion team for the majority
of the game and lost, 4-1, to the Devils, who were rather sloppy
defensively in the first two periods and at times looked as
disorganized as the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik had two goals and Krzysztof Oliwa and Sergei Brylin
had one goal each for the Devils, who played much better in the
final period and dominated play during that session.
</P>
<P>
   Oliwa opened the scoring 8 minutes 58 seconds into the second
period when he intercepted a pass in Atlanta's zone. Holik gave the
Devils a 2-0 lead 40 seconds later before Buchberger beat Martin
Brodeur just under two minutes later to pull the Thrashers to
within 2-1 to the delight of the crowd of 18,545.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Devils' four rookies on their 23-man roster played
and left good impressions, especially Scott Gomez, who played left
wing on the team's first line with center Jason Arnott and right
wing Petr Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden and Brian Rafalksi were the other rookies who
played. Madden was the left wing on the Holik line, which had Randy
McKay on the right wing, and Brian Falaski was paired on defense
with the team captain, Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have traditionally done well in the regular season in
the '90s. Last season they earned 105 points. It was the fourth
time in the last five seasons that the team reached the 100-point
mark. They have been the Eastern Conference winners in the regular
season for the last two seasons, but they were eliminated both
times in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This was the third consecutive opener on the road for the
Devils. Last season's opening-day loss in Chicago remained etched
in coach Robbie Ftorek's memory. Ftorek spoke of his unhappiness
about that loss all season, even during the playoff series with
Pittsburgh that led to the Devils' early exit.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek puts as much value on games early in the season as he
does on games in the spring. He learned that from Jacques Lemaire
after the Devils failed to make the playoffs the season following
their 1995 Stanley Cup triumph. Lemaire went through such agony for
missing the playoffs that he decided that making the playoffs is
just as important as winning the championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
