<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      10-02 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN GAINS STEAM, BUT
 STILL LONG SHOT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By JEFF BARKER 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  WASHINGTON _ John McCain wasn't just
kicking off his presiden tial campaign last week, he was
celebrating his rise to the top of the pack of GOP candidates who
aren't named George W. Bush.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all he had to celebrate, though, McCain still had this to
ponder: There are a hundred ways for Bush to win the nomination.
For McCain, there are just a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain is playing his cards as best as anybody
could,'' said former Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods. ``The
problem is he's not holding many cards.''
</P>
<P>
   To blunt the Texas governor's enor mous fund-raising advantage,
Mc Cain must reduce the playing field to manageable, early primary
states. There, Bush's national resources don't mean as much, and
McCain can maneuver while his opponent is still lumbering into
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is like a big, unwieldy battleship, said Dan
Schnur, McCain's communications director: ``Before it can get out
into the open sea and use all of its firepower, it's got to get
through some very narrow straits, New Hampshire and South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in those straits that McCain, with precisely targeted
campaigns aiming to be lighter and faster in the water, hopes to
outmaneuver Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hope is that a win or near-win in New Hampshire in
early February, followed by a South Caro lina victory soon
afterward, would knock Bush off stride.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Democratic nominee Walter Mondale in 1984, who had time
to recover from an early challenge by upstart Gary Hart, Bush might
be unable to rebound. That's because the key 2000 primaries are com
pressed into a narrow, six-week window ending in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he is still afloat after South Carolina, however, it's
uncertain whether McCain could muster suffi cient resources as the
battle broad ened into larger states that would include California
on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Success itself could pose another problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Bennett, a New Hampshire independent pollster, says McCain
could conceivably become next year's John Anderson, the independ
ent candidate who caught the na tional eye in 1980 by surging
unexpectedly in New Hampshire and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, so now the (1980) campaign shifts to Illinois,'' said
Bennett, who was on Anderson's staff. ``I was in the headquarters
in Rockford, and here's a roomful of checks that have come in over
the weekend because of Massachusetts, and you don't have the staff,
you don't have the where withal to process the checks to get the
money to do what you have to do. Literally, there was a closet full
of checks, and they had people doing it 24 hours a day, but it just
wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   So it could go for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say he does well in New Hamp shire, and he does well in South
Carolina,'' Bennett said. ``Then what? How does he do well against
Bush, who has been organizing constantly?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign aides said in response that contributions can
be processed much faster these days and that, unlike Anderson, they
would have a reservoir of funds to draw upon.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has more than $5 million on hand and is hoping to raise
$15 mil lion to $20 million overall. Bush has already accumulated
$56 million.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's other winning scenario hinges on a possible stumble by
Bush, who hasn't held a federal office. At the least, McCain hopes
that voters, when they begin to focus more closely, won't accept
the inevi tability of Bush's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone has a chance of beating Bush now, it's John
McCain,'' na tional Republican pollster Frank Luntz said in an
interview. ``Just as Democrats are giving a second look to Gore and
Bradley, at some point Republicans are going to give a second look
to Bush and McCain. McCain would get a second look because he is a
genuine war hero and very courageous politically, and that's what
the public is looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Give this to McCain: His campaign has now become credible enough
that reporters on his chartered jet to New Hampshire last week
began to ask each other whether the Arizonan might actually have a
shot. The answer appeared to be ``Yes, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Like a road-weary traveler, McCain's strategy will simply be to
make it home. The Arizona primary will beckon on Feb. 22, if McCain
can survive in the race that long.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, a McCain staff member years ago who now admits to having
``mixed feelings'' about the senator, doesn't believe McCain will
make it. Woods hasn't endorsed anyone, but he has helped Elizabeth
Dole and says he likes Bush ``a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an analogy,'' Woods said. ``We're getting ready to
run the Triple Crown, and George W. Bush is Secretariat. He's going
to run wire to wire. And you keep saying, if he trips, those two
(McCain and Dole) are 200 yards back.''
</P>
<P>
   Early polls show McCain trailing Bush in Arizona. The sometimes
fiery senator, a former Naval aviator and Vietnam prisoner of war,
has vowed that he would not lose his home state, his competitive
instincts doubtless stoked by Gov. Jane Hull's endorsement last
week of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods, as well as many pundits and politicians who support
other candidates, have credited Mc Cain with running a smart
tactical campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, criticized by some strat egists for skipping the Iowa
Straw Poll in August, turned it into a positive by citing ``the
absurd amount of money'' spent by the candidates to get their
voters out to the poll. It all dovetailed with McCain's theme that
big money is ruining the political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John McCain's running the smartest campaign of any of
the Republican contenders,'' said Doug Wilson, national political
director of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council. Wilson, an
Arizonan, ran the 1996 Democratic Coordinated Campaign that
designed the state's strategy for Clinton-Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain team says its goal is simply to survive each round.
</P>
<P>
   The race, according to Schnur, re sembles the NCAA Basketball
Tour nament. Candidates, like teams, must first win preliminary
contests in their philosophical ``regions'' to advance. The final
four will be decided by competition within those preliminary
brackets.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Schnur said, finds himself in a preliminary competition
with Dole, a fellow mainstream conserva tive. Dan Quayle, Lamar
Alexander and John Kasich all were in this cluster before dropping
out.
</P>
<P>
   A second grouping contains ``hard-line conservative'' candidates
Pat Buchanan, Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, all by himself, is the third group, which Schnur labels
``the son of the former president region.''
</P>
<P>
   The final group is ``the son of the millionaire regional'' and
is occupied by Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   In the NCAA tournament, Schnur said, ``the field of 64 winnows
to a Final Four, and that's when people start paying attention. And
the same thing is happening here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
