<HEADLINE>
U.S. ATTACK ON OLD VET
 CALLED OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - In the fall of 1944, near a battle front in central
France, an American GI named Bob DeHeer was told his services as an
Army mechanic were no longer required.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roughly half of DeHeer's outfit had been wounded or killed in a
German artillery barrage, and now the enemy was advancing on their
position.
</P>
<P>
   Since retreat was not an option, the job for which DeHeer had
been trained _ maintaining the company motor pool _ became
superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I volunteered for machine-gun duty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, DeHeer hadn't passed within 20 feet of a machine
gun. The only weapon he'd ever fired was an ancient World War I
rifle, and then only a couple of times during basic training. On
the ship overseas, how ever, DeHeer met a machine-gunner who'd told
him that, in combat, it's better to be in a foxhole behind an
imposing weapon than to be advanc ing in the open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured, what the hell,'' DeHeer said. ``I'd gone over there
to win that damn war, and if this is what it took, well, fine. I'd
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The young mechanic put away his wrenches and taught himself the
wrenching art of war _ firing a weapon at others and being fired
upon in return. &QL; 
Wounded hero
</P>
<P>
   DeHeer was on the line for about month before being wounded. He
was awarded the Combat Infantry man Badge, the Purple Heart and the
Bronze Star.
</P>
<P>
   He never gave an inch, never wa vered, never changed.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, when the 77-year-old DeHeer came under attack by his
own government, his battlefield in stincts resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   He dug in. He held his ground.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, the federal prosecu tors who'd been trying to
overrun DeHeer's position throughout the spring and summer,
abruptly backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can finally write an end to this ridiculous saga,''
DeHeer's attorney, Michael Rooney, told me. ``Bob prevailed, with
the bureaucrats pro tecting their backsides to the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, DeHeer drove to the Carl T. Hayden Veterans
Affairs Medical Center in Phoenix to have his hearing aids
adjusted. The condi tion can be traced to artillery shells landing
too close in '44.
</P>
<P>
   DeHeer tried to park his car in a spot at the VA hospital
temporarily labeled ``VIP'' for visiting inspec tors.
</P>
<P>
   When he was prevented from doing so, the elderly vet got into a
shouting match with federal officers. He was handcuffed, hauled off
to a holding cell and issued citations for disor derly conduct and
failing to comply with an officer. Fines for the two offenses added
up to $70.
</P>
<P>
   DeHeer refused to pay. &QL; 
Standing his ground
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning I knew I wasn't going to give in to these
people,'' he said. ``I don't think it was right, what they did, and
you can't just go along with something you feel isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors could have dropped the charges right then. They
could have recognized that Bob DeHeer earned the title ``VIP''
years ago in France.
</P>
<P>
   But the case wound up in a hands of a federal magistrate. Trial
dates were set and then postponed as lawyers argued back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Bob wanted was to talk to them,'' attorney Rooney said.
``To let the VA see his side and keep this from happening to
someone else. To maybe get an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't to be.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, however, as a new trial date approached, Rooney
re ceived written notice that, at the request of the VA,
prosecutors were withdrawing charges against DeHeer. No other
explanation was offered. No apology. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   To DeHeer, it was more of a cease-fire than a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never said they did anything wrong, they just wanted it
to go away,'' he said. ``As far as the VA and the government are
concerned, they wish all us old vets would just go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not me. Not with federal officials sending fresh brigades of
bureaucrats to the battle front every day, and so few among us,
from any generation, willing to dig in and hold the line. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
