<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ISLES-LIGHTNING-NYT &LR;      10-02 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLES-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING PREVAILS AS ISLANDERS' START IS ANYTHING BUT PROMISING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It was only one game, but because it was against
the National Hockey League's perennial doormats, the Lightning, the
Islanders' season opener had extra meaning.
</P>
<P>
   It was a forecast, and the long-term outlook does not look good.
Long Island hockey fans might want to use Tampa Bay's 4-2 victory
at the Ice Palace to measure how long and cold the coming winter
will be for their Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were not outplayed for the entire 60 minutes, just
when it counted most. An example would be on the play that led to
the game-winning goal, scored by Fredrik Modin with 2 minutes 1
second left in the third period. On the play, the Islanders' Jorgen
Jonsson was beaten on a crucial face-off, leaving Islanders goalie
Felix Potvin with no time to get set for the shot by the recently
acquired Modin.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scenario that figures to play out often this season.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four minutes before Modin's goal, Jonsson evened the
score at 2-2 with 5:50 left to play. Mike Sillinger scored Tampa
Bay's fourth goal into an empty net.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin did his part. He turned away 26 Lightning shots while
Tampa Bay's Darren Puppa stopped 32.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a considerable lack of talent on either side of the ice,
the game featured plenty of entertaining plays. And that was good
news for the Lightning owner, William Davidson, who offered Tampa
Bay fans a full refund if they were not completely entertained. The
Ice Palace was sold out for the first time since last year's
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being badly outplayed early in the game, the Islanders
managed to take a 1-0 lead into the first intermission. Mariusz
Czerkawski, the player Islanders coach Butch Goring hopes can lead
his team in scoring this season, knocked in a rebound over the
sprawling Tampa Bay goalie. Czerkawski set up himself by hitting
the post with a wrist shot from between the circles. The rebound
bounced right back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Zigmund Palffy's departure has left Czerkawski as the Islanders'
most skilled forward. Whether he wants the distinction or not, the
27-year-old right wing, who had 21 goals and 17 assists last year,
is the Islanders' go-to guy this season. Czerkawski certainly has
the talent to lead the team in scoring, but without Palffy and
Trevor Linden and Robert Reichel, all of whom were traded last
summer, it won't be easy. Czerkawski is a marked man, and he knows
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I got better,'' Czerkawski said before Saturday
night's game. ``Trevor, Robert and Ziggy aren't here anymore, so
the other team is going to come after me. I'm going to get more
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning stormed back in the second period, scoring two
goals in a 54-second span midway through the second period to put
Tampa Bay ahead by 2-1. Michael Nylander and Steve Guolla scored on
blasts from between the circles. The shots were so hard and so
clean, Potvin didn't have time to react.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
