<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG O HAS A NEW DIET FOR CRITICS: EAT WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Oliver Miller is standing in a hallway, trimmer than
he's looked in years. Sweat is pouring down his face, soaking a
T-shirt that hangs loosely over his frame.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza? No, thanks. Today, he's a man who hopes to dish up a
plateful of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Vecsey and his cheeseburger jokes. Ahmad Rashad. Doug
Collins saying he'd keep a six-pack before he keeps me. Don Nelson
saying I don't love the game,'' Miller said. ``They're going to
have to eat their words.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the strangest twists of the NBA off-season, Miller is
proof that you can go home again. After punishing a few scales and
burning a few bridges, Miller is back with the Suns. As recently as
last season, his weight ballooned near 400 pounds. He is now around
315, closer to reclaiming his career than he's ever been. At least
since leaving Phoenix in 1994 with a few parting shots at Jerry
Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is heavy. Just last season, Miller was suing the
organization, claiming great emotional distress following an act
performed by the Suns' mascot. It was an act that poked fun at
Miller's girth when he came to town with the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Miller could be the Triple X factor in the pursuit of a
championship. And if this wild gamble pays off, the Suns can thank
_ of all people _ the Gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, while his agent was crying foul over the infamous
skit, Miller buried himself in videotape. There, he had an
epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept looking at the replays,'' Miller said. ``And I'm like,
`God, am I that big?' I told myself I have kids to feed, futures to
take care of. I don't want to worry about working when they grow
up. About having to find grants so they can go to school. I went
out and got some help. That skit hurt me inside, but it made me
stronger. It made me do what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After hiring a trainer, Miller slimmed down to 320 pounds. After
confirming the results, Suns' coach Danny Ainge visited Miller in
the LA Summer League. Then came a mending of relationships with the
Colangelos.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Suns are leery. So much that Joe Kleine is still
practicing with the team, just in case old habits die hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone in this organization has ever held
anything against Oliver,'' Ainge said. ``He's just done some stupid
things in his life. He's been very immature, made a lot of
mistakes. I can't sit here today and tell you that I can rely on
Oliver Miller. He has a lot to prove before we can rely on him.
He's just a talented guy who is getting his fourth or fifth chance
with not very much risk on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   If Miller doesn't regress, the possibilities are tantalizing. He
is an excellent passer who can block shots. He can offer another
dimension at center, a set of skills not possessed by Luc Longley.
Miller's target weight for the season is 305, but that doesn't
concern Ainge. Just as long as Miller doesn't go in the other
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people doubt me, but I'm more mature now,''
Miller said. ``I make better decisions on the court. I make better
decisions off the court. I'm just going to get in the best shape
that I can, and prove to people that I'm for real. That I still
love the game. That I take my job seriously and I'm here to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross your fingers. Miller might again be a weighty problem. Not
for the Suns. For the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he understands some of his weaknesses and that the
battles are not going to end,'' Ainge said. ``We'll have to
continue to stay on Oliver to stay in shape. To not screw around in
practice. To keep Oliver from making too many turnovers. But at the
same time, he seems more conscientious. More humble. More
coachable. And that's a great start.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
