<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BKN-SUNS-TURNOVER-AZR     10-02 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-TURNOVER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDAWAY THE FINAL PIECE _ FOR NOW  
 SUNS BEGIN WITH A NEW FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here's a pop quiz:
</P>
<P>
   Name the current Suns player who has the longest tenure in a
Phoenix uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Quick. OK, pencils down.
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe it's Rex Chapman, who is entering only his
fourth season with the Suns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that out,'' Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Chapman is The Dean with only three full seasons
under his belt here.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd also is entering his fourth season, but he came a
couple of months after Chapman. Clifford Robinson is entering his
third season. Nobody else has been in a Phoenix uniform for more
than one season, with the exception of center Oliver Miller, who is
beginning his second stint with the team.
</P>
<P>
   And with training camp opening Tuesday in Flagstaff, there again
are a lot of new faces _ All-Star guard Penny Hardaway, forwards
Rodney Rogers and Corie Blount, rookie Shawn Marion. And a familiar
face, Miller, who began his career in Phoenix and returns after a
five-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Suns made a run to the NBA Finals in 1993, the
club has tinkered yearly in its quest for the league's Holy Grail.
A.C. Green was added. Then Danny Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Majerle was traded for John ``Hot Rod'' Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced Charles Barkley wouldn't deliver a championship, the
Suns traded him in 1996 for a handful of journeymen from Houston.
Those pieces led to the deal Phoenix made with Dallas for Kidd,
which started the club back on the upward track. Antonio McDyess
came and went. Tom Gugliotta and Luc Longley were added last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hardaway is viewed as the latest missing piece.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, he might represent the final major piece _ at
least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what we've done with this team, there has
been a tremendous amount of turnover,'' said General Manager Bryan
Colangelo, who orchestrated the trade for Kidd and the
sign-and-trade deal for Hardaway. ``Continuity is absolutely
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Penny, this was the first time we added a significant
piece without losing any major pieces. Not to discredit Danny
Manning or Pat Garrity (who were traded in the deal), but their
roles weren't as significant as some of the players traded in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Togetherness
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more important, the Suns now have a core of players _
Kidd, Hardaway, Chapman, Robinson, Gugliotta, Longley and Marion
who will be under contract for at least four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, we're not going to have a
bunch of free agents at the end of this season,'' said Suns Coach
Danny Ainge, who was also part of that 1993 Finals club. ``We have
a good group of players in place for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we won't look for ways to improve, but we've
got a chance starting right now to really build some continuity.
We've added Penny, Rodney, Corie and Oliver and it will take some
time because they're critical players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got a nice mix of experienced veterans and youth.
We've got more muscle and athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   While talent is the most important part of a team's success in
the NBA, continuity is valuable. Often, franchises want to break up
contending clubs because too many players are getting old at once.
It happened in Portland, where Robinson played before signing with
the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, it happened in Phoenix when the team gave up on
Majerle and Ainge in 1995. Majerle is still playing. Ainge
contended at the time that he had at least one more year in him,
and that the Suns were capable of one more run at a championship.
Instead, the club fell to 41-41 the next season and the Barkley
trade followed.
</P>
<P>
   Once NBA's best
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough call,'' Ainge said. ``Looking back, I'd say yes,
my opinion is that the decision to change at that time was too
quick. I really believe that the two years Michael (Jordan) was out
of the league, we had the best team in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after the injury to Danny Manning, I thought we were the
best team. If Charles hadn't broken down in the playoffs, I think
we could have won two championships.''
</P>
<P>
   His viewpoint was shared around the league. Chapman, who was
playing for Washington during those years, said the Suns were
considered a team on the cusp of a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really seemed like they were just a little bit of luck
away from winning it,'' he said. ``If they had been able to keep
Kevin Johnson and Charles healthy, it might have been a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams aren't real patient, but you see the teams that are
successful are the ones that have a core of players together for
awhile. Utah has been real patient. Chicago made changes when they
were on top, but they had Michael and Scottie and kept that core
together. When Houston won it twice, they had two or three key
players that had been together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers made a couple of runs early in Robinson's
career, then broke up a team that included Clyde Drexler, Terry
Porter and Buck Williams _ all aging stars. But Robinson said the
experience players have together is critical.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to know you
</P>
<P>
   ``On those teams, we tended to push each other in the ways you
need to be pushed,'' he said. ``When you're playing with different
guys every year, sometimes you don't know how to talk to a player
to get them going. Or they don't feel comfortable telling you what
you need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been around each other for a while, you feel a lot
more comfortable doing that. You've got to be able to push each
other and let each other know what you're thinking without anybody
taking offense. If you can't do that, it's hard to get anything
going on a consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Suns have a lot of new parts, some continuity
already is forming. And Ainge points out that all 13 players on the
roster showed up early for voluntary workouts, plus they'll have a
full training camp and preseason after last season's
lockout-reduced schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to build some chemistry, but for the first time since
I've been the coach I don't feel like everything has to fall
perfectly for us to be a contender,'' Ainge said. ``We've got a
more balanced roster, and we're going to have four All-Stars in our
starting lineup. That's a pretty good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be criticized if we don't win, and we should be. We all
deserve it if we don't win. But I fully expect to win. At the same
time, there are going to be at least eight teams in the Western
Conference who go into the season believing they're contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just excited to get going. I'm not going to say that it
will be a bad season if we don't win an NBA championship, but I
will say that's what we're shooting for from Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, when the Suns signed Hardaway, talked not of winning a
championship but of winning several. The optimism within the Suns
locker room is that high. But Chapman also said the Suns understand
that if they don't produce on the court, those changes will keep
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Bryan and (club President) Jerry Colangelo,''
Chapman said. ``They have shown they are not going to stand pat if
they're not winning. They want a title, and with the types of
investments they've made the last couple of years, we owe it to
ourselves and the franchise to do everything we can to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, everybody is under contract for a while. But if we don't
get the job done, that doesn't mean we're going to stay
together.'' &QL; 
I'm just excited to get going. I'm not going to say that it will be
a bad season if we don't win an NBA championship, but I will say
that's what we're shooting for from Day One. &QC; 
Danny Ainge &QC; 
PHOENIX SUNS COACH &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-02-99 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991002.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBM-AZFALL-LEAGUE-CUS     10-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBM-AZFALL-LEAGUE-CUST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUST ON THE CUSP OF GREAT NESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The first time Diamondbacks scout David May laid eyes
on Jack Cust, he was sure the young prospect was overrated.
</P>
<P>
   May had heard stories about prodigious home runs that Cust was
supposed to be hitting at Immaculata High School in Somerville,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He had a hard time believing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him before I saw him play, and just looking at him he
wasn't a huge guy,'' May said of Cust, who is now 6 foot 1, 205
pounds. ``I remember going to watch him take batting practice for
the first time, and a bunch of guys were asking me if I had seen
him take BP. They were all saying, `Wait until you see this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The fence at that field is only about 300 feet away, but there
were a couple of trees about 40 or 50 feet tall right behind the
fence. He hit maybe 14 or 15 in a row that cleared those trees by a
good distance and landed in a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to see. I had wondered if he was legitimate,
but he was. He was hitting them so high and so far they looked like
golf balls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks eventually made the left-handed hitter their
No. 1 pick in the 1997 draft, and he hasn't disappointed them a
bit. This week, he was named the organization's Minor League Player
of the Year after nearly winning the triple crown at Class A High
Desert of the California League.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cust is one of six Diamondbacks prospects playing for the
Scottsdale Scorpions in the Arizona Fall League. The Scorpions are
one of six teams in the league, which begins play Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The day May scouted Cust, he watched the outfielder take about
50 hacks, and after those first 15 or so bombs, Cust spread line
drives around to all fields. In the game, Cust drove the ball out
of the park with a lined shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never got more than 9 feet off the ground,'' May said. ``It
was just a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for May. In a scene right out of a movie, he
went looking for a phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty excited,'' he said. ``I called my cross-checker,
(former Diamondbacks scout) Brannon Bonifay, and told him he needed
to come see this guy as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cust will get to see some of the best pitching prospects
from other major league organizations, most of them from Class AAA
and AA teams.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his numbers at High Desert, it appears Cust is ready.
He led the California League with 32 home runs, finished second in
hitting with a .334 average, ranked fourth in runs batted in with
112 and second in runs with 107. Not surprisingly, he was named the
California League's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more impressive, he led the league in on-base percentage
and slugging percentage. That's a rare combination, especially for
a player so young.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young I was taught, even in batting practice, not
to swing if it wasn't in the strike zone,'' Cust said. ``My dad was
big on teaching me patience. He taught me to get something in the
strike zone that I could drive.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is an unusual knowledge of the strike zone, and the
discipline at the plate to make pitchers throw strikes. It's
something that's almost unheard of in young power hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him hit some long home runs, but the impression that
stands out in my mind is how impressive his discipline is at the
plate,'' said Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. ``It
would be very natural for him to say to himself, `They didn't draft
me to walk. They drafted me to hit it up the light tower
somewhere,' and turn into a free-swinging, wild hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he hasn't done that. To me, that's just outstanding. It's
a lot like (Diamondbacks first baseman) Erubiel Durazo. Everybody
heard a lot about this power guy, but he's the same way _ very
disciplined at the plate. Jack has that same ability to make a
pitcher throw it over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cust can't think of anybody he'd rather be compared to than
Durazo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an awesome hitter,'' Cust said. ``I saw him hit some in
spring training, and I watch him now on TV all the time. He's got
great knowledge of the strike zone and a great approach at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll just spit at stuff that's a couple inches off the plate.
He makes them throw strikes, and then just explodes. It's great to
have somebody like that as a model right in the same
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Cust also wouldn't mind modeling Durazo's quick rise to the
majors. Durazo began this season in Class AA El Paso, where Cust
likely is ticketed for the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to get to move up as quickly as possible,''
Cust said. ``That's what you dream about, making the big leagues.
But they've got a great club up there, and they aren't going to
bring anybody up there that isn't ready. I've still got a lot to
work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Cust was considered by most to be a first baseman while he was
in high school, but with Travis Lee in the organization, Cust was
moved to left field. Now with the emergence of Durazo, it's likely
his future is in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   So he's working to develop his defensive skills and arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was a good enough athlete to play the outfield,'' he
said. ``I felt more comfortable with every game I played out there.
I know when they signed me, they weren't thinking I would be a
defensive stud in the outfield by the time I was 19. They're
looking at the long-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to give up runs out there and try to make it
up with the stick. I want to be a complete ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's another attribute Garagiola loves in Cust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's certainly first and foremost an offensive
player,'' Garagiola said. ``However, he's not a one-dimensional
player. He has worked hard on his defense and he's taking pride in
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I think he'll keep working on his defense, and that will
be good enough to play in the big leagues. But those things aren't
going to come naturally to him. He's going to have to work at it,
and he's demonstrated he'll do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a burning desire to play in the major leagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
