<HEADLINE>
11 PITCHERS ON FINAL PLAYOFF ROSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Though the Diamondbacks' playoff roster has not been
released, it has been all but set in the minds of team officials.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter had toyed with the idea of taking 10
pitchers instead of 11, but in the end decided on 11.
</P>
<P>
   Deadline for submittal of the official roster to Major League
Baseball is 6 a.m., Arizona time, on Tuesday. The Diamondbacks will
open the playoffs at Bank One Ballpark on Tuesday night at 8
against an opponent that won't be determined until today or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it came down to is whether we felt a 15th position player
or an 11th pitcher could make more of a difference late in a game,
which would strengthen us the most, and we felt it would be the
pitcher,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the starting rotation, Showalter said he will go with
left-hander Randy Johnson on Tuesday night, right-hander Todd
Stottlemyre in Game 2 on Wednesday night and left-hander Omar Daal,
who started Saturday night's game against San Diego, in Game 3 on
the road on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   If a Game 4 is necessary, it appears that left-hander Brian
Anderson will be the choice if his selection as the starter in
today's regular-season finale is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   As for right-hander Andy Benes, who finished at 13-12, he is
expected to throw a handful of innings today and likely will be a
long reliever in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has started 18 games and has a 7-2 record, said he
isn't quite sure what to make of today's start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure it matters one way or the other,'' he said.
``I think it (start in Game 4) will depend on the matchups, depend
on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I want to do (today) is work on some things, get a
good tune-up and keep it going, whatever my assignment (in the
playoffs) will be.'' &QL; 
Miller says he'll play &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller, sidelined with a hairline fracture of the
inside of his lower right thumb/hand, did some very light throwing
and reported very little discomfort. He will attempt to swing a bat
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, I'm playing in the playoffs,'' he
said. ``The doctor said I really can't injure it any worse. I can
play through the pain. I don't want to miss this. I've got all
winter to rest.'' &QL; 
We can work it out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are expected to have their pre-playoff-opening
workout on Monday in late afternoon, according to Showalter. It is
uncertain when the visiting club will work out. If the Cincinnati
Reds and New York Mets play a playoff game to determine the wild
card, the visitors will not have a workout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
