<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-1ST     10-02 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LINES UP TO SEE THE ART BEHIND THE FUSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS attendance   graf before optional trim) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (lh) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service      
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a museum director's fantasy: hundreds of
people waiting on a clear, crisp morning for the doors to open on a
new exhibition. Enough reporters buzzing about to cover a small
war. A line of art patrons that grew longer and longer, even after
the doors opened and the cash registers began to rattle and hum.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the vomit bags passed out by angry Catholics, or the
gruesome posters of severed cow heads brandished by angry animal
lovers, or even the grim-faced man who stood there alone with a
sign that read, ``Hitler Was Right When He Got Rid of `Degenerate
Art.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum of Art began to harvest the benefits of
controversy Saturday as it opened ``Sensation,'' an exhibition of
contemporary British art that has spun New York City into a
political, cultural and religious uproar.
</P>
<P>
   In the museum's recent history, the largest opening-day turnout
was recorded during last winter's Monet exhibition. Gazing in
wonderment at a line that stretched all the way up the museum's
long cobblestone driveway, museum officials said Saturday's crowds
made Monet seem like some second-rate Left Bank artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had lines like this, but then we've never had
metal detectors either,'' said Lynne De Rienzo, an official in the
museum's education division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Giuliani did us a favor,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has mounted an unrelenting
campaign against the museum, accusing its board of recklessly
staging an exhibition of art he views as repulsive and offensive to
religion. He has withheld the museum's monthly city subsidy and has
started eviction proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, some visitors to the museum reacted with skepticism
upon discovering that the three subway stops closest to the museum
were closed to Manhattan-bound riders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances from transportation officials that the
closings had been scheduled in advance to make track repairs, some
wondered whether it was a ploy to make it harder for New Yorkers to
see the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a big lie,'' said Irwin Greenberg, 67, a retired
lawyer from the Upper West Side. ``First of all, it's Saturday.
They're going to start track work at noon? Somebody is faking
somebody out.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it was unclear which side in the dispute was hurt the
most. Some groups that had scheduled protests blamed the subway
closures for a light turnout. They were far outnumbered by those
who came to see the exhibition, and filled only a small portion of
the area penned off by police barricades that had been set up in
front of the museum to contain the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   And with polls showing a solid majority of the public in
disagreement with Giuliani's crusade against the museum, it was
clear that many who showed up for the exhibition did so as much to
demonstrate opposition to Giuliani as to show appreciation for the
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to see the art, but it's more to stand up for the
principle,'' said the first person in line Saturday, Paul D.
Warren, a social worker and amateur artist from the Park Slope
section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,200 people had attended the show by the 11 p.m.closing
time, a museum official said. The museum's previous single-day
record was on Jan. 3, 1998, when 5,979 people saw the Monet
exhibition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those who came for the art formed a diverse crowd, from the
young and hip with torn jeans and nose rings to middle-aged men
wearing tweed jackets and ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live right around the corner, and I'm here with my wife and
my granddaughter,'' said Donald Correa, a school custodian. ``We're
just here to see the art. I'm not protesting anything. A museum is
a museum for art. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest groups were equally diverse in their makeup and
viewpoints. A dozen or so protesters from People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals came to single out the artist Damien Hirst,
whose work features dead animals sliced into sections and suspended
in tanks of formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there is no creativity or beauty or imagination in
exploiting animals,'' said Martin Rowe, a spokesman for the group.
``We feel they're taking the animals out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic protest groups took aim at Chris Ofili, a British
artist of Nigerian descent whose painting ``The Holy Virgin Mary''
has stirred so much controversy that it had to be shielded by
Plexiglas in one of the exhibition halls. The painting shows a
black Madonna with a breast fashioned out of elephant dung,
surrounded by small cutouts from pornographic magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Although some art experts say the painting actually venerates
the Virgin Mary, noting that dung is a symbol of growth in the
African culture, many Catholics view it as blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   A busload of women from St. John Vianney, a Catholic church in
the Bronx, held up drawings of the Virgin Mary outside the museum
Saturday. ``Our Lady, the most beautiful Lady,'' they called out,
over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the soldiers of Mary,'' explained Hilda Hernandez, a
social worker and church member.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of another Catholic protest group, speaking over a
loudspeaker, repeated some of the most familiar words in Roman
Catholicism: ``Hail Mary, full of grace, the Lord is with thee,''
he said. ``Blessed art thou amongst women, and blessed is the fruit
of thy womb, Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come to her defense,'' said Elba Griffin of the
Forest Hills section of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Catholic protesters framed their opposition in terms
of the First Amendment, which, in addition to guaranteeing free
speech, guarantees freedom of religion. In their view, the city
government, by financing the museum, is indirectly supporting a
painting that attacks Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is the funding,'' said Jane Dempsey of Westchester
County. ``This painting should be shown in a private gallery. If
someone wants to use their money to show this art, well then, be
our guest.''
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters did not represent the only Catholic viewpoint
Saturday. In line for the exhibition, Stella Wilson, a retired
nurse from College Point, Queens, held the hand of her squirming
granddaughter, 5-year-old Nina Lopez. ``I believe as a Catholic,''
Mrs. Wilson said, ``that God said, `Render unto Caesar things that
are Caesar's, and render unto God things that are God's.' And I
believe that this is a secular event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
