<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL MLB SHED ITS LOSERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several big-league owners floated what seemed like a silly idea
a few months ago, shrinking the major leagues from 30 clubs to 28,
or even 26. At first, most other owners laughed at the proposition.
</P>
<P>
   But recent weeks have seen the idea gain momentum in many
circles. Suddenly, it's not such a foolish idea. In fact, there are
some owners who want to bring it up for a serious feasibility study
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   With several clubs completely unable to compete because of low
revenues and virtually no serious fan base, the idea would go
something like this: Have the remaining 26 clubs pay each of the
four struggling franchises $150 million each. Then have a dispersal
draft with the players in those organizations and have them filter
out throughout the remaining major league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   With more revenue to share among fewer clubs, several owners
believe this move would make fiscal sense.
</P>
<P>
   Or, have the four struggling clubs merge into two clubs, though
that idea has less possibility since they would still be playing in
a low-revenue area. Some of the possible clubs being mentioned for
such a drastic move include Montreal, Oakland, Kansas City,
Minnesota, Florida and Tampa Bay. All but Tampa Bay and Florida,
which was sold within the past year, are on the market.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Kansas City, none of the above-mentioned
has a feasible stadium to play in and none is in steady ownership
hands, making them all liable for a worst-case scenario. Baseball
has not had a club go belly-up in the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   Some have come close but been saved by ownerships in other
cities, such as when the Washington Senators moved to Texas in 1972
or when the St. Louis Browns relocated to Baltimore in 1954. The
old Senators also picked up and left the D.C. metro area for
Minnesota in 1960, but that was a move where the Griffith family
kept and moved the club itself.
</P>
<P>
   This is no longer a laughing matter. It's scary, especially for
baseball purists who do not want to see the game tarnished by such
an ugly move that would be certain to draw the ire of many.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mere fact that the idea is gaining steam should let
all know that the game is in some trouble, at least in some pockets
around North America. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Grace of the Chicago Cubs and former Cubs teammate and now
Texas slugger  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro are in a heated battle to become the
1990s hits leader entering the weekend. Grace entered Friday's
action with 1,752 hits, just five ahead of Palmeiro's 1,747. Name
the decade hits leaders for the previous 50 years? &QL; 
Vaughn's new home? &QL; 
There are several reasons that Cincinnati General Manager  &UR; Jim
Bowden would like to have outfielder  &UR; Greg Vaughn, a free agent
after this season, return in 2000. Of course, Vaughn's 44 home runs
and 115 RBI entering the weekend are reason enough.
</P>
<P>
   But there's so much more, Bowden believes. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because when we were down 6-1 to St. Louis last Sunday, he was
stalking the dugout snarling, `Don't give up, don't give up, don't
give up.' (The Reds came back to win, 9-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he took one of our young players privately into the
training room, stood him against a wall and said, `It's not about
you, it's about us. It's not about your stats, it is about us
winning.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Because on a hot day when it was 150 degrees on the AstroTurf
and the young players thought it was too scorching to take batting
practice, Vaughn walked to the field carrying his bat and they all
followed him like puppy dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' 95 victories entering the weekend series were the most
since the 1976 Big Red Machine finished 102-60. &QL; 
Parting words? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled and often complicated Los Angeles outfielder  &UR; Raul
 &UR; Mondesi publicly apologized for his August tirade, seven weeks
after he blasted Manager Davey Johnson and General Manager Kevin
Malone in a profanity-laced lashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel bad about this,'' Mondesi told Dodgers writers
in Spanish through translator  &UR; Eugene Mato, who also doubles as a
business associate. ``I feel bad that what happened and that I used
(foul) language and said those things. I know I'm a role model,and
you shouldn't use that type of language when you're a role model,
especially if you are. That wasn't right and I want fans to know
that I'm sorry about that. I've always loved the fans and that's
why I feel really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who reached 30 home runs and 30 stolen bases for the
second time in his career, wouldn't discuss if he still wants to be
traded or what his current feelings were toward Johnson and/or
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm going to be back or not, but I want the
fans to know how much they've meant to me,'' he said. ``Even if I
end up someplace else, I don't think I would ever find a better
group of fans. They will always be in my heart. Always.'' &QL; 
Ozzie's wizardry &QL; 
 &UR; Ozzie Guillen, who can rarely be found without a smile on his face,
went through a panic attack last weekend when he found himself in
Atlanta's starting lineup for the first time since July 31, the
same night the Braves traded for  &UR; Jose Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   As Guillen started to gather his gear he couldn't find his knee
sleeve and protective cup. After all, neither has been of much use
for Guillen, who routinely throws batting practice, in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget how to put my (stuff) on,'' he said. ``I haven't worn
a jock in two months.'' &QL; 
With all due respect &QL; 
For Detroit's final game ever at Tiger Stadium, the starters wore
the uniform numbers of the all-time Tigers team as selected by
fans. That meant  &UR; Gabe Kapler, starting in center field, wore no
number since  &UR; Ty &UR; Cobb played before uniform numbers were used in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It also meant former Diamondbacks player  &UR; Karim Garcia, starting
in right field, wore the No. 6 of Hall of Famer  &UR; Al Kaline, which
is quite a stretch considering the quiet elegance with which Kaline
patrolled that particular corner of Tiger Stadium. To his credit,
Garcia said he only hoped he could live up to the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit Free Press'' baseball writer  &UR; Gene Guidi had this to
say about Garcia's play during the final game:
</P>
<P>
   ``Garcia went out and had a Kaline-type game, making all the
plays in right field, hitting the cutoff man regularly, uncorking a
crisp throw to home plate that arrived on target on the fly to hold
a runner at third, and then capping the all-around performance with
a tiebreaking, two-run homer in the bottom of the sixth that turned
out to be the game-winning hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes fantasies do come true. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
 &UR; Robin Yount led everyone in the 1980s with 1,731 hits;  &UR; Pete Rose
was the leader in the 1970s with 2,045;  &UR; Roberto Clemente led the
1960s with 1,877;  &UR; Richie Ashburn was the 1950s leader with 1,875;
and  &UR; Lou
 &UR; Boudreau led the 1940s with 1,578 hits.  &UR; Ted Williams (1,303) and
 &UR; Joe
 &UR; DiMaggio (1,156) missed three full seasons in the 1940s while
enlisted in the military during World War II. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. AtlantaBraves are only the fourth club to have three straight
100-win seasons.  &QL; 
2. ArizonaThere's no denying that this club's rotation makes it
dangerous.  &QL; 
3. NY YankeesThe Yanks have been laying low, which could mean big
trouble for others.  &QL; 
4. ClevelandFor the second time in Indians history, a 50-win season
on the road.  &QL; 
5. CincinnatiThe Reds have very little to lose at this point,
making them scary.  &QL; 
6. HoustonYet again, the Killer B's get set to try to erase bad
playoff demons.  &QL; 
7. TexasWhere, oh where has one-time super rookie  &UR; Jeff Zimmerman's
stuff gone?  &QL; 
8. BostonHe may not be able to spell his first name, but boy
can &UR; Jimy Williams manage.  &QL; 
9. NY MetsHow big does a noose have to be for 25 players, plus one
outgoing manager? &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. MinnesotaIs 2000 the final year of baseball in the Twin Cities?
It might be.  &QL; 
29. FloridaThey won't lose 100, but they do need more than $100
million for a stadium.  &QL; 
28. Kansas CityIt may not look like it, but the Royals actually
made progress.  &QL; 
27. MontrealToo bad ``Les Expos'' played in front of far fewer fans
than they deserve.  &QL; 
26. Chicago CubsHave lost at least 93 games in two of the past
three seasons.  &QL; 
25. Colorado &UR; Pedro Astacio needs some big-time help.  &UR; Darryl Kile,
you listening?  &QL; 
24. Tampa BayHow far down and out would the Rays be without
 &UR; Roberto &UR; Hernandez?  &QL; 
23. AnaheimIf Disney is selling,  &UR; Reggie Jackson wants to be part
of the new group.  &QL; 
22. St. LouisBig Mac is impressive, but this club is filled with so
many holes. ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Detroit Tigers: The Tigers are finishing in a flurry, which
they will say will help matters in 2000. They lie. None of this
will matter. What will help this franchise is moving into new
Comerica Park next April. What will also help is pushing the
payroll from $35 million to somewhere over $50 million. This club
is not as far away as its record might indicate. Detroit has many
young players that other clubs would love to trade for. If some of
the young arms can rebound, the Tigers appear to be the only club
in this division capable of giving Cleveland a run for the division
title in the near future. Keep an eye on the Motown Cats. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oakland Athletics: Manager  &UR; Art Howe did a remarkable job of
pushing the A's into contention, keeping them there up until the
final week of the season. But the tank ran out of gas down the
stretch and Oakland is sputtering home in these final games,
apparently unable to lift itself up from having the pedal to the
metal throughout most of the second half. None of it should take
away from a wonderful list of spunky and low-budget accomplishments
this A's club managed in 1999. Coming close to repeating this
year's fortunes will be nearly impossible next season, and that's a
shame. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer and legendary center fielder  &UR; Willie Mays,
explaining the simple formula for playing the notorious swirling
winds in the outfield at Candlestick Park, ``Take two steps in and
five steps back, and get the ball.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but surely,  &UR; Brian Daubach climbed the ladder of Red Sox
rookie lore, joining the likes of  &UR; Ted Williams,  &UR; Fred Lynn,  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Rice,  &UR; Rico Petrocelli and  &UR; Tony Conigliaro. Daubach has already
become a household name in New England. With the playoffs set to
start this week, he is sure to make his presence known throughout
the country to baseball fans everywhere. Daubach entered the final
weekend series with 21 home runs and 72 RBI while batting .291 in
374 at-bats. More impressively, he made many Red Sox fans forget
all about  &UR; Mo Vaughn. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Now this is what we call giving back to the fans: In an era
when security guards often believe they are a godlike presence,
authorities freely allowed fans to reach over the low railing at
Tiger Stadium all last week and scoop up cups of dirt. A big
high-five to Tigers officials.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; People's exhibit No.  &UR; 893 against Philadelphia: During the
sixth inning last Sunday's game between the Mets and Philadelphia,
the person responsible for the music at Veterans Stadium selected
military ``Taps'' to play over the loudspeakers as the men from
Queens were on their way to being swept in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (special last-day selection): Solomon Torres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If they could somehow land Sean Casey, they may
 &UR; really have some marketing magic: The Class A Stockton Ports of the
California League will change their name to the Stockton Mudville
Nine for the 2000 season. Local historians believe  &UR; Ernest L.
Thayer penned his ode, ``Casey at the Bat,'' after a Stockton
baseball club in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thanks for coming, but you really shouldn't have: Philadelphia
climbed to a season-best 13 games over .500 on Aug. 6. The next day
the Phillies celebrated their century in baseball, a ceremony that
included former Manager  &UR; Gene Mauch, who presided over the most
well-known collapse in baseball history in 1964. The Phillies lost
34 of their next 44 games. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Diego closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman entered the weekend against
Arizona needing two saves to break  &UR; Dennis Eckersley's
consecutive-season record of 94 saves. Hoffman, who had 53 saves in
54 chances last year, had 40 in 43 opportunities this season before
the final series.
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting perspective on Cleveland's  &UR; Manny
 &UR; Ramirez and his 165 RBI: Here are the career highs for some pretty
decent hitters;  &UR; Willie Mays (141),  &UR; Mickey Mantle (130),  &UR; Ted
Williams (159),  &UR; Reggie Jackson (118),  &UR; Mike Schmidt (121),  &UR; Stan
Musial (131),
 &UR; Frank Robinson (136),  &UR; Harmon Killebrew (140),  &UR; Rogers Hornsby
(152) and
 &UR; Hank Aaron (132).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta outfielder  &UR; Brian Jordan, who had been struggling for
more than a month because of an ailing right hand and wrist, has
been treated by track guru  &UR; Bob Kersee, husband of  &UR; Jackie
 &UR; Joyner-Kersee for two weeks now. Jordan entered the weekend series
batting .333 (10 for 23) with nine RBI in his previous eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals franchise may be only 31 years old, but
already they have been on hand for the final game played at four
different stadiums. The Royals, the opponent in the final game at
Tiger Stadium Monday, have also been on had for finales at their
own Municipal Stadium in 1972, Minnesota's Metropolitan Stadium
(1981) and Texas' Arlington Stadium (1993).
</P>
<P>
   A pair of ``New York Post'' headlines describing the Mets play
during the past week: ``Chokers Wild,'' and one about Manager
 &UR; Bobby Valentine, who offered to step aside if the Mets failed to
reach the playoffs, ``Why wait? Can the Phony Now!''
</P>
<P>
   Former Florida Marlins washout prospect  &UR; Josh Booty started at
quarterback for LSU Saturday night. Booty hit .198 during five
mostly unproductive seasons in the Marlins' system. At 24, he has
to be the oldest college quarterback in the country. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle landing the 2001 All-Star Game and Milwaukee being
awarded the 2002 game, look for Arizona to be in a strong position
to lay claim to the 2004 midsummer classic, but that's only if the
D-Backs are still in the NL. Otherwise, it could be 2003 or 2005
for Bank One Ballpark to host the game.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong talk around the Bronx these days that New York
batting coach  &UR; Chris Chambliss is in jeopardy of losing his job
after this season, no matter what the Yankees do in the playoffs.
If so, look for  &UR; Don Mattingly to return to the Yankees as batting
coach.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Mike Munoz cannot pitch for Texas in the playoffs (he
dropped a computer monitor on his small right toe), Texas may be
forced to go with  &UR; Jeff Fassero in its bullpen. Fassero has a 6.06
ERA and left-handed batters are hitting .462 (6 for 13) against
him.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Buddy Bell does not land the Colorado Rockies managing
position, something terrible would have occurred. Bell is, far and
away, the leading candidate to replace  &UR; Jim Leyland, who said he
will retire after today's game.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-year extension worth $20 million, left-handed
starter  &UR; David Wells is fully aware that he may not return to
Toronto next season. Wells is 16-10 and has logged more than 222
innings. ``I thought I was going to be in New York for a long time,
and look what happened there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's  &UR; Edgar Martinez, arguably the greatest designated
hitter ever (a title that doesn't look so impressive in print, does
it?), appears to be closing in a one-year deal for the 2000 season
that will pay him somewhere around $6 million. &QL; 
